<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">2</span>
</p><!--l. 948--><p class="indent" >  Light rain and a morning chill have summoned forth the tantalizing smell of
eucalyptus. The University of California in San Diego, UCSD has a beautiful
campus, and the walk up the road from the guesthouse is pleasantly shady and
cool, but Den has decided to take a swim in the pool before walking up to
his meeting. It is quiet at the motel guesthouse. Most of the guests are busy
guzzling their breakfast or watching TV in the lounge, so he has the pool to
himself.
</p><!--l. 957--><p class="indent" >  The water is still and clear. He thrusts himself into it, shattering its glassy surface
and replacing it with frothing waves that spill outwards to the edges. He feels bubbles
of air loosening from his body as he cuts through it, ploughing an expanding dovetail
of ripples through the water.
</p><!--l. 963--><p class="indent" >  As he swims, Den runs through the walk up to the campus in his mind. He
dress-rehearsed yesterday; now he tests himself on his mental agility. It will be
important for them to feel that he is sharp and conﬁdent. Den can certainly be
conﬁdent on the surface. He makes a good impression. He still has youthful good
looks and can be charming, in an English sort of way, when he needs to be. He hasn&#x2019;t
come this far without being in command of his faculties. But that kind of discipline
requires constant testing. He likes to use the training time for running through his
list.
</p><!--l. 973--><p class="indent" >  Remember to take charge of the meeting at once. Make sure that you have all the
facts in your head. Marketing is a subtle business and the culture here is quite diﬀerent
from European culture. He should be sure to demonstrate his command of both
worlds. Then there is his other agenda, but not something that can come out. He has to
be convincing.
</p><!--l. 980--><p class="indent" >  Coming to America is always a mixed blessing. The increasing militarization of
the borders makes it harder to move around. So far the anti-terrorism laws
have not made a signiﬁcant impact on tourism and business, but soon it will
be necessary to wear electronic visa inside the country. It seems absurd to

Den. Even prisoners can opt out of wearing their dog tags if they stay in one
place. Tourists will be more accountable. The freedom of movement will
be at a premium, easy in prearranged tours by bus or by plane, but diﬃcult
by car or in solo. He must make the most of the freedoms while they still
survive.
</p><!--l. 991--><p class="indent" >  He will hire – no <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">rent </span>a car.
</p><!--l. 993--><p class="indent" >  Still, the annoyance of a barrage of questions about his intentions make the
whole eﬀort somewhat tiresome. Soon he hopes that his connections with the
top players in the game venture will aﬀord him certain privileges in that
regard.
</p><!--l. 998--><p class="indent" >  He ducks his head down and swims in long broad breast strokes just under the
surface, enjoying the extra thrust and speed it aﬀords him. It charges him with a sense
of power. He feels muscular, larger somehow and in command, isolated in the watery
cocoon from the reality of the surroundings.
</p><!--l. 1004--><p class="indent" >  “Morning, sir. How are you today?”, says a hotel employee who comes around the
corner of the building to his right.
</p><!--l. 1007--><p class="indent" >  “Morning,” his primitive brain responds. He nods back with a smile, enjoying the
pleasantly formal courtesy here in the United States.
</p><!--l. 1010--><p class="indent" >  A couple of young kids hiding behind some erupting fronds peer at him and his
audacious morning display. They giggle and tease him, fully aware that he can see
them. Hide and seek?
</p><!--l. 1014--><p class="indent" >  He suppresses an instinct to join in. Now is not the time to let down his
concentration. Success requires a measure of control, of personal sacriﬁce. No pain,
no gain, darling, <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">nez pah</span>? Whose pain? His or theirs?
</p><!--l. 1019--><p class="indent" >  Ghosts of supposed obligation. Focus, Den. Who are they? Young, middle class,
thin, white. Their eyes are probably blue. She likes horses and he likes the tanks. His
mind skips through a dozen stereotypes that characterize the moment. Always stay on
your toes. Friendship can wait. This moment is about branching out of the box and
becoming something.
</p><!--l. 1026--><p class="indent" >  Den reaches up and lifts himself from the envelope of the pool; he feels the
transitory chill of the warming air seep into his limbs. His hand grabs a towel and rubs
his body lightly down then throws on a robe. The ﬁbres will dry his skin and gently
exorcise the dead skin cells of his outer shell, cleansing his skin as well as his
mood. He dons his pool slippers and ﬂip-ﬂops back to his room, avoiding a
small cleaning device that cringes respectfully into a ball as be approaches
it.
</p><!--l. 1035--><p class="indent" >  Den climbs the short wooden steps, up the outside of the hotel wing to the second
ﬂoor, where his ﬁngerprints grant him access to the suite. The room seems dark and
murky after the brightly lit morning, but the carpet is soft and television lights up as
he enters.
</p><!--l. 1040--><p class="indent" >  There are chairs and tables as well as a bed, even a refrigerator and a kitchen here,
with a breakfast bar, but he will probably not use it. He is not really sure why anyone
would need such a thing. It makes the room seem cold and inappropriate but he

aﬀords it less than a passing thought as he moves directly to the shower. The air is
naturally conditioned for temperature, humidity and scent which is unfamiliar and
rather than relaxing him seems to trigger a disconcerting sense of suspicion. There
must surely be a limit to how invasive environmental controls can be. Certainly the
boundaries are far from what he is used to. He wonders why, in such a beautiful area
with semi-natural fragrances like eucalyptus, they could not simply open the
window and be done with it. Perhaps it would require additional insect control.
Whatever.
</p><!--l. 1054--><p class="indent" >  He slips into the shower and lets the perfect water temperature massage his scalp
and shoulders as the shampoo and conditioner revitalize his jet-lagged hair and the
soap creams his skin. The hotel bathroom products are pleasant, he has to admit and
they perform their duty in removing the eﬀects of the chlorine from the pool.
The hotel chain has probably paid handsomely for their own characteristic
scent.
</p><!--l. 1061--><p class="indent" >  Emerging from the steamy cubicle, he catches sight of the television in
the bedroom. An ad is chiming away. As always, he is both fascinated and
revolted by the advertising culture here. It is his job, but this is so alien to
him.
