</p><!--l. 2249--><p class="indent" >  Dermot Macguire-Olsen&#x2019;s small oﬃce is a collage of mess, a cellular equilibrium
of multitudinous projects, tidied regularly but each possessing a life of its own and
apparently prospering. His borrowed room at Oslo&#x2019;s Computer Crime Team
headquarters is more a testament to his productivity than to his humanity. It&#x2019;s a sterile
room, he realizes, like its occupant. He hasn&#x2019;t added a single non-functional object to
it since arriving: not a picture, nor a plant, not a shred of personality. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">It&#x2019;s a ﬁling</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">cabinet. Even my clothes are boring. Christ.</span>
</p><!--l. 2258--><p class="indent" >  Dermot is not even a real investigator. True, he&#x2019;s been with the crime team for only
a short time, but that&#x2019;s not it. He has been telling himself repeatedly for years that he
would change all this. If he can just establish himself – his credentials as a systems
analyst, then he can relax a little and pay attention to these small details. When he no
longer has to ﬁght for the attention of his colleagues, then he can begin to reform his
miserable social life. New clothes, new apartment, new lifestyle. But he knows that it
is a race against time. He is not getting any younger. He has passed the awful barrier
of thirty and the longer he waits the harder it will be to learn how to socialize
again.
</p><!--l. 2270--><p class="indent" >  He looks around him, anywhere but at the monitor screen that has been giving him
a headache these last hours. The only trace of personality in this oﬃce is his tea
corner, he thinks. Dermot insists on making quality tea – none of this instant powder
nonsense. He receives freshly roasted, ﬁne-grain tea leaves of the highest quality from
the Cameron Highlands. It is a perk of his company&#x2019;s Malaysian outsourcing. It is the
same tea that they serve at the Raﬄes. It is one of his few pleasures, apart from
computer matters.
</p><!--l. 2279--><p class="indent" >  He gets up out of his seat and paces. It is better to get out of the chair once in a
while. So they say. But where is he going? The only place worth being is in the
computer. Jesus. How did it get to this? He does not feel quite at home here.
He is hungry but nor can he quite bring himself to take any food from the
canteen.

</p><!--l. 2286--><p class="indent" >  “Aren&#x2019;t you going to eat something?” a colleague asked him a while ago.
</p><!--l. 2288--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t know. Am I allowed to take this?” He does not yet feel as though he
belongs here in this group. It seems foreign and he does not understand the system. Is
it meant for him, an outsider?
</p><!--l. 2292--><p class="indent" >  He sits down again and looks at his combo. The screen-saver has cut in and is
ﬂagging him with one of the slogans he has programmed into it to boost his
self-esteem.

</p>
