something, but who knows? She smiles shyly at him and he smiles back.
Dermot has never been very good with girls, but he knows one when he sees
one. And she really is one. He is not shy, but he is bashful. He ﬁnds himself
aroused.
</p><!--l. 3896--><p class="indent" >  He recalls the ease with which Bishop had struck up a conversation. Just look
unaﬀected and say the words, he thinks. “So when do these trams go anyway?” he
says, as matter of factly as he can.
</p><!--l. 3900--><p class="indent" >  She just smiles.
</p><!--l. 3902--><p class="indent" >  “Do you have the time?”
</p><!--l. 3904--><p class="indent" >  “Sorry.”
</p><!--l. 3906--><p class="indent" >  He stands there in the rain, watching the drops splash on the pavement. Nearby he
can hear soft ambient song echoing from a jazz cafe, contrasting with the proximity of
the thudding pellets. It is all vanishing now, slipping away. The whole meeting is
dissolving into the reality of those hammering drops. He ﬁnds himself suﬀused by a
melancholy and his eyes are drawn to the girl&#x2019;s slight ﬁgure. She seems more
important to him at this moment.
</p><!--l. 3914--><p class="indent" >  A rumbling caterpillar tram thunders around the corner, squeaking on its tracks, as
the lights change to green; it stops in front of them. Doors whoosh neatly open,
ejecting outwards and sideways, like a space capsule, and bid them entry into a
crowded chassis. There is only one double seat left. He sits down next to the girl,
looking down at her skinny legs, black tights, short skirt. Damn. What dream is he
wrestling with now?
</p><!--l. 3922--><p class="indent" >  The train rumbles through the town, shoving them from side to side, as it is
clumsily forced to alter direction by the bumps and imperfections in the track, and
thoughts abandon him. All he can see now is her blond hair and small hands as they

fumble with an old mobile handset. Something about her is special. There are
beautiful girls everywhere, but she has a quality that attracts him. An undeﬁnable
fragility. A calmness. Something else?
</p><!--l. 3930--><p class="indent" >  Several stops. He is nearing his destination. He has to say something. The eﬀort is
excruciating and results in more of a squeak than an inquiry.
</p><!--l. 3934--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s a classic,” he blurts.
</p><!--l. 3936--><p class="indent" >  “What?” she snaps. Nervous wide, Scandinavian eyes, full of terror. She knows that
he has been looking at her. She must be sure that he is a creep.
</p><!--l. 3940--><p class="indent" >  “Your mobile. I haven&#x2019;t seen one like that for years.”
</p><!--l. 3942--><p class="indent" >  “Oh.” Her voice softens. “It&#x2019;s my brother&#x2019;s.” Then, as an afterthought: “Are you into
computers?”
</p><!--l. 3945--><p class="indent" >  “Eh . . . yes,” he half-stammers, taken aback.
</p><!--l. 3947--><p class="indent" >  She nods with the outline of a smile.
</p><!--l. 3949--><p class="indent" >  He fumbles in his pocket and pulls out a paper card with his name and
position on it: a gimmick from his old company. She takes it as though it is
something dirty, ﬁngering it as though she does not really know what it is
for.
</p><!--l. 3954--><p class="indent" >  “Dermot,” she reads. “That&#x2019;s you.” It is not really a question, but he has to
say yes. “I haven&#x2019;t seen one of these for a long time.” She closes her palm
with the card in it, as if to say: this is unimportant, but I am going to keep it
anyway.
</p><!--l. 3959--><p class="indent" >  Normally people ask him about his name. What kind of a name is that? Dermot?
But not her. She seems to accept it without question. He likes that. It makes her seem
experienced and intelligent. She does not say another word.
</p><!--l. 3964--><p class="indent" >  The tram comes to a stop.
</p><!--l. 3966--><p class="indent" >  “Well, anyway. Nice to meet you.”
</p><!--l. 3968--><p class="indent" >  The girl smiles without looking his way and says nothing.
</p><!--l. 3970--><p class="indent" >  He ﬂees the tram, stepping back out into the rain and starts oﬀ towards his
apartment. That&#x2019;s about as far as he ever gets with women.
