<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">19</span>
</p><!--l. 9854--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">They don&#x2019;t come here to talk. They graze, cattle on the liquid commons. Meet down</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">at the poleaxe. Face in the trough.</span>
</p><!--l. 9857--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">“Pinta Theakstons an&#x2019; a packet o&#x2019; crisps, love.”</span>
</p><!--l. 9859--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">“Lager and lime, eh Carol?”</span>
</p><!--l. 9861--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">In front of their wooden bar; horse trappings and photographs, symbols of a</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">bygone time. Escape, into that ﬂat beer of the English countryside, from nagging</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">wives or pent up lives. Birds on a wire-less.</span>
</p><!--l. 9867--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">“Fish&#x2019;n&#x2019;chips here, petal.”</span>
</p><!--l. 9869--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">The surrogate friend and replacement spouse, welcomed by the lady of the</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">house.</span>
</p><!--l. 9871--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">But they are still on call, by ear-piece or wrist-strap, or traditional bell. Can&#x2019;t close</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">the canal, shut the sluice. The high water-mark of domestic surveillance</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">pursues.</span>
</p><!--l. 9875--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Talk to the girs on the blower, if you know &#x2019;er.</span>
</p><!--l. 9877--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Never mind the Mrs., she&#x2019;s too busy talking to hers.</span>
</p><!--l. 9879--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Kids, fun to play with for a while. Quick shag and then down the pub.</span>
</p><!--l. 9881--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">To graze, on liquid haze.</span>
</p><!--l. 9883--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">It&#x2019;s our cheap, private, virtual realm.</span>
</p><!--l. 9885--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">“Snakebite, love. Shandy for our Sharon.”</span>
</p><!--l. 9890--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-23r20"></a>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-0"></a>
<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">20</span>
</p><!--l. 9892--><p class="indent" >  Jonas watches the drunken man bossing his wife and sighs on the inside. That man
might think he is in control, but one day the elastic will be stretched to its limit and
she will snap back at him with a killing force. For now the power trip of a bottle of
liquor will sustain the illusion of his dominance.
</p><!--l. 9898--><p class="indent" >  The incident brings back a suppressed unease. These domestic altercations have
been a constant companion to him too. He is no innocent.
</p><!--l. 9902--><p class="indent" >  Others in the bar are starting to stare and predictably a bouncer is making his way
through the crowded bar to eject the pair into the outside world where they will be
able to continue the abuse in the privacy of Oslo&#x2019;s mind-your-business streets. A
young girl, out for a drink with her friends, watches with a look of horror at the pair,
as though this were somehow not a common sight for this day and age. Charming that
she can retain the innocence of a sheltered upbringing, but it won&#x2019;t last long, not here
in the city.
</p><!--l. 9925--><p class="indent" >  Jonas is forty-ﬁve. He was a successful researcher, now head of the Norwegian
Research Council project group. Now he is sitting in the bar of his favourite haunt,
taking a surreptitious drink after work, and mulling over his precarious life. He has
agreed to meet Joe, his long time and close friend, who has been striving over an
application for something he feels is crucial to Norway&#x2019;s future. They never really
have time to talk these days. They have things to discuss, some papers to exchange.
Joe still likes paper.
</p><!--l. 9934--><p class="indent" >  They all come to discuss things with Jonas. For some reason his friends
see him a paragon of stability, a pillar of strength. Jonas hardly feels like
a Hercules or Goliath. Certainly his thinning hair is not the source of any
might.
</p><!--l. 9939--><p class="indent" >  Jonas Lindgren was hired by the council because he was considered to be an
eﬃcient and creative manager, with an talent for team building and getting things
done. At least, that&#x2019;s what they said at the time. That&#x2019;s what you get for being an
eco-scientist. He is also a doer.

</p><!--l. 9944--><p class="indent" >  He always was the one who sorted things out, even as a child. He is the strong silent
type, as they say: quiet but supportive. He would bolster his mother&#x2019;s doubts and resist
his father&#x2019;s belligerence. It is an attribute that people seem to value; they come to him
for advice and even just to be with him. He has often been told that he projects
a kind of calm that other&#x2019;s ﬁnd comforting, but he has never understood it
himself. No one who understood the turmoil that he suppresses could ever
say such a thing. Sometimes he feels like a priest. No, that was Joseph&#x2019;s
calling.
</p><!--l. 9954--><p class="indent" >  Jonas has had a few girlfriends, though none of them ever seemed to measure up to
that ﬁrst experience until Kaja. Women seemed two dimensional to him after
that ﬁrst experience and he kept them at arm&#x2019;s length. His wife, Kaja, was a
surprise. She was no facsimile of his earlier lovers, but she shared many of
the usual traits that he is unfortunately and fatefully attracted to. Perhaps it
is the control-freak discipline of his personality that draws him to women
that he absolutely cannot have any control over. Women with troubled or
diﬃcult demeanours seem to ﬂock to him and he falls for them again and
again.
</p><!--l. 9965--><p class="indent" >  Jonas eventually left his wife for seeing other men. She cared for him,
but more like a faithful dog than as a lover. So he bought a dog to keep him
company for a while. Then the dog left him. It ran oﬀ somewhere and was
never seen again. He imagines it dognapped and enslaved in an east European
brothel, or perhaps in the deep freeze of a Chinese restaurant. No. It isn&#x2019;t really
funny.
</p><!--l. 9981--><p class="indent" >  Jonas shakes himself out of his dreaming and sips at his beer. The little pub has a
nice bar with a high ceiling and huge pieces of art on the walls. He used
to come here with the rest of the crew of his little company, but bit by bit
he has stopped asking them and has come here to escape. It is important to
carve a place for oneself in this world of increasingly pervasive noise. If not a
silence then a freedom from the obligation to communicate. It is a restful
place but an odd place, he thinks, full of local people from every walk of
life. It has a good buzz—a background of white noise that, in spite of the
chatter, is so unspeciﬁc that it is restful. He often turns oﬀ his mobile when
he gets here or at least pretends not to notice if someone channels him a
message.
</p><!--l. 9994--><p class="indent" >  A tall black man in threadbare jeans and a scruﬀy sweater enters the bar
and edges his way towards him. Jonas&#x2019;s friend places a salutory hand on his
shoulder.
</p><!--l. 9998--><p class="indent" >  “Joseph! How are you?” he says turning to greet the tall ﬁgure, shaking his hand.
“I&#x2019;ve been saving you a place.” He moves a bag from the bar stool next to him. “What
are you having?”
</p><!--l. 10002--><p class="indent" >  “Good to see you. Jonas. You look tired though, man. They been workin&#x2019; you too
hard?”
</p><!--l. 10005--><p class="indent" >  “You read me like a book, sir.”

</p><!--l. 10007--><p class="indent" >  “Hah. What book? Not the Bible, for sure. Maybe a tabloid magazine or
something.” He laughs. “I&#x2019;ll have a light beer. It looks like I probably can&#x2019;t stay long.
I&#x2019;m on duty at the youth centre, last minute notice.” He hands Jonas a folder of papers.
“This is for you.”
</p><!--l. 10013--><p class="indent" >  Jonas smiles and gestures with his upturned hand to Joseph&#x2019;s clothing. “Ok. You
look diﬀerent. I don&#x2019;t think I have ever seen you in jeans before.”
</p><!--l. 10017--><p class="indent" >  Joseph laughs. “Do you like them? I have always wanted to own a pair of jeans.
Call it my treat to myself. I am in the mood for a little decadence.”
</p><!--l. 10021--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s very decadent.”
</p><!--l. 10023--><p class="indent" >  “A little symbol of western capitalism, manufactured in the heart of the communist
far east.”
</p><!--l. 10026--><p class="indent" >  Jonas gestures to the girl at the bar and gets him a beer.
</p><!--l. 10028--><p class="indent" >  “So you&#x2019;re still involved in the youth centre?”
</p><!--l. 10030--><p class="indent" >  Joseph nods. “Not as much as these last years. It&#x2019;s time for me to move on, but yes,
I still play a part. Take watches. You know. It&#x2019;s good to be around the kids. It keeps
them away from the river.”
</p><!--l. 10034--><p class="indent" >  “You mean away from drugs?”
</p><!--l. 10036--><p class="indent" >  “Right.”
</p><!--l. 10038--><p class="indent" >  Jonas shifts his eyebrows. “I&#x2019;d almost forgotten about that kind of thing. You know
I live such a isolated existence these days. I can&#x2019;t remember the last time I actually
walked along the river, or was oﬀered dope.” He smiles. “I should get out
more.”
</p><!--l. 10043--><p class="indent" >  “Good to hear you say that,” his friend chimes. “You might not realize it, but other
people have things call lives. If you don&#x2019;t have one you&#x2019;re missing out.” He laughs and
pats Jonas on the arm amicably. “So anyway, what do you think?” He gestures to his
jeans.
</p><!--l. 10049--><p class="indent" >  Jonas smiles quizzically. “I like it. A new style. What came over you?”
</p><!--l. 10051--><p class="indent" >  “You mean apart from a little extra money? Ah. . .here we are. . .” His beer arrives
and he pulls it from the bar and says, “Skål Jonas!”.
</p><!--l. 10055--><p class="indent" >  “Skål!”, Jonas chimes, lifting his glass, and they drink to their meeting.
</p><!--l. 10057--><p class="indent" >  “Ah that&#x2019;s good, man,” Joe says appreciatively. “Lots of things have been coming
over me lately. I have been thinking a lot about our project with the schools, talking to
the other countries participatin&#x2019;. You know. It&#x2019;s good.”
</p><!--l. 10062--><p class="indent" >  “Good?”
</p><!--l. 10064--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s good to get out for me too. I&#x2019;ve been doing more of it lately. Should have
started a long time ago.”
</p><!--l. 10067--><p class="indent" >  Jonas&#x2019;s eyes narrow with curiosity. It seems like an unusual thing for his friend to
say. Joseph has been becoming a de facto priest for the Catholic church for as
long as he can remember. Indeed, Jonas&#x2019;s scepticism for all kinds of religion
was what made them friends to begin with. That and the similarity in their
names.
</p><!--l. 10073--><p class="indent" >  “Looking for a change?”
</p><!--l. 10075--><p class="indent" >  “Of course. Things have to change.”

</p><!--l. 10077--><p class="indent" >  “Change is healthy.”
</p><!--l. 10079--><p class="indent" >  “Change is the world at work, my friend. Everything changes: seasons,
birds, bees, morals, hairstyles. . .” He smiles. “You have to let things grow.
You let the young plant the seeds and then you trust that the universe will
unfold as it should. But we older ones can take a while to reﬂect on what is
important.”
</p><!--l. 10085--><p class="indent" >  “What is that?” Jonas says jokingly. “Tell me, I really wish I knew.”
</p><!--l. 10087--><p class="indent" >  “A pair of jeans perhaps?”
</p><!--l. 10089--><p class="indent" >  They laugh.
</p><!--l. 10092--><p class="indent" >  “Seriously, Jonas. I am looking forward to the new project. I think I can do more
there. I am tired of ﬁghting ﬁres in these youth centres. I want to go to the source.” He
taps the folder of papers.
</p><!--l. 10097--><p class="indent" >  Jonas conceals his surprise with no more than a wrinkle of an eyebrow. This is not
the Joe he knew in college. That one had learned that you just don&#x2019;t ask too
many questions and you follow the so-called Good Book, or its hypocritical
soothsayers.
</p><!--l. 10102--><p class="indent" >  “I thought you were happy doing what you were doing.”
</p><!--l. 10104--><p class="indent" >  “Mmmm,” he sounds, gulping at his beer. “Well.”
</p><!--l. 10106--><p class="indent" >  Jonas snorts, waiting for his completion. This is typical of Joe to say something
provocative.
</p><!--l. 10109--><p class="indent" >  “You can reach – well, let&#x2019;s say, a dicey plateau of contentment, or you can
achieve blissful oblivion or denial. No, man. No sense in trying to hide from the
truth.”
</p><!--l. 10113--><p class="indent" >  “Joe the heretic!”.
</p><!--l. 10115--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m quoting you, Jonas!”
</p><!--l. 10117--><p class="indent" >  “Oh.” He grins.
</p><!--l. 10119--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s a random walk. Open ourselves up to the truth of our suﬀering. It&#x2019;s what life is
about. The struggle. It&#x2019;s not the arriving, but the getting there.”
</p><!--l. 10123--><p class="indent" >  Jonas grunts.
</p><!--l. 10125--><p class="indent" >  “You know it, Jonas. I think you have always understood it. But it has taken me
longer to see that you were right.”
</p><!--l. 10128--><p class="indent" >  This is a new Joe, for certain.
</p><!--l. 10130--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Quoting me at me? Did I make such an impression?</span>
</p><!--l. 10141--><p class="indent" >  “Religion&#x2019;s just an outmoded form of politics, anyway”, Jonas would grumble. ”A
way of using fear to control people because you don&#x2019;t have a decent system of law and
order. How easy to preach true morality and have it enforced on penalty of an eternity
of suﬀering.”
</p><!--l. 10148--><p class="indent" >  Joe laughed, “You know what they are calling the Christians now? Ringbearers.
You know the rings they wear now to show that they are saving their virtue for
marriage?”
</p><!--l. 10164--><p class="indent" >  “All right. Actually, I heard that there was a development in the project, a sudden
interest from the Americans? I haven&#x2019;t really had time to follow things. I have been
busy with the Fulbright stuﬀ. It was one of the contacts there that leaked it to

me.”
</p><!--l. 10169--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s right. You wouldn&#x2019;t have thought it would you? I guess they are
coming around to the idea that this is the only way that they are going to
ﬁght crime in the long term. Scrub ‘zero tolerance&#x2019;, this is deeper again.
Trouble is, they want to own it. But they want to buy us out. I&#x2019;m not sure about
it.”
</p><!--l. 10175--><p class="indent" >  It seems like a ﬂash of good news to him, but his alarm bells are ringing. The noble
initiative was a Norwegian idea, from the Peace Institute, but that is no guarantee that
it would catch on elsewhere. Every country is the same though: rising petty crime,
drug abuse, anti-social tendencies. That was why he pushed the funding of this
project. There is no respect for the power of education anymore, except perhaps
amongst a rich elite who already have one. People want everything on the cheap
now.
</p><!--l. 10184--><p class="indent" >  So why not perform a little attitude adjustment directly at lower school level, teach
kids manners and consideration again, like they used to?
</p><!--l. 10188--><p class="indent" >  “Is the interest corporate or governmental?” he asks. “Or is it Ringbearers?”
</p><!--l. 10191--><p class="indent" >  Joseph smile. “What&#x2019;s the diﬀerence?”
</p><!--l. 10193--><p class="indent" >  “Government can have some controls. If companies are involved, they will use this
as an opportunity for targeted advertising. If the church is involved, they could use it
for indoctrination.”
</p><!--l. 10199--><p class="indent" >  “Church is already involved, Jonas. Well, we&#x2019;ve made mistakes in the past. That&#x2019;s a
long story. Innocent mistakes.”
</p><!--l. 10202--><p class="indent" >  “Innocence.” He whistles playfully.
</p><!--l. 10204--><p class="indent" >  He shrugs and swallows some ale.
</p><!--l. 10206--><p class="indent" >  Jonas recalls the incident. Businesses saw it as an opportunity to use market forces
to change minds about basic attitudes. But, they also wanted to proﬁt from the results,
so marketing departments dreamt up campaigns that would make the company look
good and altruistic. Unfortunately, the marketeers were not that savvy; the cogs
turned, and before they knew what had happened, the thing had taken on a mind of its
own. They were churning out corporate advertising, trying to sell their products to
kids, rather than trying to teach them basic manners. They sort of lost the
reins.
</p><!--l. 10216--><p class="indent" >  “Well. Par for the course. Yee-hah, Doctor Frankenstein. Anyway, I think it&#x2019;s great.
The project has gained some international support now. The French have shown
interest in it. It seems that governments are ﬁnally understanding the need for
education for everyone. There is also growing interest in Asia and the far
East.”
</p><!--l. 10222--><p class="indent" >  “All true. It might actually make a diﬀerence. So, did you see our write-up in the
paper? They speak well of our achievements here in Oslo.”
</p><!--l. 10226--><p class="indent" >  “No, which paper?”
</p><!--l. 10228--><p class="indent" >  “Le Monde.”
</p><!--l. 10230--><p class="indent" >  “Not my grazing grounds, I&#x2019;m afraid.”
</p><!--l. 10232--><p class="indent" >  “I heard that the custodians of the oil fund were pressured by the industrialized

nations to put the project into action.”
</p><!--l. 10235--><p class="indent" >  “What do you mean?”
</p><!--l. 10237--><p class="indent" >  “I mean the government here. Someone had to come up with the money.”
</p><!--l. 10239--><p class="indent" >  “Well that was me,” Jonas quips. “Though it&#x2019;s true that we did get a bonus pot for
that project. I haven&#x2019;t heard anything about the reasons. I&#x2019;ve been a bit too tied up to
ﬁnd out.”
</p><!--l. 10243--><p class="indent" >  Joe nods. “You look tired, Jonas.”
</p><!--l. 10245--><p class="indent" >  “No kidding.”
</p><!--l. 10247--><p class="indent" >  “What&#x2019;s up? Something with Kaja?”
</p><!--l. 10249--><p class="indent" >  Jonas takes the name like a shot across his bow. He does not want to enter into a
discussion about his private life just now. Joseph will delve if he is given
the chance. He ﬂounders slightly and steers the conversation back. “You
know, I was talking to this kid the other day. He has just started a masters at
the University here. He actually told me that he felt school was a waste of
time.”
</p><!--l. 10256--><p class="indent" >  “Is this so unusual? I mean kids say that all the time, right?”
</p><!--l. 10258--><p class="indent" >  “Well, more than that. He said that no one had ever demanded anything of him –
never stretched him – not even once throughout his entire career. Don&#x2019;t you think it is
a little scary?”
</p><!--l. 10262--><p class="indent" >  “You are asking someone from Africa about how scary a lack of education
is?”
</p><!--l. 10264--><p class="indent" >  “I think someone predicted something like this in about 2000. I mean,
that the world has been getting dumber for some time. They claimed that it
is part of the convenience society. There was some research done. I forget
where. In the end we are so lazy that we are helpless. It&#x2019;s one of the Doomsday
scenarios.”
</p><!--l. 10270--><p class="indent" >  Joseph raised his glass. “And the great wheel keeps on turning. I think that&#x2019;s a cue
for a drink. Here&#x2019;s to our programme!”
</p><!--l. 10273--><p class="indent" >  They drink.
</p><!--l. 10275--><p class="indent" >  “By the way,” Jonas recalls. “Do you remember a Professor Egeland? He taught
some of the early science courses?”
</p><!--l. 10278--><p class="indent" >  “Uh huh.”
</p><!--l. 10280--><p class="indent" >  “He just quit the university after thirty years to become a writer.”
</p><!--l. 10282--><p class="indent" >  “Good for him.”
</p><!--l. 10284--><p class="indent" >  “No, he is very bitter about it. Disillusioned by the Department of Education and its
budget-rent-a-prof attitude to education. He told me that there is no sense in banging
your head against the wall, when all they want is cheap feel-good recipes that they can
follow without question.”
</p><!--l. 10291--><p class="indent" >  “I. . .”
</p><!--l. 10293--><p class="indent" >  “Jonas Lindgren! Is that you?!” Something punches him amicably on the arm. A
short stocky man with a fat face appears beside him, closer than Jonas would prefer.
“Leif Erik Larsen. We met at the conference on ecological development last
April?”

</p><!--l. 10298--><p class="indent" >  Jonas glances helplessly at Joseph. “How do you do.” He shakes his hand. “Do you
come here often?”
</p><!--l. 10301--><p class="indent" >  “No. not really. You know I have been trying to contact you for several days. You
are a hard man to reach.”
</p><!--l. 10304--><p class="indent" >  “Uh, yes. I am very busy.” With everything except my job, he thinks.
</p><!--l. 10306--><p class="indent" >  “Well, this is a lucky coincidence. I don&#x2019;t mean to interrupt you gents.”
</p><!--l. 10309--><p class="indent" >  “Well, I . . .”
</p><!--l. 10311--><p class="indent" >  “I won&#x2019;t take up much of your time. This is important and I have been calling your
number for a while.”
</p><!--l. 10314--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m not very well prepared. It might be better if you called me tomorrow.”
</p><!--l. 10316--><p class="indent" >  “Oh this won&#x2019;t take a moment.”
</p><!--l. 10318--><p class="indent" >  Jonas squirms, looking to Joe for backup, but he is looking restless.
</p><!--l. 10320--><p class="indent" >  “Look, I have to go, Jonas,” Joe says. “Let&#x2019;s do this again soon.”
</p><!--l. 10322--><p class="indent" >  “Eh . . . Joe. Look. Never mind. All right. Sorry about this.”
</p><!--l. 10324--><p class="indent" >  “No, really. I should go anyway.”
</p><!--l. 10326--><p class="indent" >  The man looks modestly apologetic. “Look, I don&#x2019;t mean to intrude or break
anything up here. . .”
</p><!--l. 10329--><p class="indent" >  “I have to go anyway. Let me know what you think, Jonas.” He gestures to the
papers he brought.
</p><!--l. 10332--><p class="indent" >  Joseph leaves.
</p><!--l. 10334--><p class="indent" >  “So Mr. Lindgren, you might remember, I am from the ministry of foreign aﬀairs.
You know that we&#x2019;ve been studying the famine in Eastern Africa. We are hoping that
you will fund a study that will help our budget commitment to the famine
relief.”
</p><!--l. 10339--><p class="indent" >  Jonas frowns. “Well, you know the budget has been ﬁnalized now and the funding
assignments have pretty much already been decided.”
</p><!--l. 10342--><p class="indent" >  “Well, we are hoping that you will make an exception in this crisis.”
</p><!--l. 10345--><p class="indent" >  It is true, he knows: this is the ﬁrst major famine in years. The newspapers have
been oﬀering their usual stew of inﬂamed hearsay, hammered to the point of a double
edged sword. Pleading eyes and desperate faces, chosen with editorial care, adorn the
covers of newspapers and magazines to maximize the world&#x2019;s guilt for allowing this
natural disaster to occur.
</p><!--l. 10352--><p class="indent" >  “Other nations are making statements of support, and long term commitments to
address the climate issues. We feel we should do the same.”
</p><!--l. 10355--><p class="indent" >  “But surely that is not a matter for a research council?”
</p><!--l. 10357--><p class="indent" >  “The ministry feels it is: it would send a good signal to be seen to be investing in
long term solutions, rather than just direct aid. You can&#x2019;t just put a plaster on the
future!”
</p><!--l. 10361--><p class="indent" >  Nice slogan, but guilt is not an emotion that Jonas has ever felt compelled to
exhibit. The eyes of Europe are on this disaster and the cries for help and being
answered with nominal budget reallocations.
</p><!--l. 10366--><p class="indent" >  “I think my job is to fund progress not famine relief.”

</p><!--l. 10368--><p class="indent" >  This pipsqueak civil servant is asking him to give up his hard won pittance for
research to cover another budget with more political feel-good ﬂoss? The sums of
money he has at his disposition are hardly signiﬁcant for something like
this.
</p><!--l. 10373--><p class="indent" >  “But you know what they say – no more than four meals from anarchy.”
</p><!--l. 10375--><p class="indent" >  “Or four extra meals to libertarianism.”
</p><!--l. 10377--><p class="indent" >  He sends him an uncomprehending stare.
</p><!--l. 10379--><p class="indent" >  “I feel conﬁdent that we can work out an arrangement. This will mean a lot to
Norway&#x2019;s image as a global player. It will make us practically an economic
superpower, compared to other countries.”
</p><!--l. 10383--><p class="indent" >  Jonas hides his reaction by emptying his glass of beer.
</p><!--l. 10385--><p class="indent" >  “So I&#x2019;ll come by at the end of the week to make the arrangements then.” It was not
a question.
</p><!--l. 10388--><p class="indent" >  “Well, I am going to be pretty busy with the details of the collaborative research
conference. And the Research Open Day is coming up with the Colleges and
Universities.”
</p><!--l. 10392--><p class="indent" >  “We have an obligation to help. I know you&#x2019;ll come around.”
</p><!--l. 10394--><p class="indent" >  Something in his tone tells Jonas that the matter has already been decided. Now he
will leave and everything will be as he has implied. Jonas feels the relief of a
drowning man who knows that it is time to accept his fate.
</p><!--l. 10399--><p class="indent" >  “I suppose we can look at the budgets again.”
</p><!--l. 10401--><p class="indent" >  Why couldn&#x2019;t Joe have stayed put? Christ. He came here to get away from it all.
Oslo is too small, he thinks.
</p><!--l. 10404--><p class="indent" >  What is the point of a pub if you can&#x2019;t escape from your day job? And how do you
get away from the ball and chain that hangs on your wrist? People can&#x2019;t blow smoke
in each others&#x2019; faces anymore, but at least they can zone out and pretend to be talking
to someone else if they don&#x2019;t like their company. We&#x2019;re all sitting here not sure
whether we want to meet each other or hide from each other. Everyone has their own
story.
</p><!--l. 10412--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">So what is mine?</span>
</p><!--l. 10414--><p class="indent" >  And look at the loser on the end of the long bar. Who is that sad old fuck? He sits in
the bar every night and never says a word, drinking his beer, all by himself. Then he
staggers home drunk to whatever awaits him. Is it an unhappy home? Or maybe no
home at all?
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 10419--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 10420--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 10423--><p class="indent" >  Jonas feels a rhythmical pulsing in the arm of his sweater. Obviously he forgot to
switch oﬀ his mobile today. He is using his bracelet watch today as his organizer. He
glances brieﬂy at it. It&#x2019;s ﬂashing him an E-mail. He ought to ignore it but, like most

people, he can&#x2019;t quite free himself from its charms. There is a message from John, the
English intern at the oﬃce. They talked about going to the gym together, but Jonas
feigned other plans.
</p><!--l. 10443--><p class="indent" >  He leaves the bar and steps out into the wintery darkness. The time is about 20:00,
but you can never quite tell in January. With only a few hours of daylight, and the
cloud-cover to provide a roof for the city&#x2019;s electrical lighting, it is diﬃcult to tell one
time from another. He trudges up the narrow street looking as he always does at
the buildings along the way: no two of them alike, a variety of architectural
styles from the last century that pepper Oslo with the good the bad and the
ugly. Cars are parked at every place of both sides of the road of this back
street. He squeezes through a gap, climbing over the mound of cleared snow
to cross the street where he can get oﬀ the more populated main street of
Grünerløkka.
</p><!--l. 10455--><p class="indent" >  Jonas pauses. Snow is falling as he trudges methodically up the slight incline by the
old brewery. It is much milder suddenly and the calm that only accompanies falling
snow seems to envelop the street. A slight rumble glides past him—a car. He stops to
admire its grace in this quiet street. How paradoxical that the archetypal opposite of
nature, the car, could move so silently through it, almost respectfully sliding
through the ﬂakes with only the slightest crackle from the studded tires. It is a
beautiful sight. A silver bullet moving in slow motion through nature&#x2019;s song of
peace.
</p><!--l. 10466--><p class="indent" >  He continues his meager climb up to the top of the hill, glancing down at the
waterfall as he walks on by. It has frozen over in the last day or two. The weather
is getting stranger by the year, it seems. Warm. Cold. Warm. Cold. Snow.
Rain. Sun. Gone are the days when one knew roughly when winter would
start.
</p><!--l. 10472--><p class="indent" >  Back in the 1950s, John Von Neumann dreamed that we would be able to control
the weather, using computers to make accurate predictions, but even he probably
realized that there was only a slim chance of being able to describe it accurately
enough. Managing it is something else altogether; for that you would need a machine
at least as complicated as nature itself, in which case it would just be a storm of its
own.
</p><!--l. 10479--><p class="indent" >  Jonas stops and looks around. Behind him, a few feet away, tree bark shatters into
dust, leaving a ﬂaky hole in the side of the old tree. At ﬁrst he looks away, not
realizing what has happened. Then, too incredulous to believe it, he simply stands and
stares.
</p><!--l. 10484--><p class="indent" >  His mobile rings. He taps the control on his watch. ”Hello?”
</p><!--l. 10487--><p class="indent" >  “Jonas, it&#x2019;s me. Can I come over?”
</p><!--l. 10489--><p class="indent" >  It&#x2019;s Kaja.
</p><!--l. 10491--><p class="indent" >  “Not really, I&#x2019;m not home.” He moves closer to the tree to look at the place where
the shot struck it.
</p><!--l. 10494--><p class="indent" >  “I need to talk to you,” she says. She sounds miserable, but that is normal; it does
not necessarily mean that she is. She is used to getting her way, by indulging her

emotions at any cost to those around her.
</p><!--l. 10499--><p class="indent" >  He sighs. “I&#x2019;ll call you when I get home,” he lies. “I&#x2019;m kind of busy right
now.”
</p><!--l. 10502--><p class="indent" >  He hangs up. The mobile rings again. Impatiently, “Yes?”
</p><!--l. 10505--><p class="indent" >  This time there is no voice, just a few moments of silence and the connection is
broken. His mobile signals that a ﬁle has been uploaded, but the information about the
ﬁle is empty. Then the mobile screen goes dark and starts the reboot.
</p><!--l. 10510--><p class="indent" >  “What the..?” For a moment there is a temptation to destroy the peaceful falling of
the snowﬂakes. It is a long time since his mobile actually crashed. But he is tired and
just stuﬀs the little device into his pocket.
</p><!--l. 10522--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-24r21"></a>
<a 
