</p><!--l. 11111--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Attention Mr. Al Arrabi on ﬂight AE457 to London, please contact information</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">immediately. Thank you.</span>
</p><!--l. 11114--><p class="indent" >  Den fumes at the stupidity of it all. A woman practically walks into him.
Her vision is focused on an image behind her glasses, not on where she is
going.
</p><!--l. 11118--><p class="indent" >  Every year now, more and more people are killed in traﬃc because they were
looking elsewhere. People in cars and on foot, each of them believing that their
remote activities were more important than their physical well-being. Each
of them delegating the responsibility for their welfare to the world around
them.
</p><!--l. 11124--><p class="indent" >  Den sees that billboard again, the same one he saw in San Diego, but running in real
time now. He is not aware of any subliminal messages but he knows they are there,
and they are telling him he doesn&#x2019;t like this guy much, so maybe he deserved it after
all.
