</p><!--l. 11376--><p class="indent" >  The sudden realization that the jarring ring entering his ears is not part of his dream,
ruptures a soothing fantasia on his life, and an uncomfortable angst explodes into his
consciousness. Jonas forces movement into his arm to kill the alarm clock, before
realizing that it is not his programmed wakeup call that is assailing him. The mobile
handset is on the table beside his bed.
</p><!--l. 11383--><p class="indent" >  Instinct triumphs over slower faculties; he grabs the device and opens the
line.
</p><!--l. 11386--><p class="indent" >  “Ja?” Croak.
</p><!--l. 11388--><p class="indent" >  “Jonas? It&#x2019;s me.”
</p><!--l. 11390--><p class="indent" >  “Kaja? Jesus, what time is it?” He tries to see the clock, but he parked a glass of
water in front of the display last night.
</p><!--l. 11393--><p class="indent" >  “Early. I have to take Martin to the doctors. I think he is sick. Everything is going
wrong. I just needed to hear your voice.”
</p><!--l. 11397--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Fine</span>, he thinks. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I am still on your leash.</span>
</p><!--l. 11399--><p class="indent" >  He rolls over onto his side to stop himself falling asleep again and looks at the
clock. It is 7:30 but it seems dark. The nights are getting darker quickly now. It&#x2019;s
about time he got up anyway.
</p><!--l. 11403--><p class="indent" >  “What&#x2019;s wrong?”
</p><!--l. 11405--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t know. He&#x2019;s talking about a sore throat and he&#x2019;s got the shivers. Do you
think it could be inﬂuenza?”
</p><!--l. 11408--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t think the ﬂu usually shows up this early, unless it&#x2019;s from last year. Could be
anything.”
</p><!--l. 11411--><p class="indent" >  “But it could be serious.”
</p><!--l. 11413--><p class="indent" >  “Look, practically half the illnesses in the book start like that. It&#x2019;s probably just
some virus thing. He&#x2019;ll enjoy being out of school for a couple of days.”
</p><!--l. 11417--><p class="indent" >  “Do you think you could pick him up? I mean take him to the doctor?”
</p><!--l. 11420--><p class="indent" >  “Are you sure he needs a doctor?”
</p><!--l. 11422--><p class="indent" >  “He&#x2019;s a child, Jonas!”

</p><!--l. 11424--><p class="indent" >  He groans. Best not to get into an argument this early. “Well, I don&#x2019;t think I can
come over until late this afternoon. I have meetings all morning.”
</p><!--l. 11428--><p class="indent" >  “Jonas, you spend half the day walking around the city. You don&#x2019;t need to be in
your oﬃce.”
</p><!--l. 11431--><p class="indent" >  “Kaja,. . .”
</p><!--l. 11433--><p class="indent" >  “He&#x2019;s your son, Jonas.”
</p><!--l. 11435--><p class="indent" >  He lets his head fall into the pillow and suppresses a sigh. “I could pick him up
around one. . .”
</p><!--l. 11438--><p class="indent" >  “But what am I going to to with him? I can&#x2019;t stay at home. I have to work. I have to
be where I have to be.”
</p><!--l. 11441--><p class="indent" >  “Uh huh..” Bend and raise the knees. Breath. Oxygenation of key faculties. “Well,
take him with you to work.”
</p><!--l. 11444--><p class="indent" >  “How can I do that? He can&#x2019;t sit there in the shop, in a draft, waiting for
you.”
</p><!--l. 11447--><p class="indent" >  “What about you mother?”
</p><!--l. 11449--><p class="indent" >  “You&#x2019;re his dad, Jonas. Why can&#x2019;t you do something for him for once? It isn&#x2019;t as if I
ask you to do something very often, is it? If this were one of those bloody robots you
send to Mars or whatever you do, you would be over there in ﬂash, but if I ask you to
do one little thing you can&#x2019;t.”
</p><!--l. 11455--><p class="indent" >  He closes his eyes, realizing that there is no way out of this now. “All right?”
</p><!--l. 11458--><p class="indent" >  “What? If you.. what?”
</p><!--l. 11460--><p class="indent" >  “I said yes. Fine. Take him with you and I&#x2019;ll pick him up as soon as I can. What
time are you starting?”
</p><!--l. 11463--><p class="indent" >  She hesitates. “Eight.”
</p><!--l. 11465--><p class="indent" >  Like hell, he thinks. When were you ever on time? “Well it will probably take me
an hour to get there. When does he have to be at the doctor&#x2019;s?”
</p><!--l. 11468--><p class="indent" >  “I haven&#x2019;t made any appointment.”
</p><!--l. 11470--><p class="indent" >  Of course not. The whole thing is just a bluﬀ, a way of making him jump through
hoops. “Fine. Expect me in an hour.” He hangs up.
</p>
