</p><!--l. 13283--><p class="indent" >  “Have you ever looked at an entirely familiar object and suddenly it seems
completely foreign, as though you have suddenly been thrust into some parallel
universe where nothing is quite right.”
</p><!--l. 13288--><p class="indent" >  A young man ﬂounders at the coﬀee unit of the meeting room, talking a little louder
than would be incidental, private muttering.
</p><!--l. 13291--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m standing here like an idiot, holding this spoon and wondering what the hell
I&#x2019;m supposed to be doing with it. It is just a piece of metal! How does it
work?”
</p><!--l. 13295--><p class="indent" >  Bishop walks past and claps him on the shoulder.
</p><!--l. 13297--><p class="indent" >  “A new graduate like you should be able to ﬁgure it out in no time.”
</p><!--l. 13300--><p class="indent" >  He winks at Preeta who is hanging as casually as she can while the members of the
little group arrange for their home comforts.
</p><!--l. 13303--><p class="indent" >  Someone else, who looks like a computer geek, beams at him and says:
“You have to realize the spoon is not a spoon! Only when you know this . .
.”
</p><!--l. 13307--><p class="indent" >  “Thank you, Tom!” He ﬂashes a burst of feigned annoyance.
</p><!--l. 13309--><p class="indent" >  The warm fruity smell of rose-hip tea explodes into the room from the hot water
boiler and makes her suddenly thirsty.
</p><!--l. 13312--><p class="indent" >  “Tea?” someone asks her.
</p><!--l. 13314--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, please.”
</p><!--l. 13316--><p class="indent" >  The young man looks at her peculiarly. “You don&#x2019;t need to say please here,” he
laughs,
</p><!--l. 13319--><p class="indent" >  “Sorry.”
</p><!--l. 13321--><p class="indent" >  “No, no, never mind. You want rose hip or Earl Grey?”
</p><!--l. 13323--><p class="indent" >  “Ehhm. Do you have Assam?” she replies.
</p><!--l. 13325--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 13327--><p class="indent" >  “Tea?”
</p><!--l. 13329--><p class="indent" >  “Oh, is that some kind of special tea? We only have ordinary Earl Grey.”

</p><!--l. 13331--><p class="indent" >  Her face cannot conceal its scepticism. “Earl Grey is ordinary?”
</p><!--l. 13333--><p class="indent" >  “Isn&#x2019;t it?”
</p><!--l. 13335--><p class="indent" >  “Could I have some water?”
</p><!--l. 13337--><p class="indent" >  “Cold water and plastic cups over there. . .” he points to a dispenser.
</p><!--l. 13339--><p class="indent" >  “No, I mean hot water. . .”
</p><!--l. 13341--><p class="indent" >  “Suit yourself. I thought you wanted tea.”
</p><!--l. 13343--><p class="indent" >  Bishop&#x2019;s voice cuts across the gathering chatter. “All right everyone, let&#x2019;s take a
pew and get started.”
</p><!--l. 13346--><p class="indent" >  Shuﬄing bodies accrete at the oval table in the little meeting room, birch-wood
with woven cushions. Very Scandinavian. Preeta is surprised that, so deep into the
heart of the central police authority, no one is wearing a uniform. Correction, one
uniform enters, nodding a greeting.
</p><!--l. 13351--><p class="indent" >  Bishop clasps his hands at the head of the oval.
</p><!--l. 13353--><p class="indent" >  “All right, Good Morning. Most of you know Preeta by now. For those of you who
don&#x2019;t, she has been here for a few days now and will stay for at least a few weeks. We
have ‘borrowed her&#x2019; from the game&#x2019;s outsourced diagnostic team in Malaysia.
Welcome, Preeta, to our little working group.”
</p><!--l. 13359--><p class="indent" >  A wave of nods and acknowledgements cycles around the table. She nods
reservedly back.
</p><!--l. 13362--><p class="indent" >  The faces span several generations, she observes. She is amongst the youngest of
the group, but two other faces also seem young: one male, one female.
</p><!--l. 13366--><p class="indent" >  “What we do here is varied, but important.”
</p><!--l. 13368--><p class="indent" >  “What we do is to drink coﬀee and read the papers,” someone says.
</p><!--l. 13370--><p class="indent" >  “And we call ourselves a think-tank,” someone else laughs.
</p><!--l. 13372--><p class="indent" >  “Sometimes we play games.”
</p><!--l. 13374--><p class="indent" >  There is laughter around the table, more like sniggering.
</p><!--l. 13376--><p class="indent" >  “All right,” Bishop says, patiently. “Our primary mandate is to ensure that the
police forces of the world all have a job in the next ten years. It&#x2019;s getting harder for
everyone to enforce laws, society is changing, and we have been assembled to look at
strategies for the future of policing. In that connection, we are studying things like the
psychological warfare techniques being used by the United States in their virtual
reality game.”
</p><!--l. 13384--><p class="indent" >  “Batman to the rescue.”
</p><!--l. 13386--><p class="indent" >  “So why don&#x2019;t we go around the table and say who we are and what we do?
Jonathan, do you want to start?”
</p><!--l. 13390--><p class="indent" >  Jonathan, a medium height, medium build, medium blond man, somewhere
between twenty-ﬁve and thirty years old. “Uhm. Okay. I am Jonathan Moen. I&#x2019;ve
been here for about six months. Finished Police College and have a degree in
computational sociology. I am working on the forensic patterns in VR sims.” He
shrugs and looks to the next man.
</p><!--l. 13396--><p class="indent" >  “Jonathan comes to us with an excellent background from academia. He has been
pretty central to our eﬀorts to integrate proactive campaigns into policing. We are
lucky to have people with top schooling among us.”

</p><!--l. 13400--><p class="indent" >  Jonathan keeps a stoney face, but Preeta sees from his eye movements that he is
blushing on the inside.
</p><!--l. 13403--><p class="indent" >  “Ivar?”
</p><!--l. 13405--><p class="indent" >  “Ivar Jensen. I am doing research on the propaganda engine in the game. I guess
we&#x2019;ll have a lot to talk about.” He is ﬂabby, overweight.
</p><!--l. 13408--><p class="indent" >  Preeta nods a smile.
</p><!--l. 13410--><p class="indent" >  “Was that it? Ivar?” The young woman at the table laughs in disbelief.
</p><!--l. 13412--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m a man of few words.”
</p><!--l. 13414--><p class="indent" >  “And few manners”
</p><!--l. 13416--><p class="indent" >  “You&#x2019;re welcome!”
</p><!--l. 13418--><p class="indent" >  “Keep going,” Bishop injects with studied patience.
</p><!--l. 13420--><p class="indent" >  “Hi I am Nina. Not The Nina. . .”
</p><!--l. 13422--><p class="indent" >  The others laugh.
</p><!--l. 13424--><p class="indent" >  Jonathan explains: “As in Nina Hagen.”
</p><!--l. 13426--><p class="indent" >  “Our glorious leader, the ice queen.”
</p><!--l. 13428--><p class="indent" >  “Nina! Pretty ballerina!”
</p><!--l. 13430--><p class="indent" >  “She is the head of our international police division.”
</p><!--l. 13432--><p class="indent" >  “No that is not me. I am just Nina. I&#x2019;m a masters student at Police College. Just
starting really. I am going to be studying the use of symbolism in the visual slogans
and imagery used in electronic gaming. I&#x2019;m hoping to ﬁnd out how eﬀective the
diﬀerent images are, compared to a study that was made ten yeas ago. The idea is to
see how much society has changed.”
</p><!--l. 13439--><p class="indent" >  Preeta chances a comment. “You mean here in Norway?”
</p><!--l. 13441--><p class="indent" >  The question is repeated in expectant looks from the table.
</p><!--l. 13443--><p class="indent" >  “We haven&#x2019;t ﬁgured that out yet,” she replies. “It depends where we can get data
from. The earlier study we have is from the United Kingdom. It would be
best to repeat it in the same place. If not it will have to be a comparative
study,”
</p><!--l. 13448--><p class="indent" >  Preeta nods in interest. Like everyone else here, she would like to know the
answer.
</p><!--l. 13451--><p class="indent" >  The door opens and a youngish man with short reddish hair and heavy outdoor
clothing bustles in. Eyes turn to inspect his non-descript form. He is neither tidy nor
shabby, but somehow he looks a mess. The next one around the table is wondering
whether the baton has been passed.
</p><!--l. 13457--><p class="indent" >  “Sorry I&#x2019;m late,” he says.
</p><!--l. 13459--><p class="indent" >  “Take a seat and you can join the parade,” Bishop pipes. “We are just going around
the table introducing ourselves. And, as long as you&#x2019;re here, it looks like its your
turn.”
</p><!--l. 13463--><p class="indent" >  Like a deer caught in the headlights, Dermot displays panic and disorientation for a
second, then: “Uh okay.”
</p><!--l. 13466--><p class="indent" >  Dermot seats himself and pulls his shoulder back oﬀ his bulky anorak, taking up
more space and time than he needs to. He does not unzip the bulky jacket, but looks
around the table. “I&#x2019;m Dermot,” he says. He sits there like a polar explorer who just

dropped in for tea.
</p><!--l. 13471--><p class="indent" >  The others snigger. “Mr. Pizza.”
</p><!--l. 13473--><p class="indent" >  Bishop remarks, “Dermot is on loan to us from the big gaming company, here in
Oslo. He is one of the game experts. You two will have a bit in common. He is the one
who implemented your algorithm for us, and we are bringing him into the fold in our
research.”
</p><!--l. 13478--><p class="indent" >  Dermot looks bemused, or perhaps simply uneasy at being the centre of
attention.
</p><!--l. 13481--><p class="indent" >  “Is this. . .?”
</p><!--l. 13483--><p class="indent" >  “This is Preeta Dhawan, from the outsourcing in Malaysia.”
</p><!--l. 13485--><p class="indent" >  “Hello,” he tries.
</p><!--l. 13487--><p class="indent" >  “Hello.”
</p><!--l. 13489--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;ve – eh, heard you were coming. . .eh. . .”
</p><!--l. 13491--><p class="indent" >  “All right, let&#x2019;s keep going.”
</p><!--l. 13493--><p class="indent" >  “Keep going.”
</p><!--l. 13495--><p class="indent" >  Next man, an older greying man with sun-damaged skin; the only man with a
uniform: “My name is Art. Art Haugen. I am the liason with the foot-soldiers in the
ﬁeld. My job is to make sure these thinkers keep their feet on the ground and deliver
solutions to the men and women in blue.”
</p><!--l. 13501--><p class="indent" >  “Art is an important member of the group. . .”
</p><!--l. 13503--><p class="indent" >  “Well, I&#x2019;m not really a part of the group, but I can still get past the bouncers. .
.”
</p><!--l. 13505--><p class="indent" >  “We need people to keep us in touch, and to take us out into the ﬁeld. Art can call
upon us to help with speciﬁc cases if the regular police need assistance. It doesn&#x2019;t
happen too often, but sometimes. . .”
</p><!--l. 13509--><p class="indent" >  Art interrupts: “Ed, can I just ask a practical detail?”
</p><!--l. 13511--><p class="indent" >  “Go ahead.”
</p><!--l. 13513--><p class="indent" >  “If Preeta is going to be working here temporarily, what security clearance is she
going to have? We need to ﬁgure this out if we are going to be involving her with
operations.”
</p><!--l. 13517--><p class="indent" >  Preeta&#x2019;s eyes morph, visibly increasing in their intensity.
</p><!--l. 13519--><p class="indent" >  “We&#x2019;ll be discussing that later. Essentially, she will have full clearance for game
related projects. She already knows as much as we do. Anything else would be
senseless.”
</p><!--l. 13523--><p class="indent" >  “All right.”
</p><!--l. 13525--><p class="indent" >  Talking in general, “Preeta has been working for the main outsource diagnostic ﬁrm
in Malaysia. She also happens to be an expert on the new tools that I presented to you
last month. We have been sharing notes with her for some time, in the developers&#x2019;
fora. We have also been talking about bringing her to the U.S. We&#x2019;re arranging cover
at Dermot&#x2019;s ﬁrm.”
</p><!--l. 13532--><p class="indent" >  “That doesn&#x2019;t sound like a good idea.”
</p><!--l. 13534--><p class="indent" >  “What happened now was that she was identiﬁed as a target and we had to evacuate
her. The mob has started moving in on the game since the hoo-hah in the press about it

recently. They&#x2019;ve been falling behind and they have apparently identiﬁed Asia as
the place to start getting their foot in the door. Preeta thinks they have been
staking out her company for some time, and that they have singled her out for
coercion, for whatever reason. She is a key diagnostician, young, single, female. .
.”
</p><!--l. 13542--><p class="indent" >  “So what happens now?”
</p><!--l. 13544--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah, won&#x2019;t they simply move on to someone else?”
</p><!--l. 13546--><p class="indent" >  Preeta feels a cold dagger slice through her stomach.
</p><!--l. 13548--><p class="indent" >  “Probably, but they won&#x2019;t get as far as fast without Preeta. That gives us a chance to
. . . nip this in the bud, before it gets out of hand. I&#x2019;ve already been in touch with
Interpol in Asia. We are working together on this, and they are looking over Preeta&#x2019;s
company.”
</p><!--l. 13553--><p class="indent" >  “Stake out.”
</p><!--l. 13555--><p class="indent" >  “Nikita.”
</p><!--l. 13557--><p class="indent" >  Preeta tries to smile, though the humour is not really her cup of rose-hip tea. They
seem a little like children to her, except for Bishop. He seems like a person of
authority—not forced authority, like a military man, but a man of natural authority. He
is someone she can respect. Then there is the late-comer, who is just quiet. He seems
like someone she could be around.
</p><!--l. 13564--><p class="indent" >  “So, let&#x2019;s ﬁnish the introductions. Alex?”
</p><!--l. 13566--><p class="indent" >  The last, stocky young man stammers his reply. “Alexander. Alex. Flow
analyst.”
</p><!--l. 13568--><p class="indent" >  “Meaning that this young man is an intelligence coordinator. He works partly with
the defence department. Part of our ﬁnding comes from them.”
</p><!--l. 13571--><p class="indent" >  “I. . .I. . .just want to say welcome,” he adds. “I think we are lucky to have you. I
know that Preeta is actually one of the best people in sim diagnosis.”
</p><!--l. 13574--><p class="indent" >  “Thank you very much, you are very kind. . .”
</p><!--l. 13576--><p class="indent" >  “Preeta, you have to learn one thing. We don&#x2019;t say thank you all the time here. .
.”
</p><!--l. 13578--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s enough,” Bishop jabs. “It&#x2019;s about time we had some manners in here. Let
me apologize for our rudeness.”
</p><!--l. 13581--><p class="indent" >  She shakes her head, trying to tuck her chin and recede back into her long dark
hair.
</p><!--l. 13584--><p class="indent" >  “So tell us, do people in Malaysia blame America for what is going on?”
</p><!--l. 13586--><p class="indent" >  “Ivar, do you have to. . ..”
</p><!--l. 13588--><p class="indent" >  “No, it&#x2019;s a fair question. It&#x2019;s relevant. . .”
</p><!--l. 13590--><p class="indent" >  “Well, the question is a loaded question. How can you answer it now without either
being defensive or feeling obligated to agree?”
</p><!--l. 13593--><p class="indent" >  “Obliged to agree.”
</p><!--l. 13595--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s what I said.”
</p><!--l. 13597--><p class="indent" >  “You said obligated.”
</p><!--l. 13599--><p class="indent" >  “So, what&#x2019;s your point?”
</p><!--l. 13601--><p class="indent" >  “Boys! Are you going to let her answer? If you ask a question. . .”

</p><!--l. 13603--><p class="indent" >  “Would you like to answer, Preeta. . .?”
</p><!--l. 13605--><p class="indent" >  Her face leaks a betrayal of indecision and reticence. “I am not sure I know what
you are asking.”
</p><!--l. 13608--><p class="indent" >  “America is a superpower. They have been driving this technological, every
conglomerate for itself politics for some time. They have been telling us all about
morality and then they forgot to observe it themselves.”
</p><!--l. 13612--><p class="indent" >  “Well. Her generation has seen it coming for some time,” Bishop adds. “The
Americans are the last remaining superpower <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">because </span>they won a propaganda war, not
because they were morally superior. Now other countries have been following
suit. Today it is candid information warfare. Everything happens behind the
scenes.”
</p><!--l. 13618--><p class="indent" >  “American is not the place where society is breaking up as much as in other place,”
Preeta inserts, more conﬁdently now. “It is here and in Japan, Korea, Russia and the
former soviet states – where people are reserved. That is where the mobile gaming has
made people isolate themselves.”
</p><!--l. 13624--><p class="indent" >  “She&#x2019;s right. America is suﬀering civil disorder because of the formation of
gangs and mobs. Its about challenging the government, not about retreating
from it. If there&#x2019;s one thing the Americans are good at it&#x2019;s talking to each
other.”
</p><!--l. 13629--><p class="indent" >  “So we are to blame for the collapse of society. That&#x2019;s a comforting thought.”
</p><!--l. 13631--><p class="indent" >  “What makes you think we ever had one?” Dermot quips.
</p><!--l. 13633--><p class="indent" >  “But it&#x2019;s still the same thing. De-centralization of power is the result, and it comes
about because people feel empowered by all these devices that allow them to
manipulate pretty much anything they want from wherever they are. . . What do you
need authority for?”
</p><!--l. 13638--><p class="indent" >  “All right, let&#x2019;s focus a minute,” Bishop sounds. “The aim of this meeting was to let
us all meet one another and to maybe hear some ideas about the problems that we are
seeing, and how we are going to make use of Preeta&#x2019;s skills while she is
here.”
</p><!--l. 13643--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, down to business.”
</p><!--l. 13645--><p class="indent" >  “Good. Our group&#x2019;s long term goal is to look at ways of restoring a respect for law
and order by using the same techniques for suggestion as the gaming engine. We are
trying to sell people the idea of society again. Buy back what gave you what you now
have.”
</p><!--l. 13650--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah, it&#x2019;s like saving the rain forests.”
</p><!--l. 13652--><p class="indent" >  “But Preeta, here, has been telling me for some time that the methods used in the
game are doomed to failure. Can you tell us a little more?”
</p><!--l. 13655--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;ll try. . .”
</p><!--l. 13657--><p class="indent" >  Ivar interjects: “We are looking for ways of doing two things: counter-propaganda
for law enforcement. Ways of tracing cause and eﬀect for forensic analysis.”
</p><!--l. 13661--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, we are working with a group in Spain that has some special expertise there.
We have seen that it is possible to disrupt the directed messages in the game
so that they are eﬀectively useless. Someone has been doing it a lot lately.

We are not sure whether they are doing it on purpose, or whether it is an
accident.”
</p><!--l. 13667--><p class="indent" >  “It doesn&#x2019;t matter,” Preeta says. “It will happen anyway.”
</p><!--l. 13669--><p class="indent" >  The others look at her, in surprise.
</p><!--l. 13671--><p class="indent" >  “Interesting that you say that. I know that you have been talking about this for some
time. But for us, this is a new idea.”
</p><!--l. 13675--><p class="indent" >  “We just mentioned it the other day.”
</p><!--l. 13677--><p class="indent" >  “The messages cannot work because there are just too many of them. Not only is it
too hard to absorb all of the messages, the software has a ﬂaw in it&#x2019; which limits the
amount of hashing space for template expansion.”
</p><!--l. 13681--><p class="indent" >  “Gesundheit!”
</p><!--l. 13683--><p class="indent" >  “Uhm. If you are not a programmer, it has to do with the way the directed messages
are rendered in the backgrounds and surfaces. Some of the messages are crashing or
getting mixed up because of the way the authorization checks are implemented. .
.”
</p><!--l. 13688--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;ve seen that,” Dermot says.
</p><!--l. 13690--><p class="indent" >  “And you probably know what she&#x2019;s talking about too.”
</p><!--l. 13692--><p class="indent" >  “Yes I do.”
</p><!--l. 13694--><p class="indent" >  She experiences a glow of satisfaction at having marked her territory.
</p><!--l. 13696--><p class="indent" >  She continues. “The game designers have tried to add the authorization stuﬀ in at a
level where they can use it to essentially block any messages they don&#x2019;t want to get
through and pass ones that they do, but the lack of hashing space means that the
messages are just getting mixed up or corrupted because of this intervention. They are
colliding.”
</p><!--l. 13702--><p class="indent" >  “Can&#x2019;t they just increase the space?”
</p><!--l. 13704--><p class="indent" >  She shakes her head. “It&#x2019;s not that simple. It has knock-on consequences. They have
essentially reached a limit in the current resources. It will take a long time to
ﬁx.”
</p><!--l. 13707--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, and the hashing space is distributed. It&#x2019;s not like it&#x2019;s all in one place and you
can just add more – it is in multiple versions of software running on hardware in a
dozen countries. . .if you start changing things in one place, you have to change them
everywhere, or at least have a strategy for assuring compatability with previous
versions.”
</p><!--l. 13713--><p class="indent" >  “So there is no quick-ﬁx.”
</p><!--l. 13715--><p class="indent" >  “Instead of controlling the messages, they are actually corrupting them?”
</p><!--l. 13717--><p class="indent" >  “Something like that.”
</p><!--l. 13719--><p class="indent" >  “I have talked to the group in San Diego, and they are trying to make out that this is
an administrative error, but I think that, if you look at the code, you have to see that
this is a deliberate attempt to add a veto and replacement message. It&#x2019;s very cryptic,
but I have done an analysis.”
</p><!--l. 13725--><p class="indent" >  “The eﬀect is that the centralized control is lost and all of the messages and
sims are fragmenting themselves, just like what we see happening in the real
world.”

</p><!--l. 13729--><p class="indent" >  “And yet the game has not yet fallen apart.”
</p><!--l. 13731--><p class="indent" >  “Nor has society, thankfully.”
</p><!--l. 13733--><p class="indent" >  “We should bear in mind that the recent interest by the gangs is going to mean more
trouble for us.”
</p><!--l. 13736--><p class="indent" >  “Why would we be in danger?”
</p><!--l. 13738--><p class="indent" >  “They could try to kill you.”
</p><!--l. 13740--><p class="indent" >  Preeta starts. Since the incident in KL, she has often placed her hands inside her
pants and just held on, remembering the invasion.
</p><!--l. 13744--><p class="indent" >  “Let&#x2019;s not get over excited here,” Art interrupts. “What we do know is that some of
the hooligan gangs attached to neo-Nazi wings have attached themselves to football
colours and are using their maﬁa contacts to get involved in more meaningful
attacks.”
</p><!--l. 13749--><p class="indent" >  “You mean they have become hired thugs?”
</p><!--l. 13751--><p class="indent" >  “Exactly right, but they are also game junkies. We have an operation on going now
to break up a war-game in Jotunheimen. . .”
</p><!--l. 13754--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s the mountains here in Norway..”
</p><!--l. 13756--><p class="indent" >  “. . .As long as they are on the loose with their own propaganda ﬂowing freely. .
.”
</p><!--l. 13758--><p class="indent" >  “. . .by ﬁst. . .”
</p><!--l. 13761--><p class="indent" >  “. . .no one can think of themselves as being safe. It is obviously a time of
year where they come out of the woodwork. There&#x2019;s been a lot of activity
lately.”
</p><!--l. 13764--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah. . .” Dermot recalls his encounter and feels ill.
</p><!--l. 13766--><p class="indent" >  “So the upshot is that all of these messages are having a real eﬀect on what is going
on out there, and that means we cannot discount the possibility of the kind of thing
that Preeta has experienced coming here to Oslo.”
</p><!--l. 13770--><p class="indent" >  “I expect that makes her feel a lot better.”
</p><!--l. 13772--><p class="indent" >  “Well, at least she is with people who can protect her, and who can make use of her
skills,” Art puts.
</p><!--l. 13775--><p class="indent" >  “Yes,” Bishop adds, “While Preeta is here, I want you to make the most of her
knowledge and her skills. We need to test out our own ideas.”
</p><!--l. 13779--><p class="indent" >  She senses a thrill. No one has really referred to her skills before.
</p><!--l. 13782--><p class="indent" >  As the meeting simply falls into disarray, a couple of members of the little group
focus increasingly on Preeta, digging for facts about her. Others simply fade out and
try to ignore her presence, as though they are shunning her, or perhaps are
simply in-equipped to deal with new acquaintances, with no common frame of
reference.
</p><!--l. 13788--><p class="indent" >  They begin to ﬁddle with their mobile gadgets, hooking in to some private world, as
if blowing smoke in her face; that is what they would have done in India. In this
country, she has seen people using their mobile devices frequently as protective garbs
and defensive ploys. It is easy to see why this, of all places, would be in need of a
smart police force, savvy in the ways of bringing people back to a sense of civic
responsibility. She has not been here more than a handful of days, but already she has

seen how this society is fragmented into little labelled pieces. Kids in little
groups, talking to their remote friends as they walk down the middle of a
street.
</p><!--l. 13799--><p class="indent" >  Light ﬂakes of snow are falling in the grey haze outside. They melt as they meet the
window. It oﬀers a serenity, a quiet sleepiness.
</p><!--l. 13804--><p class="indent" >  “They have tried to be too ambitious. By trying to tie every game and simulation
into a single framework, they have introduces inconsistencies. you just cannot force an
entire world to conform, even when you own the platform. Remember what happened
to Microsoft.”
</p><!--l. 13812--><p class="indent" >  She has never been a shy person, but something about this dislocation has made her
reticent.
</p><!--l. 13815--><p class="indent" >  “So what&#x2019;s it like in Malaysia?”
</p><!--l. 13817--><p class="indent" >  She shrugs. “The same. Diﬀerent.”
</p><!--l. 13819--><p class="indent" >  “We could go into the VR to chat?”
</p><!--l. 13821--><p class="indent" >  Bishop intervenes. “No. Stay here. Face up to it.”
</p><!--l. 13827--><p class="indent" >  “But I could see that it was not going to work. I was doing my job as I
was supposed to. I just wanted to do my best, as an analyst. We get these
speciﬁcations that we are supposed to follow. I think they looked okay from
a design point of view, but we have tools that perform fancy analyses. It&#x2019;s
something i have been playing with in my spare time, to kind of secure my
future.”
</p><!--l. 13834--><p class="indent" >  “But it was a good thing that we found you. The secret is out already. Nothing
anyone could do about that. And it was just a matter of time, no big surprises
there. Of course, originally no one thought that anyone would be able to
ﬁgure out what is really going on in such a huge enterprise, nor be able to do
anything about it even if they could. But then this story was leaked to the
free press, and even the Americans had to print it eventually. You can&#x2019;t stop
the ﬂow of news. That was when they arranged to whitewash conference in
California. They are nervous now and that means they are getting to be more
dangerous.”
</p><!--l. 13845--><p class="indent" >  “Why don&#x2019;t they just move to an island somewhere?”
</p><!--l. 13847--><p class="indent" >  “Eventually all this will be done on oﬀ-shore ships, but international law is also
changing slowly to clamp down on pirate communities.”
</p><!--l. 13853--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t worry about your friends. We have Interpol on surveillance of the company.
They will inform your old boss that you are helping us with our enquiries, as they
say.”
</p><!--l. 13857--><p class="indent" >  Her gaze wanders around the modern interior and wooden kitchen units. through
the windows, the world is brightening. It seems almost as though the sun would
shine.
</p><!--l. 13864--><p class="indent" >  “Something has come up.”
</p><!--l. 13867--><p class="indent" >  “I think it was the Russian maﬁa. They have grown big in our part of the
world.”
</p><!--l. 13870--><p class="indent" >  “No, that can&#x2019;t be it. They have been working with the C.I.A. for some time. They

have similar goals.”
</p><!--l. 13873--><p class="indent" >  It is a private war behind the scenes, with governments, corporations, the U.N. and
the federated maﬁa all vying for control. It feels like the Day of the Condor,
Bollywood style.
</p><!--l. 13877--><p class="indent" >  She meets the contact here. She discovers that he is one of the characters she has
been talking to in the VR.
</p><!--l. 13880--><p class="indent" >  “I am just an analyst.”
</p><!--l. 13884--><p class="indent" >  “You wanna go out tonight? See the city?”
</p><!--l. 13886--><p class="indent" >  She is bored with herself. What else could she say?
</p><!--l. 13888--><p class="indent" >  “Thank you.”
</p><!--l. 13897--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-31r28"></a>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-0"></a>
<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">28</span>
</p><!--l. 13900--><p class="indent" >  Outside Den&#x2019;s oﬃce, he sees the old tree, which has watched over this area as long
as anyone can remember. Over time, the tree has sought to spread its message of life
and growth, of freedom and competition. It has gone forth and extended itself, roots
and branches raging against their masonic captivity.
</p><!--l. 13906--><p class="indent" >  Tree surgeons are battling with the tree&#x2019;s assumption of control, using weapons that
go far beyond decent competition; but age reaches down into the hollow interior of
London, clasping the ground like a clenched ﬁst. Prying, cellulose ﬁngers holding
on. They have started to weaken the roof of the tunnels below. Concrete is
crumbling and falling. His tree has been condemned to death for resisting its own
incarceration.
</p><!--l. 13914--><p class="indent" >  Den thinks the houses in San Diego and the displeasure he felt at seeing desert
chaos intervene with human order, but here it is again.
</p><!--l. 13917--><p class="indent" >  He looks out at the London skyline, consumed with hard concentration. He is that
tree: a message desperate to compete with a million others, against immovable odds,
and he is about to begin the next phase of his growth.
</p><!--l. 13922--><p class="indent" >  Returning from his trip from San Diego has felt like an anti-climax so far. His head
is swimming with the phantoms of conversations and sensations: sensations of a
privileged lifestyle, of sunshine and change, and of Cathy Kim. What a desirable
woman she is.
</p><!--l. 13927--><p class="indent" >  He went to San Diego to move GrapeVine into the hot seat of directed imaging: to
exploit the advantages that a U.K. company has for an American business: to divest
accountability, and navigate a way around U.S. information legislation that
would make the gaming operations more transparent than the consortium
would like. It is a lucrative if not entirely honest assignment, but it seems
no worse to the board than any other job in advertising. The aim is not to
be fair and reﬂective, but to push and to sell. No qualms of conscience are
necessary.
</p><!--l. 13937--><p class="indent" >  And for his own sake, his aim, to steer the event to his own advantage, was a

moderate success? He was called in and told what to do by Cathy and then by
the Senator. . . but he put himself in that position. It was his choice, wasn&#x2019;t
it?
</p><!--l. 13942--><p class="indent" >  So he was noticed. He was a success. And yet his own weakness for female grace
has left him committed to helping Cathy Kim rise up the rungs of her own
evolutionary ladder. Who is actually steering this ship? Is it really to his beneﬁt too?
What has he actually signed himself up for?
</p><!--l. 13948--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Networking, Den. Networking.</span>
</p><!--l. 13950--><p class="indent" >  In some ways he is glad to be back. There are interesting challenges afoot and
dreaming about them doesn&#x2019;t help. There is work to be done. That means he will be
here in London for a little while. That, in itself, in a novelty. He does not
often spend much time in the London oﬃce. It has always seemed preferable
to orchestrate the activities from his private home in the High Wycombe
countryside, where he can look out across the misty hills and count sheep
as he works. Better than counting cars locked in battle in London&#x2019;s metal
aneurism.
</p><!--l. 13959--><p class="indent" >  “Den!” A colleague shouts from across the oﬃce space beyond his open door.
“Looks like you did well, my old son!”
</p><!--l. 13962--><p class="indent" >  “We aim to please.”
</p><!--l. 13964--><p class="indent" >  “Good on ya.” He disappears from sight, only to return a moment later, leaning on
the open doorway, shirt sleeves rolled up and tablet in hand. “Hey, by the way, our
contract with Amidrug might be in trouble. Did you hear the latest on the Safety
Commission?”
</p><!--l. 13969--><p class="indent" >  “No, I&#x2019;ve been too tied up in the gaming stuﬀ.”
</p><!--l. 13971--><p class="indent" >  “No kidding. Well, it&#x2019;s like this. The Consumer Safety Commission has decreed
that the competing ADD drugs are all unsafe by American standards and have
to be regulated by batch testing. Novarctic reckon that&#x2019;s going to throttle
their supply channel so much that they will not be able to sustain a market
presence.”
</p><!--l. 13977--><p class="indent" >  “Crafty bastards.”
</p><!--l. 13979--><p class="indent" >  “No shit. They&#x2019;re well pissed oﬀ.”
</p><!--l. 13981--><p class="indent" >  “And that means. . .that Amidrug don&#x2019;t need to advertise as much to dominate the
market?”
</p><!--l. 13984--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s the size of it, mate.”
</p><!--l. 13986--><p class="indent" >  Den frowns. The American Consumer Product Safety Commission has been
placing tight restrictions on their reputedly free markets for a long time, a bone of
contention for advertisers for years. The slogan of their free market economy is really:
you are free to leave prison and compete in the world, but please wear this
straitjacket. They bury competitors in pointless bureaucracy: counting the railings in
children&#x2019;s cots and enforcing higher standards on imports than om home-grown
products.
</p><!--l. 13995--><p class="indent" >  “So are we screwed or can we persuade them to move to where they will need us
even more?”

</p><!--l. 13998--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t know yet. It&#x2019;s still on-going. Just thought I&#x2019;d give you an update.”
</p><!--l. 14000--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah, thanks.”
</p><!--l. 14002--><p class="indent" >  “You probably have enough to think about.”
</p><!--l. 14004--><p class="indent" >  “Small under-statement.”
</p><!--l. 14006--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah – well are you gonna join us down the Elephant and Castle later on? We&#x2019;re
having a few beers after work to lighten the mood.”
</p><!--l. 14009--><p class="indent" >  “We&#x2019;ll see. I might be heading back to Wycombe.”
</p><!--l. 14011--><p class="indent" >  “Nah. Leave it out. You wanna get your arse down the pub and get some decent
beer back inside you, my son. It&#x2019;s all this American piss water that&#x2019;s messing up your
head.”
</p><!--l. 14015--><p class="indent" >  Den shrugs with his eyebrows. “Well, don&#x2019;t count me out yet. I&#x2019;ll have to see how
far I get with this follow-up. I haven&#x2019;t quite got it sussed out yet.”
</p><!--l. 14019--><p class="indent" >  “Denny boy, a few beers will make everything clearer.” He laughs. “We&#x2019;ll be going
from here about half-ﬁve, awright?”
</p><!--l. 14022--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah, cheers.”
</p><!--l. 14024--><p class="indent" >  “See ya.”
</p><!--l. 14026--><p class="indent" >  He disappears from view.
</p><!--l. 14028--><p class="indent" >  Den picks up a tablet and starts to sketch a plan. He writes the name of the Senator,
and Cathy Kim, and the consortium in a triangle and pulls up his notes on each. The
plans for the consortium are the most complete. They have been working on that for
some time. Then he starts to make a list of tasks under each name, grouping the
activities that are compatible and common between them. Information gathering.
Weaknesses. Attack analysis. It takes half an hour before he can see any
structure in it, but there is something there to get started on. If GrapeVine
starts on the common aspects ﬁrst, it will proceed more quickly. He should
bring the others into it as soon as possible, and yet he has a nagging worry
about what it is he is supposed to be doing. What was meant to be his grip on
the future, on the latest game technology, is starting to be more a potential
liability.
</p><!--l. 14043--><p class="indent" >  An intern knocks at his open doorway.
</p><!--l. 14045--><p class="indent" >  “Mr. Morris?”
</p><!--l. 14047--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s me.”
</p><!--l. 14049--><p class="indent" >  “Uhm..”
</p><!--l. 14051--><p class="indent" >  “Come on in, Raj.”
</p><!--l. 14053--><p class="indent" >  “Sorry to interrupt, sir.”
</p><!--l. 14055--><p class="indent" >  “No problem. What can I do you for?”
</p><!--l. 14057--><p class="indent" >  “Mr. Brown asked me to give you these.”
</p><!--l. 14059--><p class="indent" >  “Courier work, eh? Nice of him to make good use of your skills.”
</p><!--l. 14061--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t mind.”
</p><!--l. 14063--><p class="indent" >  “Just as well.”
</p><!--l. 14065--><p class="indent" >  He hands him a pair of cards, of the kind typically used for carrying encrypted
data.
</p><!--l. 14068--><p class="indent" >  “What&#x2019;s this about?”

</p><!--l. 14070--><p class="indent" >  “Designs from the Conway job, innit. Billboards and stuﬀ. He said you know the
project keys.”
</p><!--l. 14073--><p class="indent" >  “Ugh. Okay. Thanks.” He puts them distractedly to one side of his desk.
</p><!--l. 14075--><p class="indent" >  “Aren&#x2019;t you going to look at them?”
</p><!--l. 14077--><p class="indent" >  “Later. I&#x2019;m sort of busy on something else right now.”
</p><!--l. 14079--><p class="indent" >  “From your trip?”
</p><!--l. 14081--><p class="indent" >  “Yes.”
</p><!--l. 14083--><p class="indent" >  “How was your presentation?”
</p><!--l. 14085--><p class="indent" >  Den looks up at him from his tablet screen. “Good question,” he says. “Good
question.”
</p><!--l. 14088--><p class="indent" >  “Okay.”
</p><!--l. 14090--><p class="indent" >  “I think it went well.”
</p><!--l. 14092--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m sure it was very good, Mr. Morris.”
</p><!--l. 14094--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah.”
</p><!--l. 14096--><p class="indent" >  “I have seen you make presentations before.”
</p><!--l. 14098--><p class="indent" >  “Really?”
</p><!--l. 14100--><p class="indent" >  “At the annual kickoﬀ.”
</p><!--l. 14102--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s right. You remember that?” He snorts, recalling.
</p><!--l. 14104--><p class="indent" >  “You are an excellent speaker.”
</p><!--l. 14106--><p class="indent" >  “Thanks, Raj. That&#x2019;s kind. I guess it went okay.”
</p><!--l. 14108--><p class="indent" >  “Okay?”
</p><!--l. 14110--><p class="indent" >  Den frowns. “It was ﬁne. It just didn&#x2019;t have quite the eﬀect I had imagined, that&#x2019;s
all.”
</p><!--l. 14113--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t understand.”
</p><!--l. 14115--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s not that important. I&#x2019;m just a bit tired from the trip. Ask me again tomorrow.”
He grins.
</p><!--l. 14118--><p class="indent" >  “Did you make the contacts you were hoping for?”
</p><!--l. 14120--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s the strange thing. . .”
</p><!--l. 14122--><p class="indent" >  “How so, Mr. Morris?”
</p><!--l. 14124--><p class="indent" >  “Well, I don&#x2019;t know what I was expecting, really.”
</p><!--l. 14126--><p class="indent" >  “But you made contacts.”
</p><!--l. 14128--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, yes. An ambitious individual and a balmy senator.” He laughs.
</p><!--l. 14130--><p class="indent" >  The intern shrugs.
</p><!--l. 14132--><p class="indent" >  “I think I was looking to impress people by our work so that more clients would be
interested in work from us of the same kind. Instead, I have simply earned greater
trust from a couple of people deeper down who want to use us for their own special
agendas.”
</p><!--l. 14137--><p class="indent" >  “They say that the Lord works in mysterious ways.”
</p><!--l. 14139--><p class="indent" >  “So I&#x2019;ve heard.”
</p><!--l. 14141--><p class="indent" >  “So. Is there anything I can do to help? You could use an intern on this, right, Mr.
Morris?”
</p><!--l. 14143--><p class="indent" >  Den smiles, recognizing ambition. “What did you have in mind?”

</p><!--l. 14145--><p class="indent" >  “Well, the way I see it, Mr. Henderson doesn&#x2019;t really need me. I am just
wasting my time on the Conway project. I was wondering if you needed any
help?”
</p><!--l. 14149--><p class="indent" >  “You want to work up here?”
</p><!--l. 14151--><p class="indent" >  “I have alway been interested in the VR gaming.”
</p><!--l. 14153--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah. . .” Den is distant, as if contemplating.
</p><!--l. 14155--><p class="indent" >  “Of course, you probably don&#x2019;t need any help. I just thought, if I could get some
experience. . .”
</p><!--l. 14157--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t know. Maybe. Just a sec.” Den strides across his room and fumbles in his
jacket pocket for a storage card. The work he did on the plane is on it. He spent some
time relating strategies, which they have been using for the game, to the points raised
by the activists he met. Their angle showed up several weaknesses in the
consortium objectives. He pulls the card out of a pocket, blows ﬂuﬀ oﬀ it and
slots it into the top of his tablet. He ﬂips through his ﬁles and pulls up the
cause-chart.
</p><!--l. 14166--><p class="indent" >  “What do you make of this?”
</p><!--l. 14168--><p class="indent" >  Den hits the screen tab and the image on his tablet appears on the smart-wall next to
them, at three times the size.
</p><!--l. 14171--><p class="indent" >  “What is it?”
</p><!--l. 14173--><p class="indent" >  “A new project, related to the old one. Could be important for us. From my visit to
the States.”
</p><!--l. 14175--><p class="indent" >  “Well. . .”
</p><!--l. 14177--><p class="indent" >  “There&#x2019;s a lot going on here, and it looks at bit of a dog&#x2019;s dinner at the moment, but
it&#x2019;s related to what we&#x2019;ve been doing already. You&#x2019;ve been in on that haven&#x2019;t you? The
Chequers billboards and active motion analysis?”
</p><!--l. 14182--><p class="indent" >  “Yes. We did Chequers together.”
</p><!--l. 14184--><p class="indent" >  “Oh yes, so we did.” He sighs. “Must be getting old. Sorry. Well, take a look at this
then.” He points to the left hand side of the treelike ﬂow diagram, its lines and
boxes interweaving in complex ﬂows of cause and eﬀect. “The blue coloured
lines are input from a group of protesters that I met. That gave me some new
ideas.”
</p><!--l. 14190--><p class="indent" >  Raj studies the diagram for several minutes, saying nothing.
</p><!--l. 14192--><p class="indent" >  “Does it make any sense to you?”
</p><!--l. 14194--><p class="indent" >  He draws breath, and Den sees his youthful humility evaporate into conﬁdent
concentration as the cog-wheels go around inside his head.
</p><!--l. 14197--><p class="indent" >  “These extra inputs are from activists, as in the protesters that have been in the
news?”
</p><!--l. 14199--><p class="indent" >  “Exactly.”
</p><!--l. 14201--><p class="indent" >  “And . . . they are casting doubt on the older part of the causation model by
saying that the government&#x2019;s popular slogans are having the opposite eﬀect to
what they are supposed to have—I mean, at least it looks like it from your
notes.”
</p><!--l. 14206--><p class="indent" >  Smart kid. He is going to be a formidable colleague.

</p><!--l. 14209--><p class="indent" >  “Good.”
</p><!--l. 14211--><p class="indent" >  “At least, it looks that way. . .”
</p><!--l. 14213--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;d say that&#x2019;s a correct assessment of the situation.”
</p><!--l. 14215--><p class="indent" >  He looks pleased, then pleasure dissolves as he makes the next step in his mind.
“So. . .”
</p><!--l. 14218--><p class="indent" >  “So?”
</p><!--l. 14220--><p class="indent" >  “So who is right?”
</p><!--l. 14222--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s what we have to ﬁgure out.”
</p><!--l. 14224--><p class="indent" >  “It seems pretty important.”
</p><!--l. 14226--><p class="indent" >  Den laughs. “No shit. This could be the exact thing that makes or breaks our
campaign for the consortium. Of course, if the activists are right, then the consortium
is not going to like the answer.”
</p><!--l. 14230--><p class="indent" >  “You would tell them that everything they are doing is wrong?”
</p><!--l. 14232--><p class="indent" >  “We would have to make a little campaign of our own to break the news to them
gently.”
</p><!--l. 14234--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s funny.”
</p><!--l. 14236--><p class="indent" >  “Funny?”
</p><!--l. 14238--><p class="indent" >  “Having them pay us to persuade them that they are actually wrong.”
</p><!--l. 14240--><p class="indent" >  Den nods. “I see your point. Then again, that&#x2019;s what they are paying us for. To get
them results.” He paces around. “It&#x2019;s ironic though. I mean these activists were trying
to persuade me to help their cause, I think. If they have given us the very weapons to
help us to do what they don&#x2019;t want. . .”
</p><!--l. 14246--><p class="indent" >  “Then what?”
</p><!--l. 14248--><p class="indent" >  “Then what indeed.”
</p><!--l. 14250--><p class="indent" >  “Do you make the changes?”
</p><!--l. 14252--><p class="indent" >  “Then we make recommendations to our employer so that they get their
results.”
</p><!--l. 14255--><p class="indent" >  The intern&#x2019;s face seems to grapple with indecision. “Is that the right thing?”
</p><!--l. 14258--><p class="indent" >  “They are paying our bills. We are under contract.”
</p><!--l. 14260--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, yes,” he agrees and resumes his shawl of humility. “But what is it they
actually want to do? I&#x2019;m not sure I have understood it.”
</p><!--l. 14263--><p class="indent" >  Den nods. “That&#x2019;s it, isn&#x2019;t it? That is the sixty-four billion dollar question.”
</p><!--l. 14266--><p class="indent" >  “Mr. Morris?”
</p><!--l. 14268--><p class="indent" >  “Call me Den. What they want us to do, Raj, is to spread their gospel to
game-players everywhere. They want the world to trust them again, to see that
American stands for values that can be trusted. And they want Americans to lie down
quietly, like they used to.”
</p><!--l. 14273--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;ll tell you what I see here, Mr. Morris,” the intern says. “I see the same old story.
People wanting to sell their product without any idea of what they are trying to
say.”
</p><!--l. 14277--><p class="indent" >  He ducks behind his eyes, as if fearing a come back, but Den nods to him. “Go
on.”

</p><!--l. 14280--><p class="indent" >  “This job is for the consortium. They are pretty much the government, as I see
it.”
</p><!--l. 14283--><p class="indent" >  Den shrugs. “Certainly, they are run more or less by the same people that make
Federal government policy.”
</p><!--l. 14285--><p class="indent" >  “Their message is banal and predictable. Support us. Do what we say. Be
satisﬁed with what you&#x2019;ve got. There&#x2019;s no imagination in the marketing. They
want us to create a message for them, because they don&#x2019;t have one of their
own”
</p><!--l. 14290--><p class="indent" >  Den looks at him.
</p><!--l. 14292--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s good,” he says, feeling a certain admiration for this youngster. “You&#x2019;ll do
well here, if any of us do.”
</p><!--l. 14295--><p class="indent" >  “Thanks.”
</p><!--l. 14297--><p class="indent" >  “You&#x2019;re welcome.”
</p><!--l. 14299--><p class="indent" >  “So. . .”
</p><!--l. 14301--><p class="indent" >  “So?”
</p><!--l. 14303--><p class="indent" >  “Can I work on this with you?” he asks.
</p><!--l. 14305--><p class="indent" >  “You want to help out?”
</p><!--l. 14307--><p class="indent" >  “I do.”
</p><!--l. 14309--><p class="indent" >  Den nods. “Sure. I think you are just what I need to sort this out.”
</p><!--l. 14311--><p class="indent" >  The intern grins and then suppresses it. “Can you tell Mr. Brown? He doesn&#x2019;t really
want me there anyway.”
</p><!--l. 14313--><p class="indent" >  “Hmmm.”
</p><!--l. 14315--><p class="indent" >  “Please? I am just wasting my time down there.”
</p><!--l. 14317--><p class="indent" >  “We can do it later. Right now, I want you to look at this part of the chart.” He
waves to a series of lines and arrows that seem to be feeding into the name of Cathy
Kim. “This person is a researcher who is working with U.S. law enforcement. She
wants us to cooperate with her organization to share the information we are authorized
to collect.”
</p><!--l. 14324--><p class="indent" >  Raj whistles. “You mean, break our NDAs?”
</p><!--l. 14326--><p class="indent" >  Den shrugs. “Perhaps. The rewards could be substantial, if we can impress the
right people. We should check what the Non Disclosure Agreements actually
say on the information we gather. If we can pass on information to them, in
conﬁdence, piggy-backing oﬀ another agreement, we might be able to do it
legally.”
</p><!--l. 14332--><p class="indent" >  Raj nods. “It might be doable. But. . .”
</p><!--l. 14334--><p class="indent" >  “Should we?”
</p><!--l. 14336--><p class="indent" >  “Is it ethical?”
</p><!--l. 14338--><p class="indent" >  “Raj, in this day and age, nothing is ethical. It&#x2019;s only ﬁnancial or personal.”
</p><!--l. 14341--><p class="indent" >  The intern looks uncomfortable.
</p><!--l. 14343--><p class="indent" >  “If we decide that this is something we want to pursue, the ethics of it are our
business. We just need to know who our allies are.”
</p><!--l. 14346--><p class="indent" >  “Then wouldn&#x2019;t we be behaving like the gangsters the government are
trying to abolish? Just looking after our own friends and to hell with anyone

else?”
</p><!--l. 14349--><p class="indent" >  Den nods. “Even national governments are just gangsters. It&#x2019;s not about whether
you are working for a gang or not—it&#x2019;s about how big and powerful your particular
gang is.”
</p><!--l. 14353--><p class="indent" >  Raj looks at him, as if to acknowledge that he already knew that, but was hoping to
be convinced otherwise. “We still need to check the legality of sharing that
information.”
</p><!--l. 14357--><p class="indent" >  “Agreed.”
</p><!--l. 14359--><p class="indent" >  “And you have have to get me out of the Conway job.”
</p><!--l. 14361--><p class="indent" >  Den smiles. “You don&#x2019;t give up easily do you?”
</p><!--l. 14363--><p class="indent" >  “I am here to learn.”
</p><!--l. 14365--><p class="indent" >  “And you are absolutely certain,” he teases.
</p><!--l. 14367--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, I am deﬁnitely interested. This is where I have the most to learn.”
</p><!--l. 14369--><p class="indent" >  “And this is what we are good at. It is why we were picked for this job.”
</p><!--l. 14371--><p class="indent" >  “So the Conway job. . .?”
</p><!--l. 14373--><p class="indent" >  “Well, I don&#x2019;t know. . .we might still need you on that.”
</p><!--l. 14375--><p class="indent" >  “Please?”
</p><!--l. 14377--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;ll see what I can do.”
</p><!--l. 14379--><p class="indent" >  He grins. “Then I&#x2019;ll start planning. Can I make a copy of this?” He gestures to the
wall chart.
</p><!--l. 14382--><p class="indent" >  Den nods and pokes some menus on his tablet. “I&#x2019;ll add you to this project. Add
your key, and we&#x2019;ll brainstorm this together for a little while, before bringing in
anyone else, okay?”
</p><!--l. 14386--><p class="indent" >  “Okay!”
</p><!--l. 14388--><p class="indent" >  “Good, now you&#x2019;d better get back. Come back here in a couple of hours. I have to
do a few things ﬁrst.”
</p><!--l. 14391--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, Mr. Morris.”
</p><!--l. 14393--><p class="indent" >  “Call me Den.”
</p><!--l. 14395--><p class="indent" >  Den checks his messages on the tablet, with a sense of having made progress
without actually doing anything. He should call up Mary and see whats she has for
him.
</p><!--l. 14399--><p class="indent" >  But ﬁrst things ﬁrst. He, they, need some legal advice.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 14401--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 14402--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 14405--><p class="indent" >  A young woman, slender, long legs, with dark-auburn, shoulder-length hair, in a
smart grey skirt-suit comes down the hall towards him. He follows her approach,
admiring her grace. They play these games.
</p><!--l. 14410--><p class="indent" >  She has that fashionable ragged look, contrasting with the smart look of her dark
grey skirt-suit. He scans her body curves and secret places and re-aﬃrms that

she could satisfy his carnal craving, as she always does. She has a magic.
Something.
</p><!--l. 14415--><p class="indent" >  For a moment he is unsettled by her presence. His instincts rebel against one
another. Is it not true that he has made an unspoken promise to Cathy Kim now? So
soon after seeing her, he should not be attracted to Kylie. But has he made any
promise? Has she? Their union was surely one of admiration, not one of
obligation.
</p><!--l. 14421--><p class="indent" >  “Love”, she taunts, in a cute Scottish accent.
</p><!--l. 14423--><p class="indent" >  “Excuse me?”
</p><!--l. 14425--><p class="indent" >  “Love,” she repeats, and smiles with her characteristic, cheeky sarcasm.
“You were thinking about sex. You are supposed to do it in connection with
love.”
</p><!--l. 14429--><p class="indent" >  “Right. I hadn&#x2019;t thought about that.”
</p><!--l. 14431--><p class="indent" >  She smiles at him conﬁdently as if asking: do you recognize me then? We ﬂirted
with each other last time you were in town.
</p><!--l. 14434--><p class="indent" >  “Did you want something?”
</p><!--l. 14436--><p class="indent" >  “You&#x2019;re a guy.” She beams.
</p><!--l. 14438--><p class="indent" >  The Scottish are the masters of sarcasm, Den thinks. They make an anti-social
rudeness into charming entertainment. One has to admire the sculpting of personal
image that allows something so negative to become so positive. They make
excellent marketeers, he decides and pigeon-holes the thought for future analysis.
She looks him up and down, pausing a little too long at his crotch to tease,
and then looks right to his face, unblinking. “I am stuck on this American
project.”
</p><!--l. 14447--><p class="indent" >  “Which one?” The ID badge on her waist shows an unﬂattering picture with the
name Kylie McLachlan.
</p><!--l. 14450--><p class="indent" >  “The free coke and training shoes with every burger ad&#x2019; to train the punters to
swallow American nationalist bullshit. . .what do you think?” Again the raised
eyebrow, beady eyed glare. “It&#x2019;s not important. I need to really sell this to a big
American company, pretending to be a world government, with lots of dosh, tosh.
It&#x2019;s for The Client. Any ideas?” She is obviously just ﬂirting with him so
he plays the part. She is not merely attractive, she is sexy. Especially the
accent.
</p><!--l. 14459--><p class="indent" >  Den shrugs. “Standard formula. Fill it with glorious adverbs, and then say: you
KNOW it makes sense!.”
</p><!--l. 14462--><p class="indent" >  “Can&#x2019;t,” she says. “No adverbs.”
</p><!--l. 14464--><p class="indent" >  “Oh?”
</p><!--l. 14466--><p class="indent" >  “Americans have obliterated the adverb, as you should know, Mr. Morris, having
just returned from their play pen.”
</p><!--l. 14468--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 14470--><p class="indent" >  She summons herself, looking at her pad, waves a theatrical hand and
proclaims:

     <span 
class="ptmr7t-">“Go quiet in the push and shove</span><br 
class="newline" /><span 
class="ptmr7t-">Go bold where no person has gone before</span><br 
class="newline" /><span 
class="ptmr7t-">Do it fast and furious</span><br 
class="newline" /><span 
class="ptmr7t-">Do it thorough and good</span><br 
class="newline" /><span 
class="ptmr7t-">Do it calm and thoughtful</span><br 
class="newline" /><span 
class="ptmr7t-">Speak clear of good meaning intentions</span><br 
class="newline" /><span 
class="ptmr7t-">And meet every new soul real peaceful,</span><br 
class="newline" /><span 
class="ptmr7t-">Salute, them respectful, like</span><br 
class="newline" /><span 
class="ptmr7t-">Ships passing quiet in the night.”</span>
</p><!--l. 14483--><p class="indent" >  Den looks at her blankly, uncertain as to whether he has understood her satire, if
that is what it was.
</p><!--l. 14486--><p class="indent" >  She looks quizzical and continues: “And how are you Mrs. MacenBurger? ‘Good!
Real good!&#x2019; Well I am sorry, Mrs. MacenBurger but we&#x2019;ll have to see what Santa
Claus has to say about that! Or did you mean: really well?”
</p><!--l. 14490--><p class="indent" >  Den has no idea what she is talking about, but he cannot help himself and a smile
breaks onto his lips.
</p><!--l. 14493--><p class="indent" >  Finally, she gives up waiting a response. “Never mind. You English have no sense
of humus.” She winks. ”There are no adverbs. But I need to talk to you about your
project.”
</p><!--l. 14497--><p class="indent" >  “You got my message then?”
</p><!--l. 14499--><p class="indent" >  “I did.”
</p><!--l. 14501--><p class="indent" >  “Have you looked at the contracts?”
</p><!--l. 14503--><p class="indent" >  “I have.”
</p><!--l. 14505--><p class="indent" >  He waits for more. “So? Don&#x2019;t keep me in suspense.”
</p><!--l. 14507--><p class="indent" >  She sighs. “You can&#x2019;t do it.”
</p><!--l. 14509--><p class="indent" >  “Can&#x2019;t do what?”
</p><!--l. 14511--><p class="indent" >  “You can&#x2019;t take on these side projects, disclosing information that is gathered in
connection with the others.”
</p><!--l. 14514--><p class="indent" >  She looks at his smart wall, that displays his reﬁned causation chart. He has tidied it
up and added pictures of Cathy Kim and the Senator to remind himself that they are
people.
</p><!--l. 14518--><p class="indent" >  “Can we share information, legally, with these American law enforcement
people.”
</p><!--l. 14520--><p class="indent" >  “Is she really law enforcement?”
</p><!--l. 14522--><p class="indent" >  “Yes. No. . .I don&#x2019;t think so.”
</p><!--l. 14524--><p class="indent" >  “What about our Non-Disclosure Agreements?”
</p><!--l. 14526--><p class="indent" >  “Is that her? Very nice. . .” She whistles and nudges him irritatingly. “Our
commitment is clear. We are supposed to generate billboard content and story-lines
for the game scenarios. We are not supposed to divulge our research to third
parties.”
</p><!--l. 14531--><p class="indent" >  “Are they really third parties though? I mean the Senator is part of the consortium,
as I understand it. And Kim. . .”
</p><!--l. 14534--><p class="indent" >  “Your fancy woman.”

</p><!--l. 14536--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 14538--><p class="indent" >  “Sorry. Your law enforcement researcher. . .what is she really?”
</p><!--l. 14540--><p class="indent" >  “Well, I haven&#x2019;t checked her out fully. . .”
</p><!--l. 14542--><p class="indent" >  She smirks. “Really? You must be slipping, Denny.”
</p><!--l. 14544--><p class="indent" >  “We would obviously have to do that.”
</p><!--l. 14546--><p class="indent" >  “Obviously,” she nods, turning her head slightly to view him through the corner of
her eyes..
</p><!--l. 14549--><p class="indent" >  “But if she is a legitimate part of the consortium, by contract, then what?”
</p><!--l. 14551--><p class="indent" >  “Well it would depend on what kind of contract.”
</p><!--l. 14553--><p class="indent" >  “But if she is working in their best interests?”
</p><!--l. 14555--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m afraid that would not be a precise enough criterion for their lawyers.”
</p><!--l. 14557--><p class="indent" >  “So you don&#x2019;t think it is doable?”
</p><!--l. 14560--><p class="indent" >  Kylie McLachlan&#x2019;s humorous facade wavers.
</p><!--l. 14562--><p class="indent" >  “Den. . .”
</p><!--l. 14564--><p class="indent" >  “Ms McLachlan?”
</p><!--l. 14566--><p class="indent" >  She sighs, showing frustration. “I think you must be a little crazy to take on this
thing in the ﬁrst place.”
</p><!--l. 14569--><p class="indent" >  “Really. Is that a professional opinion? I didn&#x2019;t know you had been studying
psychiatry.”
</p><!--l. 14572--><p class="indent" >  “Oh, you&#x2019;d be surprised what we legal people have to know.. But all this goes just a
little beyond advertising, don&#x2019;t you think?”
</p><!--l. 14575--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s a natural progression. It&#x2019;s excellent money. It is not something that I could say
no to easily. If I had said no, we could have been dropped like a hot potato. The end of
our contract and we might never be able to get back into it again. Not only the end of
our contract but the end of our business. The future of advertising is in the
game.”
</p><!--l. 14582--><p class="indent" >  “So you let them push you around and pull your strings?”
</p><!--l. 14584--><p class="indent" >  “I did some pushing,” he protests. “I pushed.”
</p><!--l. 14586--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s not the kind of pushing I was thinking of,” she chides. “I know you too
well, Den.”
</p><!--l. 14589--><p class="indent" >  He ignores the innuendo. “I just thought that, it&#x2019;s better to have their trust and to be
on the inside than on the outside. If we are working with them, we can inﬂuence the
direction of things. If we are on the outside, we are completely at their mercy. I don&#x2019;t
like being in that situation.”
</p><!--l. 14595--><p class="indent" >  “So you were merely working undercover. I see. Well done, Mr. Bond. Of course,
you realize that you have just likened their behaviour to just one more of these
American gangs. Isn&#x2019;t that where most of them hang out, along the Mexican
border?”
</p><!--l. 14600--><p class="indent" >  “Kyl. . .”
</p><!--l. 14602--><p class="indent" >  “Den, wake up. You might have gone there with the intention of securing our
future, but they seem to be using that over-willingness to wrap you around their little
ﬁnger. Who is really in charge?”

</p><!--l. 14606--><p class="indent" >  He stares out of the window at his tree. Many of its larger branches are now gone.
What is left is a knobbly trunk of stumps.
</p><!--l. 14609--><p class="indent" >  “I was invited to play a special role. That&#x2019;s all. What they are suggesting is not
something illegal or anything.”
</p><!--l. 14612--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s invading people&#x2019;s recreational space with zombie juice, that&#x2019;s what it
is.”
</p><!--l. 14615--><p class="indent" >  For the ﬁrst time, since he has known her, Den thinks that she looks genuinely
upset.
</p><!--l. 14618--><p class="indent" >  “Look at it this way: we are just helping them to maintain the American
dream.”
</p><!--l. 14621--><p class="indent" >  “Ah, the American dream. Fine. Say no more. Well, we&#x2019;re very sorry to disappoint
you, Captain America – you see, here in Great Britain we don&#x2019;t have a dream. That&#x2019;s
because we are actually awake.”
</p><!--l. 14625--><p class="indent" >  “So, you are not keen then,” he inﬂects with a little irony.
</p><!--l. 14627--><p class="indent" >  “The consortium is a well-deﬁned entity, Den. Even if one of its members wanted
to ask you for services outside of the scope of the agreement, it would be
dodgy. America is litigation central. You don&#x2019;t want to mess with that kind of
thing.”
</p><!--l. 14632--><p class="indent" >  “Well, they are going to come back to me. It will be diﬃcult to go back on this
now. That much is certain. I think they now view us as the experts in this
area.”
</p><!--l. 14636--><p class="indent" >  “And you think we could handle it, even if it were legal?”
</p><!--l. 14638--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, I do. I think it puts us in the driving seat. If we are on the inside, then we can
take charge in our own way. After all, we will be the one&#x2019;s with access to the
billboards.”
</p><!--l. 14642--><p class="indent" >  “Just as well.”
</p><!--l. 14644--><p class="indent" >  “Why?”
</p><!--l. 14646--><p class="indent" >  “Because it is probably going of be a pile of trouble for us.”
</p><!--l. 14648--><p class="indent" >  “So what should I do?”
</p><!--l. 14650--><p class="indent" >  “Well. We&#x2019;ll need some kind of policy for dealing with this senator friend of yours.
You realize that, here in the U,K. you could be thrown in prison under the
oﬃcial secrets act for saying anything that the government doesn&#x2019;t like. It isn&#x2019;t
like in the U.S. where they have freedom of speech and information, you
know.”
</p><!--l. 14656--><p class="indent" >  “Maybe that is why they are keen for a British company to be involved?”
</p><!--l. 14659--><p class="indent" >  “Now we&#x2019;re approaching the truth perhaps. The British government are involved in
this too?”
</p><!--l. 14662--><p class="indent" >  “They have links to the consortium, I think.”
</p><!--l. 14664--><p class="indent" >  “We need to be very careful.”
</p><!--l. 14666--><p class="indent" >  Den looks suddenly downcast. What seems like a good idea suddenly seems more
like the rope that will hang him.
</p><!--l. 14669--><p class="indent" >  “And I thought I was onto something.”
</p><!--l. 14671--><p class="indent" >  “More like someone.” She winces. “Sorry – I have to stop that. Bad habit.”

</p><!--l. 14674--><p class="indent" >  Her expression softens and resumes its playfulness. She has beautiful, lively green
eyes, he thinks. She steps forward and takes his ﬁngers and hand and pulls him
towards the door.
</p><!--l. 14678--><p class="indent" >  “Come on,” she says. “I&#x2019;ll buy you a bad Italian coﬀee around the corner and you&#x2019;ll
tell me more about what actually happened in the land of two for the price of
one.”
</p><!--l. 14682--><p class="indent" >  He withdraws his hand and nods.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 14684--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 14685--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 14691--><p class="indent" >  Kylie McLachlan plays with the foam on her cappuccino. The little coﬀee shop is
arty but cramped; it is starting to thin out after a post lunch-time burst of activity. The
air smells of fresh coﬀee and chocolate, and the gurgling hiss of the espresso machine
forces them to speak more loudly than they would like. Den pulls at a croissant and
eats as she speaks.
</p><!--l. 14698--><p class="indent" >  “Hawshaw&#x2019;s a sweet old man who has had dealings with my family for years.” Her
face becomes strangely calm, when she is not joking. Den likes it. Her eyes like
pools of water. “He used to deal in jewellery until gold became the symbol of
the gang culture. When it changed from a symbol of overt wealth to one of
intellectual poverty, he decided that it was no longer something he could deal
in.”
</p><!--l. 14705--><p class="indent" >  She stirs the foam.
</p><!--l. 14707--><p class="indent" >  “He died last year. Just before then, he told me that you should never sacriﬁce
principles for the common will. He found the idea vulgar. Noble ideas come from
individuals with strong messages, not weak instincts that are programmed into our
biology. Strong messages emerge from the chaos of a melting pot of minds and build a
consensus against the odds. They win by natural selection, because they are better
than the alternatives.”
</p><!--l. 14715--><p class="indent" >  “Fine philosophy.”
</p><!--l. 14717--><p class="indent" >  “He died for it.”
</p><!--l. 14719--><p class="indent" >  Den takes a sip of his own blend. “I wonder if anyone can aﬀord to keep to
principles like that in this day and age?”
</p><!--l. 14722--><p class="indent" >  “What makes you think they can&#x2019;t?”
</p><!--l. 14724--><p class="indent" >  “Too many pressures.”
</p><!--l. 14726--><p class="indent" >  “Pressures?”
</p><!--l. 14728--><p class="indent" >  “Politics of production.”
</p><!--l. 14730--><p class="indent" >  A trace of a smile waxes then wanes. “Oh ye man-folk of little backbone.”
</p><!--l. 14732--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m serious. We are constantly under pressure today. It&#x2019;s the economics of our
time. Back in the days of Queen Victoria, you could perhaps have had some lofty
ambitions about building a better world, but now it&#x2019;s more cut-throat than

that.”
</p><!--l. 14737--><p class="indent" >  “Oh that&#x2019;s nonsense. I&#x2019;m serious too,” she counters. “And I&#x2019;m not sure that it was
not even more cut-throat in Victoria&#x2019;s day.”
</p><!--l. 14740--><p class="indent" >  “Everything is about production goals now. The numbers are more important than
the results. Quality is measured as throughput.”
</p><!--l. 14743--><p class="indent" >  “Time is money. It was always a rather simplistic equation.”
</p><!--l. 14745--><p class="indent" >  “But we believe it more these days.”
</p><!--l. 14747--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s a pretty weak excuse.” She puts on a stern expression. “What kind of a man
do you claim to be, Den Morris?”
</p><!--l. 14750--><p class="indent" >  “Sorry, I left my sporran by the vanity mirror.”
</p><!--l. 14752--><p class="indent" >  “Really? How interesting.” She grins. “But you know something? I&#x2019;m not sure
anyone was ever encouraged to stand up to anyone else, not in history, not
now. If you are going to make a stand on principles then you have to do it
without the sanction of your proverbial ‘times&#x2019;. That&#x2019;s just the sad lament of the
wicked.”
</p><!--l. 14758--><p class="indent" >  Den stuﬀs a piece of croissant into his mouth to avoid having to reply.
</p><!--l. 14760--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s where dear old Mr. Hawshaw was a hero. I tend to think that the
strong characters of history have always been the ones who were just crazy
enough to defy common lore and stick to their guns like that. None of them had
their lives made easier by making the choices that they made, but somehow
they traded practical discomfort for an equivalent mental anguish. Though
they do tend to be revered posthumously rather than by their peers, which is
unfortunate.”
</p><!--l. 14768--><p class="indent" >  “Mary Queen of Scots?”
</p><!--l. 14770--><p class="indent" >  “Speaking of cut-throat.”
</p><!--l. 14772--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s not a very comforting thought.”
</p><!--l. 14774--><p class="indent" >  “You might be right, but come on. Maybe that&#x2019;s exactly our problem these days: too
much comfort. We&#x2019;re not used to getting our hands dirty, not willing to take chances
anymore. The pain threshold is lower. Everything is too safe, too controlled.” She
shakes her hands in mock fear. “We never even try to swim upstream because we can&#x2019;t
dial it up on our mobile.”
</p><!--l. 14781--><p class="indent" >  “Is that what you think I&#x2019;m being asked to do? Go with the ﬂow?”
</p><!--l. 14783--><p class="indent" >  “Isn&#x2019;t that what marketing is about? Creating a ﬂow to go with?”
</p><!--l. 14785--><p class="indent" >  “Partly, I suppose.”
</p><!--l. 14787--><p class="indent" >  “Seems to me that these cronies from Washington have created a ﬂow of their own,
with the meeting you attended, and they sucked you right in, with a little rattling of
the bling bling.”
</p><!--l. 14791--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t think of myself as a gangster yet.”
</p><!--l. 14793--><p class="indent" >  “Glad to hear it, Den Morris. Wi&#x2019;or&#x2019;wi&#x2019;out yarr sporran.”
</p><!--l. 14795--><p class="indent" >  Den smiles.
</p><!--l. 14797--><p class="indent" >  “There, that&#x2019;s better.”
</p><!--l. 14799--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 14801--><p class="indent" >  “A smile.”

</p><!--l. 14803--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m a little ray of sunshine.”
</p><!--l. 14805--><p class="indent" >  “Do you good to laugh a little more. You always were a rather serious man, Den
Morris.”
</p><!--l. 14808--><p class="indent" >  “Me?”
</p><!--l. 14810--><p class="indent" >  “Oh, not so?”
</p><!--l. 14812--><p class="indent" >  “I have no idea what you&#x2019;re talking about.”
</p><!--l. 14814--><p class="indent" >  “We see it you know,” she says.
</p><!--l. 14816--><p class="indent" >  “Sorry?”
</p><!--l. 14818--><p class="indent" >  “We see the change.”
</p><!--l. 14820--><p class="indent" >  His face is a question mark.
</p><!--l. 14822--><p class="indent" >  “In society. I have a friend who is a barrister, working on criminal law. He&#x2019;s a bit
older than I am. He says that people do not have the same concept of right and wrong
as they used to.”
</p><!--l. 14826--><p class="indent" >  “Doesn&#x2019;t every generation say that?”
</p><!--l. 14828--><p class="indent" >  “Possibly, but it is not always objectively true.”
</p><!--l. 14830--><p class="indent" >  “And he thinks it is true now? Why?”
</p><!--l. 14832--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s because we have everything we want. You and I are criminals. The law does
not have daily consequences for us, so we tend to ignore it, try its limits. In the past
you would have had to rely more on others around you. That&#x2019;s what makes society
work, and the law was made to reﬂect that cooperation. Today, your little gadgets
make you invincible and you don&#x2019;t have to think of the well-being of anyone except
your nearest and dearest. And if you should want for something, you can just order it
take-away from your wristband.”
</p><!--l. 14841--><p class="indent" >  “So you think people are weak?”
</p><!--l. 14843--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s not just that. They are not just weak, they are unable to appreciate the law.
Why should you agree to be nice to anyone else, when you can have anything you
want at the push of a button?”
</p><!--l. 14847--><p class="indent" >  “You are a misunderstood genius, Kyl.”
</p><!--l. 14849--><p class="indent" >  “Why thank you, sir.” she struts. “Then, have I ever told you that you are a
handsome man, and just a little sweet?”
</p><!--l. 14852--><p class="indent" >  “Now, that sounds a lot like me,” he agrees. “It&#x2019;s my ragged, unshaven
charm.”
</p><!--l. 14855--><p class="indent" >  “Something like that.”
</p><!--l. 14857--><p class="indent" >  Den looks at his wristband, stretches back and rubs that back of his neck. “I could
do with a swim.”
</p><!--l. 14860--><p class="indent" >  “Why not? Oﬀ you go then.”
</p><!--l. 14862--><p class="indent" >  “Want to join me?”
</p><!--l. 14864--><p class="indent" >  “Oh no. Not unless you talking about a quick one behind the bike shed?”
</p><!--l. 14866--><p class="indent" >  “Ah. Is that how you do it in the law courts?”
</p><!--l. 14868--><p class="indent" >  “Every chance we get.”
</p><!--l. 14870--><p class="indent" >  “Well not this time. I should really be getting back. This thing is buzzing away. . .”
He lifts and rattles his mobile wristband.
</p><!--l. 14873--><p class="indent" >  “Me too. Come on then.”

</p><!--l. 14875--><p class="indent" >  She rises up, pulling her skirt down a little as she extricates herself from the tables
and chair of the little coﬀee shop. Den follows.
</p><!--l. 14878--><p class="indent" >  They step out into the whining of the London Open Air Experience. It is slightly
quieter now, but the sound is more irritating. Den is still old enough that he
remembers the days before compulsory electriﬁcation of the inner-city traﬃc,
when the rumbling of petrol and diesel engines was the sound of the city
purring.
</p><!--l. 14884--><p class="indent" >  He puts his arm around Kylie McLachlan as they walk the hundred metres back to
Grapevine.
</p><!--l. 14887--><p class="indent" >  “You&#x2019;re worried about our complicity in something unethical?” he comments as
they walk.
</p><!--l. 14890--><p class="indent" >  She nods slightly. “It&#x2019;s not so much the ethics. You can debate that, but I am
worried about the complicity in something criminal.”
</p><!--l. 14893--><p class="indent" >  “This is congress and Interpol. They are the law.”
</p><!--l. 14895--><p class="indent" >  “Oh yes! Go Sylvester!”
</p><!--l. 14897--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t see that we are complicit by fulﬁlling a contract, if it comes to
that.”
</p><!--l. 14899--><p class="indent" >  “If it comes to something in writing, we are at least on ﬁrmer ground.”
</p><!--l. 14901--><p class="indent" >  “Did you see TIME?”
</p><!--l. 14903--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t read magazines much.”
</p><!--l. 14905--><p class="indent" >  “Never mind. I&#x2019;ll try to get something in writing.”
</p><!--l. 14907--><p class="indent" >  “If it&#x2019;s legit, they shouldn&#x2019;t mind.”
</p><!--l. 14909--><p class="indent" >  “I sort of have the feeling that&#x2019;s not the way it&#x2019;s supposed to be done here,” he says.
“It feels as though it should be a gentleman&#x2019;s agreement.”
</p><!--l. 14913--><p class="indent" >  “Well, without wanting to sound like a rabid feminist. I would say that gentlemen&#x2019;s
agreements are just a nice way of saying rampant corruption.”
</p><!--l. 14917--><p class="indent" >  Den does not reply.
</p><!--l. 14919--><p class="indent" >  “But I can try to call some friends and ask them to put out feelers?”
</p><!--l. 14921--><p class="indent" >  “To check out the legality?”
</p><!--l. 14923--><p class="indent" >  “To check out the people, ﬁrst. Do either of us really know who these people
are?”
</p><!--l. 14926--><p class="indent" >  “I got Mary to pull me a bunch of stuﬀ on Cathy Kim.”
</p><!--l. 14928--><p class="indent" >  “Is that what you call safe sex?”
</p><!--l. 14930--><p class="indent" >  “Just wanted to know who she was. She seemed legitimate.”
</p><!--l. 14932--><p class="indent" >  “Well, that kind of thing can easily be faked.”
</p><!--l. 14934--><p class="indent" >  They come to the Grapevine entrance and McLachlan stops..
</p><!--l. 14936--><p class="indent" >  She checks a list of contacts. “I could do some checking. I&#x2019;ve got Arjan Latiﬁ. He is
quite new to me, but he knows a lot about government dealings in the E.U.. He
might be able to help us. I can get Sanihje to call him up for lunch. She&#x2019;s a
sweetie.”
</p><!--l. 14941--><p class="indent" >  “Aaron Oxley came by and asked after you, by the way.”
</p><!--l. 14943--><p class="indent" >  “Me? Now what would he want?” She sighs.
</p><!--l. 14945--><p class="indent" >  “You coming back up?”

</p><!--l. 14947--><p class="indent" >  She shakes her head. “Have to be somewhere.”
</p><!--l. 14949--><p class="indent" >  “All right. See you then.”
</p><!--l. 14951--><p class="indent" >  She winks at him. “Yeah. Fuck you later, handsome.”
</p><!--l. 14955--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-32r29"></a>
<a 
