<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">29</span>
</p><!--l. 14959--><p class="indent" >  A ﬂuﬀy white face is peering at her through the brambles and branches. Vibe is
exhausted and shaken, but the sheep seems unconcerned of her plight. It is merely
curious as to what the hell she is doing there in such a stupid place. Well, she
thinks, if sheep have managed to get here, this must be about the stupidest
place to be. You can always trust sheep to get themselves into the biggest
trouble.
</p><!--l. 14966--><p class="indent" >  She feels herself beginning to tire. At least she is out of reach of her pursuers. It is
unlikely that they can hear her from up there. She has the aural camouﬂage of wind
and water to hide her.
</p><!--l. 14970--><p class="indent" >  The fear has passed, but she is as taut as the branch she is holding onto. If she
removes a hand, she will surely fall.
</p><!--l. 14973--><p class="indent" >  It reminds her dismally of a rock-climbing experience, when she was hanging on in
a freezing wind with ﬁngers she could barely feel. She was not even certain that her
cold body could move fast enough to save her if she moved, so she petriﬁed in that
position until someone tightened a rope. But there is no rope here to catch
her.
</p><!--l. 14979--><p class="indent" >  The sheep seems to lose interest in her, obviously she is not entertaining enough.
She needs to do something soon.
</p><!--l. 14982--><p class="indent" >  The mud beneath her seems to have packed since she stopped moving, and her
elbow is well dug in. She feels some purchase at her hip, and risks drawing her knees
up to her stomach. The extra strain on the branch makes it give a little, and she stops.
Another adrenalin ﬂood knocks her slightly senseless, and she has to pause. She tries
again, and this time manages to bring her boots up to the edge of the ledge, so that all
of her is on approximately solid ground. Now, if she can somehow pack the mud
underneath her, to get enough friction to press with her calves, she could
release one hand and try to get out of her backpack, which is pinning her
down.
</p><!--l. 14993--><p class="indent" >  The branch gives and she recoils. Her legs brake her slightly, but not enough and

she is catapulted uncontrollably backwards, and slides over the edge.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 14997--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 14998--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 15002--><p class="indent" >  When she comes to her senses, Vibe is incredulous to ﬁnd that she has not moved
more than half a metre. Her backpack is snagged on a branch and it now pins her, on
her side, hanging just over the edge of the ledge. So all that time hanging on
had been a waste of strength. Now she is exhausted and just as trapped as
before.
</p><!--l. 15008--><p class="indent" >  She risks straining forward to look over the edge. It&#x2019;s not that far down to more
slope, but she would have hurt herself had she fallen uncontrolled. She reviews her
options. At least she now has her hands free. Her backside is wedge uncomfortably on
a rock at the edge. If she releases the backpack straps, it should be possible to get out
of it. Then, if she falls, at least she stands a chance of landing properly. What the
hell.
</p><!--l. 15016--><p class="indent" >  She undoes the waist strap, feeling the relief of pressure there, and then carefully
twists her upper arm out of the shoulder strap. It sears at her hip, with all her body
weight supported by the friction of her hip and buttock, but it feels solid enough to
roll onto her stomach and clutch at grass and shrubs with her hands. She is
out.
</p><!--l. 15023--><p class="indent" >  She drags her backpack free and clambers carefully down the remaining incline to
another rocky trail. Best to sit here for a moment and recover her state of
mind.
</p><!--l. 15028--><p class="indent" >  “Are you okay?” A voice calls, something between a call and a whisper. She hears
the rustling of a jacket running towards her.
</p><!--l. 15031--><p class="indent" >  Vibe looks around and sees a middle aged man in dark blue waterproofs clambering
over the terrain towards her.
</p><!--l. 15034--><p class="indent" >  “Are you Sara Stensrud?”
</p><!--l. 15036--><p class="indent" >  She starts and a ﬂood of adrenalin whitens the world. “How do. . .”
</p><!--l. 15038--><p class="indent" >  “About time too,” he says. “Wait a minute.”
</p><!--l. 15040--><p class="indent" >  He wriggles something in his gloves.
</p><!--l. 15042--><p class="indent" >  ”Frank? Checkpoint three. We&#x2019;ve found Sara.”
</p><!--l. 15044--><p class="indent" >  She stares at him. He does not look dangerous. He does not look like someone who
would threaten her.
</p><!--l. 15047--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m with the local police. Why didn&#x2019;t you report in sooner?”
</p><!--l. 15050--><p class="indent" >  She looks glum.
</p><!--l. 15052--><p class="indent" >  “Are you hurt?”
</p><!--l. 15054--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t think so.”
</p><!--l. 15056--><p class="indent" >  “You had a bit of a slide. You could have broken something.”
</p><!--l. 15058--><p class="indent" >  She nods.

</p><!--l. 15060--><p class="indent" >  “We thought perhaps you had had an accident or were in trouble.”
</p><!--l. 15062--><p class="indent" >  “As it happens. . .not until you came.”
</p><!--l. 15064--><p class="indent" >  Sceptical regard taints her welcome start.
</p><!--l. 15066--><p class="indent" >  “Sorry. I didn&#x2019;t mean it like that.”
</p><!--l. 15068--><p class="indent" >  “You could have ruined our operation.”
</p><!--l. 15070--><p class="indent" >  “Your operation?”
</p><!--l. 15072--><p class="indent" >  He sighs, and pulls his hood oﬀ, looking around. Lowering his voice again, he says:
“Haven&#x2019;t you been paying attention? We have a situation here. There are gangs
roaming around. We are still trying to round up the remainders. They can still be
dangerous.”.
</p><!--l. 15077--><p class="indent" >  She chews her lip and gives him sad puppy eyes. Best not to say anything for
now.
</p><!--l. 15080--><p class="indent" >  Ten minutes pass before Frank clambers into view.
</p><!--l. 15082--><p class="indent" >  “Hello again,” he says, panting.
</p><!--l. 15084--><p class="indent" >  “Hi.”
</p><!--l. 15086--><p class="indent" >  “You okay? Heard you had a fall. . .”
</p><!--l. 15088--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m okay.”
</p><!--l. 15090--><p class="indent" >  “Told you we should have walked together.”
</p><!--l. 15092--><p class="indent" >  She curls her lip.
</p><!--l. 15094--><p class="indent" >  “You didn&#x2019;t ﬁnd your friends, I take it?”
</p><!--l. 15096--><p class="indent" >  She shakes her head marginally. “I had this idea, and got distracted. I thought I
could ﬁnish my work. So I never made it to Leirvassbu and didn&#x2019;t ﬁnd them. I&#x2019;m
headed there now.”
</p><!--l. 15100--><p class="indent" >  “Not now you&#x2019;re not.”
</p><!--l. 15102--><p class="indent" >  “We&#x2019;d better get you to the road,” the other says.
</p><!--l. 15104--><p class="indent" >  “The road?”
</p><!--l. 15106--><p class="indent" >  “There&#x2019;s a patrol car waiting. But we&#x2019;ll have to wait a while. We have a straggler
coming this way.”
</p><!--l. 15110--><p class="indent" >  “But I have to get to Leirvassbu.”
</p><!--l. 15112--><p class="indent" >  “No way, not now. You&#x2019;ll have to come with us along the valley.”
</p><!--l. 15114--><p class="indent" >  “But..! I have a meeting I have to get to.”
</p><!--l. 15116--><p class="indent" >  “Sorry. That&#x2019;s out of the question now,” the other man says.
</p><!--l. 15118--><p class="indent" >  A surge of rage and tantrum threatens to surface in her. She recognizes it and
breathes slowly to let it pass.
</p><!--l. 15121--><p class="indent" >  “I was headed towards the cabin. I am supposed to be staying there with a private
group for a few days.”
</p><!--l. 15124--><p class="indent" >  “We can&#x2019;t let you spoil our operation. Anyway, it will be winter any day soon. You
shouldn&#x2019;t really be up here alone anyway. It&#x2019;s not safe.”
</p><!--l. 15127--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s why I need to ﬁnish my work. If I could only ﬁnd the team. . .”
</p><!--l. 15129--><p class="indent" >  “Hang on – we&#x2019;re on. Here he comes. We have his mobile signal. He should be line
of sight now. Better get down and look as though you are having a hiking
break.”
</p><!--l. 15133--><p class="indent" >  “Is that who was following me?”

</p><!--l. 15135--><p class="indent" >  “Our straggler. You saw him?”
</p><!--l. 15137--><p class="indent" >  “There was someone behind me. I could see him from up there. Maybe a kilometre
behind me. I didn&#x2019;t know who it was. I was taking the high road to stay dry and avoid
the bushes.”
</p><!--l. 15141--><p class="indent" >  “So why did you come down here?”
</p><!--l. 15143--><p class="indent" >  “I thought. . .”
</p><!--l. 15145--><p class="indent" >  They wait for her.
</p><!--l. 15147--><p class="indent" >  “I saw this other person up ahead and . . . it spooked me.”
</p><!--l. 15149--><p class="indent" >  “Why?”
</p><!--l. 15151--><p class="indent" >  She shrugs. Now is not the time to be telling them about Lindgren&#x2019;s bizarre
message. Stupid girl. “What makes you think he&#x2019;ll come down here?”
</p><!--l. 15155--><p class="indent" >  “We don&#x2019;t know. We have someone up there too. That&#x2019;s probably who you
saw.”
</p><!--l. 15158--><p class="indent" >  She nods.
</p><!--l. 15160--><p class="indent" >  “There are still two more that we haven&#x2019;t located yet.”
</p><!--l. 15162--><p class="indent" >  “Wait, I have an idea.”
</p><!--l. 15164--><p class="indent" >  They look at her quizzically.
</p><!--l. 15166--><p class="indent" >  “Maybe I can help?”
</p><!--l. 15170--><p class="indent" >  A message comes in; they do not have time to respond.
</p><!--l. 15172--><p class="indent" >  “Wait – Finn has him in sight. Top road. We&#x2019;re okay – just stay out of sight and
keep quiet.”
</p><!--l. 15175--><p class="indent" >  She purses her lips.
</p><!--l. 15178--><p class="indent" >  Quietly, he says: “We&#x2019;ll have to walk along the valley before we can get onto a trail
where we can use transport. From there we can take you to the lensman&#x2019;s
oﬃce.”
</p><!--l. 15183--><p class="indent" >  “Will I be allowed to come back up here and work again afterwards?”
</p><!--l. 15185--><p class="indent" >  “Can&#x2019;t say.”
</p><!--l. 15187--><p class="indent" >  “But my work?”
</p><!--l. 15189--><p class="indent" >  “Safety ﬁrst.”
</p><!--l. 15191--><p class="indent" >  Vibe ﬂicks through the settings on her mobile.
</p><!--l. 15193--><p class="indent" >  “What&#x2019;s that beeping?”
</p><!--l. 15195--><p class="indent" >  Shit. She looks more sheepish than the sheep she was staring at. “Something I was
supposed to do earlier. I have a form to send.”
</p><!--l. 15198--><p class="indent" >  “Sounds like its mandatory. Mountain rescue?”
</p><!--l. 15200--><p class="indent" >  She nods. “Maybe I should just send it.”
</p><!--l. 15202--><p class="indent" >  “Maybe you should.”
</p><!--l. 15204--><p class="indent" >  She smiles or grimaces, as if to say “sorry” with her teeth and pushes the button.
They will probably hang her for this, in some appropriate country, after she has been
sentences to hard labour for most of her life.
</p><!--l. 15208--><p class="indent" >  Some how things look bleak. Her body feels the bleakness. She feels . . .
bleak.
</p><!--l. 15210--><p class="indent" >  Vibe wearily pulls up the positions of the VeiVeks, while they are waiting, and sees
that they are still heading towards a few main cabins, close to the main mountain road.

It looks as though the French want to collect them and do a runner. They are retrieving
them and pulling out – without any consultation or consideration. That was not the
arrangement they were supposed to have. Betrayal. Not merely bleakness, but
mutiny.
</p><!--l. 15218--><p class="indent" >  They wait in tense silence for several long minutes. Then they hear a crack.
</p><!--l. 15221--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s it. He&#x2019;s down.”
</p><!--l. 15223--><p class="indent" >  “You shot him?” She looks shocked.
</p><!--l. 15225--><p class="indent" >  “Tranquilizer dart.”
</p><!--l. 15227--><p class="indent" >  “Elephant juice.”
</p><!--l. 15229--><p class="indent" >  Whatever kind of idiots the hooligans might be, the idea of death close by is more
than she wants to experience.
</p><!--l. 15232--><p class="indent" >  “Oh.”
</p><!--l. 15234--><p class="indent" >  “We might shoot bad buys in our spare time,” Frank says, waving his ﬁnger at her
mobile interface, “but in the real world, it costs too much”.
</p><!--l. 15237--><p class="indent" >  “Now we just have to do something with the body. The helicopter is too far
away. We&#x2019;ll have to package him and walk him out of here, unless he gives us
trouble.”
</p><!--l. 15241--><p class="indent" >  “That means we&#x2019;ll be oﬀ soon.”
</p><!--l. 15243--><p class="indent" >  “But that means I can go to Leirvassbu now. It must be the closest point to the road
for any of us?”
</p><!--l. 15246--><p class="indent" >  “But we don&#x2019;t know where the others are. We haven&#x2019;t searched that way
yet.”
</p><!--l. 15249--><p class="indent" >  “So isn&#x2019;t it a good time to do it?”
</p><!--l. 15251--><p class="indent" >  “We need to join Finn up there on the higher trail.”
</p><!--l. 15253--><p class="indent" >  “Okay, let&#x2019;s gather our things. Are you okay, Sara?”
</p><!--l. 15255--><p class="indent" >  She stares at him without answering him either verbally or non-verbally. “What if I
could help you to ﬁnd the last gang members?”
</p><!--l. 15259--><p class="indent" >  Smiles broaden their sunshine faces. “Oh no you don&#x2019;t.”
</p><!--l. 15261--><p class="indent" >  “But I have a network of little spies up here, with their own network, and they have
been little magnets for these assholes already.”
</p><!--l. 15264--><p class="indent" >  They look at one another. “Don&#x2019;t see what you could do.”
</p><!--l. 15266--><p class="indent" >  “Track them down for starters.”
</p><!--l. 15268--><p class="indent" >  “How?”
</p><!--l. 15270--><p class="indent" >  “I could start by asking them the last time they encountered someone. They are
programmed to register the passing hikers – it&#x2019;s our way of searching for intelligent
life in the national park.”
</p><!--l. 15274--><p class="indent" >  “Well, I think we can agree that that discounts ﬁnding any of our targets,” says the
local policeman.
</p><!--l. 15277--><p class="indent" >  “But you could see where there has been activity. It might give you a search
area.”
</p><!--l. 15281--><p class="indent" >  “Okay – tell us.”
</p><!--l. 15283--><p class="indent" >  “So I can stay?”
</p><!--l. 15285--><p class="indent" >  “I doubt it. No promises.”

</p><!--l. 15287--><p class="indent" >  “Tell us what you know ﬁrst, and then we&#x2019;ll talk about it.”
</p><!--l. 15289--><p class="indent" >  Vibe nods. “Don&#x2019;t suppose you have anything to drink? I&#x2019;m freezing.”
</p><!--l. 15291--><p class="indent" >  “Put some layers on and keep warm. Then follow me down to the main checkpoint.
You need to keep moving or you&#x2019;ll stiﬀen up.”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 15299--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 15300--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 15303--><p class="indent" >  Vibe calls out to her little babies. She feels like some kind of goddess,
sending out her summons across the lands. Hark subjects! Your lady calls.
Little sparks of electromagnetic sermon hail the moist air in the mountain
valley.
</p><!--l. 15308--><p class="indent" >  Her coverage is not as good as before. She has lost contact with about a third of
them. Some must have moved out of range. That would never have happened without
the interference of The Adversary. Part of the Mars programming they are testing out
is to prevent them from moving too far apart for too long, so that they do not lose
contact with one another. Otherwise they could lose their way, or lose one another.
They should be small and numerous, and the general helpers should bind the experts
together. There are no geosynchronous satellites around Mars to join them together, or
to send them a positioning signal. The inﬁltrators of the God of War can not rely on an
umbilical.
</p><!--l. 15319--><p class="indent" >  Probably her panicked French team-mates, if that is indeed what she ought to
call them, have long since overridden such concerns. She needs line of sight
between all the VeiVeks for communications to work in an ad hoc relay mode.
Now that the transmitter is gone, there is no centralized relay point. Trying to
talk to them is essentially like spreading rumours. Say, have you seen X?
Don&#x2019;t know, I can only see Y and Z, I&#x2019;ll ask them. Can&#x2019;t see anyone else right
now.
</p><!--l. 15327--><p class="indent" >  So then: she looses her magic arrow and starts the communion.Go, Quicksilver,
seek and report from the Eastern front! Coz I gotta know, yeah, I really gotta know.
Yeah, baby.
</p><!--l. 15331--><p class="indent" >  Vibe maps the command program into her specs and blackens the lenses to cut out
the daylight. It will be quicker if she can tie into her VR interface. She can watch the
picture build up and go straight to the relevant data. It&#x2019;s all there. She has been
working on this for some time.
</p><!--l. 15337--><p class="indent" >  Signals rush out across the marsh, reﬂect from the bare rock and return from the
stark edges of the valley. Speak to me, with many voices. Tell me of what you
know.
</p><!--l. 15341--><p class="indent" >  The ﬁrst few answer quickly. The closest is perhaps a kilometre away, based on the
timing. At that distance, this will cost her her batteries. She should not stay on too
long. But it will be worth it. She is logging all of the data she receives from the little

robots whenever she can. It can all be analyzed later. Just keep it safe from the
Adversary.
</p><!--l. 15348--><p class="indent" >  So, into the First.
</p><!--l. 15350--><p class="indent" >  –Greetings lady, I bid you welcome.
</p><!--l. 15352--><p class="indent" >  –Tell me what you know, my subject.
</p><!--l. 15354--><p class="indent" >  –Ah, what can I say? I hear the hissing of the sun and stars in these microwave ears.
All is quiet here until your great voice hailed me to your service.
</p><!--l. 15357--><p class="indent" >  –Good, good, little friend. Tell me of any others.
</p><!--l. 15359--><p class="indent" >  –Ah, the eyes that last I saw in kind: my neighbour. Let me relay you to
him.
</p><!--l. 15361--><p class="indent" >  –Stand still friend. Let me stand on your giant shoulders that I might see farther.
And you, tell me subject, who have you seen?
</p><!--l. 15364--><p class="indent" >  –Greetings lady, I am the second. I have seen more. Not two hours past, I observed
a temperature anomaly – the tinge of warm ﬂesh – and a seismic tremor – the
thumping of boots on the hard ground. The signal of a communications beacon lit my
world, thundering against the song of sun and stars. I present you its captured ID as
my humble oﬀering.
</p><!--l. 15370--><p class="indent" >  The communion continues and is over within a matter of seconds. The positions of
the little robots have not altered signiﬁcantly. They cannot move very quickly across
the terrain, even with their advanced power sources. She can still reach a few of
them, but the others are in shadow of the mountains somewhere. She can talk
to ﬁve of her babies from this point. But that has already revealed useful
information.
</p><!--l. 15378--><p class="indent" >  The sensor logs for tourist encounters mostly date from several days ago. None of
the VeiVeks along the valley has seen anyone for some time, except for the second to
answer. That is what one would expect from a mountain that has been forcibly
quiescent. The VeiVeks she met a few days ago have moved out of range. She can just
read one behind her. She sees that it has been attacked with paint-balls, but that was
several days ago.
</p><!--l. 15386--><p class="indent" >  Vibe feels uplifting satisfaction at her own ability to see. This proves perhaps that
the VeiVeks can be useful in the mountains, in search and rescue operations, even here
on Earth. They have not been able to test this before, but she understands the
signiﬁcance of the result. And she will save the evidence for her thesis.
</p><!--l. 15392--><p class="indent" >  She saves the mobile ID inside a note and makes it ready for passing on to Frank
and his friend. She pulls oﬀ the glasses and packs them carefully into her
backpack.
</p><!--l. 15396--><p class="indent" >  In the distance, she hears the stomping of someone approaching. She rotates her
upper body and feels the numbness of her backside, on the cold rock. Frank is
coming.
</p><!--l. 15400--><p class="indent" >  “Get anything?”
</p><!--l. 15402--><p class="indent" >  “Actually, yes.”
</p><!--l. 15404--><p class="indent" >  “Really?”
</p><!--l. 15406--><p class="indent" >  “Are you impressed?” She grins.

</p><!--l. 15408--><p class="indent" >  He nods. “If it&#x2019;s true. It would be great.”
</p><!--l. 15410--><p class="indent" >  “Why wouldn&#x2019;t it be true?”
</p><!--l. 15412--><p class="indent" >  “Ah, sorry. I didn&#x2019;t mean it quite like that.”
</p><!--l. 15414--><p class="indent" >  His friend comes too, a little older, a little more jaded. “You have to tell us what
you found ﬁrst. Then we can decide if it&#x2019;s a lead we can use.”
</p><!--l. 15417--><p class="indent" >  “Okay.” She pulls oﬀ her wrist strap and ﬂattens it out across her knee. “Are you
ready to receive some data? I can send it broadcast.”
</p><!--l. 15420--><p class="indent" >  “Ugh, I&#x2019;m not sure we can accept data from civilians. . .”
</p><!--l. 15422--><p class="indent" >  “Yes we can,” Frank shows him. “Just go to Receive Evidence and open a
sandbox.”
</p><!--l. 15424--><p class="indent" >  “Okay.”
</p><!--l. 15426--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Don&#x2019;t they train these monkeys to use their bananas? </span>Vibe thinks.
</p><!--l. 15428--><p class="indent" >  “Okay – ready to receive.”
</p><!--l. 15430--><p class="indent" >  She transmits on short-range. A map and a mobile ID on the person she
detected.
</p><!--l. 15432--><p class="indent" >  “The sighting is a couple of hours old, so that gives you a search area, I
guess.”
</p><!--l. 15434--><p class="indent" >  “We could check it out.”
</p><!--l. 15436--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s not that far away.”
</p><!--l. 15438--><p class="indent" >  Frank grins. “I can check where the &#x2019;copter is.”
</p><!--l. 15440--><p class="indent" >  The other nods.
</p><!--l. 15442--><p class="indent" >  “How many more do we have to ﬁnd?”
</p><!--l. 15444--><p class="indent" >  “Based on the original surveillance, two more. It would be a big plus if we could
locate them quickly. We could ask the boss.”
</p><!--l. 15446--><p class="indent" >  Switch on the Voice That Gets You What You Want. “You know, if the helicopter
could give me a ride, I could contact all my babies much more quickly from the
air. . . The trouble is that the mountains shield my signal, and the range is
limited.”
</p><!--l. 15451--><p class="indent" >  “Your babies?”
</p><!--l. 15453--><p class="indent" >  “Robots.”
</p><!--l. 15455--><p class="indent" >  “Right.”
</p><!--l. 15457--><p class="indent" >  The oﬃcers&#x2019; eyes question one another, attempting to switch their minds to
comprehension and trust. Busy day, too much to process. Cold and damp. The thought
lingers, broken oﬀ by a nod. “I suppose I can ask. Let me see if I can reach the
command car.” The other wags a lingering nod and moves oﬀ to make a
call.
</p><!--l. 15462--><p class="indent" >  Frank risks a prototypical smile. “So you&#x2019;re going to save us?”
</p><!--l. 15464--><p class="indent" >  She shrugs. “I&#x2019;ll do what I can.”
</p><!--l. 15466--><p class="indent" >  He smiles and steps away over the stones, leaving her standing there, sending her a
look without even looking at her. She feels it burning into her humility. Shy boy. He
likes her.
</p><!--l. 15470--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Goddamn you, Peter Green. Why can&#x2019;t you rescue me from my agony? </span>Why is she
still hanging on to that idea?

</p><!--l. 15473--><p class="indent" >  Her rear end plops down onto a stone, half in a huﬀ and half in exhaustion. Around
her, sheer tonnage of rock impresses its stature on the land. She feels as though she
could be transformed into this landscape, if she remains here. She is small and weak
and tired. Eggs lake. Head hurts.
</p><!--l. 15479--><p class="indent" >  For a moment she forgets even the mobile that clasps her body with its technopathic
tethers. She could dial comfort and understanding in a heartbeat, but she just feels
weary.
</p><!--l. 15483--><p class="indent" >  After a short recess, the other comes back.
</p><!--l. 15485--><p class="indent" >  “Sara!”
</p><!--l. 15487--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah.”
</p><!--l. 15489--><p class="indent" >  “Tap in to this call.”
</p><!--l. 15491--><p class="indent" >  She surfaces and touches her tie-in sequence. An image appear in her glasses. It
seems to be from within the command car. Some police oﬃcer.
</p><!--l. 15494--><p class="indent" >  “Sara Stensrud?”
</p><!--l. 15496--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s me.”
</p><!--l. 15498--><p class="indent" >  “My name is detective sergeant Myhre. I hear you want to help us.”
</p><!--l. 15500--><p class="indent" >  “If I can.”
</p><!--l. 15502--><p class="indent" >  “You have some kind of robots with cameras.”
</p><!--l. 15504--><p class="indent" >  “Not exactly, more like sensors. But they are designed to detect people.”
</p><!--l. 15506--><p class="indent" >  “And you think you can ﬁnd our stragglers?”
</p><!--l. 15508--><p class="indent" >  She nods. “Maybe.”
</p><!--l. 15510--><p class="indent" >  “The oﬃcer says you need the chopper?”
</p><!--l. 15512--><p class="indent" >  “It would give me better access to my robots. We are in communications shadow.
They only have a short range ad hoc net right now. Someone took away our relay
transmitter.”
</p><!--l. 15516--><p class="indent" >  “Tell me about these robots.”
</p><!--l. 15518--><p class="indent" >  She draws a slow breath. “It&#x2019;s a research project, it&#x2019;s registered. Look it
up.”
</p><!--l. 15521--><p class="indent" >  “I already have. I see a mountain watcher project.”
</p><!--l. 15523--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s part of it.”
</p><!--l. 15525--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m checking your ID but I cannot see that you are registered with this mountain
watcher project. . .”
</p><!--l. 15528--><p class="indent" >  “I should be there, but I am not a primary team member. That&#x2019;s just the French and
the Americans. . .”
</p><!--l. 15531--><p class="indent" >  “No, I can&#x2019;t see anything here. Wait a minute.”
</p><!--l. 15533--><p class="indent" >  The line goes dead for a second and then cuts back in.
</p><!--l. 15535--><p class="indent" >  “All right, we found you. A Sara Vibeke Stensrud.”
</p><!--l. 15537--><p class="indent" >  “C&#x2019;est moi.”
</p><!--l. 15539--><p class="indent" >  “All right. They tell me that you have possibly identiﬁed the location of the
stragglers.”
</p><!--l. 15542--><p class="indent" >  “I have a probable sighting.”
</p><!--l. 15544--><p class="indent" >  “We are checking it out now.”
</p><!--l. 15546--><p class="indent" >  “Cool.”

</p><!--l. 15548--><p class="indent" >  “If it checks out, we might be interested in your information.”
</p><!--l. 15550--><p class="indent" >  “Okay.”
</p><!--l. 15552--><p class="indent" >  “I suggest that you listen carefully to these oﬃcers and do as you&#x2019;re told.”
</p><!--l. 15555--><p class="indent" >  She nods, but does not say anything. She is expecting an earful, but it doesn&#x2019;t
come.
</p><!--l. 15558--><p class="indent" >  “If they can have seen anyone, they can tell me. That allows you to either eliminate
some areas or pin-point when and where they were.”
</p><!--l. 15561--><p class="indent" >  “All right, let&#x2019;s give it a try.”
</p><!--l. 15564--><p class="indent" >  “Could you tell me something?”
</p><!--l. 15566--><p class="indent" >  “Yes?”
</p><!--l. 15568--><p class="indent" >  “Is there a Peter Green registered with the current team?”
</p><!--l. 15570--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t know. Is there a problem?”
</p><!--l. 15572--><p class="indent" >  “Good question. Never mind.”
</p><!--l. 15574--><p class="indent" >  “All right, I&#x2019;ll leave you in the hand of the duty oﬃcers.” He cuts out.
</p><!--l. 15577--><p class="indent" >  The other says: “Okay, let&#x2019;s get moving. Can you walk okay?”
</p><!--l. 15580--><p class="indent" >  “I think so.”
</p><!--l. 15582--><p class="indent" >  “Good. Then we should get started before you stiﬀen up.”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 15584--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 15585--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 15588--><p class="indent" >  “Mamma, it&#x2019;s me.”
</p><!--l. 15590--><p class="indent" >  “Hello, stranger. How&#x2019;s your trip?”
</p><!--l. 15592--><p class="indent" >  “Ahh. Next question.”
</p><!--l. 15594--><p class="indent" >  “Is anything wrong?”
</p><!--l. 15596--><p class="indent" >  She explains.
</p><!--l. 15598--><p class="indent" >  “And you&#x2019;re stuck without access to your work? I&#x2019;m so sorry, honey. How
frustrating!”
</p><!--l. 15600--><p class="indent" >  “Actually, they want me to help them catch some low life football hooligans that are
surﬁng on your taxes.”
</p><!--l. 15603--><p class="indent" >  “Sounds important.”
</p><!--l. 15605--><p class="indent" >  “I want to work on my project.”
</p><!--l. 15607--><p class="indent" >  “If they are asking you to help, it&#x2019;s quite a compliment. You should be
proud.”
</p><!--l. 15610--><p class="indent" >  “But it&#x2019;s not my job.”
</p><!--l. 15612--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t pass up an opportunity to do a good deed, Sara. It might be old-fashioned,
but it&#x2019;s something to live by.”
</p><!--l. 15615--><p class="indent" >  “What about my degree?”
</p><!--l. 15617--><p class="indent" >  “Your degree can wait. What happens in the real world is more important. Besides,
in my experience any experience is good experience. It will all help you in the
end.”

</p><!--l. 15621--><p class="indent" >  “Right.”
</p><!--l. 15623--><p class="indent" >  “Take care, little one.”
</p><!--l. 15625--><p class="indent" >  “Wish I could talk to dad.”
</p><!--l. 15627--><p class="indent" >  “Me too.”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 15629--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 15630--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 15634--><p class="indent" >  A helicopter comes. Spiralling air lifts them into a place of open clarity. The rocks
lose their sharpness and she fades away from nature into an urban dullness that haunts
the inside the cabin. Civilization has intruded into her escape. It feels like a
disappointment.
</p><!--l. 15640--><p class="indent" >  The girl is weary, dizzy and nauseous. The helicopter ride seems to be
wrenching at her body, speaking diﬀerently to her skin and to her guts. She feels
out of synch, out of place. The dizziness seems to extend to a sharp pain in
her ears, which slides down a tense muscle to her throat. Everything feels
wrong.
</p><!--l. 15646--><p class="indent" >  Even as she sits, the world becomes greyer and more hostile. Colours are losing
their ﬂavours, and sounds only hurt. She feels as a bucket of water must feel in the
hands of a running window-cleaner. She only hopes that he does not fall oﬀ his
ladder.
</p><!--l. 15651--><p class="indent" >  “So what can you see?” a voice says.
</p><!--l. 15653--><p class="indent" >  They are talking to her. She would turn to face the voice, but the disorientation
presides over her faculties. A recollection of looking for people surfaces and she looks
down at her mobile. There it is, a little larger and heavier than usual. Or is it her hands
that are larger?
</p><!--l. 15659--><p class="indent" >  “Sara?”
</p><!--l. 15661--><p class="indent" >  She focuses on the mobile. The interface is alive; she knows what to do, and yet her
body is sluggish and unresponsive.
</p><!--l. 15664--><p class="indent" >  “Sara? Are you okay?”
</p><!--l. 15666--><p class="indent" >  A map of the mountains appears and she sees the remnants of her little tribe of
babies. They are a rag-tag bunch now, barely cooperating — just ﬂeeing the scene,
like rats responding to a rogue harlequin. All she can think of is how she has been
betrayed by the research team and how she will no longer be able to complete her
research. The reason is no longer important. It is only the knowledge of it that
matters.
</p><!--l. 15674--><p class="indent" >  The helicopter makes a turn, swinging them around, slopping soapy water out of
her bucket. She feels a shiver through her very soul.
</p><!--l. 15677--><p class="indent" >  “Sara?”
</p><!--l. 15679--><p class="indent" >  “Yes?”
</p><!--l. 15681--><p class="indent" >  “You don&#x2019;t look very well. Try to concentrate on the mountains.”

</p><!--l. 15683--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m . . . okay.”
</p><!--l. 15685--><p class="indent" >  But something tells her that she is not. She is not even sure why, she only knows
that she would like to go to sleep.
</p><!--l. 15688--><p class="indent" >  The world falls away as they pass over a mountain. She attempts to connect to her
babies once again. She can see a few more now, but they seem to be spinning around
and her hands are too big to work the controls of her mobile.
</p><!--l. 15693--><p class="indent" >  I am sick, she thinks. This is what it is like to be sick. As a child she can recall lying
in bed with a feverish mirage before her – like a galaxy of swirling dust, full of pins
and needles, rotating in front of her. An astral shield, keeping her in her bed. If she
tried to rise, it would push her down again. It was a frightening experience then, now
she can feel the same sensations returning, as if some old ghost from a childish
nightmare has returned to taunt her.
</p><!--l. 15701--><p class="indent" >  “Sara, look at me.”.
</p><!--l. 15703--><p class="indent" >  There is that voice again. Why can&#x2019;t she turn her head? Is it the dream where she is
paralyzed? Is she asleep now?
</p><!--l. 15706--><p class="indent" >  She feels a growing fear, an anxiety. Something is wrong. It is not possible to put a
ﬁnger on what it is. It is simply growing like a culture of disease, eating into her. The
only thing she can remember is that she is going to fail her doctorate, that
her work is doomed and that they are after her. When they catch her it is
going to be bad. She needs to run, but that is not going to happen any time
soon.
</p><!--l. 15713--><p class="indent" >  Sleep is what she needs.
</p><!--l. 15715--><p class="indent" >  Sleep.
</p><!--l. 15717--><p class="indent" >  As metal blades lunge at the frozen air beyond their cocoon, the sound of
conquered sky thunders above her; emptiness felled by the whirling blade. It tramples
her senses into oblivious denial.
</p><!--l. 15721--><p class="indent" >  And, without her realizing it, darkness comes.
</p><!--l. 15724--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-33r30"></a>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-0"></a>
<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">30</span>
</p><!--l. 15727--><p class="indent" >  The pitter-pattering of wintery rain splashes onto his window. It is hypnotic,
distracting. It is as though nature is trying to gain his attention, trying to communicate
with him in Morse code.
</p><!--l. 15731--><p class="indent" >  What is it trying to say?
</p><!--l. 15733--><p class="indent" >  You must be crazy, Dermot? What a loser Dermot?
</p><!--l. 15735--><p class="indent" >  His combo beeps the arrival of new mail. All around him, little streams of
communication are pleading with his senses, vying for is attention. Look at
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">me</span>!
</p><!--l. 15739--><p class="indent" >  He shakes his head free of its involuntary ruminations and looks for his tea. He is
beginning to get a headache and tea is high in salicylic salts; it is natural aspirin. He
ﬂicks his kettle on in preparation.
</p><!--l. 15744--><p class="indent" >  Beyond his window, silver birches are waving a muted dance as they cling
precariously onto balding foliage. Something metal clanks loudly, blown over in a
guest of wind and penetrates the sound barrier. It is at times like this that Dermot feels
safest, viewing the world from behind a glass membrane, in warm denial of its chilly
bite. He browses forth some classical music and ﬁnds new energy from his glance
though the pane.
</p><!--l. 15752--><p class="indent" >  What is he doing here anyway? He has seldom felt so out of place. He ought to
be working on Bishop&#x2019;s project. Why did he ever agree to it? That&#x2019;s easy
to answer: because he is weak. He cannot say no, but he cannot just do it
either.
</p><!--l. 15757--><p class="indent" >  And Bishop trusts him to do it. That makes him feel a little bad, but then he more or
less forced it on him. Make me a pathogen, Dermot. Where are the ethics? There are
players all over the game who have paid to kill and maim and be lawless, and he wants
to tell them all that they are morally bankrupt and that they should all hail the
police as the saviours of society? Why should he be the one to trick them? It&#x2019;s
dishonest.
</p><!--l. 15764--><p class="indent" >  On the other hand, he can see a certain sense to it. He cannot stand violence in the

real world—outside the game. People are getting dangerous now. Like those Nazi
assholes. There are bad people all over.
</p><!--l. 15769--><p class="indent" >  They&#x2019;ve got griefers messing up their game scenarios in the sims to pot—but
that is not the same thing as having the evangelical churches manipulate
the games for their own gain. That&#x2019;s brainwashing. And what was the latest
thing he heard? The Russian maﬁa moving in on the technology for extortion
purposes? Christ. He doesn&#x2019;t know what to think, and he doesn&#x2019;t know what to
do.
</p><!--l. 15776--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">So why don&#x2019;t I just do as I&#x2019;m told?</span>
</p><!--l. 15778--><p class="indent" >  Maybe because he doesn&#x2019;t know whose judgement to trust. I <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">am </span>a loser, he thinks.
Won&#x2019;t listen, won&#x2019;t do, just mind my own business. And that means nothing. I don&#x2019;t
have any business. I&#x2019;m just a kid. A stupid juvenile. That means I just hide when I
don&#x2019;t know what to do.
</p><!--l. 15783--><p class="indent" >  He makes his tea and slurps its hot essence down a dry throat. Back to the
window.
</p><!--l. 15786--><p class="indent" >  The ground outside is now a slushy mixture of melting snow. Not long ago this was
a delicate whip of pure white crystals. Now the crust at the roadside is a black cement
of car emissions, dirt and water. The janitor has tried to make little piles of leaves,
neatly placed into object-oriented piles. What is the point of making these attempts at
keeping order? The wind keeps on messing them up. Even the household waste is
neatly separated into metal, glass, organic. . . but people are too lazy to check
properly. It gets mixed.
</p><!--l. 15795--><p class="indent" >  Law and order for leaves? It doesn&#x2019;t work.
</p><!--l. 15797--><p class="indent" >  He senses a sigh forming, deep inside his being. Better suppress that. There is not
sense in crying over things that can&#x2019;t be controlled. Force majeur, act of god.
There is no point in having a law unless you can enforce it. It costs to enforce
order.
</p><!--l. 15802--><p class="indent" >  It&#x2019;s all a waste of time. It&#x2019;s a jungle out there.
</p><!--l. 15804--><p class="indent" >  They can&#x2019;t keep anything separated: not out there, not in here. The failure is not in
the objects, he thinks but in the operations and channels between them. The forces that
link them together. . .
</p><!--l. 15808--><p class="indent" >  Hey, wait. The channels. Maybe that&#x2019;s it.
</p><!--l. 15811--><p class="indent" >  Mind returns to the programming task. The game is just as complicated as the
world outside. It&#x2019;s just that when things go crazy, they call it an error instead of an act
of god. And he is the janitor of the Lord of the game, cleaning up these little fragile
piles of leaves and blow around in such a storm.
</p><!--l. 15817--><p class="indent" >  What a loser, Dermot.
</p><!--l. 15819--><p class="indent" >  All right. Integration of the objects is the key to stability. That means that every
prehistoric XML pipe between them is a potential point of failure. But does that mean
that isolation, separatism, objectization is fundamentally the source of the
error? No. That is just housekeeping. The interrelationships are the key to
stability. That is where the problem is. Small services are ﬁne with lightweight
coordination.

</p><!--l. 15826--><p class="indent" >  He feels a surge of satisfaction at the insight.
</p><!--l. 15828--><p class="indent" >  Then there is this other thing. They have adopted such a rigid object model for
programming that it is inﬂexible. You just can&#x2019;t do that. You can&#x2019;t backtrack either,
they&#x2019;ve spent way too much time investing in this model. It would cost too much time
and money. If they are going to change anything here, some other approach will be
needed. Something like social engineering.
</p><!--l. 15835--><p class="indent" >  The ways that modern programs are written, with their closed architecture,
standardized objects means that every game in the world will now inherit the same
class of methods. Inﬁltrating game software with cheap subliminal rendering tricks is
now trivial. Before you know what has happened, entertainment is not the main
channel for mind control.
</p><!--l. 15842--><p class="indent" >  That is what the Indian girl said essentially: they cannot ﬁx the problems of the
game easily because it would mean change for everyone. Everything is controlled
from one place. A house of cards built on a sturdy but bad idea.
</p><!--l. 15847--><p class="indent" >  Weary of the triviality of his options, Dermot puts the coding problem aside. He
ﬁgures that he will sort it out tomorrow now. The crucial insight has been made; that
is enough to put his mind at rest.
</p><!--l. 15852--><p class="indent" >  On the desk, a copy of TIME magazine is lying opened at a signiﬁcant page. He has
been meaning to read that article for some time now — it is the story that blew open
the rumours of the U.S. government&#x2019;s involvement in the game. He should read it.
Bishop gave it to him. He was supposed to read it, to convince him of the usefulness
of what they are doing. Little does he understand yet that he is wasting his time on a
misﬁt.
</p><!--l. 15859--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I don&#x2019;t even care</span>, he realizes. Bishop&#x2019;s arguments are all well and good, but Dermot
is not in the right place to invest emotional currency in a faceless problem of
supernatural proportions. Soon, it will be his compulsory day at the crime centre once
again. It pays well, but his heart is not in it. There seem to be more pressing matters
for him to deal with: like getting his life sorted, like getting laid, maybe even just
getting high once. All this Christian propaganda business seems just a little above his
head.
</p><!--l. 15868--><p class="indent" >  Can it really be as important as they are making it out to be? It&#x2019;s like talking about
the end of the world or something. Wouldn&#x2019;t they have seen some kind of
sign?
</p><!--l. 15872--><p class="indent" >  And then there is the girl. He is not sure what to make of this girl, Prima or
whatever her name is. She is smart, there&#x2019;s no doubt about that, but she has the feeling
of someone self-taught who doesn&#x2019;t quite know the right things to say. On the other
hand, that&#x2019;s cool though. And she&#x2019;s pretty. Very pretty. But not exactly his
type.
</p><!--l. 15878--><p class="indent" >  Loser, Dermot.
</p><!--l. 15880--><p class="indent" >  As for the others. They mainly notice him when he cannot deliver on time, or if he
is absent or sick. Even his father, whom he tried to visit once, treated him like a ghost.
Receiving him was more of a duty to be dispatched than a caring. Once he went to
visit the old man after promising to visit for a long time. When he ﬁnally arrived his

father sat him immediately down at the kitchen table where a single place was set and
presented him with an overcooked dinner plate. One knife, one fork and burned
chicken. Then he announced that he was going out to meet a friend and would be back
in a couple of hours.
</p><!--l. 15890--><p class="indent" >  It is probably his own fault. He has never been very good at ﬁtting in. Well, it&#x2019;s too
late now, unfortunately.
</p>
