</p><!--l. 15894--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 15897--><p class="indent" >  Bishop. Now there&#x2019;s a strange kettle of ﬁsh. The other day, Dermot heard him
talking on his mobile, in the oﬃce down the hall, audio only. It was as though a
diﬀerent person had crawled out of him, ripping the latex mask from his
face.
</p><!--l. 15902--><p class="indent" >  “Hi Cato.”
</p><!--l. 15904--><p class="indent" >  “Ed.”
</p><!--l. 15906--><p class="indent" >  “How&#x2019;s Treena, the kids?”
</p><!--l. 15908--><p class="indent" >  “She&#x2019;s ﬁne. They&#x2019;re all ﬁne.”
</p><!--l. 15910--><p class="indent" >  “What&#x2019;s it been now? Twenty-ﬁve years?”
</p><!--l. 15912--><p class="indent" >  “Something like that.”
</p><!--l. 15914--><p class="indent" >  “Got your health?”
</p><!--l. 15916--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m all right. Not so bad. How about you?”
</p><!--l. 15918--><p class="indent" >  A married man. Bishop is a married man. He has lived with, probably slept with, a
woman for twenty-ﬁve years. They have kids. Is this the same man? If envy were a
reaction to shattered illusion, it would ﬂow out if him. Instead, Dermot feels shame
and humility. It is so far from his life. It is what everyone was supposed to do in those
days, maybe even now. When was it that people stopped getting together like
that?
</p><!--l. 15926--><p class="indent" >  “I suppose you big-wigs are all busy up there?”
</p><!--l. 15928--><p class="indent" >  “Always busy, yes.”
</p><!--l. 15930--><p class="indent" >  As the conversation scraped to a close, arrested by its own friction, Dermot walked
up the hall to look at Bishop—just to check that it really is him. Bishop usually
broadcasts an outward authority. There, in that moment, he was simply small,
an ordinary man. He saw Dermot looking, nodded, and went back to his
business.
</p><!--l. 15937--><p class="indent" >  Dermot prefers not think about his childhood. All he can really remember is being
disinterested in other kids and their families. His family was always distant. It suited
him just ﬁne.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>

<!--l. 15942--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 15943--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 15947--><p class="indent" >  Henrik walks by his desk in the open oﬃce landscape, dressed in purple tights and
a yellow corduroy jacket. His showy oﬃce-mate dresses up as a diﬀerent person each
day. Some bizarre game of his own with role playing. He probably has some serious
personality conﬂict.
</p><!--l. 15954--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">The girl is just a child. What can she possibly know that we don&#x2019;t?</span>
</p><!--l. 15956--><p class="indent" >  How to be a child?
</p><!--l. 15958--><p class="indent" >  What instinct knows, that canned conformity has not shut out. Freedom of spirit?
Fearless adventure?
</p><!--l. 15961--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Should I go on?</span>
</p><!--l. 15964--><p class="indent" >  Henrik says: “No one you meet is ever who they seem to be. When the aliens sent
