</p><!--l. 16358--><p class="indent" >  Jonas has cancelled his meeting and taken a taxi to the police station. Martin is
trailing in toe, hanging onto his hand. He feels ﬂustered and anxious.
</p><!--l. 16362--><p class="indent" >  “Do you have any idea how many calls like this we hear about these days?”
</p><!--l. 16364--><p class="indent" >  “Are you saying they&#x2019;re common?”
</p><!--l. 16366--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m not saying that the threats are not serious, but this is a widespread problem.
It&#x2019;s not yours in particular.”
</p><!--l. 16369--><p class="indent" >  “So you think this is just a crank call?”
</p><!--l. 16371--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s hard to say.”
</p><!--l. 16373--><p class="indent" >  “But I was shot at!”
</p><!--l. 16375--><p class="indent" >  The duty oﬃcer is calm and matter-of-fact. “It&#x2019;s not pleasant for you I would think,
but I don&#x2019;t see what we can do. Still, I think it&#x2019;s best to err on the side of
caution.”
</p><!--l. 16379--><p class="indent" >  Jonas snorts. “Right. Of course, but is there nothing you can do about it? Can&#x2019;t you
ﬁnd out who it&#x2019;s from?”
</p><!--l. 16383--><p class="indent" >  “I doubt it. I can&#x2019;t see anything in the call logs. The call is registered from an
anonymous Internet location, not from a registered mobile ID. That means we can&#x2019;t
ﬁnd out who really sent it.”
</p><!--l. 16387--><p class="indent" >  “Why is that even possible?” Jonas exclaims in exasperation.
</p><!--l. 16389--><p class="indent" >  The oﬃcer on duty wrinkles his brow. “Good question. Freedom of the Internet.
They don&#x2019;t think about the police when they make these contraptions.”
</p><!--l. 16393--><p class="indent" >  Jonas is looking for advice. “So what now? What should I do? I have to ﬁgure out
what to tell his mother.”
</p><!--l. 16396--><p class="indent" >  “Best advice I can give is to watch your back. We&#x2019;ll make a note of your ID and set
up a panic button on your mobile.” He works at his console behind the clear barrier,
manipulating something. “That way the net will monitor you and you have a short-cut
to assistance.”
</p><!--l. 16401--><p class="indent" >  Jonas stares at nothing through a furrowed brow. Why, of all days, does this have to
happen now?

</p><!--l. 16404--><p class="indent" >  The oﬃcer points a sort of wand at him. “There, you should see a police icon on
your display. It will remain there for a week. After that time you must either renew it
by checking in with us, or let it go.”
</p><!--l. 16409--><p class="indent" >  Jonas nods, stroking the hair on Martin&#x2019;s sleepy head. This has been an exhausting
morning for both of them. Martin has barely said a word all morning.
</p><!--l. 16413--><p class="indent" >  “Let us know if there are any further developments. Apart from that, we just have to
wait and see.”
</p><!--l. 16416--><p class="indent" >  Resignation sinks in; he turns to leave but stops short of the exit. He goes
back.
</p><!--l. 16419--><p class="indent" >  “Can&#x2019;t you tell me something about the group?”
</p><!--l. 16421--><p class="indent" >  The oﬃcer is already doing something else, but replies cheerfully as he types away.
“Most likely the Russian mob, but it&#x2019;s hard to say.”
</p><!--l. 16425--><p class="indent" >  What?! “The mob? Why would they be interested in me?”
</p><!--l. 16428--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t be surprised. They have a hand in most things. Wherever they see an
opportunity to gain power or inﬂuence. Used to be sex and drugs, but other things
have grown in importance.”
</p><!--l. 16432--><p class="indent" >  Nausea pervades Jonas&#x2019; mid-regions. He cannot remember having been scared
before. Not like this. Anxiety, he is no stranger to, but fear? Is it real? Isn&#x2019;t that the
