</p><!--l. 16583--><p class="indent" >  Jonas shakes his head. “Something important came up.”
</p><!--l. 16585--><p class="indent" >  “Well, you had better know then.”
</p><!--l. 16587--><p class="indent" >  “Know what?”
</p><!--l. 16589--><p class="indent" >  “Things have been happening this morning while you were away.”
</p><!--l. 16591--><p class="indent" >  “What things?”
</p><!--l. 16593--><p class="indent" >  “They revoked next year&#x2019;s proposal from the council board.”

</p><!--l. 16595--><p class="indent" >  “Who did?”
</p><!--l. 16597--><p class="indent" >  “The ministry,” Alnes adds.
</p><!--l. 16599--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 16601--><p class="indent" >  There is nodding. They exchange signiﬁcant looks.
</p><!--l. 16603--><p class="indent" >  “The ministry wants to override our plan for the coming year?”
</p><!--l. 16605--><p class="indent" >  “They already have done.”
</p><!--l. 16607--><p class="indent" >  “How can they. . .”
</p><!--l. 16609--><p class="indent" >  “All our plans for the year are now forfeit.”
</p><!--l. 16611--><p class="indent" >  “How did this happen?”
</p><!--l. 16613--><p class="indent" >  “We were outvoted by a single vote on the board.”
</p><!--l. 16615--><p class="indent" >  He struggles to comprehend. “But, weren&#x2019;t we all agreed?”
</p><!--l. 16617--><p class="indent" >  “We were, but I think someone has been spreading rumours behind the scenes. You
know Skagen is a puppet for the ministry.”
</p><!--l. 16620--><p class="indent" >  “Skagen did this?”
</p><!--l. 16622--><p class="indent" >  “The little creep.”
</p><!--l. 16624--><p class="indent" >  “Great. I turn my back for a moment. . .”
</p><!--l. 16626--><p class="indent" >  “This is bad news, Jonas. They are laughing at us.”
</p><!--l. 16628--><p class="indent" >  “They are not the only ones. The whole of the research community is going to be
laughing at us, and hopping mad.”
</p><!--l. 16631--><p class="indent" >  “We&#x2019;ll take the brunt of it.”
</p><!--l. 16633--><p class="indent" >  “Where&#x2019;s John?”
</p><!--l. 16635--><p class="indent" >  “Who?”
</p><!--l. 16637--><p class="indent" >  “The intern. English guy. He was going to attend for me, in case there were any
questions to be answered.”
</p><!--l. 16640--><p class="indent" >  “But he can&#x2019;t vote for you?”
</p><!--l. 16642--><p class="indent" >  “I realize that.”
</p><!--l. 16644--><p class="indent" >  “I haven&#x2019;t seen him. Maybe he is still in the meeting. I think they are still talking
about other stuﬀ.”
</p><!--l. 16647--><p class="indent" >  “This is outrageous.”
</p><!--l. 16649--><p class="indent" >  “We never stood a chance you know. It was decided high up at the last
minute.”
</p><!--l. 16652--><p class="indent" >  “We have spent months ﬁguring out these allocations. All the work in reviewing the
proposals, all the time spent. . .”
</p><!--l. 16655--><p class="indent" >  “You don&#x2019;t have to convince us.”
</p><!--l. 16657--><p class="indent" >  He feels himself boiling. “What the hell is the point of wasting our time carrying
out this whole rigmarole procedure if they never had any intention of letting us
decide?”
</p><!--l. 16661--><p class="indent" >  “Keeping up the appearance of democracy?”
</p><!--l. 16663--><p class="indent" >  “What democracy?” he stabs.
</p><!--l. 16665--><p class="indent" >  His mobile announces an incoming call from the reception. He juggles with
whether to take the call or ignore it. He has only sent his new mobile ID to a few
key contacts, but this is not quite the time for just anyone to call. He buries
it.

</p><!--l. 16670--><p class="indent" >  “This little pin-prick with a tight collar, from the ministry, came up here and started
telling us that there is a crisis taking place in world opinion.”
</p><!--l. 16673--><p class="indent" >  “What the hell is that supposed to mean?”
</p><!--l. 16675--><p class="indent" >  His combo registers an incoming message. Jonas kills the sound.
</p><!--l. 16677--><p class="indent" >  “It means that we have to divert funds to approved charities to be perceived as a
good Christian nation by the U.S..”
</p><!--l. 16680--><p class="indent" >  “By the U.S.?”
</p><!--l. 16682--><p class="indent" >  “Who else? The U.S. is claiming that they are going to start selecting their
collaborative grants more carefully, so as to only work with so-called decent Christian
countries. It is part of the Moral Campaign Against Terror.”
</p><!--l. 16686--><p class="indent" >  Martin is tugging at his arm, always quiet, but wanting attention.
</p><!--l. 16688--><p class="indent" >  “What is it, tiger?”
</p><!--l. 16690--><p class="indent" >  He whispers in Jonas&#x2019; ear.
</p><!--l. 16692--><p class="indent" >  “Ah, sorry, pal. You just sit tight here, and I&#x2019;ll be back in a little while.” He beckons
the others out of the oﬃce.
</p><!--l. 16695--><p class="indent" >  “Sorry, he doesn&#x2019;t like it when we get agitated. Daddy&#x2019;s supposed to be the calm
one.”
</p><!--l. 16697--><p class="indent" >  They translate their conversation to the hall space: a small group of seats next to a
shelf of journals.
</p><!--l. 16700--><p class="indent" >  “What were we saying? So the ministry is saying what?”
</p><!--l. 16702--><p class="indent" >  “America. Christian countries.”
</p><!--l. 16704--><p class="indent" >  “Right. So, is that us or not us?”
</p><!--l. 16706--><p class="indent" >  “Well, his argument goes roughly like this. The failure of the E.U. to ratify the
Christian State has blackened Europe&#x2019;s name in Congress, so they are turning to the
most Christian countries and bypassing the parliament. Scandinavia has a large
evangelist community. . .so. . .”
</p><!--l. 16712--><p class="indent" >  “Religious means evangelist, pretty much.”
</p><!--l. 16714--><p class="indent" >  “And that means. . .”
</p><!--l. 16716--><p class="indent" >  “That we have to be in America&#x2019;s good books, so we have to make a strong
commitment to support an openly Christian project.”
</p><!--l. 16719--><p class="indent" >  “The famine relief?”
</p><!--l. 16721--><p class="indent" >  “Research is not a religious calling,” Roness says ironically. “You can&#x2019;t sell
knowledge to moralists.”
</p><!--l. 16724--><p class="indent" >  “Meaning what? That we cannot spend money on actual research if we want to be
in their good books? It sounds like an excuse to keep the rest of the world behind
competitively, if you ask me.”
</p><!--l. 16728--><p class="indent" >  “There&#x2019;s probably a hundred ways to interpret it. The bottom line is that we are
being steam-rollered by the ministry.”
</p><!--l. 16731--><p class="indent" >  “And they just spring this on us today?”
</p><!--l. 16733--><p class="indent" >  “Just today.”
</p><!--l. 16735--><p class="indent" >  Jonas&#x2019; mobile announces another call. It is from Kaja.
</p><!--l. 16737--><p class="indent" >  “Damn.” He throws the others a glance. “I have to take this, can I talk to you
later?”

</p><!--l. 16740--><p class="indent" >  He rises and goes back into his oﬃce. A incoming memo has arrived, in the folder,
right next to his panic button. Sara has been asking for help again, but he simply
doesn&#x2019;t have time to talk to her directly, or ﬁgure out what is going on with the
embassy.
</p><!--l. 16745--><p class="indent" >  He accepts the call. “Kaja?”
</p><!--l. 16747--><p class="indent" >  “Yes? I saw that you called.”
</p><!--l. 16749--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;ve been trying to call you for hours.”
</p><!--l. 16751--><p class="indent" >  “I was busy. You know that I am at work.”
</p><!--l. 16753--><p class="indent" >  “I know, but something has come up.”
</p><!--l. 16755--><p class="indent" >  He hears her voice quality change, as an edge of hostility enters. “And you
are going to tell me that you have something more important to do than my
work?”
</p><!--l. 16758--><p class="indent" >  “No, that isn&#x2019;t what. . .”
</p><!--l. 16760--><p class="indent" >  “What did the doctor say?”
</p><!--l. 16762--><p class="indent" >  “The doctor?”
</p><!--l. 16764--><p class="indent" >  “That doctor? That you were supposed to. . .”
</p><!--l. 16766--><p class="indent" >  “Ah.”
</p><!--l. 16768--><p class="indent" >  “Jonas! Didn&#x2019;t you take him to the doctor? You were supposed to take your son to
the doctor!”
</p><!--l. 16770--><p class="indent" >  Shit. “Sorry, Kaja. Something happened and it wasn&#x2019;t possible.”
</p><!--l. 16772--><p class="indent" >  “My god, Jonas. What is wrong with you?”
</p><!--l. 16774--><p class="indent" >  “I know it . . .”
</p><!--l. 16776--><p class="indent" >  “Can&#x2019;t I ask you to do even a simple thing?”
</p><!--l. 16778--><p class="indent" >  “Something more important came up. We need to talk about it.”
</p><!--l. 16780--><p class="indent" >  “What could possibly be more important than your son?”
</p><!--l. 16782--><p class="indent" >  “Nothing, and that&#x2019;s why I can&#x2019;t have him with me. Is there any way your mother
could look after him today?”
</p><!--l. 16785--><p class="indent" >  “My mother?”
</p><!--l. 16787--><p class="indent" >  “We should get him out of the town.”
</p><!--l. 16789--><p class="indent" >  “What are you talking about, Jonas?”
</p><!--l. 16791--><p class="indent" >  “I might have to leave the city. Could we take him to your mother&#x2019;s?”
</p><!--l. 16793--><p class="indent" >  “Why? I just asked you to do a simple thing. Why can&#x2019;t you just do as I ask? I can&#x2019;t
leave work, you know I can&#x2019;t”
</p><!--l. 16796--><p class="indent" >  “I could take him myself, if you would call. . .”
</p><!--l. 16798--><p class="indent" >  “I could lose my job.”
</p><!--l. 16800--><p class="indent" >  “We really need to take him somewhere safe.”
</p><!--l. 16802--><p class="indent" >  “What are you talking about? If you were a little more. . .”
</p><!--l. 16804--><p class="indent" >  “Kaja, please listen to me.”
</p><!--l. 16806--><p class="indent" >  “I am tired of listening to your whining. This time you are just going to have to
look after him. I have work, and I have plans. . .”
</p><!--l. 16809--><p class="indent" >  “What plans? Look, Kaja, this is important.” So she is going out? With
whom?

</p><!--l. 16811--><p class="indent" >  “I am important, Jonas. I am a human being. You might not want to have a life, but
I certainly do.”
</p><!--l. 16814--><p class="indent" >  “Wait, you didn&#x2019;t say anything about going out tonight.”
</p><!--l. 16816--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t have to tell you about my plans.”
</p><!--l. 16818--><p class="indent" >  “What about me?”
</p><!--l. 16820--><p class="indent" >  “What about you? We are broken up, don&#x2019;t you remember?”
</p><!--l. 16822--><p class="indent" >  How could I forget. “So, you never even. . .”
</p><!--l. 16824--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 16826--><p class="indent" >  ”All this was to get me to baby-sit Martin because you are going out? He isn&#x2019;t
really sick at all, right? This was your idea.” He winces, seeing Martin pretending not
to listen in the corner of the room.
</p><!--l. 16830--><p class="indent" >  “I ask you to do a simple thing. . .”
</p><!--l. 16832--><p class="indent" >  “So who are you seeing? No, don&#x2019;t tell me I don&#x2019;t want to know.”
</p><!--l. 16834--><p class="indent" >  “I wouldn&#x2019;t tell you even if you asked.”
</p><!--l. 16836--><p class="indent" >  He attempts to wrench himself back from pyrotechnics. “Fine. Look, Kaja,
something odd happened today that is important.”
</p><!--l. 16839--><p class="indent" >  “Jonas, how many times do I have to say it. It is your turn. I don&#x2019;t care what you
have on your plate today. I am also important and you are going to be a father to your
child.”
</p><!--l. 16843--><p class="indent" >  “Kaja, please listen.”
</p><!--l. 16845--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t you dare make me come over there and get him, Jonas!” She exudes
something between a growl and a scream and terminates the call.
</p><!--l. 16848--><p class="indent" >  Silence. Embarrassment in front of his child.
</p><!--l. 16850--><p class="indent" >  He reels momentarily at her rebuttal, though he is well used to these by now. With a
little transcendental meditation and some deep breaths, he will be back in play.
Breathe deeply. Breathe.
</p><!--l. 16854--><p class="indent" >  What bothers him the most is that, in the whole of their interaction, he did not
manage to communicate a single piece of important information.
</p><!--l. 16857--><p class="indent" >  Stress pursues him, he believes, like a predator.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 16860--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 16861--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 16865--><p class="indent" >  Jonas has a poem that helps him to calm down. Something he learned as a child. It
helps him to recite it, to focus on the words.
     Astronomy is 1derful<br />
     And interesting 2<br />
     The ear3volves around the sun<br />
     And makes a year 4 you<br />
     The moon aﬀects the sur5 heard<br />

     By law of phy6 great<br />
     It&#x2019;s 7 when the stars so bright<br />
     Do nightly scintill8<br />
     If watchful providence be9<br />
     With good intentions fraught<br />
     Should not keep up her watch divine<br />
     We soon should come to 0 (nought).<br />
</p><!--l. 16883--><p class="indent" >  The verse is old. He believes it comes from the early part of the twentieth century. It
reminds him of a more innocent age: an age in which topics like knowledge and
astronomy were viewed diﬀerently: as fanciful escapist concepts, for a world that was
interested in playing with ideas—a world that respected science and mathematics.
There are no politics in the verse. It is pure and clean. It is about cleverness and
goodness, not hidden agendas or deception.
</p><!--l. 16891--><p class="indent" >  How did science reach this sorry state of aﬀairs? When did politics become more
important than creativity? He looks at Martin and wonders whether his innocent
interest in books that he cannot understand is fundamentally misplaced, in this age.
That kind of innocence belongs to a less cynical time.
</p><!--l. 16897--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">So what are we going to do, you and I?</span>
</p><!--l. 16900--><p class="indent" >  Jonas looks at his mobile, wondering who he can call, or what it can do for him to
get him out of this mess. How much we rely on this thing. How useless it seems now.
He ought to take Martin out of town. It was a stupid idea to come here, the most
obvious place to ﬁnd him. He starts to pack some things. They can stay at a
hotel
</p><!--l. 16906--><p class="indent" >  It is at times like this he wishes they still had their baby-sitter. When Martin was
younger, and he and Kaja were still a couple, they would try to get out, to keep the
romance alive. They had a sitter then. He liked their baby-sitter; she was a round,
red-faced woman, in the process of shedding middle age. She was full of life and
good humour. She kept them in good spirits. She lived out of the centre of
town.
</p><!--l. 16913--><p class="indent" >  Every Thursday evening they would pick up Martin from the sitter and plan to go
out for dinner to a restaurant where he could play in a special adventure pen. They
always asked the sitter if she would join them.
</p><!--l. 16918--><p class="indent" >  “Lill—you can join us, if you like,” he would say, but she would always
decline.
</p><!--l. 16921--><p class="indent" >  He remembers her cheerful ruddiness.“No—you kids go ahead. I have these
menopausal ﬂushes, I&#x2019;m afraid, loves. There&#x2019;s no way I can be out. Sweat like a pig.
Drives me crazy. Oﬀ you go now!”
</p><!--l. 16925--><p class="indent" >  She was hindered by hormones, simply chemicals without malice — surely a better
fate to be than to be hindered by a brain-dead bureaucracy that knows full well what it
is doing. He would pay her double now, if she were still sitting. Then he could put
Martin somewhere safe and try to sort things out here. He cannot just run away from
his responsibilities.

</p><!--l. 16933--><p class="indent" >  He looks through his messages. Little advertisement billboards shift and change on
the display. There are some notes about Sara&#x2019;s funding, some internal memos and an
anonymous message, routed from his old ID. ‘<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">We will give you one week to provide us</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">with the information we need. We have located the girl. We are watching</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">you.</span>&#x2019;
</p><!--l. 16939--><p class="indent" >  He feels a chill, in spite of the reassurances by the police..
</p><!--l. 16941--><p class="indent" >  And Kaja will be dating someone, probably surrendering her beauty to someone he
does not even know. He feels a surge of anger or panic, something indeﬁnable. He
remembers the noise she made before cutting their call; he wants to repeat
it.
</p><!--l. 16946--><p class="indent" >  Who can imagine how Martin must be feeling right now, to be abandoned like this
by his mother. She is a perfect product of the modern age: self-centred and incapable
of doing wrong. She has tricked him into being her baby-sitter, and now even
unwittingly exposed him to danger.
</p><!--l. 16951--><p class="indent" >  He considers ripping the mobile out of his clothes. Suddenly this part of him
seems like a tumour – a malignancy that has grafted itself onto his body and
opened him to a slow degenerative disease. The temptation is strong, but
who can do without one? Soon, even Martin will have to have one of his
own.
</p><!--l. 16957--><p class="indent" >  He watches his child, wanting to go over and hug him, but not wanting to interrupt
his play; he seems happy, in a world of his own. He is reading about ancient Egypt
and drawing, absorbed in the colour images. He does not need computer animated
antics to satisfy any need for stimulation. He does not seem concerned with
whatever he perceives is going on around him today. So trusting. Jonas envies
him that level of detachment. What he would give to go back to that time of
innocence, that feeling of safety and wonder. Things change though, don&#x2019;t
they?
</p><!--l. 16968--><p class="indent" >  The chapter title in his book triggers a memory of his own growing up: Tut Ankh
Amon. The name that kept changing. As a child it was just Tooten Karmen – or even
Rootin Tootin Karmen. Then suddenly, at some indeﬁnable moment, the
word Anhk became apparent to him, in the blur of sounds. He learned about
the Ankh symbol. He learned its meaning of freedom. Then he learned the
word Amon, a king. And then there were three words: the transformation
was complete. He would never hear the sounds with the same ignorance and
innocence again. How does one express what that change meant? It was a
time of ambivalence: a feeling of enrichment, combined with a feeling of
loss.
</p><!--l. 16979--><p class="indent" >  That process of learning is going away now, he realizes. Society is no longer
interested in those details. As long as you can fake it, you&#x2019;re accepted.
</p><!--l. 16983--><p class="indent" >  He looks at the clock on his wall panel. It is almost 15:30. If they are going to get
out of the city, he should leave now.
</p><!--l. 16986--><p class="indent" >  The door pushes open again. “Jonas, we need to talk.”
</p><!--l. 16989--><p class="indent" >  Roness enters again.

</p><!--l. 16991--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m a bit short on time right now.”
</p><!--l. 16993--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s important. They want to put a stop to all expenditure on current projects. That
means that hundreds of stipends and fellowships will be frozen.”
</p><!--l. 16996--><p class="indent" >  “Can anything else go wrong today?”
</p><!--l. 16998--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t jinx it.”
</p><!--l. 17000--><p class="indent" >  “But they cannot just stop those monies, surely. Isn&#x2019;t it illegal?”
</p><!--l. 17002--><p class="indent" >  “They have made the terms so complicated that no one is sure, to be honest. We
will have to consult lawyers.”
</p><!--l. 17005--><p class="indent" >  “Can we move some funds to safety for emergencies?”
</p><!--l. 17007--><p class="indent" >  She raises an eyebrow.
</p><!--l. 17009--><p class="indent" >  “All right, stupid question.”
</p><!--l. 17013--><p class="indent" >  “I just heard that I will have to re-apply for funds that I have already received.”
</p><!--l. 17016--><p class="indent" >  “Re-apply?”
</p><!--l. 17018--><p class="indent" >  “The ministry has overridden the decision of the funding committee. They have
enforced a political agenda, apparently based on this business of Christian
politics.”
</p><!--l. 17022--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s terrible.”
</p><!--l. 17024--><p class="indent" >  “I can think of another word.”
</p><!--l. 17026--><p class="indent" >  “What can we do?”
</p><!--l. 17028--><p class="indent" >  “I would suggest moving to another country, but they are all the same now. The
system has become corrupt.”
</p><!--l. 17031--><p class="indent" >  “Everywhere.”
</p><!--l. 17033--><p class="indent" >  “We have to ﬁght them at their own game.”
</p><!--l. 17035--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t know. What are we going to do, bribe people in the ministry?”
</p><!--l. 17037--><p class="indent" >  “Why not. When you work in a system this complex, low level corruption becomes
a survival tool – an act of rebellion against the bureaucracy.”
</p><!--l. 17041--><p class="indent" >  He laughs, uncertain whether to take the idea seriously.
</p><!--l. 17044--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s half of it – something we need to discuss seriously here as a matter of
policy. I don&#x2019;t think we should accept this decision without a ﬁght.”
</p><!--l. 17048--><p class="indent" >  “How can we stop it?”
</p><!--l. 17050--><p class="indent" >  “We could strike? I don&#x2019;t know—there are things we could do.”
</p><!--l. 17052--><p class="indent" >  “Strike?” That is a thought he has not considered before.
</p><!--l. 17054--><p class="indent" >  “Think about it.” She sees that he is collecting his things together. “Are you
leaving?”
</p><!--l. 17057--><p class="indent" >  “Uh, yes. Something important has come up with Martin here. I have to
leave.”
</p><!--l. 17059--><p class="indent" >  “Will you be at the Social Science Seminar tomorrow?”
</p><!--l. 17061--><p class="indent" >  “Is that tomorrow?” He snorts. “Of course it is. That&#x2019;s out of town somewhere, if I
recall. Sundvolden?”
</p><!--l. 17064--><p class="indent" >  “It was moved. Just past Holmenkollen.”
</p><!--l. 17066--><p class="indent" >  “Really? How are you getting there?”
</p><!--l. 17068--><p class="indent" >  “There&#x2019;s a bus or the Tube. Atle might be taking a car.”

</p><!--l. 17070--><p class="indent" >  “Right. Yes. Actually that suits me very well. But I&#x2019;ll have to bring Martin with
me.”
</p><!--l. 17073--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t suppose anyone will mind. Sweet child.” She winks at him, but he is not
looking.
</p><!--l. 17076--><p class="indent" >  “Good, then we can talk some more there.”
</p><!--l. 17078--><p class="indent" >  “What&#x2019;s the other half?”
</p><!--l. 17080--><p class="indent" >  “Excuse me?”
</p><!--l. 17082--><p class="indent" >  “You said that civil disobedience was only half the story.”
</p><!--l. 17084--><p class="indent" >  “Oh. It was on the news. Some high level programmer has been kidnapped in
Slovenia. Some kind of Russian hacker collective has been trying to track him
down.”
</p><!--l. 17088--><p class="indent" >  “Slovenia?”
</p><!--l. 17090--><p class="indent" >  “A lot of programming houses. It was apparently motivated by game-related
conﬂicts spilling over into the real world.”
</p><!--l. 17093--><p class="indent" >  “People have some funny ideas about this game.”
</p><!--l. 17095--><p class="indent" >  “Police channels have issued an alert to American civilians. The American
embassy has shut down after threats of reprisals, in connection with the leaked
story.”
</p><!--l. 17099--><p class="indent" >  “Really? That might explain a few things. Have they known about it a long
time?”
</p><!--l. 17102--><p class="indent" >  “The kidnap is new, but apparently they have been receiving threats every since the
damn broke.”
</p><!--l. 17105--><p class="indent" >  And now we&#x2019;re all damn broke, he thinks. A voice call comes in on his combo.
Internal.
</p><!--l. 17108--><p class="indent" >  “All right – I&#x2019;ll see you tomorrow.”
</p><!--l. 17110--><p class="indent" >  She nods and leaves.
</p><!--l. 17112--><p class="indent" >  He accepts the call. “Hello, Mr. Lindgren.”
</p><!--l. 17115--><p class="indent" >  “Hi.”
</p><!--l. 17117--><p class="indent" >  “We spoke earlier, about the funds for your student. I thought I had better let you
know that the problem is now moot. I&#x2019;m afraid that the funds have now been frozen by
executive order. To gain access to them, you will have to re-apply for coverage under a
new environmental program.”
</p><!--l. 17123--><p class="indent" >  News travels fast. “So I heard.”
</p><!--l. 17125--><p class="indent" >  “Do you want me to start the procedure?”
</p><!--l. 17127--><p class="indent" >  “I suppose you better had.”
</p><!--l. 17129--><p class="indent" >  “Okay. I&#x2019;ll come back to you with details later.”
</p><!--l. 17131--><p class="indent" >  “Bye.”
</p><!--l. 17133--><p class="indent" >  He sighs. “Martin, come on, pal. We have to leave.”
</p>
