<!--l. 17637--><p class="indent" >  “Hey Preeta, what&#x2019;s up?”
</p><!--l. 17639--><p class="indent" >  Ivar.
</p><!--l. 17641--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m looking at the incoming reports on maﬁa activities.”
</p><!--l. 17643--><p class="indent" >  “How come?”
</p><!--l. 17645--><p class="indent" >  “I have a personal interest.”
</p><!--l. 17647--><p class="indent" >  “They have a site online. There are probably people in intelligence who know how
to access them too.”
</p><!--l. 17650--><p class="indent" >  “I know.” She looks at him. “What?”
</p><!--l. 17652--><p class="indent" >  “Nothing.”
</p><!--l. 17654--><p class="indent" >  Manipulating the controls on the interfaces is second nature to her. She can do it,
even while reading his unconvincing expression.
</p><!--l. 17657--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s nothing that I&#x2019;m not supposed to be doing.”
</p><!--l. 17659--><p class="indent" >  “Oh, of course not! That&#x2019;s not what I meant.”
</p><!--l. 17661--><p class="indent" >  “But I still have a personal interest.”
</p><!--l. 17663--><p class="indent" >  He waits until she can no longer stand the prickling on the nape of her
neck.
</p><!--l. 17666--><p class="indent" >  “I want to see if I can ﬁnd out anything about my friend.”
</p><!--l. 17668--><p class="indent" >  “So, why didn&#x2019;t she just come with you?”
</p><!--l. 17670--><p class="indent" >  “She still has a job. Besides, I can&#x2019;t talk about my work there. It was a private
project. It was for non-disclosure.”
</p><!--l. 17673--><p class="indent" >  He gives her the look again.
</p><!--l. 17675--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 17677--><p class="indent" >  “You&#x2019;re an odd one.”
</p><!--l. 17679--><p class="indent" >  “I am not!”
</p><!--l. 17681--><p class="indent" >  “You&#x2019;re kind of jumpy. We&#x2019;re just trying to be nice to you, you know. You seem all
suspicious and. . .”
</p><!--l. 17684--><p class="indent" >  “Look, I was threatened and attacked, you know, before I came here.”
</p><!--l. 17686--><p class="indent" >  He nods. “Right. Sorry.” His body breaks out into a sweat. “So what are we looking
at?”
</p><!--l. 17690--><p class="indent" >  “There is all kind of activity – a whole new wave of incidents of crime and game
related complaints since the news story about the game broke.”
</p><!--l. 17694--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah, Jonathan was talking about there being cases of glitches in the advertising
technologies that have been showing up examples of government manipulation. There
is a whole conspiracy theory about it going down.”
</p><!--l. 17698--><p class="indent" >  Preeta does not reply. At times like this, she almost wishes she wore the hijab. It
can be an eﬀective shield.
</p><!--l. 17701--><p class="indent" >  “So, have you heard any news from anyone back home?”
</p><!--l. 17703--><p class="indent" >  She shakes her head imperceptibly. “I am trying to ﬁnd out something through the
developer forum chat lines, but I don&#x2019;t have access oﬃcially any more. They seem to
be under a lock-down.”
</p><!--l. 17707--><p class="indent" >  “Well, do they know what has happened to you?”
</p><!--l. 17709--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s not it. I&#x2019;m not important.”
</p><!--l. 17711--><p class="indent" >  “Then what?”

</p><!--l. 17713--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s what I&#x2019;m trying to ﬁnd out.”
</p><!--l. 17715--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">How about just leaving me alone for now? Don&#x2019;t you have work to do?</span>
</p><!--l. 17717--><p class="indent" >  She cannot aﬀord to say it, even if her mind is striking a gong in complaint; echoes
of Asia resound in the emptiness of her skull. There is no sweat shop here. The
workers barely work. If anything they come and bother her in the name of work. They
spend too much time talking. Perhaps it is just the novelty of a new face. They are
probably trying to be nice to her. But one cannot help but wonder if they ever do
anything.
</p><!--l. 17724--><p class="indent" >  Had this been Kuala Lumpur, she would have welcomed the distraction. If there had
even been as much as a single good looking man here. . .
</p><!--l. 17728--><p class="indent" >  “So, is the software you have been working on any good? Have you found out
anything interesting?”
</p><!--l. 17731--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m not sure. I&#x2019;m still looking. I promised Bishop that I would get started on
testing it out – the software.”
</p><!--l. 17734--><p class="indent" >  “You designed it, right?”
</p><!--l. 17736--><p class="indent" >  “Not exactly. I just applied someone else&#x2019;s ideas to the game.”
</p><!--l. 17738--><p class="indent" >  “Who?”
</p><!--l. 17740--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 17742--><p class="indent" >  “Whose ideas?”
</p><!--l. 17744--><p class="indent" >  She glances at him, while still trying to ignore him with her face buried in the
screen. “I can&#x2019;t say.”
</p><!--l. 17747--><p class="indent" >  He looks dissatisﬁed with the answer, but seems to accept it.
</p><!--l. 17749--><p class="indent" >  “So what are you searching for?”
</p><!--l. 17751--><p class="indent" >  “You already asked me that.”
</p><!--l. 17753--><p class="indent" >  “I mean where?”
</p><!--l. 17755--><p class="indent" >  She suppresses a sigh. “Police reports, records. I was trying to get to Interpol, but I
don&#x2019;t know how to get in yet, so I&#x2019;m looking through Europol.”
</p><!--l. 17758--><p class="indent" >  “Find anything useful?”
</p><!--l. 17760--><p class="indent" >  “Not really.”
</p><!--l. 17762--><p class="indent" >  “Look at this though.” She ﬂicks through the list. “A report here, from yesterday
about a similar story, here in Oslo. Someone being threatened for knowledge about
game strategies.”
</p><!--l. 17766--><p class="indent" >  “Well I&#x2019;ve heard of people auctioning game-skills for money, but that&#x2019;s taking it a
bit far.”
</p><!--l. 17769--><p class="indent" >  “It is reported as a realistic threat.”
</p><!--l. 17771--><p class="indent" >  “Coincidence?”
</p><!--l. 17773--><p class="indent" >  “Or someone looking for me?”
</p><!--l. 17775--><p class="indent" >  He shrugs. “No need to be paranoid now. You&#x2019;re safe enough here.”
</p><!--l. 17777--><p class="indent" >  “Easy for you to say.”
</p><!--l. 17779--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah.”
</p><!--l. 17781--><p class="indent" >  “There&#x2019;s more. Maybe just a coincidence.”
</p><!--l. 17783--><p class="indent" >  “More? What?”
</p><!--l. 17785--><p class="indent" >  “Look at this.”

</p><!--l. 17787--><p class="indent" >  Ivar looks at the screen, then to her, then back at the screen and back at her again.
His expressions says: what exactly am I looking at?
</p><!--l. 17790--><p class="indent" >  “Perhaps Jonathan should see this.”
</p><!--l. 17792--><p class="indent" >  He shakes his head profusely. “That&#x2019;s a project in itself.”
</p><!--l. 17794--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 17796--><p class="indent" >  “Let&#x2019;s keep it between us.”
</p><!--l. 17798--><p class="indent" >  “Because he is diﬃcult to talk to?”
</p><!--l. 17800--><p class="indent" >  “No, he has no trouble starting a conversation. He just doesn&#x2019;t know how to end
one.”
</p><!--l. 17803--><p class="indent" >  “Ah.” Shyness comes in many forms. “But we should talk to someone?”
</p><!--l. 17806--><p class="indent" >  “But we don&#x2019;t know anything yet.”
</p><!--l. 17808--><p class="indent" >  “Well, nothing exact. What about suspicion?”
</p><!--l. 17810--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t think that&#x2019;s going to sell anyone.”
</p><!--l. 17812--><p class="indent" >  She sighs. “I&#x2019;m not getting anywhere. I should be, but this is the closest thing I&#x2019;ve
found to .. something.”
</p><!--l. 17815--><p class="indent" >  “Too bad.”
</p><!--l. 17817--><p class="indent" >  “But don&#x2019;t you think it&#x2019;s a bit strange?”
</p><!--l. 17819--><p class="indent" >  He shrugs. “Why?”
</p><!--l. 17821--><p class="indent" >  A sigh can also sound silently on the inside. “My instinct tells me that this is
important.”
</p><!--l. 17824--><p class="indent" >  “I wouldn&#x2019;t spend too much time on it, if I were you. Stuﬀ like this comes in a
lot.”
</p><!--l. 17827--><p class="indent" >  She shakes her head. No time to lose heart. She wants to do something.
There needs to be some action. Too much running away, not enough standing
ground.
</p><!--l. 17831--><p class="indent" >  Memory kicks in. The methods. The ﬁve weaknesses. She needs to change the
balance of power. She unties her hair from its pony tail and lets it fall across her
shoulders. She rubs her neck, lifting her arm to puﬀ up her breasts. This usually has an
eﬀect on men. She is not certain whether she is really pretty, but it usually seems to
work.
</p><!--l. 17837--><p class="indent" >  “I would feel a lot better knowing that I had made a contribution here. I feel so
useless.”
</p><!--l. 17840--><p class="indent" >  Ivar notices and seems uncertain whether to be uncomfortable.
</p><!--l. 17842--><p class="indent" >  “No, you&#x2019;re not useless. Don&#x2019;t say that.”
</p><!--l. 17844--><p class="indent" >  “Then why not try to do something?”
</p><!--l. 17846--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah,” he says. “Yeah. Better to be safe than sorry.”
</p><!--l. 17848--><p class="indent" >  She looks directly into his eyes. People don&#x2019;t do that often here. It is too intimate. It
mesmerises. It turns the tables and assumes control.
</p><!--l. 17851--><p class="indent" >  “Let&#x2019;s ask Jonathan. He is police and he will understand. He can do something.”
</p><!--l. 17854--><p class="indent" >  Ivar nods, but remains dumb.
</p><!--l. 17856--><p class="indent" >  She waves across the room. Jonathan strolls over, yawning. “What is it?”
</p><!--l. 17859--><p class="indent" >  Ivar re-animates. “Preeta found something interesting with the new software.”
</p><!--l. 17862--><p class="indent" >  “Really?”

</p><!--l. 17864--><p class="indent" >  She shrugs. “I&#x2019;m not sure. It&#x2019;s hard to say.”
</p><!--l. 17866--><p class="indent" >  “So what is it?”
</p><!--l. 17868--><p class="indent" >  “I was digging into stuﬀ, following some leads.”
</p><!--l. 17870--><p class="indent" >  “Why?”
</p><!--l. 17872--><p class="indent" >  “Well, I have to learn this system somehow, don&#x2019;t I? If I&#x2019;m going to help you catch
criminals.”
</p><!--l. 17875--><p class="indent" >  “Okay.”
</p><!--l. 17877--><p class="indent" >  “I found that you have a honeypot.”
</p><!--l. 17879--><p class="indent" >  He nods. “So?”
</p><!--l. 17881--><p class="indent" >  “Well. It&#x2019;s hard to explain all the connections that . . .”
</p><!--l. 17883--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s why we use the software right?”
</p><!--l. 17885--><p class="indent" >  She smiles. “Right.”
</p><!--l. 17887--><p class="indent" >  Jonathan urges her on.
</p><!--l. 17889--><p class="indent" >  “Well, I was correlating stuﬀ with the new software, just trying it out, and I found
the name of a girl. A student. She is working on a form of robotic programming. Well,
that&#x2019;s not important, well not yet, maybe. Look.”
</p><!--l. 17893--><p class="indent" >  She demonstrates the visualization on the screen in front of her, showing various
interlocking threads, passing through a landscape of colour. “The colours represent
the signiﬁcance of correlations. Hot and cold, you know.”
</p><!--l. 17897--><p class="indent" >  Jonathan appears interested. The graphics are impressive if nothing else.
</p><!--l. 17899--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t really understand this but it looks cool.”
</p><!--l. 17901--><p class="indent" >  “Anyway. Here is the girl. It turns out that she has been spending time in your
honeypot, doing some interesting things. And she is related, in the model, to someone
in the city who was threatened by a mystery caller, assumed Russian maﬁa. They are
both correlated to gaming models that include control of autonomous agents using
open media signals.”
</p><!--l. 17907--><p class="indent" >  “Are you following this?”
</p><!--l. 17909--><p class="indent" >  “This girl they are trying to ﬁnd is one of the people in your honeypot logs, on the
tracker.”
</p><!--l. 17912--><p class="indent" >  “And something about a threat. . .”
</p><!--l. 17914--><p class="indent" >  “A College professor. He was threatened by a Russian sounding voice who asked
about game related knowledge. That correlates with my attack, although it was
probably just a misunderstanding.”
</p><!--l. 17918--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah?” Absorbing the signiﬁcance of the information.
</p><!--l. 17921--><p class="indent" >  “It turns out that she walked into one of the police honeypots and she has been
using the environments to simulate behavioural stuﬀ. It&#x2019;s actually very clever. She has
probably been driving them crazy.”
</p><!--l. 17926--><p class="indent" >  Jonathan looks fatigued, uninterested. “Once more?”
</p><!--l. 17928--><p class="indent" >  “According to the system, she has been correlated with several activities, She
came up on mountain rescue violations, maﬁa threats, an American complaint
about attempting to sabotage an experiment, and a police report somewhere
recently.”
</p><!--l. 17933--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s quite a list.”

</p><!--l. 17935--><p class="indent" >  “It doesn&#x2019;t necessarily mean anything, but it gives her a high ranking. Strictly
speaking, correlations are not proof of anything important.”
</p><!--l. 17938--><p class="indent" >  “I suppose not. But I was looking at what she does.”
</p><!--l. 17940--><p class="indent" >  “What does she do?”
</p><!--l. 17942--><p class="indent" >  “She a student. She works on making small robot agents collaborate in
groups.”
</p><!--l. 17944--><p class="indent" >  “So?”
</p><!--l. 17946--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t you see? That is what people are trying to do in the game. By creating an
environment in which people are brought together, without real guidance, but just a
few hints and principles to make them act. ”
</p><!--l. 17951--><p class="indent" >  “Please tell me this is going somewhere.”
</p><!--l. 17953--><p class="indent" >  “What is impressive is that she also knows how to disrupt that cooperation. She has
been doing in the honeypots.”
</p><!--l. 17956--><p class="indent" >  “How can you know that?”
</p><!--l. 17958--><p class="indent" >  “Software.”
</p><!--l. 17960--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah? It really works?”
</p><!--l. 17962--><p class="indent" >  She makes a noise of exasperation. “I don&#x2019;t know if it works. I&#x2019;m just telling you
what it says.”
</p><!--l. 17965--><p class="indent" >  Ivar nods. “So you&#x2019;re saying that she could tell us how to break up this Christian
propaganda campaign that Bishop is so worries about.”
</p><!--l. 17969--><p class="indent" >  “I was thinking that maybe this could help us. We could learn something from this
incident.”
</p><!--l. 17972--><p class="indent" >  “Or from her.”
</p><!--l. 17975--><p class="indent" >  “So, does Bishop know?”
</p><!--l. 17977--><p class="indent" >  Is he serious, or humouring her?
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 17980--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 17981--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 17985--><p class="indent" >  Imagine being a bird, up there in the sky. The wind is blowing hard, buﬀeting you.
You&#x2019;re cold and dizzy with oxygen. Sore from the rushing of the air and wind. It is
this physical sensation that is missing from the VR. You cannot simulate that with
hardware, suits or visual cues. That kind of light, pervasive touch will never be
reproducible as a solitary experience.
</p><!--l. 17992--><p class="indent" >  Preeta has been hiding in the VR until now. But that is no escape. Freedom is not
given, it is taken. She feels dull and uninteresting in this grey winter world of Oslo.
She wants to shop, or get a manicure or do something feminine—anything. If she is
going to go out on the town, then she needs clothes. Being surrounded by these geeky
boys, who know nothing of adventure, does nothing for her self-esteem. She needs
that buﬀeting, that oxygen.

</p><!--l. 18000--><p class="indent" >  Lunch time is the time when the Norwegians ﬂock to consume what they profess to
be a form of food. Dark squares wrapped in noisy paper. It scarcely seems to be
plausible source of nourishment; fortunately, it is possible to opt out of these rituals.
Her absence will not be conspicuous.
</p><!--l. 18005--><p class="indent" >  During such cracks in their interface, she can plan small excursions into the
daylight city. Small trips build conﬁdence. Incremental moves, exploring, learning,
growing.
</p><!--l. 18009--><p class="indent" >  She wanders out of the Police building, into the shopping street. It is getting close
to Christmas and they shops are ﬁlling with bright decorations and insipid carols. Her
mobile is still new to her and there are grounds for caution; she is not used to the
advertising that streams, knocking against her ﬁrewall. She has been trying to exorcise
a stream of unwanted messages selling mobile-insurance for some days now.
Ironically, when she is out on the street, what she most needs is insurance against the
insurance.
</p><!--l. 18018--><p class="indent" >  She passes through the curtains of icy rain and ﬁnds her way into an arcade. Parasol
to paraply: she has learned, if nothing else, to carry an umbrella here. Rumour has it
that this is a place to buy perfume and clothing, straws to clutch to make her new self
complete.
</p><!--l. 18023--><p class="indent" >  The shops light up an inviting radiance in the rainy darkness. Little islands of
simulated humanity in a ﬁlm-noir daytime gloom. As hot air blasts down onto her
umbrella at the mall threshold, water ﬂies from its membrane and her mobile writhes
in a new deluge of incoming ads.
