<!--l. 18197--><p class="indent" >  A short video sequence, on the ﬂoor in front of her, shows news coverage of a
crowd that has gathered in downtown Oslo, not far away from the arcade. Foreign
culturals have gathered on the street, seeking a togetherness that is absent from their
daily lives. The reportage shows that the faces are all dark and non-native. She expects
that native Norwegians would all be in their isolation tanks, demonstrating from the
comfort of their mobiles.

</p><!--l. 18205--><p class="indent" >  She stands for a while, absorbing the information, and watching the style of the
imagery. It is nothing like what she knows from Asia. Nor does it resemble what she
has seen from American broadcasts. She stays there to watch for a few moments.
She&#x2019;ll have to get back to work very soon.
</p><!--l. 18211--><p class="indent" >  Then a shadow passes over where she is standing. It is an angel ﬂuttering in the
smart screen, above her head. She has been standing still for too long and the angels
are programmed to close in on people standing. Perhaps it thinks she is a vagrant and
has come to save her soul. Christian mythology has become an integral part of
marketing now. It is the same in Asia, of course, but the Hindu gods are cooler and
look better in the fashion-wear of the region.
</p><!--l. 18219--><p class="indent" >  Still, new imagery makes interesting watching. She has never seen this kind of
catholic propaganda before, not in such detail. The graphics are impressive. The angel
is trying to send an audio signal to her mobile, but her barriers are preventing it. Let&#x2019;s
not go there.
</p><!--l. 18225--><p class="indent" >  Multitudes of services are hiding in these walls, surely. She can see them with her
mobile, conﬁgured in scan mode. There are so many transactions between the smart
walls and the passing mobiles that it must be costing people a stash of money to just
walk through this trading tunnel. Most of them probably have no idea what they are
paying for, or what they are getting: a faithful umbilical, serving them their
dose.
</p><!--l. 18233--><p class="indent" >  Preeta feels exhausted already. She ducks into a clothing store to escape the current
of bodies. Relative calm presides here, except for the thumping of some popular
music. The piles of garments oﬀer a sense of comfort. A young girl, standing at the
rear end of the narrow shop, indicates that she has seen her come in but does not come
to her assistance. That suits her ﬁne.
</p><!--l. 18240--><p class="indent" >  The clothes are fashionable; there is nothing here for an older audience. Bright
colours and adaptive shades, synthetics and designer jeans. Blue jeans are back
again.
</p><!--l. 18244--><p class="indent" >  She takes a moment to breath and ﬁnd her inner calm. The girl is eyeing her from
the back of the shop.
</p><!--l. 18247--><p class="indent" >  She sees a pair of trousers and a top that she likes. They are black. It seems like a
statement of daring, given her dark complexion, but perhaps that is what she needs: to
feel as though she stands out. Do not cower all your life, she thinks. Think of life here
as you would think of a game room. Be bold.
</p><!--l. 18253--><p class="indent" >  She downloads the details of the clothes to her mobile. Perhaps she will order them
by post later. For now, small things.
</p><!--l. 18256--><p class="indent" >  She picks out a tightly-ﬁtting T-shirt top, of the kind that clings to the body and
makes one&#x2019;s breasts stand out, it looks great on the wriggling mannikins, and the size
will adapt to her. It seems like a safe buy, even if she can&#x2019;t ﬁnd anything to go with it.
She ought to be buying warm clothes, but with a new jacket, this is still wearable.
Who needs sensible clothes anyway?
</p><!--l. 18263--><p class="indent" >  She takes the garment to the back of the shop, feeling that she ought to buy
something, as the only customer. The girl smiles broadly as she receives the garment

and begins wrapping it absently. A display of bangles, on the side of the counter,
attracts her attention.
</p><!--l. 18268--><p class="indent" >  “Oh, this is just like a bracelet that I had when I was a girl!”
</p><!--l. 18270--><p class="indent" >  The girl glances at her from the corner of an uncertain eye. Seeing that she is
talking to her, her smile drops like a tossed pancake onto a cold ﬂoor; brow
furrows with suspicion. Are you talking to me? She completes the transaction
with a winced smile, and Preeta is dismissed. Apparently, she has crossed a
boundary.
</p><!--l. 18276--><p class="indent" >  She leaves quickly back into the media tunnel.
</p><!--l. 18279--><p class="indent" >  The smart walls seem to be tied into the game. They probably belong to a gaming
shop close to the end of this passage. Some of the billboards have errors in them: there
are clear signs of image corruption in some of the billboards. The sickness has
reached here too. It brings her down to Earth. Time is moving on. She should get back
to the group.
</p><!--l. 18287--><p class="indent" >  She moves back into the ﬂow of people and is almost carried through the arcade to
the exit and ejected back into the street, next to what looks like cloisters of a
church.
</p><!--l. 18291--><p class="indent" >  A turn of her head reveals her casual reﬂection in a mirrored panel, surrounding the
portal of the shopping tunnel. Her new clothes still look unfamiliar to her. She looks
like a man, but for her long, dark hair. Winter clothing hides her femininity even more
than the customs of her past life. Somehow, she envisioned herself in a diﬀerent style.
There will be time for that later.
</p><!--l. 18298--><p class="indent" >  Winter cannot last here for ever.
</p><!--l. 18301--><p class="indent" >  Preeta steps out, almost into the path of an African Muslim woman with a huge
backside, pushing a pram. She is surrounded by an entourage of miniature children.
The image looks suddenly absurd. Compared to these Westerners, she is a bowling
skittle, donned up in that Sharia garb of khaki brown. Is this the secret weapon of
Mohammed? A militia of giant Muslim bowling skittles with prams to inﬁltrate the
West.
</p><!--l. 18308--><p class="indent" >  Suddenly, Preeta does not feel so unglamorous.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 18311--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 18312--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 18316--><p class="indent" >  Dermot greets her cordially, as though they have never met. Bishop has arranged a
meeting of the group. A couple of days has passed since she sparred with Dermot
in his game. She remembers him well enough. Has he forgotten how she
looks?
</p><!--l. 18322--><p class="indent" >  “Bishop is here,” someone announces.
</p><!--l. 18324--><p class="indent" >  “Anyone know what he wants?”
</p><!--l. 18326--><p class="indent" >  “He wants to heal the world, my son.”

</p><!--l. 18328--><p class="indent" >  Nina laughs, “Do you think he qualiﬁes as a fanatic?”
</p><!--l. 18330--><p class="indent" >  They laugh covertly at his expense, as Bishop strolls in, unaware or untouched by
the jokes. His mind is apparently elsewhere. Art Haugen, the police liason, follows
him in. They both seem relaxed and cheerful.
</p><!--l. 18334--><p class="indent" >  Bishop sees Dermot and Preeta sit down together, as the small group congregates
around the table. “So you two should be working together.” It is not clear whether it is
an order, a statement of expectation or a question.
</p><!--l. 18339--><p class="indent" >  Dermot&#x2019;s discomfort simmers beneath his nonchalance. His body language is
stuttering, as if he has been hauled in against his will. “Uh — I&#x2019;m actually working on
something else.” He immediately seems to regret saying it.
</p><!--l. 18344--><p class="indent" >  “Something tells me that you could be working together anyway.” This time the
order is clear.
</p><!--l. 18347--><p class="indent" >  Dermot nods, face practically in his sweater.
</p><!--l. 18349--><p class="indent" >  “I think we have some things in common,” Preeta poses constructively.
</p><!--l. 18351--><p class="indent" >  “Sure.”
</p><!--l. 18354--><p class="indent" >  “I have been wanting to talk with you,” Preeta tells him.
</p><!--l. 18356--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;ve been attending a police seminar in Santa Monica.”
</p><!--l. 18358--><p class="indent" >  “I didn&#x2019;t know you had been away. I&#x2019;m sorry.”
</p><!--l. 18360--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;ve been here. I was attending by VR, but that means sleeping at odd
times.”
</p><!--l. 18362--><p class="indent" >  “Oh, stupid me.”
</p><!--l. 18364--><p class="indent" >  “Cheaper and quicker, if not perfect. Art was with me.”
</p><!--l. 18366--><p class="indent" >  Art Haugen nods, his eyebrows raised. “Frankly, I would prefer to have made the
trip. I&#x2019;m strictly a beat-cop by nature.”
</p><!--l. 18369--><p class="indent" >  “Our meeting has raised some issues that we need to deal with, folks. We need to
speed up our virus work.”
</p><!--l. 18372--><p class="indent" >  “What does that mean?”
</p><!--l. 18374--><p class="indent" >  “It means we need to coordinate. Dermot,” Bishop directs. “We need to make your
work a matter of priority.”
</p><!--l. 18377--><p class="indent" >  “Has something changed?” Jonathan asks.
</p><!--l. 18379--><p class="indent" >  “There is an Interpol warning out. Intelligence from the U.S. tells us that the
Christian lobby is about to make an oﬀensive that is aimed at exploiting a loophole in
regulations. That means we need your countermeasures prepared. How is that
going?”
</p><!--l. 18384--><p class="indent" >  “This comes as a bit of a surprise,” he deﬂects. “I thought we had more
time.”
</p><!--l. 18387--><p class="indent" >  “It is not a surprise, just a bit inconvenient.”
</p><!--l. 18389--><p class="indent" >  “What form is this oﬀensive going to take?”
</p><!--l. 18391--><p class="indent" >  “We don&#x2019;t know that yet. There are leaks about a possible new bill for congress and
a ballot, combined with a big media campaign.”
</p><!--l. 18394--><p class="indent" >  “And the religions of the world have been hijacked by despotic regimes and the
clergy. Oops, I mean the U.S. government!”
</p><!--l. 18397--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah? What about the Muslim countries?”

</p><!--l. 18399--><p class="indent" >  “Focus please,” Bishop commands, as if used to dealing with a group of unruly
children. “Our friends in the States need our help, not our judgement at this
stage.”
</p><!--l. 18404--><p class="indent" >  “Actually, we are having enough of a situation right now tracing the roots of the
gang violence that is blossoming.”
</p><!--l. 18407--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m aware of that.”
</p><!--l. 18410--><p class="indent" >  “It never rains, but it pours.”
</p><!--l. 18412--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t see where any extra resources are going to come from.”
</p><!--l. 18414--><p class="indent" >  Bishop stays focused on his goals, looking past the obstacles. “So, Dermot, how are
you doing?”
</p><!--l. 18417--><p class="indent" >  He squirms, barely visibly.
</p><!--l. 18419--><p class="indent" >  Preeta observes that Dermot is not the same conﬁdent ﬁgure that he was in the VR.
He seems ill at ease. His body language cries out that he has not done something that
he was supposed to do. If the others notice this, they do not let on, except perhaps for
Bishop who seems to give up.
</p><!--l. 18424--><p class="indent" >  “Why is there a honeypot?” Preeta interjects.
</p><!--l. 18426--><p class="indent" >  Bishop: “Honeypot?”
</p><!--l. 18428--><p class="indent" >  “I was looking through some of the data and I found a police honeypot, linked to
Interpol.”
</p><!--l. 18431--><p class="indent" >  “Not my area,” Bishop shrugs. “You should ask the operations people on the
computer crime team.”
</p><!--l. 18434--><p class="indent" >  She nods.
</p><!--l. 18436--><p class="indent" >  “So this coming action is coming from where?”
</p><!--l. 18438--><p class="indent" >  Dermot nods to her, covertly. Presumably it is his way of saying thank
you.
</p><!--l. 18440--><p class="indent" >  “The Christian lobby has apparently put up a lot of money to extend their
campaign. They have the resources now to dominate the media in the U.S.. Other
factions in the game consortium are ﬁghting back. The FBI is asking for us to be on
our guard, especially here in Scandinavia where the evangelist churches have roots of
their own. There is also talk of something they are holding as a closely guarded secret,
maybe coming soon. We are being asked to stay alert to make sure they don&#x2019;t pull a
fast one.”
</p><!--l. 18449--><p class="indent" >  “Which means we have to pull out the stops?”
</p><!--l. 18451--><p class="indent" >  “Small country, time on our hands.”
</p><!--l. 18453--><p class="indent" >  “And all our ﬂying pigs.”
</p><!--l. 18455--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 18457--><p class="indent" >  “They wait until we are busy with an upsurge in gang activities.”
</p><!--l. 18459--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s just a little suspicious, don&#x2019;t you think? Just a little coordinated?” Ivar
bristles. “I&#x2019;ll bet they arranged the violence as a distraction.”
</p><!--l. 18463--><p class="indent" >  “Let&#x2019;s not get too paranoid. It&#x2019;s the other factions who have generally been
promoting interest in violence. The Christian lobby is ﬁghting them, as far as we can
tell.”
</p><!--l. 18467--><p class="indent" >  “So what kind of campaign are they going to mount?”

</p><!--l. 18469--><p class="indent" >  “We don&#x2019;t know that, I&#x2019;m afraid.”
</p><!--l. 18471--><p class="indent" >  “With all their resources, they are going to have an advantage. It&#x2019;s a strong signal
and it will be coming out in a pretty noisy background.”
</p><!--l. 18475--><p class="indent" >  “So wipe it out.”
</p><!--l. 18477--><p class="indent" >  “With what?”
</p><!--l. 18479--><p class="indent" >  “You tell us. That&#x2019;s why we hire you egg-heads,” Haugen says.
</p><!--l. 18481--><p class="indent" >  “You are all smart people, but I want you to focus on the job now. Let&#x2019;s drop the
conspiracy theories and prejudices and stick to what we know.”
</p><!--l. 18485--><p class="indent" >  “What about an anti-signal? Like sound-neutralizing headphones? What do you
think?”
</p><!--l. 18488--><p class="indent" >  “Make it work and I&#x2019;ll let you know.”
</p><!--l. 18490--><p class="indent" >  “What are the alternatives?”
</p><!--l. 18492--><p class="indent" >  Preeta opens her mouth to speak, but stops short of actual words.
</p><!--l. 18494--><p class="indent" >  “Surely the easiest place to stop it is at source. Can&#x2019;t they do something in the U.S.
to make the campaign illegal?”
</p><!--l. 18497--><p class="indent" >  “The campaign is already illegal. The point is that they are not following the rules.
They are powerful enough to avoid the repercussions.”
</p><!--l. 18500--><p class="indent" >  “Classic corruption scenario.”
</p><!--l. 18502--><p class="indent" >  “Isn&#x2019;t the police powerful too?”
</p><!--l. 18504--><p class="indent" >  “Yes and no. The F.B.I. has orders from government to back oﬀ.”
</p><!--l. 18506--><p class="indent" >  “So if no one else is following orders. . .”
</p><!--l. 18508--><p class="indent" >  “Ivar, if the police force is not seen to obey the chain of command, they
would be shooting themselves in the foot. Anything they do has to be oﬀ the
record.”
</p><!--l. 18512--><p class="indent" >  “So they&#x2019;re shutting us all down?”
</p><!--l. 18514--><p class="indent" >  “No. They can&#x2019;t. They can only shut down the FBI. But that means we have to help
them from the outside.”
</p><!--l. 18517--><p class="indent" >  “Conspiracy nuts are going to love this.”
</p><!--l. 18519--><p class="indent" >  Bishop underlines once again. “This overrides our other activities. There is some
urgency to this. They have the technology to dominate billboards, smart surfaces and
any environmental scenery in the game. That might not sound like much, but we
already know that this is what starts the ball rolling. Once they have momentum, it
becomes a locomotive.”
</p><!--l. 18525--><p class="indent" >  “We&#x2019;ll need Preeta&#x2019;s help. She knows how the rendering works, and she has taught
us to follow the players&#x2019; lifelines.”
</p><!--l. 18528--><p class="indent" >  She nods. “But you know, to be honest, I&#x2019;m not convinced that they can do
it.”
</p><!--l. 18530--><p class="indent" >  “Let&#x2019;s not take that chance.”
</p><!--l. 18532--><p class="indent" >  Bishop concludes. “All right, folks. Go to work. We&#x2019;ll talk again as soon as I know
more. But please do your best on this.”
</p><!--l. 18535--><p class="indent" >  The group splits and Preeta turns to Dermot. “So are we working together?”
</p><!--l. 18538--><p class="indent" >  He shrugs. “It probably makes sense.”
</p><!--l. 18540--><p class="indent" >  She smiles. “And don&#x2019;t forget you&#x2019;re coming out with us tomorrow. ”

</p><!--l. 18542--><p class="indent" >  He frowns. “We&#x2019;ll see.” Then he gets up and ﬂees.
</p><!--l. 18544--><p class="indent" >  She marshals her spinning thoughts. New urgency presides, but is there any point to
it, when the whole game is self-destructing? How can they put into more messages
when the system is already maxed out? Frankly, she would rather ﬁnd out what is
going on at home.
</p><!--l. 18549--><p class="indent" >  “Mr. Bishop, can I please talk to you?”
</p><!--l. 18553--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
