<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">34</span>
</p><!--l. 18556--><p class="indent" >  The helicopter apparently touched down, at a ground station, somewhere unfamiliar
to her. The recollection is fuzzy. She was half asleep. Someone carried Vibe out of the
cabin and put her into a car. There was driving, sharp swings, and she does not
remember anything else, except for a feverish confusion.
</p><!--l. 18562--><p class="indent" >  In a dream someone asked her:
</p><!--l. 18564--><p class="indent" >  “Would you like a room for the night?”
</p><!--l. 18566--><p class="indent" >  Not really. But necessary. “Yes.”
</p><!--l. 18568--><p class="indent" >  They are in a mountain cabin hotel. It is a luxurious place. Frank is here with her,
and Peter Green is sitting by the ﬁreplace. She goes towards him and stands close to
the sofa where he is sitting.
</p><!--l. 18572--><p class="indent" >  “We&#x2019;ll be here by ourselves for an hour or two yet.”
</p><!--l. 18574--><p class="indent" >  “Sara?”
</p><!--l. 18576--><p class="indent" >  “Yes?”
</p><!--l. 18578--><p class="indent" >  “Are you okay?”
</p><!--l. 18580--><p class="indent" >  She sags a little and ﬂashes a half-hearted smile, more a purse of the lips in one
corner of her face. She is exhausted.
</p><!--l. 18583--><p class="indent" >  “Come here.”
</p><!--l. 18585--><p class="indent" >  He puts his arms around her legs and his hand slides up under her skirt, almost
matter of factly, she sags and melts and bends down to kiss him. It is Frank sitting
there, not Peter Green.
</p><!--l. 18590--><p class="indent" >  “Make love to me,” he says.
</p><!--l. 18592--><p class="indent" >  “I need to check my messages,” she says. “Excuse me.”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 18595--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 18596--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>

<!--l. 18599--><p class="indent" >  Daylight, silvery and uncertain. It is a welcome relief from the dark murmurings of
a fever. For a moment, when she woke, she seemed certain that she was lying in her
bivvy bag, up on the mountainside. The bedclothes are damp around her from the
sweat of illness. But the bed is soft and forgiving.
</p><!--l. 18605--><p class="indent" >  It is quiet here. The air seems to have swallowed sound, but for a distant clanking of
a chimney ﬁn. There is a vague aroma of wood burning somewhere. She sees that
Bea has been trying to call her, but she has been ﬂoating in feverish sensory
deprivation.
</p><!--l. 18610--><p class="indent" >  She peels the salty, sopping duvet from her body and tries to sit.
</p><!--l. 18612--><p class="indent" >  A window, with thin curtains is letting enough light to bring her fully to
consciousness. She ﬁnds herself in a medium-sized room with walls of typical
Norwegian cabin panelling – sun-darkened light-wood.
</p><!--l. 18616--><p class="indent" >  Someone has undressed her and put her into some way-baggy pyjamas. A thought
makes her heart skip a beat and she reaches down to check. Then the memory starts to
return. Someone has changed her. . .no, she did it herself. The humiliation of having
someone else clean up her monthly leaching will not compound her misery. Be
grateful for small mercies.
</p><!--l. 18623--><p class="indent" >  A nagging sensation informs her that she ought to be worried about something, but
the body is still too weak to support such a fervour. She suﬃces to lie on her back
feeling tired and weak in every part of her battered body.
</p><!--l. 18628--><p class="indent" >  She must have been here several hours, since yesterday? Is it morning?
</p><!--l. 18630--><p class="indent" >  She rises as carefully as she can and goes into the bathroom, located behind
a sliding door next to the bed. It feels good to be back in civilization after
exposure to more rugged surroundings. The underﬂoor heating soothes the
sores on her feet. Her calves and shin-muscles ache. She staggers like an old
woman.
</p><!--l. 18636--><p class="indent" >  She makes it back to the bed, but by now the sweat has grown cold and the damp
covers are uninviting. She needs clean sheets if she is going to stay there. She scans
around for her clothes and sees them folded up on a chair in the corner of
the room, along with her rucksack. She should probably get dressed. She
pulls some easy training clothes out of her pack, some light shoes and starts
the sluggish process of folding her body into maneuvers that ought to be
straightforward.
</p><!--l. 18644--><p class="indent" >  She creeps, like something between a tortoise and a stick-insect, to the door of the
little room and looks out into the corridor. The ﬂoor is wooden and cold. There is a
damp, limey smell that tells her she is still in the mountains. The smell of a drying
room ﬁlled with mountain clothing and earthen fumes. This seems to be a cabin or
hotel of some kind.
</p><!--l. 18651--><p class="indent" >  Along the corridor, she can hear activity. She places one foot in front of the other
until she is in some kind of reception.
</p><!--l. 18654--><p class="indent" >  Frank is not here, but his partner is sitting in the lounge area writing something.
</p><!--l. 18657--><p class="indent" >  “How are you feeling?”
</p><!--l. 18659--><p class="indent" >  “I feel awful.”

</p><!--l. 18661--><p class="indent" >  “Welcome to our impromptu base of operations.”
</p><!--l. 18663--><p class="indent" >  “Where are we?”
</p><!--l. 18665--><p class="indent" >  “Not all that far from Gjendesheim. We have are using this place as a point of
contact, and as an inﬁrmary for you. You seem to have come down with a
bug.”
</p><!--l. 18669--><p class="indent" >  She laughs. Understatement of the millennium.
</p><!--l. 18672--><p class="indent" >  “Did we catch the bad guys?”
</p><!--l. 18674--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m afraid you passed out on us.”
</p><!--l. 18676--><p class="indent" >  “Where are we?”
</p><!--l. 18678--><p class="indent" >  “Mountain Rescue. Looks like they ﬁnally caught up with you.”
</p><!--l. 18680--><p class="indent" >  She laughs again, yawning at the same time.
</p><!--l. 18682--><p class="indent" >  “Someone is looking for you,” he says.
</p><!--l. 18684--><p class="indent" >  “Who?”
</p><!--l. 18686--><p class="indent" >  “Someone called Lindgren.”
</p><!--l. 18688--><p class="indent" >  She breaths out deeply and then pants for a while in relief. “Did you tell him where
I am?”
</p><!--l. 18691--><p class="indent" >  “Of course.”
</p><!--l. 18693--><p class="indent" >  “I should call my mum too.”
</p><!--l. 18695--><p class="indent" >  “We can take you somewhere where you can catch a bus if you want. But we&#x2019;ll
need to ask you some questions ﬁrst.”
</p><!--l. 18698--><p class="indent" >  “I let you down. I was supposed to help ﬁnd the remaining . . . the stragglers.”
</p><!--l. 18700--><p class="indent" >  “Not to worry. We&#x2019;ve got help from the army now.”
</p><!--l. 18702--><p class="indent" >  “The army?”
</p><!--l. 18704--><p class="indent" >  He nods. “They have certain skills that us police-folks don&#x2019;t have.”
</p><!--l. 18706--><p class="indent" >  She ﬂops down into an opposing chair. “Any chance of a cup of tea?”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 18708--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 18709--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 18713--><p class="indent" >  Sara Stensrud seems to have been under the covers for days now. The shivering and
the shaking have passed into aching lethargy.
</p><!--l. 18716--><p class="indent" >  Her body has been waging war on insurgents that have invaded her, selﬁshly
waving around their unauthorized DNA slogans in her private cells.
</p><!--l. 18720--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Don&#x2019;t post bills in my bloodstream assholes.</span>
</p><!--l. 18722--><p class="indent" >  In the ﬁnal analysis, she knows that this is her own fault, the result of her
own misadventure. She has not slept very well. She has not eaten very well.
She has been hot and cold and hot and cold. . . It is the ideal way to break
down her defences to junk DNA that is circulating on the recesses of her
body.
</p><!--l. 18728--><p class="indent" >  She is feeling better. Stronger.

</p><!--l. 18730--><p class="indent" >  They have been asking her questions about the VeiVeks and about what she saw of
the gangs. At one point, a police commander came and gave her a stern talking-to
about irresponsible behaviour.
</p><!--l. 18734--><p class="indent" >  She tells them about her project and about the warning that Dr. Lindgren gave her.
They inspect her mobile and ﬁnd a surveillance virus. She ﬁlls out some forms and
tries to call home.
</p><!--l. 18739--><p class="indent" >  She spends an hour playing the game, in one of the low level battle sims. She needs
to limber up after her ordeal. Some good-old mindless gaming is good for her state of
mind. She does not exactly cream at the idea of maiming and killing, not like her
brother, but it feels good to expunge some aggression.
</p><!--l. 18745--><p class="indent" >  Physically, she needs the rest, but mentally she needs to let oﬀ some steam, to
lash out at someone—a kind of inverted game rage, apparently. The muscles
down her back are aching, and she feels tired. The instinct to sleep is still
strong, but her stubbornness overrides it. Probably she has now slept very
well.
</p><!--l. 18751--><p class="indent" >  They ﬁght hand to hand, or with weapons. She shoots and kicks at the phantasms of
the LinearAssault Castle Keep. They fall or they melt or they explode into
the oblivion of relief. It does not bother her that the game designers have
made all of the enemies look like Bedouin nomads, or Chinese assassins.
She would have preferred it if they had looked like the French team, but her
imagination is good enough to think of them as French team with plastic
surgery.
</p><!--l. 18759--><p class="indent" >  Maybe she would exclude Peter Green. Or maybe they should all look like him. A
quick back-ﬂip and a kick to the jaw. Follow up with a laser pulse. A quick death, ﬁfty
points.
</p><!--l. 18763--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">What the hell am I still thinking about here?</span>
</p><!--l. 18765--><p class="indent" >  Does he even know what is going on? He doesn&#x2019;t know that she is here, or who she
is.
</p><!--l. 18768--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Fuck him! Why should I care.</span>
</p><!--l. 18770--><p class="indent" >  Fuck him? What would that be like?
</p><!--l. 18773--><p class="indent" >  She feels depressed for the ﬁrst time in a long time. This is not the way things were
supposed to happen. She could call Bea to broadcast her humiliation, but for once she
just wants a little privacy.
</p><!--l. 18777--><p class="indent" >  So she goes to Plovdiv and enters the sims without Bea. She goes to kick ass and
blow up tanks. This time she wants to see how bad her morality score can
be.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 18782--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 18783--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 18786--><p class="indent" >  Frank comes in, late in the evening.

</p><!--l. 18788--><p class="indent" >  “What are you doing up at this hour?”
</p><!--l. 18790--><p class="indent" >  “Couldn&#x2019;t sleep.” She has been sleeping for most of the day. He looks weary, but
calm. His voice is soft and comfortable.
</p><!--l. 18794--><p class="indent" >  There is no denying that she is fascinated. Whatever. He has a way about him. But
she didn&#x2019;t come here to meet him. What the hell is he doing confusing her like this?
She has been thinking about the French team for so long that she must at least
try to see them before changing her obsession. But she could have this one
now.
</p><!--l. 18801--><p class="indent" >  He gestures to her mobile bits and pieces lying on the table in front of
her.
</p><!--l. 18803--><p class="indent" >  “What&#x2019;s this?”
</p><!--l. 18805--><p class="indent" >  “Trying to work. I found out that I was able to reach some of the VeiVeks again by
regular net.”
</p><!--l. 18808--><p class="indent" >  He raises his eyebrows as if to politely ask if that is good.
</p><!--l. 18810--><p class="indent" >  “That means I can see what is going on again.”
</p><!--l. 18812--><p class="indent" >  “Good news?”
</p><!--l. 18814--><p class="indent" >  “Not really. The guide robots have all gone into the same state,” she say. “There
could be a bug somewhere. If I were feeling fresher, I could make a work around,
but I am not really up to it. I was just interested in why it would happen at
all.”
</p><!--l. 18819--><p class="indent" >  “So what are they doing?”
</p><!--l. 18821--><p class="indent" >  “Some of them are gravitating to one particular route through the mountains, and
others are going oﬀ at random. They seem to have decided this of their own
accord.” She heaves a sigh. “To be honest I haven&#x2019;t got the energy to care right
now.”
</p><!--l. 18826--><p class="indent" >  He reaches forward and puts his palm on her forehead.
</p><!--l. 18828--><p class="indent" >  “You&#x2019;re still unwell. You should be resting.”
</p><!--l. 18830--><p class="indent" >  She nods. “I was about to go back and sleep. What about you?” <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Do you want to join</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">me? </span>“Don&#x2019;t you get to sleep?”
</p><!--l. 18833--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m ﬁnished now. Our team will stay here tonight and wait for new orders
tomorrow. I think we&#x2019;re done here.”
</p><!--l. 18836--><p class="indent" >  “I can take her down to the dungeon.”
</p><!--l. 18838--><p class="indent" >  Another police uniform enters. She recognizes the face. It&#x2019;s the single-mother
beat-bitch who accosted her at the train-station. Vibe scowls.
</p><!--l. 18843--><p class="indent" >  “So you came back.” Her tone is something between sarcasm and malignant
nonchalance.
</p><!--l. 18846--><p class="indent" >  Vibe doesn&#x2019;t answer.
</p><!--l. 18848--><p class="indent" >  “Thought for a moment there, you didn&#x2019;t listen to my advice.”
</p><!--l. 18850--><p class="indent" >  “Have you come to get me? Am I in some kind of trouble?”
</p><!--l. 18852--><p class="indent" >  “Someone is going to want to talk to you. About your extra-curricular activities.
But not tonight.”
</p><!--l. 18855--><p class="indent" >  Vibe looks at Frank, questioningly.
</p><!--l. 18857--><p class="indent" >  “We are just clocking oﬀ. It&#x2019;s time to get some sleep.”

</p><!--l. 18859--><p class="indent" >  The woman about-turns and goes to the reception desk to check in.
</p><!--l. 18862--><p class="indent" >  Vibe has spent a lot of time recording and understanding facial expressions. She has
an unusually expressive face. Why else would she get her way in most cases? She is
an expert manipulator. But this woman&#x2019;s face is dead. Lifeless. She is a robot. Maybe
she can be switched oﬀ.
</p><!--l. 18867--><p class="indent" >  “Let&#x2019;s all get some rest. It&#x2019;s been a long day.”
</p><!--l. 18869--><p class="indent" >  Exhaustion overcomes resentment for now.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 18875--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 18876--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 18879--><p class="indent" >  “Everyone wake up!”
</p><!--l. 18881--><p class="indent" >  “What&#x2019;s going on?”
</p><!--l. 18883--><p class="indent" >  “Weather anomaly. Sudden winter. Snow&#x2019;s coming. We need to vacate this cabin
and get to major roads.”
</p><!--l. 18886--><p class="indent" >  “What about the operations?”
</p><!--l. 18888--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s out of our hands now. Come on – hurry. We&#x2019;ve only got a couple of hours
before it starts. After that, we might not be able to get out at all.”
</p><!--l. 18893--><p class="indent" >  It has snowed several centimetres during the night and the air is still spitting small
icy snowﬂakes. The road outside has been cleared, and now seems abandoned.
Wispy white powder gusts across it, like a bleached western movie. Saloon
doors ﬂap and gun ﬁghters face each other as tumbleweed rolls into giant
snowballs.
</p><!--l. 18899--><p class="indent" >  She has spent the last hour beaming pictures of the scene outside the window of the
reception to Bea, back in the city.
</p><!--l. 18902--><p class="indent" >  “Get out your sledge, girl!” Bea told her.
</p><!--l. 18904--><p class="indent" >  “And bruise my perfect behind? Are you losing it?”
</p><!--l. 18906--><p class="indent" >  She sees a car pull up and terminates her banter. “Talk to you later.”
</p><!--l. 18908--><p class="indent" >  Frank strolls in, letting in a blast of cold mountain air and a ﬂurry of snow. He is
wearing a uniform today. It is pretty sexy, she thinks.
</p><!--l. 18911--><p class="indent" >  “Good morning,” he greets cheerily.
</p><!--l. 18913--><p class="indent" >  “Hey,” is her more sulky response.
</p><!--l. 18915--><p class="indent" >  “How are you feeling?”
</p><!--l. 18917--><p class="indent" >  “Better.”
</p><!--l. 18919--><p class="indent" >  “Made any progress with your work?”
</p><!--l. 18921--><p class="indent" >  She shakes her head. “They&#x2019;re gone. Everything has gone dead.”
</p><!--l. 18923--><p class="indent" >  “Oh?”
</p><!--l. 18925--><p class="indent" >  She lifts a hand towards the window. “The weather probably. Or maybe someone
has taken them out of service.”
</p><!--l. 18928--><p class="indent" >  “Well, glad to hear that you are on the mend.”
</p><!--l. 18930--><p class="indent" >  “So are you driving me to the bus station? Should I pack?”

</p><!--l. 18932--><p class="indent" >  “I have new orders. Looks like we&#x2019;re not getting rid of you so quickly.”
</p><!--l. 18934--><p class="indent" >  “What do you mean?”
</p><!--l. 18936--><p class="indent" >  “Command wants me to drive you to meet someone. He&#x2019;s coming up from Oslo to
see you.”
</p><!--l. 18939--><p class="indent" >  “Heah?”
</p><!--l. 18941--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t ask me. I&#x2019;m just following orders.”
</p><!--l. 18943--><p class="indent" >  “But what am I supposed to know?”
</p><!--l. 18945--><p class="indent" >  “I think it has to do with the threat that you received.”
</p><!--l. 18947--><p class="indent" >  “Oh.” She had almost forgotten. “But why come here? What&#x2019;s wrong with
calling?”
</p><!--l. 18949--><p class="indent" >  He shrugs. “No one tells me anything,”
</p><!--l. 18951--><p class="indent" >  “I should get back to Oslo.”
</p><!--l. 18953--><p class="indent" >  “Paramedic said you should rest a while. The plan is to move you closer to the main
roads. This place is going to be impassable soon. We&#x2019;ll have to close up for the
winter.”
</p><!--l. 18957--><p class="indent" >  “Now?”
</p><!--l. 18959--><p class="indent" >  “As soon as you can get ready.”
</p><!--l. 18961--><p class="indent" >  “But I should take a shower and make myself look presentable. . .”
</p><!--l. 18963--><p class="indent" >  “Never mind that. You look ﬁne.”
</p><!--l. 18965--><p class="indent" >  He puts his hand on her shoulder. Her heart skips a beat. She scowls and shakes it
free. What was that? Doesn&#x2019;t he realize that she is attracted to him? Idiot! She
turns away from him and goes to stand at the window, facing out into neutral
territory.
</p><!--l. 18970--><p class="indent" >  “I look awful.”
</p><!--l. 18972--><p class="indent" >  His partner enters, letting in another blast of freezing air.
</p><!--l. 18974--><p class="indent" >  “Are we ready?”
</p><!--l. 18976--><p class="indent" >  Frank says. “Sara&#x2019;s just going to collect her things.”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 18978--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 18979--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 18982--><p class="indent" >  The car crackles slowly along the swinging road, ploughing through the light
snowfall. The wind is gusting a little today, and the road is relatively clear, so far.
They make slow but steady progress along the mountain road. The snow plough has
been here to make a token eﬀort, but soon this road will be closed for the winter.
After an hour of driving, there is descent into a valley, where the road is
clearer.
</p><!--l. 18990--><p class="indent" >  “So what are you doing here really? At this time of year?”
</p><!--l. 18992--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m not supposed to be here at all,” she sulks.
</p><!--l. 18994--><p class="indent" >  “But you&#x2019;re here.”

</p><!--l. 18996--><p class="indent" >  She nods. “There is a team of French engineers who built these robots. They are
testing them, and I am supposed to get data from their tests, since I wrote a lot of the
reasoning algorithms. But then they suddenly went weird on me and said they were
pulling out. Then they literally just disappeared, leaving me pretty screwed—pardon
my French.”
</p><!--l. 19002--><p class="indent" >  “So you came here looking for them?”
</p><!--l. 19004--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s my mum&#x2019;s fault. She is a woman of action. I suppose I take after her a bit. It
seemed like a good idea at the time.”
</p><!--l. 19007--><p class="indent" >  “What, just to come here out of the blue?”
</p><!--l. 19009--><p class="indent" >  She shakes her head. “Huh uh. You see, Mrs. Laurent, the team leader—I think she
likes me. So she said I should come out as quickly as I could.”
</p><!--l. 19012--><p class="indent" >  “And here you are.”
</p><!--l. 19014--><p class="indent" >  “I came to try to make contact with the team who has been testing out the hardware
of the VeiVeks—my robots.”
</p><!--l. 19021--><p class="indent" >  “Sure, they have as many applications as you want. Tourism, exploration, search
and rescue, surveillance, maintenance, gardening. . .”
</p><!--l. 19024--><p class="indent" >  “They use adaptive game theory to reason.”
</p><!--l. 19026--><p class="indent" >  “What&#x2019;s that for a game of soldiers?”
</p><!--l. 19028--><p class="indent" >  “Ugh. It&#x2019;s like optimization. Tells you how to make good compromises, if you have
a rough idea of how your opponents think.”
</p><!--l. 19031--><p class="indent" >  “Sounds like something for a police force.”
</p><!--l. 19033--><p class="indent" >  “Maybe.”
</p><!--l. 19035--><p class="indent" >  “Stupid comment, huh?”
</p><!--l. 19037--><p class="indent" >  “No,” she shakes her head moodily. “I&#x2019;m not really an expert.” She shrugs. “I&#x2019;m a
user, not a dealer.”
</p><!--l. 19042--><p class="indent" >  Mountain scenery is bleak but stunning. Even the best game graphics cannot match
the experience of such a sight. At one point, she rolls down the window to remove the
glass barrier between her and the outside world. If you want to enjoy reality, you
cannot shield yourself from it.
</p><!--l. 19050--><p class="indent" >  She feels cold, dizzy and her body still aches. She needs sleep. The cold ﬁngers of
fever are tickling her again.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 19056--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 19057--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 19060--><p class="indent" >  As if the result of her premonition, a man is waiting for them when they arrive. An
American, waiting impatiently to go just outside the doorway of the hotel. He seems
anxious to leave.
</p><!--l. 19064--><p class="indent" >  Vibe&#x2019;s fury is contained only by her exhaustion.
</p><!--l. 19067--><p class="indent" >  “Hello, I am clearing up for the ESA team. I heard your were looking for them, and
I have something for you.”

</p><!--l. 19071--><p class="indent" >  She measures her response with all of the control she can muster. “Have you seen
them?”
</p><!--l. 19074--><p class="indent" >  “No, I was brought in to clear up the equipment. I wasn&#x2019;t told when they left. Wait a
minute, I have something for you.”
</p><!--l. 19080--><p class="indent" >  He seems to be waiting to leave, with boxes loaded onto a trailer. He returns with a
small cubical box, sealed with tape.
</p><!--l. 19083--><p class="indent" >  “Is that the swarm?” she hisses, pointing to the boxes.
</p><!--l. 19085--><p class="indent" >  “All the ones I could recover.”
</p><!--l. 19087--><p class="indent" >  “I am supposed to give this to you in person. Can I have your ID?”
</p><!--l. 19090--><p class="indent" >  She beams him her credentials on infrared.
</p><!--l. 19092--><p class="indent" >  “Fine. This is yours.”
</p><!--l. 19095--><p class="indent" >  ”Do you know where they are now?”
</p><!--l. 19097--><p class="indent" >  “No, sorry. All I know is that they are pissed at us for some reason and they have
been yanked home.”
</p><!--l. 19100--><p class="indent" >  “Fine.”
</p><!--l. 19102--><p class="indent" >  “I can pass on a message if I hear anything.”
</p><!--l. 19104--><p class="indent" >  “All right. Tell them I was looking for them. And that they have no fucking right to
mess up my project.”
</p><!--l. 19107--><p class="indent" >  She receives a trace smile, which immediately fades to a blank look.
</p><!--l. 19109--><p class="indent" >  “So, let&#x2019;s see.” He looks down at his mobile screen and reads, “Sara Veye-beak
Stennsrudd.”
</p><!--l. 19112--><p class="indent" >  She smiles with the anatomy of a duck.
</p><!--l. 19114--><p class="indent" >  “Veee-behhhh-kuhhhhh,” she assists with a huﬀy look. Peasant. “Just call me
Vibe.”
</p><!--l. 19119--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-38r35"></a>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-0"></a>
<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">35</span>
</p><!--l. 19122--><p class="indent" >  “Why the hell are they using the Norwegians for this? Aren&#x2019;t there any US allies we
could be working with?”
</p><!--l. 19125--><p class="indent" >  The virtual presence of Republican senator MacMillan seems strangely immobile
for its level of agitation; the reality of the image is not entirely convincing, sitting at
this long conference table. Den is sitting near to the bottom of the table. He bides his
time. There is no hurry to speak up here. There are plenty of others here talking:
government aids, consortium members and external guests from a variety of religious
organizations.
</p><!--l. 19133--><p class="indent" >  “Aren&#x2019;t they allies?” someone asks.
</p><!--l. 19135--><p class="indent" >  “They produce oil, therefore they cannot be an ally.”
</p><!--l. 19137--><p class="indent" >  “Great Britain is an ally. Don&#x2019;t they produce oil?”
</p><!--l. 19139--><p class="indent" >  “The hell with Great Britain. They do what we tell them.”
</p><!--l. 19141--><p class="indent" >  Den smiles in the privacy of his own cave. The older senator has apparently not
mastered the idea of a virtual meeting. Sitting there in Washington, he really thinks he
is surrounded by Americans. That, or he simply doesn&#x2019;t care who he oﬀends. The
marionettes in this gloriﬁed phone-conference are well rendered human ﬁgures, but
they do not necessarily look like the people who are operating their strings.
Players experience a low threshold for oﬀending pieces of artwork, with only
simulated facial expressions. Still, one wonders what this man is like face to
face.
</p><!--l. 19151--><p class="indent" >  “The Norwegians are the least of our troubles. They are safe, sir,” says an apparent
aid.
</p><!--l. 19154--><p class="indent" >  “Apparently, Reverend Weinberg likes spending his holidays there, Senator,” one of
his aids supplements. “Norway and the U.S. apparently share a common blessing: a
Christian South. A Bible belt. He tells me that it is a country where we actually have
great inﬂuence, through the right channels.”
</p><!--l. 19160--><p class="indent" >  “No kidding?” The senator&#x2019;s gruﬀness takes pause for a second of thought. “What
do you make of this, Tony?”

</p><!--l. 19163--><p class="indent" >  “Well it&#x2019;s just a country, but politically it is not a bad decision. Norway is always
wanting to be in on the action. They never try to lead the way, or try to get the upper
hand. It&#x2019;s just always there, trying to compromise, trying to get involved. I like that.
Stay in the shadows; make no enemies.”
</p><!--l. 19169--><p class="indent" >  “But do they have experience of the kind of technology we are looking
at?”
</p><!--l. 19171--><p class="indent" >  “We hire only the best. It&#x2019;s a high tech country, Sam.”
</p><!--l. 19173--><p class="indent" >  “No kidding?”
</p><!--l. 19175--><p class="indent" >  “That is my estimation.”
</p><!--l. 19177--><p class="indent" >  “Well good. I guess it&#x2019;s nothing to worry about. Good. But doesn&#x2019;t this add
an extra level of complication to our strategy? Do you think we can cope
with it? Could we make contact with the Christian base directly – to help us
somehow?”
</p><!--l. 19182--><p class="indent" >  “It might be possible, but strictly speaking that&#x2019;s not our problem. That is why we
have secured ourselves Mr. Morris&#x2019;s services. We intend to use our contacts in the
evangelical churches to apply pressure where we can. I&#x2019;m in touch with the embassy
on that – but that is a side issue here.”
</p><!--l. 19188--><p class="indent" >  “This is the man Dean picked up?”
</p><!--l. 19190--><p class="indent" >  “Morris? Yes, sir. Here is here with us at the meeting.”
</p><!--l. 19192--><p class="indent" >  Den allows his avatar, his VR likeness, to raise a hand in silence. As an image
designer, he likes these virtual meetings. The great advantage of an intermediary
reality is that one can simulate the little ﬁnesses of human social contact, like the
raising of a hand to speak, or seeing all of the members of the meeting in a bird&#x2019;s-eye
view. It is less intimidating than having a bunch of cameras pointing at all of the
members&#x2019; faces, and then trying to watch nine diﬀerent views at the same
time and butt in at the right moment. Technology has its beneﬁts. He has
chosen his image here carefully; it does not resemble his actual physical
appearance, but rather that of an older man, more portly and staid than he
is. He has not met anyone here. Senator Dean has not yet shown up at the
meeting.
</p><!--l. 19205--><p class="indent" >  “Hello, Mr. Morris.”
</p><!--l. 19207--><p class="indent" >  “Hello.”
</p><!--l. 19209--><p class="indent" >  “Where is Dean, anyway?”
</p><!--l. 19211--><p class="indent" >  “He&#x2019;s supposed to be joining us, sir. I guess he&#x2019;s been delayed.”
</p><!--l. 19213--><p class="indent" >  “Fine, all right. Why don&#x2019;t we get started, before we all go nuts. What are we all
doing here? What&#x2019;s the agenda. Jerry?”
</p><!--l. 19216--><p class="indent" >  “Thank you, sir. Welcome everyone to this virtual meeting. I&#x2019;ll be presenting to you
in a moment our plan for rapid action, but for the beneﬁt of the group, let me just run
though the names. You should be seeing them on your displays now.” He pauses only
slightly. “Now, as you all know, our special interest here is to bring the morality of the
church back into the fore of leadership in this country. The greatness of our
spiritual institutions has been diluted over the years by the sinners in politics,
who would have it that there is no place for a moral content to government.

The American people disagrees with this, but so-called liberals have long
held the reins of media and they have polluted the airwaves with all kinds of
decrepitude.”
</p><!--l. 19228--><p class="indent" >  Assent of: “Hear, hear!”
</p><!--l. 19230--><p class="indent" >  So, Den thinks, you sly bastards. We are working for the church, after all.
Somehow, he is not surprised. A cloud of doubt and suspicion condenses in his mind
from the vapours of the past week. Once again, his eﬀorts to take charge of his future
lead him merely into greater servitude.
</p><!--l. 19235--><p class="indent" >  “As you know, our strategy has been to supplant the traditional media outlets
with a single, more powerful array of options. We are already succeeding
in attracting people away from the traditional media – although we have
been unable to do this without the help of Hollywood and certain technology
interests.
</p><!--l. 19241--><p class="indent" >  “We seem to have to have that situation under control, but we are still lagging
behind on the transfer of focus to our position of authority. The traditional media are
mostly in bed with the government, and we need to shift attention from them over to
the church&#x2019;s machine.”
</p><!--l. 19247--><p class="indent" >  “Jerry, I think we are all familiar. . .”
</p><!--l. 19249--><p class="indent" >  “Well, I . . . all right. Let&#x2019;s move on.”
</p><!--l. 19251--><p class="indent" >  He pauses, perhaps out of disappointment, or perhaps to call on new powers.
</p><!--l. 19253--><p class="indent" >  “I am here to inform everyone about our planned up-coming R.A.O.”
</p><!--l. 19255--><p class="indent" >  “What&#x2019;s that?” Den asks.
</p><!--l. 19257--><p class="indent" >  “Our Rapid Action Operation. This has come upon us more quickly than
anticipated. Our intelligence services have been planning this for some time, but
recent revelations . . .” He makes inverted commas with his ﬁngers. “. . .necessitate a
small change in the schedule.”
</p><!--l. 19262--><p class="indent" >  He throws up a diagram on the presentation wall of the meeting room
and each attendee gets a smaller copy in front of them, closer to their visual
ﬁeld.
</p><!--l. 19266--><p class="indent" >  “This is a map of the game plan for drawing support to the congregations. We have
an opportunity to cement the power base of the country in the evangelical churches
more permanently than before, while the civil government and its arms are quite
weak.”
</p><!--l. 19271--><p class="indent" >  A British voice pipes up: “Why do you say that the forces of civil government
are weak?” Den identiﬁes the man as a member of the British civil service,
McEnzie—presumably with delegated powers of government. He speaks with that
insuﬀerable poshness, which belies Britain&#x2019;s continued predilection for private
schools that groom for government.
</p><!--l. 19278--><p class="indent" >  “Because we now have a window.”
</p><!--l. 19280--><p class="indent" >  “Explain it, Jerry.”
</p><!--l. 19282--><p class="indent" >  “Here it is. Civil government is currently stretched by the rise in lawlessness. By
the lack of moral values in society – the very noose which they have made for
themselves, you might say. The riots and gangland crime is keeping them busy. The

forces in the U.S. are particularly over-stretched and the Japanese are apparently
seeing the same kind of thing. We have a window of opportunity to move on our
agenda because of recent revelations about the gaming software, as you are all aware.
So far we have had to move carefully. The F.B.I. has been watching us, at the behest
of our more secular colleagues. These who oppose our motion, claim to stand for the
federal will. But, we are not disheartened. The revelations about the game have now
unleashed a number of attacks by the mob on the computing industry. The F.B.I.&#x2019;s
hands are pretty much full trying to quell these attempts to move in on the
game.”
</p><!--l. 19297--><p class="indent" >  “Why didn&#x2019;t we think of that sooner?”
</p><!--l. 19299--><p class="indent" >  “What the hell does the mob want with the game?” someone asks.
</p><!--l. 19301--><p class="indent" >  “Yes. They&#x2019;re crooks, not politicians?”
</p><!--l. 19303--><p class="indent" >  Den smiles, alone in his cave, wondering if there is a distinction. Politics is a
dangerous sport, he thinks. You spend time ﬁghting one another instead of ﬁghting the
true enemies of the world.
</p><!--l. 19307--><p class="indent" >  “Well, that&#x2019;s a bit simplistic. The mob are looking for opportunities, just like
everyone else.”
</p><!--l. 19310--><p class="indent" >  “Quite,” says the English voice. “These days, who is to distinguish between one
group from the next? Strikes me that we are dealing with cliques and mobs wherever
you look.”
</p><!--l. 19314--><p class="indent" >  “Isn&#x2019;t that why we are here? To bring all these people back into the ﬂock?”
</p><!--l. 19317--><p class="indent" >  “But the maﬁa? Gang violence? That&#x2019;s an underground operation. Why would they
want to get involved in media?”
</p><!--l. 19320--><p class="indent" >  “Simple. Identity theft. Extortion. If you control the game, you can trick people out
of their private information and assume their identities. If you can do that, then
you have access to all of their resources. Information is power, ladies and
gentlemen.”
</p><!--l. 19325--><p class="indent" >  “Jesus Christ. It just gets worse.”
</p><!--l. 19327--><p class="indent" >  “Sir, please moderate your blasphemy.”
</p><!--l. 19329--><p class="indent" >  “Pardon me, Mr. Pournelle.”
</p><!--l. 19331--><p class="indent" >  “We have to be aware of all of these things. People are in competition over this. Our
campaign is going to have to work on a number of levels.”
</p><!--l. 19335--><p class="indent" >  “Well, we have a head-start. We have been planning our campaign for some time.
And it&#x2019;s a campaign with many facets. Not just a simple operation.”
</p><!--l. 19339--><p class="indent" >  “Indeed. The campaign has been building up for some time, but never openly. What
we are suggesting now is a more concerted eﬀort, a strong push that will capture a
large congregation in one fell swoop. It&#x2019;s an opportunity that we have to
grasp.”
</p><!--l. 19344--><p class="indent" >  The bong of a gong sounds in Den&#x2019;s head. A overlaid text shows a new arrival at the
meeting. The table adjusts its length and Senator Dean materializes.
</p><!--l. 19348--><p class="indent" >  “Welcome, Senator Dean,” says the aid apparent.
</p><!--l. 19350--><p class="indent" >  “Hello, everyone. Mr. Morris. Sorry I&#x2019;m a little late. I had some business with my
youngest. Somehow they never quite leave the fold. What did I miss?”

</p><!--l. 19354--><p class="indent" >  MacMillan says, “We just started, but the timing is good. Mr. Morris. . .” He turns
his attention down the non-existent table, sending packets of information to and fro&#x2019;
beneath the Atlantic ocean, in tightly conﬁned ﬁbres. “You have been singled out as a
key person in this operation. With your access to game information streams, we
can tap directly into the game channels without going through the oﬃcial
consortium route. We don&#x2019;t want to draw unnecessary attention to this project
amongst competing interest groups. They would probably place barriers in our
way.”
</p><!--l. 19364--><p class="indent" >  Silently observing and mulling, Den does not feel like making reply, but knows that
he should. Now is not the time to be herded like cattle by these Christian cowboys. “I
was recently asked to help, yes,” he says. “My understanding was that you wanted us
to invent a speciﬁc campaign from scratch. That will take a few days to come up with,
at least. More than that I have not learned yet. I have not been long back in the
U.K..”
</p><!--l. 19372--><p class="indent" >  “That is one reason for holding this meeting today,” Dean interposes. “Not
everyone has been introduced. Everyone participating in this net meeting will be
receiving bios and contact information to everyone else in the group.”
</p><!--l. 19377--><p class="indent" >  Den adds. “I confess that I&#x2019;m not exactly clear about what kind of campaign
you want us to instigate. It sounds as though you already have a campaign. I
was led to believe that I would be starting this from scratch, with creative
control.”
</p><!--l. 19382--><p class="indent" >  “That is not entirely true,” senator MacMillan puts. “We have a partial
campaign for the U.S., but we have larger ambitions here. The game has been put
together to be a global event. We are not just supplanting the regular media
here in the U.S., but all over the world. If we play our cards right, we can
reach out and unify the world into a single moral and spiritual entity. But our
campaign, thus far, is tied to the U.S., and I am told that it will not work
elsewhere, for whatever reason. Perhaps Claire can tell us something about
that?”
</p><!--l. 19391--><p class="indent" >  A female ﬁgure, sitting at the table, is highlighted. “Our research shows that U.S.
advertising culture is diﬀerent enough from the rest of the world that we must
employ local expertise to reach out beyond our borders. But that applies
mainly to the billboards and slogans. The core parts of the gaming can be used
universally.”
</p><!--l. 19397--><p class="indent" >  “Such as?”
</p><!--l. 19399--><p class="indent" >  “You tell us, Mr. Morris” MacMillan says. “Senator Dean seems to think that you
are the man for the job.”
</p><!--l. 19402--><p class="indent" >  “Mr. Morris and his company pretty much have their ﬁnger on the pulse and have
the keys to the game. I think you can help us, can&#x2019;t you Mr. Morris.”
</p><!--l. 19406--><p class="indent" >  Den notes that it is not a question he is presented with. He is pleased that
he chose to switch oﬀ the emotional rendering in his apparition. “I am still
checking out some legal details,” he says. “I can only discuss generalities at this
time.”

</p><!--l. 19411--><p class="indent" >  “May I remind you of the deal you made with Senator Dean, Mr. Morris. Are you
telling us that you are considering changing your position?”
</p><!--l. 19415--><p class="indent" >  “I think we made only a verbal agreement,” Den corrects. “I am an honourable
person,” Den says. “But I am also a law abiding person. I am treating this meeting is
a conﬁdential consultancy. But I have made no promise yet. I still have to
let my legal department investigate our position in helping you.” He feels
Kylie McLachlan&#x2019;s arms embrace him from behind, in his London cave,
watching and advising. It is just as well the others cannot see that she is there, he
thinks.
</p><!--l. 19424--><p class="indent" >  “Well, please ﬁnd it out quickly. the clock is now ticking and we need your help.
We can either reward you handsomely, or you are out of it.”
</p><!--l. 19427--><p class="indent" >  “And we shall hold you to your NDA, Mr. Morris.”
</p><!--l. 19429--><p class="indent" >  “Fine. What I can tell you is that we have the technology and the rendering
techniques to make a broad campaign. When I know the details, I can put together a
suggestion for both active content and passive content. I&#x2019;ll need more information,
obviously.” We also have certain ethics standards in our company, he thinks, but omits
to mention it at this juncture. They go somewhat beyond the idea of a Non-Disclosure
Agreement. “It shouldn&#x2019;t be a problem.”
</p><!--l. 19437--><p class="indent" >  The ﬁgure, referred to as Claire, continues. “I can say a little more about the general
campaign,” she drawls. “For the gaming part, we have two new point-scoring scripts:
a conspiracy mystery and a classic adventure hunt. These are popular game items,
according to our research.”
</p><!--l. 19443--><p class="indent" >  “How will these help the campaign?”
</p><!--l. 19445--><p class="indent" >  “We&#x2019;ve had morality barometers for some time now, in several parts of the game,
but we want to go even further. We&#x2019;ve been pushing to have it built into the
fundamental platform that all the gaming software uses, so even third party
contributions have it. If you don&#x2019;t behave as we want you to, you don&#x2019;t score in the
game and you lose privileges. Kids respond to that kind of thing, they are more ﬁckle,
but not adults.”
</p><!--l. 19453--><p class="indent" >  “Neat.”
</p><!--l. 19455--><p class="indent" >  “We have a separate program for coaxing kids back to patriotism.”
</p><!--l. 19457--><p class="indent" >  “Preying on kids seems a little harsh.”
</p><!--l. 19459--><p class="indent" >  “Hah. Right. Let&#x2019;s make no mistake here, these kids are already under attack from a
whole host of sources.”
</p><!--l. 19462--><p class="indent" >  “Under attack?”
</p><!--l. 19464--><p class="indent" >  “Sure. From both inside and outside the country, there are professional
recruiters, turning kids into hackers and criminals, promising them all kinds
of things for working on their behalf. Kids don&#x2019;t have a moral compass at
an early age. They just want to have a good time. They think of crime as a
game.”
</p><!--l. 19470--><p class="indent" >  “The strategy is to trace their activities over time, learn who their friends are and
then make them think that they are letting their closest friends and parents down by
not acting in their country&#x2019;s best interests.”

</p><!--l. 19474--><p class="indent" >  “Actually, it is easier to make virtual friends for many of these kids. They can&#x2019;t
usually tell the diﬀerence. A lot of them don&#x2019;t meet, except in the game.”
</p><!--l. 19478--><p class="indent" >  “So you make them a role model to your own speciﬁcations?”
</p><!--l. 19480--><p class="indent" >  “Gotta catch&#x2019;em early” Claire makes a nervous soccer-mom laughs. ”Anyways.
Our department reckons these game modules will have pretty universal appeal, and we
can put a fair bit or resources into tying in popular music and star appearances for the
kids.”
</p><!--l. 19485--><p class="indent" >  “Is this going to be enough?” MacMillan asks. “Sorry, I know that I am not an
expert here, but shouldn&#x2019;t we actually go up against the war-games and . . .you know.”
His avatar waves its hands expansively.
</p><!--l. 19489--><p class="indent" >  “Some of the treasure hunting scenes are placed in amongst the government&#x2019;s
war-games, i.e. belonging other modules. We are adding our own subliminal content
there to paint them in a black light, but we cannot get involved directly in the warring
regions ”
</p><!--l. 19494--><p class="indent" >  “Why not?”
</p><!--l. 19496--><p class="indent" >  “We have to engage players in more sedate scenarios to program their
attitudes.”
</p><!--l. 19499--><p class="indent" >  Den proﬀers an explanation. “Once the pulse is racing, once it goes above about a
hundred, and the body is secreting adrenalin, it is not receptive to higher cognitive
impulses. People don&#x2019;t listen when they are agitated. They are basically on primitive
autopilot. So we have to place these suggestions in the parts of the game where people
are thinking.”
</p><!--l. 19506--><p class="indent" >  “Exactly.”
</p><!--l. 19508--><p class="indent" >  “So you draw them away from the ﬁghting?”
</p><!--l. 19510--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s the idea.”
</p><!--l. 19512--><p class="indent" >  “And once they are away from the ﬁghting”
</p><!--l. 19514--><p class="indent" >  “Then we hit them with all kinds of impulses, live and static.”
</p><!--l. 19516--><p class="indent" >  MacMillan shakes his head, and murmurs with a certain awe. “I don&#x2019;t know. This is
all a new world, isn&#x2019;t it? Do we really have it under control?”
</p><!--l. 19520--><p class="indent" >  Claire continues: “We have noted one thousand facial expressions that stimulate the
emotional responses we want. These play a key role in representing our outreach
campaign. They engage people.”
</p><!--l. 19524--><p class="indent" >  Den interjects again: “Facial rendering is a something that we spend a lot of time
developing in diﬀerent social groups. That is one of the areas where our company has
signiﬁcant expertise. If the dynamical billboards and smart surfaces do not convey the
right expressions to the right players, you can end up simply harming your
cause.”
</p><!--l. 19530--><p class="indent" >  He feels Kylie&#x2019;s ﬁngers tug at him, telling him not to be too eager. Don&#x2019;t get carried
away, Den.
</p><!--l. 19533--><p class="indent" >  “We know that, Mr. Morris. And that is an area where we will be needing your
help.”
</p><!--l. 19536--><p class="indent" >  “We get the players to meet and compare facial expressions. And we make them
laugh, at least once every session. Laughter helps you to unwind. It counter-acts stress

and builds a bond of trust. The governmental games are about winning – greed, value
and aggression – scoring points at other peoples&#x2019; expense. We are saying: when you
play with us, you will be happy and healthy.”
</p><!--l. 19543--><p class="indent" >  “Laughter is a resonance phenomenon. If you laugh, the whole world laughs with
you.”
</p><!--l. 19546--><p class="indent" >  “So they say.”
</p><!--l. 19548--><p class="indent" >  “The billboards are central here too—in the games, but our campaign is more than
that. The government&#x2019;s message is multi-faceted. On the one hand, it is essentially
trying to keep the populace open to the idea of military interventions around the
world. Our form of governance is peaceful. We want to spread a calming inﬂuence
around the game, not an agitation. On the other hand, they want to makes themselves
in the image of a strong authoritative leadership.”
</p><!--l. 19556--><p class="indent" >  Den purses his lips, inside the VR balaclava. These religious groups might not want
to promote war, but they do want to have absolute control by essentially rendering
everyone passive and be accepting of the guidance they receive from their leaders.
Who was it that said democracy comes in waves? The tide seems to have been going
out on this kind of social order.
</p><!--l. 19563--><p class="indent" >  The Reverend speaks. “The president has always been a strong ﬁgure. We do that
well in the United States. One man speaking with a clear voice, like the pope or like
my own shows. Be a lighthouse, be a beacon, and people will follow. They want to be
told the Truth. The Way.”
</p><!--l. 19568--><p class="indent" >  “And we are going to tell them, Reverend.”
</p><!--l. 19570--><p class="indent" >  The man who introduced the meeting glows somewhat impatiently in his meeting
apparition. “Can we get back to the logistics of this operation? I know you all have
limited time, and I certainly do.”
</p><!--l. 19574--><p class="indent" >  “All right,” Dean says. “Tell us.”
</p><!--l. 19576--><p class="indent" >  A southern voice: “Ain&#x2019;t it real easy? We ingress the procedure, real quick.
Do our business and egress the hell out before they know what it was hit
&#x2019;em!”
</p><!--l. 19580--><p class="indent" >  “We can expect resistance from the F.B.I.”
</p><!--l. 19582--><p class="indent" >  “From Interpol.”
</p><!--l. 19584--><p class="indent" >  “This is not a military operation, sir.” The British voice stirs. “If one is savvy in the
approach, and chooses the moment accordingly, the more they try to stop it, the faster
it is likely to succeed. It&#x2019;s just like quicksand—an unfortunate childhood fantasy of
mine.”
</p><!--l. 19589--><p class="indent" >  “We can start pretty much straight away, here in the U.S., and that is the plan. But
we have one small problem that is delaying us. . .”
</p><!--l. 19592--><p class="indent" >  “Problem? Don&#x2019;t we want solutions?”
</p><!--l. 19594--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, sir. If they are forthcoming.”
</p><!--l. 19596--><p class="indent" >  “Then solve the problem.” A laugh of arrogance. A military laugh.
</p><!--l. 19598--><p class="indent" >  “Well, the problem might actually work to our advantage too.”
</p><!--l. 19600--><p class="indent" >  “Now you&#x2019;re talking. So what&#x2019;s the problem?”

</p><!--l. 19602--><p class="indent" >  The man&#x2019;s virtual rendition moves to the head of the table and ﬂips a ﬂip-chart to
reveal a new colour image.
</p><!--l. 19605--><p class="indent" >  “This is a billboard that has been placed in the game. As you can see, it is not what
we designed.”
</p><!--l. 19608--><p class="indent" >  The image is detailed in compositional layers, with images and subliminal text
shown clearly. Errors have crept into the rendition, however. Den recognizes the
pattern from his investigations, and from what Cathy Kim told him.
</p><!--l. 19613--><p class="indent" >  “We are apparently experiencing some technical problems. I understand that these
will be solved soon? At least if these Norwegians are as smart as they claim to
be.”
</p><!--l. 19617--><p class="indent" >  “Asia.”
</p><!--l. 19619--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 19621--><p class="indent" >  “I think the work is done mostly in Asia.”
</p><!--l. 19623--><p class="indent" >  The senator sighs. “It just gets worse. Don&#x2019;t we do anything ourselves anymore?
How the hell did that happen?”
</p><!--l. 19626--><p class="indent" >  “Globalization has a certain momentum. We kinda started it. . .”
</p><!--l. 19628--><p class="indent" >  “Can we get back to the point, please?”
</p><!--l. 19630--><p class="indent" >  “What are you suggesting?”
</p><!--l. 19632--><p class="indent" >  “I am suggesting that this problem with the billboards can work to our
advantage.”
</p><!--l. 19635--><p class="indent" >  “How so?”
</p><!--l. 19637--><p class="indent" >  “We can get our people to provide a solution and sending it to these companies
through the consortium infra-structure. We already have people who work in these
groups. That will allow us to control these billboards even more to our advantage than
ever before. As long as interpol is busy ﬁghting oﬀ this maﬁa threat, they will not
have the resources to notice and make a fuss about it. They probably will not even
know about it.”
</p><!--l. 19645--><p class="indent" >  “We could compound the distraction.”
</p><!--l. 19647--><p class="indent" >  “Are you suggesting that we help the maﬁa?”
</p><!--l. 19649--><p class="indent" >  “Well, we don&#x2019;t have to explicitly help <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">them</span>, just supplement what they are going.
Cause a distraction.”
</p><!--l. 19652--><p class="indent" >  “It would help us to move along.”
</p><!--l. 19654--><p class="indent" >  “It could work.”
</p><!--l. 19656--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t know as I&#x2019;m all that comfortable with that idea.”
</p><!--l. 19658--><p class="indent" >  “Is it ethical?”
</p><!--l. 19660--><p class="indent" >  “Ethics is a relative matter, let&#x2019;s not second guess. . .”
</p><!--l. 19662--><p class="indent" >  “I think it&#x2019;s just ﬁne.”
</p><!--l. 19664--><p class="indent" >  “Gentlemen. Lady. The Lord will be our shepherd.”
</p><!--l. 19666--><p class="indent" >  The words cut a silence. They take pause, apparently looking at each other around
the non-existent table. As the packets of data swim, to and fro, across the Atlantic,
Den wonders if serene crustacean life is aware of what is brewing in the hairline
optical ﬁbres that crisscross their domain. Would it raise the temperature of the
Atlantic seaﬂoor just a little?

</p><!--l. 19673--><p class="indent" >  The rendered faces of their puppet-masters look oddly dead on the avatar
apparitions, leaving the meeting to speculate on the meaning of its silence.
</p><!--l. 19677--><p class="indent" >  Finally, Dean speaks. “We&#x2019;ll get through this,” he says. “And the country will be
better oﬀ for it.”
</p><!--l. 19680--><p class="indent" >  It is followed by grunts and murmurs and more ponderous inertia. Then, in the
noise of disarray, a single clear voice speaks with leadership and breaks them out of
indecision.
</p><!--l. 19684--><p class="indent" >  “So, here is the timetable for this R.A.O..”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 19688--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 19689--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 19692--><p class="indent" >  Billboards, billboards everywhere.
</p><!--l. 19694--><p class="indent" >  Broken billboards. Who should care?
</p><!--l. 19696--><p class="indent" >  There it is: the whole list, and Mary keeps coming back with more of them.
</p><!--l. 19698--><p class="indent" >  The puzzle remains. He knows of no explanation, and no solution to the
phenomenon and he has not received any information back from the game consortium
about his own reports.
</p><!--l. 19702--><p class="indent" >  Den Morris emerges from the elevator almost into the arms of his new
assistant.
</p><!--l. 19705--><p class="indent" >  “Ah Mr. Morris,” he says.
</p><!--l. 19707--><p class="indent" >  “Den,” says Den. “Call me Den.”
</p><!--l. 19709--><p class="indent" >  “Sorry. I am ready anytime you want to start.”
</p><!--l. 19711--><p class="indent" >  “&#x2019;Okay.&#x2019;
</p><!--l. 19713--><p class="indent" >  A passing Henderson interrupts. “Dennis. You stole my intern.”
</p><!--l. 19715--><p class="indent" >  Den winks at him and keeps on walking.
</p><!--l. 19717--><p class="indent" >  “Mr. Morris. There has been a call for you.”
</p><!--l. 19719--><p class="indent" >  Ah yes, he diverted his calls to the help desk. Nice save. Den shrugs and walks past
Henderson again.
</p><!--l. 19722--><p class="indent" >  “Who was it?”
</p><!--l. 19724--><p class="indent" >  “A Mrs. Waites.”
</p><!--l. 19726--><p class="indent" >  “Mrs. Waites?”
</p><!--l. 19728--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s what she said.”
</p><!--l. 19730--><p class="indent" >  What on Earth? “What did she sound like? Old, young? British, American?”
</p><!--l. 19732--><p class="indent" >  “American woman. Middle aged, I don&#x2019;t know.”
</p><!--l. 19734--><p class="indent" >  “Damn.”
</p><!--l. 19736--><p class="indent" >  “Anything wrong?” Raj asks.
</p><!--l. 19738--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t know.”
</p><!--l. 19740--><p class="indent" >  He was not expecting to hear from her.
</p><!--l. 19742--><p class="indent" >  “Thanks. I&#x2019;ll deal with it.”
</p><!--l. 19744--><p class="indent" >  “So, I&#x2019;m ready, Mr. . . Den.”

</p><!--l. 19746--><p class="indent" >  Den nods positively. “Well done, that man! A little later. Keep up the good
work. Oh. . .” He lowers his voice slightly. “Would you mind asking Kylie
McLaughlin to come in? And I don&#x2019;t want us to be disturbed for the next
hour.”
</p><!--l. 19751--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, Mr. . .I mean, Den.”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 19753--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 19754--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 19757--><p class="indent" >  Kylie McLachlan has removed her jacket and is perched on the edge of his desk.
She is looking stunning as always, but Den can see that she has had a busy day and
that her patience is on the thin side. Den places the oﬃce in private-meeting
mode.
</p><!--l. 19762--><p class="indent" >  “So, I looked at the sequences they sent you. Some would ﬁnd them a little strange
to say the least.”
</p><!--l. 19766--><p class="indent" >  “I know.” He pauses, recapping in his head. “I had Raj start tracing the
precedents, following the standard model, just to see what had been done before
in this area. It actually seems to have begun after the Iraqi invasion in the
early 2000s, after the two-towers incident in New York. An elderly American
politician started a television campaign naming Europe as America&#x2019;s next
great threat to American national security, because the French and German
governments would not cooperate in legitimizing the Anglo-American invasion
force.”
</p><!--l. 19776--><p class="indent" >  He ﬂips through some of the images.
</p><!--l. 19778--><p class="indent" >  “But Europe? The enemy? Who are they kidding?”
</p><!--l. 19780--><p class="indent" >  “He did seem serious.”
</p><!--l. 19782--><p class="indent" >  “No doubt.” Kylie McLachlan shakes her head subtly as she reads the
auto-transcript.
</p><!--l. 19784--><p class="indent" >  “These broadcasts were sent on American television sometime in 2003, I
think.”
</p><!--l. 19787--><p class="indent" >  “Well, aside from the fact that this sounds like the rantings of a James Bond
world-domination psychopath, nothing much would surprise me anymore
about the American right wing. These are people with more money than
sense.”
</p><!--l. 19791--><p class="indent" >  “It makes me a bit uncertain. Do you think we can use any of this? What is it telling
you?”
</p><!--l. 19794--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m not sure what it&#x2019;s telling me, but it seems clear that you cannot use anything
like this in our campaign?”
</p><!--l. 19796--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s pretty morbid.”
</p><!--l. 19798--><p class="indent" >  “Didn&#x2019;t you say there was a British member in the group? Doesn&#x2019;t he have anything
to say about this?”

</p><!--l. 19800--><p class="indent" >  Den shrugs. “He seemed to be along for the ride. Perhaps he isn&#x2019;t privy to all the
info.”
</p><!--l. 19803--><p class="indent" >  Kylie rolls her eyes. “Oh come on, Den! It&#x2019;s supposed to be a battle for hearts and
minds, not for spreading hate and inciting enemies.”
</p><!--l. 19806--><p class="indent" >  “Well, you know the old dictum: when you have them by the balls, hearts and
minds will follow.”
</p><!--l. 19809--><p class="indent" >  “Dennis Morris, wash out your mouth this instant! Don&#x2019;t repeat that shite in front
of me after a bad day. It&#x2019;s just not funny.” She articulates the words with a
school-mistress sarcasm. The Scottish accent nails it.
</p><!--l. 19813--><p class="indent" >  “Right.”
</p><!--l. 19815--><p class="indent" >  “But this is not the Christian lobby surely? It doesn&#x2019;t seem their style?”
</p><!--l. 19817--><p class="indent" >  “This comes more from hard liners, who want to be seen as Christian, but they are
not directly connected to the church. They might be working together. After all, there
is no more holy a war than a Holy War.” He shrugs at her scowl. “From what we have
seen, there are those who simply want to keep people ﬁghting in the game, to keep
them open to the use of violence to solve America&#x2019;s political problems. These people
come partly from the N.R.A. and partly from the government. Then there are
the Christians who basically want to wrest power from the law and place it
back in the hands of the church. They have won a number of victories over
constitutional law in recent years and now they seem to be mounting their
oﬀensive. Both parties oﬀering us a lot of money to help them out with our expert
services.”
</p><!--l. 19831--><p class="indent" >  “You&#x2019;re not seriously thinking of going along with this?”
</p><!--l. 19833--><p class="indent" >  Den stops; he can imagine a video scenario where a respected senator delivers a
message to the American people, and an angel comes down and touches him. He
would probably burst into ﬂames, but it is a chilling premonition.
</p><!--l. 19837--><p class="indent" >  “I still haven&#x2019;t said yes to them.”
</p><!--l. 19839--><p class="indent" >  “I should think not.”
</p><!--l. 19841--><p class="indent" >  Den looks down sullenly. “You know, I thought this could really be our big chance.
Our opportunity to make money and become famous.”
</p><!--l. 19844--><p class="indent" >  “Are you not already famous, Dennis Morris?” she invokes the school-mistress
again. “Did you not just stand in front of a thousand people and talk about your
successes?”
</p><!--l. 19848--><p class="indent" >  He shrugs and nods reluctantly. “But this is an additional contract that could mean
millions for the company. And I&#x2019;m sort of worried that if we don&#x2019;t agree, they&#x2019;ll ﬁnd a
way to cut us out of the work we are already doing.”
</p><!--l. 19852--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s a risk. But at least you&#x2019;d have the law on your side.”
</p><!--l. 19854--><p class="indent" >  He nods. “That still leaves us with the question of what to do. Being idealistic
doesn&#x2019;t solve the conundrum.”
</p><!--l. 19857--><p class="indent" >  She sits down behind his desk and swivels in his chair. “I know this was important
to you, Denny,” she says more softly. “But why could you not play with the nice boys
on the block?”
</p><!--l. 19861--><p class="indent" >  “Maybe it&#x2019;s not as bad as we think.”

</p><!--l. 19863--><p class="indent" >  “Maybe.” She nods. “We can hope so. Otherwise I&#x2019;m not sure the human race is
going to have all that many brownie points at the pearly gates.”
</p><!--l. 19866--><p class="indent" >  Den looks up, at her. Focus, he thinks. Don&#x2019;t wallow. Outlook. Intellect before
dejection. Discipline.
</p><!--l. 19869--><p class="indent" >  “So why do you think they are so keen on this new campaign now? What has really
changed?”
</p><!--l. 19872--><p class="indent" >  Kylie stirs from her posture and inhales a deep breath. “Fear has taken over the
wheel of politics,” she philosophises, “especially in the U.S., but also the world over.
Fear mongering has been too successful for its own good.”
</p><!--l. 19877--><p class="indent" >  “Fear of what though?”
</p><!--l. 19879--><p class="indent" >  “Freedom, or loss of freedom. The Western way of life.”
</p><!--l. 19881--><p class="indent" >  “Come on. . .”
</p><!--l. 19883--><p class="indent" >  ”Come on! Everything we hear these days is telling us that the West is going to
have to sacriﬁce its position of privilege, to make way for better human rights in other
countries, and allow the developing world to have a larger share of the cake. They
must be terriﬁed.”
</p><!--l. 19889--><p class="indent" >  “And somewhere like China actually has the power to do it. . .”
</p><!--l. 19891--><p class="indent" >  “And then they have a succession of presidents who drone on about truth and
freedom around the world, at the same time as they are dictating the terms of that
freedom. American citizens are probably asking themselves: are <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">we </span>really living in a
free society?” She aﬀects a silly voice: “The government says that America is the
Land of the Free, which means we feel like we ought to be able to do what we like.
But the government is pretty big on telling people what they should do. How do you
resolve that?”
</p><!--l. 19902--><p class="indent" >  “Do you think people are malcontent?”
</p><!--l. 19904--><p class="indent" >  “The conﬂict is ﬁnally being noticed, and it seemed to be coming to a
head. The NRA and libertarians have been lobbying for that for years, right?
But it&#x2019;s really just propaganda and people are realising it now. America has
been one of the most tightly authoritarian societies since its inception, at
least in its attitudes. If it&#x2019;s citizens ever got real freedom, it might all just fall
apart.”
</p><!--l. 19911--><p class="indent" >  “What is freedom anyway?”
</p><!--l. 19913--><p class="indent" >  “Now there&#x2019;s the real debate.”
</p><!--l. 19915--><p class="indent" >  “So the propaganda message is backﬁring.”
</p><!--l. 19917--><p class="indent" >  “Well, that&#x2019;s my guess. This strong focus on liberty and freedom has persuaded
people that they should have it themselves. Never mind the middle East, or North
Korea. What about right there at home in the U.S.? It&#x2019;s a provocation.”
</p><!--l. 19922--><p class="indent" >  “Well, sometimes you need someone to shake people out of their rut to get them
moving? Otherwise the will quietly subsist in pleasant servitude.”
</p><!--l. 19925--><p class="indent" >  “Like the Nazis did? So, what, you need a prophet: a Hitler or a Jesus
Christ?”
</p><!--l. 19927--><p class="indent" >  “Ronald Raygun or George Nucular Freedom?”
</p><!--l. 19929--><p class="indent" >  “You took the words right out of my gob, Dennis Morris!”

</p><!--l. 19931--><p class="indent" >  She looks him up and down with one of those ﬂirtatious glances of disapproval that
she masters like no other. She is sexy when she is boyish.
</p><!--l. 19935--><p class="indent" >  “So freedom propaganda has destabilized red-neck America, sparking riots, and
brings gangs and organized crime out of the shadows, and it has spread out to the rest
of the world. The Kylie McLachlan Theory of Everything.”
</p><!--l. 19940--><p class="indent" >  She smiles, like: <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">who me</span>? “So they have created a monster.”
</p><!--l. 19942--><p class="indent" >  “Like Frankenstein himself.”
</p><!--l. 19944--><p class="indent" >  “And now they have to take their monster out into the world—into polite company,
teach it some manners, rules of social engagement. . .”
</p><!--l. 19947--><p class="indent" >  “Again, like Frankenstein. . .”
</p><!--l. 19949--><p class="indent" >  “Mixing. It&#x2019;s all about mixing. Averaging the extremes. That is what is missing
from their world. They are too . . . singular.”
</p><!--l. 19952--><p class="indent" >  “So why are the Christians winning?”
</p><!--l. 19954--><p class="indent" >  “Should I have to tell you all the answers?”
</p><!--l. 19956--><p class="indent" >  “I very much think you should.”
</p><!--l. 19958--><p class="indent" >  “Well, all right. Let me see. Suppose Johnny is a southern Baptist. They teach him
only that that he is worthless from an early age. The only way that he can redeem his
soul is to be a good Christian and then they will look after him, as only the church
can, with all that singin&#x2019; and lovin&#x2019; and fallin&#x2019; and pushin&#x2019;—and me-oh-my what else
they get up to. Johnny doesn&#x2019;t know how lucky he is! So? It&#x2019;s more plausible care
story than a welfare payment.”
</p><!--l. 19966--><p class="indent" >  “And we know that people are so easily bought.”
</p><!--l. 19968--><p class="indent" >  “Or else you would be out of a job.”
</p><!--l. 19970--><p class="indent" >  “So what&#x2019;s with the blame it all on Europe strategy?”
</p><!--l. 19972--><p class="indent" >  “Standard part of the doctrine. Blame it on someone else. ”
</p><!--l. 19974--><p class="indent" >  “Hmmm.”
</p><!--l. 19977--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s ironic isn&#x2019;t it? The Americans are so open hearted and generous as
individuals. Then you put them together and they form a jigsaw picture of a
monster.”
</p><!--l. 19981--><p class="indent" >  “Mass hypnosis. Never confuse a country with its leaders.”
</p><!--l. 19983--><p class="indent" >  Back to the issue. “All they are asking for is for us to level the ﬁeld so they can have
the chance to poke their heads up.”
</p><!--l. 19986--><p class="indent" >  “Den, you don&#x2019;t believe that surely?”
</p><!--l. 19988--><p class="indent" >  “So maybe we need some kind of a whitewash. There are others pumping out these
messages, so we need to bury them in distraction. What about some kind of paparazzi
trash campaign maybe against?”
</p><!--l. 19992--><p class="indent" >  “They want you to DDT the competition.”
</p><!--l. 19994--><p class="indent" >  “We need some inspiration.” He thinks. “I should to talk Cathy Kim.”
</p><!--l. 19997--><p class="indent" >  “Your mystery lady. What can she tell you?”
</p><!--l. 19999--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s her country. She will have more experience. She might know something that
we don&#x2019;t.” He avoids her glance. “Besides, I said I would.”
</p><!--l. 20002--><p class="indent" >  She smirks at him, nodding. “I&#x2019;ll bet.”
</p><!--l. 20005--><p class="indent" >  “We could learn something.”

</p><!--l. 20007--><p class="indent" >  “Well, if that&#x2019;s your answer. . .” She springs up from the chair. ”Before you do, let
me show you something.”
</p><!--l. 20010--><p class="indent" >  Den stares at her for a while and stretches out a hand. She takes it and she
about-turns and pulls him through a doorway at the rear of his oﬃce. It conceals a
small room where there is a small VR test-cave, not much bigger than a street
lavatory, and a couch for resting. She brushes past him in and moves past the couch
and into the cubicle. There is no one here.
</p><!--l. 20017--><p class="indent" >  “Is this where you work?”
</p><!--l. 20019--><p class="indent" >  “Only when I want some peace and quiet.”
</p><!--l. 20021--><p class="indent" >  He follows her in, admiring her rear end and feeling a slight dizziness. She activates
a simple scenery program.
</p><!--l. 20024--><p class="indent" >  She has cleverly managed to manipulate him, willingly into a position where they
are close and facing one another. He touches her arm and she swoons towards him
with a sly smile.
</p><!--l. 20028--><p class="indent" >  “Hello,” she says.
</p><!--l. 20030--><p class="indent" >  Den grins and pulls her towards him, holding her nose just in front of his. She
smells sweetly with a tutti-frutti kind of perfume. She is breathing heavily now and
staring at his face, too close to see him.
</p><!--l. 20034--><p class="indent" >  “Research?”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 20038--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 20039--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 20042--><p class="indent" >  He dials up the call info from Celia Waites. Now he is even more curious as to what
she wants.
</p><!--l. 20045--><p class="indent" >  “Celia. This is Den Morris. I got a message that you had called me.”
</p><!--l. 20047--><p class="indent" >  “Den. How nice of you to call. I&#x2019;ve missed you.”
</p><!--l. 20049--><p class="indent" >  “Really.” He tries to conceal his annoyance. Has she called just to play
games?
</p><!--l. 20051--><p class="indent" >  “Of course. Don&#x2019;t tell me you haven&#x2019;t missed me. . .”
</p><!--l. 20053--><p class="indent" >  “Celia. I&#x2019;m pretty busy. Your message said this was important.”
</p><!--l. 20055--><p class="indent" >  “I know, I know. I am doing this for you, Den. Well, partly.”
</p><!--l. 20057--><p class="indent" >  “Celia. . .”
</p><!--l. 20059--><p class="indent" >  “I want you to come to New York. There is someone you need to meet.”
</p><!--l. 20061--><p class="indent" >  “I just got back from the States.”
</p><!--l. 20063--><p class="indent" >  “I know that.”
</p><!--l. 20065--><p class="indent" >  “If it&#x2019;s so important, can&#x2019;t I meet this person here? Why can&#x2019;t they come to
me?”
</p><!--l. 20067--><p class="indent" >  “But then I wouldn&#x2019;t be able to see you. I can&#x2019;t come to Europe, you know we can&#x2019;t
travel.”
</p><!--l. 20070--><p class="indent" >  “Celia. . . I promise to visit you the next time I am there, you know that.”

</p><!--l. 20072--><p class="indent" >  “But I&#x2019;m holding the keys to your future,” she taunts. “I&#x2019;m not asking so much, am
I?” She sighs. “Anyway,the person you need to meet cannot visit you for a while. And
this is something you need to do now. I can set up a meeting. Time is of the essence. .
.”
</p><!--l. 20077--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t know.”
</p><!--l. 20079--><p class="indent" >  “Fuck, Den. You could be a little nice. I&#x2019;m trying to help you.”
</p><!--l. 20081--><p class="indent" >  “Celia. I would love to spend some time with you, but I am completely tied up right
now.”
</p><!--l. 20084--><p class="indent" >  “Then you can rot in hell, you bastard.”
</p><!--l. 20086--><p class="indent" >  “Celia. . .”
</p><!--l. 20088--><p class="indent" >  “Den, I am going to destroy you. You are an egotistical bastard and I want to
see you fail for once. Every time you are on the verge of success I will be
there waiting, ready to destroy any chance you have. And you will come
and fuck me if you value anything in this world, because I am going to have
you.”
</p><!--l. 20094--><p class="indent" >  He hears a barely concealed sob before the line goes dead.
</p><!--l. 20101--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

