</p><!--l. 22593--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 22596--><p class="indent" >  Preeta knocks hesitantly at his oﬃce, as if detecting his discomfort.
</p><!--l. 22598--><p class="indent" >  “Are you okay?” she asks.

</p><!--l. 22600--><p class="indent" >  He turns his head away, and tries to look busy. “Uh, yeah. What can I do for
you?”
</p><!--l. 22603--><p class="indent" >  She cocks her head. “You look even paler than usual. You could use a
break.”
</p><!--l. 22605--><p class="indent" >  “You look . . .” He considers lashing out, but reins himself in, like a good dog,
snatching a glance at her. “Nice.” She probably doesn&#x2019;t mean to be butting in on his
aﬀairs. It was a kind gesture to ask about him.
</p><!--l. 22610--><p class="indent" >  “Thank you very much,” she says with the very cute Indian lilt. “You know, I was
wondering if you wanted to go out this evening. I haven&#x2019;t had a chance to do anything
like this for a long time. While I am here I want to sample the nightlife here, feel as
though I am actually alive.”
</p><!--l. 22616--><p class="indent" >  Yes, alive. What is that exactly? “I am pretty busy. . .”
</p><!--l. 22619--><p class="indent" >  “It looks as though you could do with a night oﬀ.”
</p><!--l. 22621--><p class="indent" >  “Yes.” He nods, mainly to himself. He is not doing anything useful. “Yes, I
could.”
</p><!--l. 22624--><p class="indent" >  She edges her way into his oﬃce a little further, without invitation. She is trying to
be nice to him. Why? Anyway, he should be grateful.
</p><!--l. 22627--><p class="indent" >  “Did I tell you what I found out?”
</p><!--l. 22629--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 22631--><p class="indent" >  “I am not a real person.”
</p><!--l. 22633--><p class="indent" >  Dermot looks at her, wondering what she is trying to say. “Well, don&#x2019;t ask me. I
can&#x2019;t tell the diﬀerence.”
</p><!--l. 22636--><p class="indent" >  She grins, and he is forced to laugh at his own remark.
</p><!--l. 22638--><p class="indent" >  “I am a character in someone&#x2019;s game.”
</p><!--l. 22640--><p class="indent" >  The humour drains out of him. “So, are you going to explain that, or just leave me
guessing?”
</p><!--l. 22643--><p class="indent" >  “I found out. Your boss is part of a network that has been manipulating
me, choreographing my moves ever since I started working on the game in
Malaysia.”
</p><!--l. 22647--><p class="indent" >  “What? Why?”
</p><!--l. 22649--><p class="indent" >  “From what I can tell, they needed someone under cover to get inside the
information in the game.”
</p><!--l. 22652--><p class="indent" >  “A spy?”
</p><!--l. 22654--><p class="indent" >  “An involuntary spy.”
</p><!--l. 22656--><p class="indent" >  “A stooge.”
</p><!--l. 22658--><p class="indent" >  “I suppose it amounts to that, doesn&#x2019;t it? You know the strangest thing about
it?”
</p><!--l. 22661--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 22663--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t really care.”
</p><!--l. 22665--><p class="indent" >  “You don&#x2019;t care?”
</p><!--l. 22668--><p class="indent" >  She shrugs. “No, I don&#x2019;t care.”
</p><!--l. 22670--><p class="indent" >  “Why not, I mean. . .”
</p><!--l. 22672--><p class="indent" >  She meets his gaze. “I&#x2019;m better oﬀ, aren&#x2019;t I?”

</p><!--l. 22674--><p class="indent" >  He can identify with that.
</p><!--l. 22676--><p class="indent" >  “Do you think that attack on you was set up too?”
</p><!--l. 22678--><p class="indent" >  “What!?” A bolt of disgust breaks her expression. She gasps, bordering on a
scream.
</p><!--l. 22681--><p class="indent" >  “The attack. You said you were kidnapped, I mean. Right?”
</p><!--l. 22683--><p class="indent" >  “What? You mean, it could have been engineered to bring me here?”
</p><!--l. 22686--><p class="indent" >  “Just an idea. What better way to make you help them than to make you think that a
well-known enemy is out to get you. They step in to the rescue and bring you here. It
all seems very convenient. ” There is a quiver in his voice, as if he realizes that he has
gone too far.
</p><!--l. 22691--><p class="indent" >  Her eyes are wide and she precesses like a gyroscope in the doorway. “Would
someone arrange an attack on me to manipulate me?”
</p><!--l. 22694--><p class="indent" >  “Well, we might do something like that in a game. So, I mean, you know, it could. .
. It was just a thought.”
</p><!--l. 22697--><p class="indent" >  “Shut up! Don&#x2019;t say it!”
</p><!--l. 22699--><p class="indent" >  “Just thinking out loud, sorry.”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 22701--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 22702--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 22705--><p class="indent" >  The thought requires processing, but she drops it for now like a hot coal.
</p><!--l. 22708--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Not processing, not processing. No, no, no, no, no.</span>
</p><!--l. 22710--><p class="indent" >  Not an idea to be entertained in her current frame of mind. Go away.
</p><!--l. 22712--><p class="indent" >  Dermot sees eﬀect of the idea on her and feels responsible. Best to change the
subject. “So anyway. That thing we are supposed to be doing now,”
</p><!--l. 22716--><p class="indent" >  “Stopping the Christians. . .”
</p><!--l. 22718--><p class="indent" >  “Yes.” He suppresses an instinct to correct the details of what she said. That is a bad
habit, a geek habit. That is not who he wants to be.
</p><!--l. 22720--><p class="indent" >  “What about it?”
</p><!--l. 22722--><p class="indent" >  “Got anywhere?”
</p><!--l. 22724--><p class="indent" >  She stares sulkily into space. “I was looking around and I had an idea.”
</p><!--l. 22727--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 22729--><p class="indent" >  She does not look happy. She came here perhaps to cheer him up and he has cut her
down and made her feel as bad as he does.
</p><!--l. 22732--><p class="indent" >  “Would you like some tea?” he asks. “It&#x2019;s from the Cameron Highlands, in
Malaysia.”
</p><!--l. 22735--><p class="indent" >  Her trance breaks and she smiles with conciliatory eyes. “Thanks. That sounds nice.
On one condition.”
</p><!--l. 22738--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 22740--><p class="indent" >  “You have to come out with me later, to a bar.”
</p><!--l. 22742--><p class="indent" >  A smile forms between them.

</p><!--l. 22744--><p class="indent" >  “All right then,” he says happily. This is progress. This is good. He has reached out
and she accepted. Perhaps it doesn&#x2019;t have to be so hard, after all. “Let me make some
tea.”
</p><!--l. 22748--><p class="indent" >  “Black or green?” she asks.
</p><!--l. 22750--><p class="indent" >  “Black, plain or with vanilla.”
</p><!--l. 22752--><p class="indent" >  She smiles. “Plain, please. So, something else. I found a connection using my
software. Some people here in Oslo who are working on environmental robots. They
have some of the technology that we need. I don&#x2019;t know how it works, but I ﬁgured
that Bishop was going to want to know about it.”
</p><!--l. 22758--><p class="indent" >  “You told him?”
</p><!--l. 22760--><p class="indent" >  “Yes. He rushed oﬀ.”
</p><!--l. 22762--><p class="indent" >  Dermot is impressed. He would never have thought of that. She has been
there for a couple of weeks now and already she is more imaginative than he
is.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 22767--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 22768--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 22771--><p class="indent" >  Consternation, over the ulcerated fabric of the city, racks his mood as they venture
out into the chill winter vapours. It does not do to see the repairs that maintain the
city&#x2019;s appearance. No one wants to know of blemishes on the perfection of things.
Pockmarks in the asphalt foundations are quietly being steam-rollered into
denial by night-workers, under halogen illumination and ﬂashing amber.
The city is sinking into a marsh; like Atlantis, he thinks. How long do we
have?
</p><!--l. 22780--><p class="indent" >  The homeless are hanging in the recesses of shuttered shop doorways now, as if
driven out of their usual haunts by a gathering storm. Dermot&#x2019;s mobile indicates that
there is a police alert in the city tonight. A football game. That means there will be
police everywhere. It is seldom that he ventures out of a tram or a bus at this time of
day, in such caustic air. Besides, he is usually working. Dermot the action
hero.
</p><!--l. 22788--><p class="indent" >  They are ﬁve puﬀed up blimps feeling their way forward, towards the a place
rumoured to be known to one of them, none of them certain of where they are going.
They are a blind gang leading a stranger through the night; rosy cheeks, slapped by
the winter.
</p><!--l. 22793--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">There should be more people here, shouldn&#x2019;t there? Is it safe to be out at this time</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">of day?</span>
</p><!--l. 22796--><p class="indent" >  He feels conspicuous, walking with such a large group, avoiding cracks in the
paving. They are standing out too much. The few people around are watching them.
Where are the police? Why can&#x2019;t they see any police? If they are suppose to be out in
force, why aren&#x2019;t they here?

</p><!--l. 22801--><p class="indent" >  As if to laugh at him, a black cat shifts in a shadow, raised momentarily from its
smug camouﬂage by the tenderest kiss of ambient light.
</p><!--l. 22805--><p class="indent" >  “Let&#x2019;s get out of here and go out tonight,” Preeta said.
</p><!--l. 22807--><p class="indent" >  “You go ahead. I&#x2019;ll join you later maybe. I need to prepare something
ﬁrst.”
</p><!--l. 22809--><p class="indent" >  “Come on, Dermot,” Preeta said. “Take a break. Let&#x2019;s go out and have a good
time!” She smiled, bearing a wicked streak. “I&#x2019;ve always been a bit of a rebel, you
know.”
</p><!--l. 22813--><p class="indent" >  Preeta said, Preeta said. What was he thinking? He had been absorbed by his work
for almost a full day, but the suggestion arrested his thoughts abruptly. It touched a
primal contact within him, unleashing a spark of arousal. It would be good for him to
get out and see people in a social situation. His heart beat suddenly to the rhythm of a
diﬀerent drum.
</p><!--l. 22820--><p class="indent" >  Dermot seemed to glide down the corridor without feeling his feet touch the
ground. He could have been ﬂoating or levitating from the attention; if he were only
attached to reality at all he might have realized that all he was missing was the very
cause of his elation. But he was feeling good, on a cloud, and every worldly tether
seemed beyond him at that moment. Break free—burn the candle at both ends.
Progress.
</p><!--l. 22828--><p class="indent" >  But now his nerve is shaken. After work activity is not common here. People are
usually just glad to get home at the end of a day. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">We do not know how to socialize.</span>
Some of the older people have families and the younger people just aren&#x2019;t in the habit.
This is breaking new ground.
</p><!--l. 22834--><p class="indent" >  Their short walk passes, free of incident and they arrive in a small side street
amongst a few shops which nest in the ground ﬂoors of the four-story ﬂats: the
restaurant is really not that far from the police building. Dermot observes a pub
next door ﬁlled with long and ﬂamboyant leather coats, and black dyed hair,
boots and metallic studs. It is a room that seems removed from the rest of this
Asian area, like a puzzle to be solved, but he is not in the game now. It must
be a real meeting place for these black haired denizens. He begins to feel
daring.
</p><!--l. 22844--><p class="indent" >  Little Saigon. The restaurant is not very James Bond. There are no glamorous
dresses and shirt-tails, no roulette tables and exotic bars. The brown Formica tables
and orange plastic seats belong to a diﬀerent stratum and age, but the food is tasty.
Garlic and chilli, wrapped in plastic, peanuts and mint, crunch inside his mouth. Small
candles ﬂicker in appreciation of their custom.
</p><!--l. 22851--><p class="indent" >  “This place is amazingly cheap,” someone says. “And the food is good and the beer
is cheap.”
</p><!--l. 22854--><p class="indent" >  “You want a beer Preeta?”
</p><!--l. 22856--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;ve never tried beer before”.
</p><!--l. 22858--><p class="indent" >  “Really?”
</p><!--l. 22860--><p class="indent" >  She shrugs. “Okay, I&#x2019;ll try a small one.”
</p><!--l. 22862--><p class="indent" >  Preeta and Dermot.

</p><!--l. 22864--><p class="indent" >  World-lines crossed.
</p><!--l. 22866--><p class="indent" >  She does not know all the faces at the table, but as she drinks the strangely sour
liquid, with her food, the unfamiliarity seems to matter less.
</p><!--l. 22870--><p class="indent" >  She feels important: a meal in her honour.
</p><!--l. 22872--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I am not dead here.</span>
</p><!--l. 22874--><p class="indent" >  “So welcome to our country,” one of the group announces, raising his glass..
Unknown face. A friend of Jonathan. “The land of taxidermy and taxes plenty.
Skål!”
</p><!--l. 22878--><p class="indent" >  “What do you make of our crime team? All the little students and boﬃns?”
</p><!--l. 22881--><p class="indent" >  “Everyone seems very nice.”
</p><!--l. 22883--><p class="indent" >  “She&#x2019;s too polite!”
</p><!--l. 22885--><p class="indent" >  “Prima, no, what&#x2019;s your name?”
</p><!--l. 22887--><p class="indent" >  “Preeta.”
</p><!--l. 22889--><p class="indent" >  ”We heard you are a wiz with the diagnostics.”
</p><!--l. 22891--><p class="indent" >  “I have had lots of practice,” she tells them modestly.
</p><!--l. 22893--><p class="indent" >  “So is it true that you have to work twice as many hours in Malaysia?”
</p><!--l. 22895--><p class="indent" >  She smiles. “Not yet.”
</p><!--l. 22897--><p class="indent" >  “And do they put you in jail if you spit on the ground?”
</p><!--l. 22899--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s Singapore, idiot!”
</p><!--l. 22901--><p class="indent" >  “Not even a whipping?”
</p><!--l. 22903--><p class="indent" >  “Well, that must make it the opposite of here.” Ivar. “Here we spit all the time and
work half the time.”
</p><!--l. 22906--><p class="indent" >  “No one gets anything done here,” Dermot mutters. “We don&#x2019;t put in the hours. Too
much free time and vacation.”
</p><!--l. 22909--><p class="indent" >  “Look who&#x2019;s talking! When was your last vacation, Dermot?”
</p><!--l. 22911--><p class="indent" >  He squirms. “Not for a while.”
</p><!--l. 22913--><p class="indent" >  “This man works two jobs. You need a life, my man.”
</p><!--l. 22915--><p class="indent" >  “I have a life, thanks,” he replies with a trace of anger.
</p><!--l. 22918--><p class="indent" >  Preeta sips her beer and feels a creeping numbness, almost like a pain that does not
hurt, somewhere in her brain. The world is simpler; details do not seem to matter as
much. It is as though something has clasped her head and she is wearing
it.
</p><!--l. 22923--><p class="indent" >  The boss-lady of the house inspects their table over the top of her glasses
and shouts something in Vietnamese. Anything else for you? Peanuts and
noodles. This is a taste of home, in an unlikely igloo. Location stored for future
reference.
</p><!--l. 22928--><p class="indent" >  Time gets gobbled up like spring-rolls, their infused and weary bodies supported in
the uncomfortable chairs. Dermot goes quiet as usual, and seems to be anxious to go
somewhere else. How long have they been sitting here? It is 23:00 hours and the
conversation is beginning to peter out. Preeta is tingling and she does not want the
evening to end yet.
</p><!--l. 22935--><p class="indent" >  “You know, I should go,” Dermot says.
</p><!--l. 22937--><p class="indent" >  “But we are about to plan our work for the next week,” Jonathan jokes.

</p><!--l. 22939--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah – let me know. Uh – nice to meet you all. Preeta, I guess I&#x2019;ll see you
tomorrow.”
</p><!--l. 22942--><p class="indent" >  “No, you can&#x2019;t go now,” Ivar complains. “Preeta wanted a night out, Look, why
don&#x2019;t we go and have one more drink at this bar just around the corner. By then, we
might be all ﬁnished.”
</p><!--l. 22946--><p class="indent" >  “I am pretty tired.”
</p><!--l. 22948--><p class="indent" >  “Preeta, you&#x2019;ll come with us won&#x2019;t you?”
</p><!--l. 22950--><p class="indent" >  She nods, dizzily. “Yes, I would like that. Dermot, you should come too. Just for a
little while?”
</p><!--l. 22953--><p class="indent" >  He checks his mobile, demonstratively for an excuse to leave. There is
none.
</p><!--l. 22955--><p class="indent" >  Preeta puts a hand on his shoulder and tugs at his jacket. “Just for a little
while?”
</p><!--l. 22957--><p class="indent" >  He squeaks inside. And what if he doesn&#x2019;t come? Will she go home with one of
the others? Will he have missed an opportunity? No, he cannot think like
that.
</p><!--l. 22961--><p class="indent" >  “Come on, Derm! Come with us for another half-litre.”
</p><!--l. 22963--><p class="indent" >  Trapped. He nods, “Okay,” and is rewarded by Preeta&#x2019;s broad smile.
</p>
