>
<!--l. 22965--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 22966--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 22969--><p class="indent" >  They walk back out into the cold night, sounds of drunken shouting and distant,
swooshing cars. Just a few blocks towards Young&#x2019;s Square and then slip into a bar. It
is a dimly lit place, with small tea-candles ﬂickering at the tables. The bar
itself is brightly lit: row upon row of coloured bottles, with luminous and
animated labels line the shelves at the bar. Colours, shapes and sizes. Each label
is trying to attract attention with its kaleidoscopic antics. Which of these
appeals to you most? Some of the drinks can even change colour, or is it the
bottles?
</p><!--l. 22978--><p class="indent" >  They occupy a table in the shifting half-spaces.
</p><!--l. 22980--><p class="indent" >  “We have to go up to the bar to get drinks here. I&#x2019;ll go ﬁrst,” Jonathan
informs.
</p><!--l. 22983--><p class="indent" >  Unfathomable sound: it is a cacophony of fragmented voices, coming from
everywhere at once, like a ﬂock of squawking birds. It reverberates around every
corner of the establishment, devolving into a ﬂat mixture of meaningless jabber. Too
much information is simply noise. Superposed onto this nocturnal aviary is music,
which beats out a simple pulsing rhythm, something to focus on if not to listen to. It
is like a string of buoys on the ocean, or a ladder up the smooth side of a
skyscraper; it is a crutch for gaining purchase on the otherwise featureless
audio.

</p><!--l. 22993--><p class="indent" >  “Oh my god,” Ivar chants.
</p><!--l. 22995--><p class="indent" >  It is amazing that a single voice can be heard over this din, truly a testament to the
power of the human brain to focus on a single message when shrouded in static. This
is Bishop&#x2019;s doctrine in action, Dermot thinks.
</p><!--l. 22999--><p class="indent" >  “Have you seen that skirt?”
</p><!--l. 23001--><p class="indent" >  Their attention is drawn to a pair of black legs, terminated in the merest slip of a
loin-cloth.
</p><!--l. 23004--><p class="indent" >  “Now that&#x2019;s how you get someone&#x2019;s attention.”
</p><!--l. 23006--><p class="indent" >  They laugh, though the sound is laced with a nervous strain.
</p><!--l. 23008--><p class="indent" >  “She&#x2019;s beautiful,” she mouths.
</p><!--l. 23010--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s probably been patented.”
</p><!--l. 23012--><p class="indent" >  “Take a picture and send it to Bishop. This could be the start of a whole new theory
of grabbing attention. If we equipped all the WPCs with this equipment, it would
bring power back into the hands of the law. No one would be able to say no to
them.”
</p><!--l. 23017--><p class="indent" >  “No kidding.”
</p><!--l. 23019--><p class="indent" >  Small groups of mainly male or of female friends, are scattered around. They are
not exotically dressed, at least not most of them. Jeans and sweaters. It is low-key,
informal. Preeta sees football colours and shirts on one table, making a noise. She can
see a few couples, but this does not seem to be the place for romantic encounters.
The women seem to oﬀer one another vacuous hugs and air kisses as they
meet.
</p><!--l. 23027--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s like the girl in the honeypot,” Preetha says.
</p><!--l. 23029--><p class="indent" >  Dermot glances at her, with a barely posed curiosity.
</p><!--l. 23031--><p class="indent" >  “One of her tricks for getting attention. Sexy clothes that promise more than they
reveal.”
</p><!--l. 23034--><p class="indent" >  “Right,” Ivar chimes.
</p><!--l. 23036--><p class="indent" >  “Hey, do you remember that woman, a witness in a robbery case last year. She
took like seventy megabytes of pictures and sound in the name of fashion or
something.”
</p><!--l. 23039--><p class="indent" >  “Fashion?”
</p><!--l. 23041--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah. Apparently she thought this woman, in front of her in the shop, was so cool
that she recorded her just walking around. Then suddenly the woman did a runner:
robbed the store.”
</p><!--l. 23045--><p class="indent" >  “People still rob stores?”
</p><!--l. 23047--><p class="indent" >  “Of course they do.”
</p><!--l. 23049--><p class="indent" >  “Not cash: detergent. She stole some expensive detergent, for a cleaning company, I
think it was.”
</p><!--l. 23052--><p class="indent" >  “All right, let&#x2019;s cut out the work talk everyone. This is our night out.”
</p><!--l. 23054--><p class="indent" >  “So is this our ﬁnal destination?”
</p><!--l. 23056--><p class="indent" >  “We probably shouldn&#x2019;t be out too late,” Dermot warns. “There&#x2019;s been a football
match. There might be trouble.”

</p><!--l. 23059--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah, I heard Ullevål lost on their home turf. They are probably breaking up the
pubs on Karl Johan as we speak.”
</p><!--l. 23062--><p class="indent" >  “Who cares?”
</p><!--l. 23064--><p class="indent" >  “Most of the city.”
</p><!--l. 23066--><p class="indent" >  “Perhaps we should ﬁnd more of a dance club, where they are not likely to
go.”
</p><!--l. 23069--><p class="indent" >  “Yes!” Preeta exuberates. “I have heard all about the Kan-Klubs. Can&#x2019;t we go
dancing?”
</p><!--l. 23072--><p class="indent" >  “We don&#x2019;t know how to dance.”
</p><!--l. 23074--><p class="indent" >  “Neither do I,” she says. “But we can watch?”
</p><!--l. 23076--><p class="indent" >  “We can all watch.”
</p><!--l. 23078--><p class="indent" >  “Yes we can, and that skirt is just asking for a picture. I didn&#x2019;t bring a cam. Derm,
do you have one?”
</p><!--l. 23081--><p class="indent" >  He shakes his head.
</p><!--l. 23083--><p class="indent" >  Liar.
</p><!--l. 23085--><p class="indent" >  Preeta peels oﬀ several layers of clothing. The transition from the outdoor
cold to heat of the bar has welled up in a considerable surplus of internal
radiance.
</p><!--l. 23088--><p class="indent" >  “So, you didn&#x2019;t ﬁnish. I&#x2019;m guessing they caught this chick with the detergent.”
</p><!--l. 23090--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah, they did. And the funny thing is, it turns out that she is part of one of these
Christian cults from Sweden.”
</p><!--l. 23094--><p class="indent" >  “A Swedish sex cult!”
</p><!--l. 23096--><p class="indent" >  They wooo in unison.
</p><!--l. 23098--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah, probably. Religion with sexual gratiﬁcation. Then they send the women out
