</p><!--l. 23130--><p class="indent" >  Ivar laughs. “Understatement of the century.”

</p><!--l. 23132--><p class="indent" >  “Have you ever been to the football?”
</p><!--l. 23134--><p class="indent" >  “Sure.”
</p><!--l. 23136--><p class="indent" >  “Really?”
</p><!--l. 23138--><p class="indent" >  He nods.
</p><!--l. 23140--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s what we like about you Dermot. You talk too much!”
</p><!--l. 23142--><p class="indent" >  Preeta: “Stop teasing him.”
</p><!--l. 23144--><p class="indent" >  Dermot looks at her and shakes his head once, sneaking a glance at her as she peels
oﬀ a sweater, leaving only a snugly ﬁtting, white T-shirt hugging her torso. Then he
regrets the discomfort: she is beautiful and exotic, he thinks. The clothes accentuate
that.
</p><!--l. 23149--><p class="indent" >  His mind races at once at the thought of what it might be like . . . No, now he is
getting confused. He is already seeing Christina. Well, who is he kidding? He is not
“seeing” anyone. And Christina is trouble, he knows it, but he is ensnared. What a
mess.
</p><!--l. 23154--><p class="indent" >  He shakes his head as if to clear it.
</p><!--l. 23156--><p class="indent" >  “Are you okay?” Preeta asks, smiling at his involuntary grimace.
</p><!--l. 23158--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m ﬁne, sorry. Just a little tired.” Now pull yourself together, he thinks. Don&#x2019;t
force it. Stop trying to make things happen. It puts people oﬀ.
</p><!--l. 23162--><p class="indent" >  A girl comes to the table, wearing a promotional nano-shirt.
</p><!--l. 23164--><p class="indent" >  “Can I get you folks something from the bar?” she asks. “We have a special
promotion this evening on these items.” She points to her T-shirt, where a picture of
the relevant substances is displayed. “I can get you one of these, or one for each of
you at half-price.”
</p><!--l. 23169--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;ll have a beer,” Ivar says ﬂatly.
</p><!--l. 23171--><p class="indent" >  “Regular drinks at the bar,” she sing-songs. “Or shots of any of these drinks at
half-price if more than two of you join in.”
</p><!--l. 23174--><p class="indent" >  “Why not?” Jonathan&#x2019;s friend pipes in. “Something exotic.”
</p><!--l. 23176--><p class="indent" >  “We&#x2019;ll try a shot of the Russian Oil, all &#x2019;round.”
</p><!--l. 23178--><p class="indent" >  She pulls a bottle from a belt on her waist, and produces ﬁve plasticized
shot-glasses of some black potion, apparently from thin air.
</p><!--l. 23181--><p class="indent" >  “Here we are.” She taps on her wristband. “Okay, I&#x2019;m broadcasting on pay and . . .
I&#x2019;m ready for ﬁve responses. One, two. . .”
</p><!--l. 23184--><p class="indent" >  They tap at their mobiles to pay. She thanks them and leaves.
</p><!--l. 23186--><p class="indent" >  “All right, people. Let&#x2019;s make a skål for new police skirts!”
</p><!--l. 23188--><p class="indent" >  “Preeta, you have to down this in one!”
</p><!--l. 23190--><p class="indent" >  Dermot cuts in. “You don&#x2019;t have to.”
</p><!--l. 23192--><p class="indent" >  “Yes you do! Mob rule. Everyone!”
</p><!--l. 23194--><p class="indent" >  They raise their glasses, some more conﬁdently than others, salute and empty.
Dermot sips and Preeta gulps.
</p><!--l. 23197--><p class="indent" >  Preeta sputters and coughs.
</p><!--l. 23199--><p class="indent" >  “Shit, that&#x2019;s disgusting,” Dermot winces.
</p><!--l. 23201--><p class="indent" >  Gasps and grins.
</p><!--l. 23203--><p class="indent" >  “I think I would like something else,” Preeta laughs.

</p><!--l. 23205--><p class="indent" >  “Shall I get you something? I know what you should try. . .”
</p><!--l. 23207--><p class="indent" >  “Give me a minute ﬁrst.” She can already feel the eﬀect of the slug of alcohol
changing something inside her, as though some dragon buried within her is ﬂexing
with its ﬁres. If they are trying to push her into a single role, make her one of them,
like a slave girl, then they are mistaken. That is what she has been running from all her
life.
</p><!--l. 23214--><p class="indent" >  “So is someone going to tell me? What is a Swedish sex cult?” she asks.
</p><!--l. 23216--><p class="indent" >  They look at one another and laugh.
</p><!--l. 23218--><p class="indent" >  “Are you interested?”
</p><!--l. 23220--><p class="indent" >  “How can I know, if you don&#x2019;t tell me about them?”
</p><!--l. 23222--><p class="indent" >  “The sex cults. That&#x2019;s religion with sex and manipulation.”
</p><!--l. 23225--><p class="indent" >  “We have them here too, just for the record.”
</p><!--l. 23227--><p class="indent" >  “Where is the religion in it?”
</p><!--l. 23229--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s ceremonial. Same thing really.”
</p><!--l. 23231--><p class="indent" >  “They are basically Christian Bible bashers, like fundamentalists, but they live in
closed quarters, usually with some kind of conﬁdence trickster nutcase at the
helm.”
</p><!--l. 23235--><p class="indent" >  “He&#x2019;s usually a dictator, and he gets people to cleanse their ﬁlthy sins by having sex
with him, or in groups, or whatever.”
</p><!--l. 23238--><p class="indent" >  “Them and their small son&#x2019;s and daughters.”
</p><!--l. 23240--><p class="indent" >  “And Bishop would like to exterminate them all.”
</p><!--l. 23242--><p class="indent" >  “You shouldn&#x2019;t make fun of Bishop.”
</p><!--l. 23244--><p class="indent" >  “Why not?” Ivar laughs. “The guy is a little over-serious at times.”
</p><!--l. 23246--><p class="indent" >  “You make him sound like the fanatic. This sounds awful.”
</p><!--l. 23248--><p class="indent" >  “Man with a mission.”
</p><!--l. 23250--><p class="indent" >  “Rumour has it that someone in his family got taken in by one of the cults once, but
it&#x2019;s just a rumour.”
</p><!--l. 23253--><p class="indent" >  “We haven&#x2019;t come very far in moving his project forward. Too many other
things to work on to ﬁght something as abstract as ﬁghting a brainwashing
campaign.”
</p><!--l. 23257--><p class="indent" >  Preeta shakes her head imperceptibly.
</p><!--l. 23259--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah, we still don&#x2019;t know how to do it. At least, I can&#x2019;t think of the goddamn
answer.”
</p><!--l. 23262--><p class="indent" >  “What about you, Dermot? How would a game designer seduce someone or
counter-seduce someone from the clutches of the enemy?”
</p><!--l. 23265--><p class="indent" >  Dermot is feeling calmer from the ingestion of alcohol. He risks an answer. “Bishop
tells us that the church is gaining ground, but I have never understood it. People are
selﬁsh today – why would they invest in something like a church, where there is a
congregation you have to take care of, unless it gave them something for free? You
have to believe that people are basically cynical, not that they&#x2019;re saints. I just don&#x2019;t get
it.”
</p><!--l. 23273--><p class="indent" >  “You don&#x2019;t have to understand it,” Jonathan says. “But it&#x2019;s deﬁnitely happening.”

</p><!--l. 23276--><p class="indent" >  “The religions are carving up Africa pretty eﬀectively,” Jonathan&#x2019;s friend chimes.
“Islam in the North and the Evangelicals and Catholics ﬁghting it out in sub-Saharan.
Maybe people feel that it gives them direction or a sense of family, when there is no
sense of safety from government?”
</p><!--l. 23281--><p class="indent" >  “People have extended families in the game. Virtual family has never been more
popular. What do they want with religion in this day and age?”
</p><!--l. 23284--><p class="indent" >  “People want to be looked after. That has to be why presidential ﬁgures are revered,
even when people disapprove of their politics. People actually want someone to stand
up and tell them that everything is all right.”
</p><!--l. 23288--><p class="indent" >  “And that&#x2019;s the point, isn&#x2019;t it? Now it is falling apart. The trust has gone out
of the presidential ﬁgures, so religious ﬁgures see their chance to step in
again..”
</p><!--l. 23292--><p class="indent" >  “The point is that they don&#x2019;t see any beneﬁts from central government, so they live
like mobs and tribes, like in Africa. Then you can have any local zealot as your local
leader, with his own agenda.”
</p><!--l. 23297--><p class="indent" >  Dermot&#x2019;s weariness is starting to fade. He feels that he is beginning to get
the hang of being out. The tiredness is passing. He has caught his second
wind.
</p><!--l. 23301--><p class="indent" >  “Preeta, do you know what you want to drink?”
</p><!--l. 23303--><p class="indent" >  She shakes her head.
</p><!--l. 23305--><p class="indent" >  “There is so much to choose from. I don&#x2019;t know where to start.”
</p><!--l. 23307--><p class="indent" >  “Did you like the beer you had?”
</p><!--l. 23309--><p class="indent" >  She shrugs. “It was interesting.”
</p><!--l. 23311--><p class="indent" >  “Why not try a cocktail?” Jonathan suggests.
</p><!--l. 23313--><p class="indent" >  “All right. I would like a blue drink,” she says.
</p><!--l. 23315--><p class="indent" >  They laugh.
</p><!--l. 23317--><p class="indent" >  “How about a margarita with that blue stuﬀ?” Ivar says.
</p><!--l. 23319--><p class="indent" >  “Will you come with me and tell me what to ask for?”
</p><!--l. 23321--><p class="indent" >  “Ehmm. Have to give me a minute on that.” He runs it up on his mobile and shows
her a picture on a tablet. “This?”
</p><!--l. 23324--><p class="indent" >  Dermot says, “I&#x2019;m going to the bar anyway. Come on, I know what it is.”.
</p><!--l. 23326--><p class="indent" >  The place is ﬁlling up now and there is a crowd at the bar. Preeta feels a body
pressing into hers, She smells the lactic sweat and wafts of pot-encrusted jackets.
Clothes, boring and beautiful. Make-up, scents, body language. Everyone is signalling
and sending their messages, ﬂagging their identity and their hopes, trying to inﬂuence
their surroundings.
</p><!--l. 23333--><p class="indent" >  If they are talking about how to turn people from the church, the answer must
surely lie in this melting pot of signals. The room is literally bursting with
audio-visual button-pushing. Bishop would love this.
</p><!--l. 23337--><p class="indent" >  Dermot&#x2019;s thoughts parallel her own. The noise in the room hinders his thinking.
How do you turn such a mass of noise into something more structured, like a
symphony? That is what everyone is trying to do.

</p><!--l. 23341--><p class="indent" >  Suddenly, from the noise, Preeta hears what she instantly perceives to be a scream.
Turning her head, a space opens up behind where they are standing, and people seem
to simply evaporate from their positions at the speed of sound. A body, a
person, comes tumbling backwards, as if in slow motion, growing in her
ﬁeld of vision, and crashes into the bar beside her, with a man practically on
top of him. Like dogs, like animals. One at the throat of the other. They are
ﬁghting.
</p><!--l. 23349--><p class="indent" >  Preeta feels the thud of the man on the wooden bar. Fists pummel into his face and
his nose spatters blood. Suddenly there are two groups ﬁghting at several locations.
The patrons have scattered to the edges of the room, like Russian Oil expelled by a
detergent.
</p><!--l. 23354--><p class="indent" >  The scene has a sickening presence. It is not like watching a bar-ﬁght in a ﬁlm, with
fake punch noises over-dubbed and balsa-wood furniture that breaks like tissue paper.
The real sound of violence is a hollow smack, as ﬂesh gives way to sudden impact,
followed by the splatter of thin red blood onto the wooden ﬂoorboards, drying in little
craters, which darken to crimson. There is the shattering thunder as furniture and
bodies crash to the wooden ﬂoor. Finally there is the swoosh and thump as
one thug takes a chair and tries to break it over the back of his adversary,
imitating the scenes he has learned from Hollywood Westerns. But, unlike in the
movies, it is not the chair that breaks. The man goes down and does not come
up.
</p><!--l. 23366--><p class="indent" >  In a moment, the ﬁghters have ﬁnished their ambush and have vacated the bar,
leaving moaning and bleeding bodies around them. The panic button has doubtless
been pressed, and police will be on their way. The thugs disappear into the night,
perhaps to pick another ﬁght elsewhere.
</p><!--l. 23372--><p class="indent" >  In the aftermath, the pounding music is suddenly apparent, ridiculously cheery
under the circumstance. All voices have desisted. A space remains, buoyed by the
shock of sudden violence. No one says anything, but two of the bar staﬀ go to see if
the groaning bodies are all right.
</p><!--l. 23378--><p class="indent" >  Preeta is frozen in position, standing up with her hands between her legs, looking
hurt.
</p><!--l. 23381--><p class="indent" >  “Are you okay. Did you wet yourself?”
</p><!--l. 23383--><p class="indent" >  She shakes her head.
</p><!--l. 23385--><p class="indent" >  The police were too far away. They could not come in time to stop this event.
Luckily, this was apparently just between gangs. They are not interested in anyone
else, except perhaps as spectators.
</p><!--l. 23389--><p class="indent" >  “You sure?”
</p><!--l. 23391--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t think I want any more to drink. Let&#x2019;s just get out of here.”
</p><!--l. 23395--><p class="indent" >  They return to their table. As if they needed proof that the gangs are a more
immediate problem. The gang violence has been a distraction lately. Bishop
has been having a lot of discussions with the boys and girls in blue about
it.
</p><!--l. 23400--><p class="indent" >  People diﬀuse away from the walls, still looking at the injured bundles of ﬂesh and

bone, lying broken on the ground, but essentially turning their backs on the incident1
and carrying on with their evening. It is over now. Not their business. Soon it will be
as if nothing has happened.
</p><!--l. 23406--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t get it,” Ivar says. “What it is with these people? What do they get out of
this?”
</p><!--l. 23409--><p class="indent" >  “Animals.”
</p><!--l. 23411--><p class="indent" >  “Football supporters. They don&#x2019;t like losing.”
</p><!--l. 23413--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah, I heard they lost on their home turf.”
</p><!--l. 23415--><p class="indent" >  “I am so sick of these freakin&#x2019; gangs,” Jonathan&#x2019;s friend gasps.
</p><!--l. 23417--><p class="indent" >  “What is a gang anyway? How do you deﬁne it?” Jonathan struts.
</p><!--l. 23419--><p class="indent" >  His friend regards him wearily. “A bunch of people with a funny handshake,
walking demonstratively down the middle of a street?”
</p><!--l. 23423--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s the seventeenth of May!” Ivar laughs, to lighten the mood. “You&#x2019;re thinking
of marching bands!”
</p><!--l. 23426--><p class="indent" >  “Well, if they are not a splinter oﬀ civilized society&#x2019;s block, I don&#x2019;t know a better
way to describe them!”
</p><!--l. 23429--><p class="indent" >  “There are all kinds of gang,” Dermot says simply.
</p><!--l. 23431--><p class="indent" >  Preeta shudders and takes the remainder of her Russian Oil and throws
it back, as the others did, medicinally. Her eyes bulge a little and then she
winces and coughs. Perhaps more of it will help to numb the trembling within
her.
</p><!--l. 23436--><p class="indent" >  “Wooo. Careful, girl. We need you to operate that new software you&#x2019;ve put
together.”
</p><!--l. 23439--><p class="indent" >  Dermot sees her and considers doing the same, but that would not be like
him.
</p><!--l. 23441--><p class="indent" >  “The gangs are happening in Asia too. You have the indoctrination clinics, or
Madrassas that oﬀer free education to young men, turning them into stooges for
Islamic extremism. . .and there are Hindu gangs.”
</p><!--l. 23445--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah, according to TerrorWatch, they actually teach them how to use weapons and
inﬁltrate organizations. . .”
</p><!--l. 23448--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah, I read that too.”
</p><!--l. 23450--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s a familiar equation: fear plus resources equals stupidity.”
</p><!--l. 23452--><p class="indent" >  Preeta does not feel like arguing in their defence. For all she knows, it might be
true.
</p><!--l. 23454--><p class="indent" >  “Preeta, you don&#x2019;t look very well. Are you okay?”
</p><!--l. 23456--><p class="indent" >  “I think we should leave,” Ivar says.
</p><!--l. 23458--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah. Let&#x2019;s get out of here.”
</p><!--l. 23460--><p class="indent" >  They don their clothing and push their way out. Several others have been thinking
the same thing, since the ﬁght.
</p><!--l. 23463--><p class="indent" >  Preeta and Dermot huddle together, as they meet the icy air outside the
bar.
</p><!--l. 23466--><p class="indent" >  “You two look like a sorry pair.”
</p><!--l. 23468--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m just a little tired,” Dermot replies.

</p><!--l. 23470--><p class="indent" >  Oﬀ in the distance, they hear a dirge of male moaning, droning out a vacant melody
èn masse, as if celebrating certain brain-damage. It could only be the sounds of a
post-pregnant football match. It booms out from a bar accompanied by vicious shouts
and guttural roars. Dermot looks unnerved, but Preeta merely feels a distant disgust
through her intoxication. They have seen the transformation from human
male to rabid animal, all for the love of a high-tech pig&#x2019;s bladder with spots
on.
</p><!--l. 23479--><p class="indent" >  “I need to go and dance and feel happy,” Preeta says, giddily.
</p><!--l. 23481--><p class="indent" >  “Do you belly dance? Can I come and watch?” Jonathan&#x2019;s friend. Idiot.
</p><!--l. 23483--><p class="indent" >  “Grow up,” Jonathan says.
</p><!--l. 23485--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t tell him to grow up. He&#x2019;s trying.”
</p><!--l. 23487--><p class="indent" >  Preeta says: “Boys. Be nice. Anyway, for the record, we don&#x2019;t ‘grow up&#x2019;. We get
worn down, we lose our sharp edges.”
</p><!--l. 23490--><p class="indent" >  “Wooo.” They laugh.
</p><!--l. 23492--><p class="indent" >  She points her ﬁnger a little too pointedly. “We make compromises and accept
society&#x2019;s lowest common denominator package of values and . . . ideas because it
saves us the eﬀort of thinking for ourselves.”
</p><!--l. 23496--><p class="indent" >  They exchange signiﬁcant glances.
</p><!--l. 23498--><p class="indent" >  “And on that note,” she slurs. “I want to party. Come on, Dermot.” She sets oﬀ in
the direction of Grensen.
</p><!--l. 23501--><p class="indent" >  Ivar says. “We&#x2019;d better look after those two.” He calls after them. “You two are
important to us, if we are going to get moving on Bishop&#x2019;s counter-campaign.”
</p><!--l. 23505--><p class="indent" >  Preeta on the new software and Dermot with the programming. Better keep a clear
head.
</p><!--l. 23508--><p class="indent" >  “Okay, ﬁrst place we ﬁnd,” Preeta shouts, pointing to a couple of girls walking
together. “Let&#x2019;s follow them.”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 23511--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 23512--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 23515--><p class="indent" >  From a line of decorated bodies, through a door bouncer control point, they descend
into the underworld of a club. The stairway leads down past black painted bricks,
spray painted with art and pseudo-graﬃti. Posters are thrown up haphazardly, showing
concerts and bands and coming attractions, overlapping and torn. A thunderous
pumping of bass reaches up to them, as if they are entering a gigantic heart, giddy on
speed.
</p><!--l. 23523--><p class="indent" >  The regular din of voice noise and laughter accompanies it. It is just the two of
them now. Jonathan&#x2019;s friend had other plans, and Ivar was looking tired. Dermot too
looks like a ghost, withdrawn and misplaced in this universe. She can see him looking
around, as if trying to ﬁnd the puzzle that he has to solve to get past this level of the
game.

</p><!--l. 23529--><p class="indent" >  Preeta is sailing, as if on dream auto-pilot. She feels drawn to the sound, to the
warmth. By luck, two bar stools are free. She throws her coat over one and sits there,
Dermot beside her.
</p><!--l. 23534--><p class="indent" >  Dark Gothic phantoms glide around with stylish mobile bracelets and silver wires
used for decoration. Coloured hair and gelled sculpture. Everyone is a painting.
Everyone is a work of art.
</p><!--l. 23538--><p class="indent" >  The art is cold, she decides, not like eastern art. It is chilly and aloof, pretentious.
They are gargoyles, not love elephants. If I were art, I would want to bring people
together, she thinks. This is masculine art. It shoots its message outward and says
‘fuck you&#x2019;. Her art would be more feminine, more inviting and would say ‘tell me
about yourself&#x2019;.
</p><!--l. 23545--><p class="indent" >  The pulsing of the lights, hypnotising, cleansing. Worries are excised. They order a
simple beer and look around them. Dermot tries to say something a few times, but
they have to press their faces close together and shout to be heard over the
music.
</p><!--l. 23550--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">He is sweet</span>, she thinks, <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">but too careful for me</span>.
</p><!--l. 23552--><p class="indent" >  There are no hot men here, but look at the girls. Sexy girls everywhere, with
amazing ﬁgures. She cannot help but gape. Feline bodies, twisting like tornadoes,
hugging an inner volcano in a tight shell; snaking like cobras, living vines. Their
short-cut dresses reveal ribs and breasts, with coloured hair and knee high boots.
Preeta is entranced. It was not like this in the subcontinent, where people are trying to
conceal middle-age obesity with airy tents.
</p><!--l. 23560--><p class="indent" >  She feels the eﬀect of the alcohol. It is a new sensation, like being in a dream.
Perhaps dreaming is like being drunk?
</p><!--l. 23563--><p class="indent" >  There is a dance ﬂoor, raised slightly, a short distance away, behind a cage
wall.
</p><!--l. 23566--><p class="indent" >  The pulsing rhythm seems to activate parts of her brain that her anaesthetised
centres would normally reject as irrational, but the prickling of the alcohol simply
makes it feel comfortable. It is like being in a womb. She feels an urge to
kick.
</p><!--l. 23571--><p class="indent" >  “Do you want to dance?” she shouts.
</p><!--l. 23573--><p class="indent" >  Dermot smiles a no. Is he feeling the same eﬀect?
</p><!--l. 23575--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I am here</span>, she thinks. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I feel free, more free than I have ever felt. </span>She has journeyed
half way around the world to be here. She turned her back on her friends, just like
those people in the bar turned their backs on the victims of violence. She is
transforming from a kind grey moth into a selﬁsh butterﬂy, with colour. But why
should she resist? Why should she care? What is there to lose. Only the string survive.
She has been trodden on all her life. Perhaps the road to happiness is not paved with
good intentions at all. Perhaps you have to push others aside and look after yourself,
because no one else will.
</p><!--l. 23586--><p class="indent" >  The notion spins inside her mind, like a rising cyclone. It seems to buoy her, lift her
out of the dread and the guilt. What is there to feel guilty about? Look around,
there is no guilt in this room. All she can see is a purging of responsibility. A

cleansing of daily stresses. She wants to join in. She too wants to be purged of
guilt.
</p><!--l. 23592--><p class="indent" >  Preeta gathers focus and smiles at Dermot.
</p><!--l. 23594--><p class="indent" >  “Come on,” she says and jumps oﬀ her stool.
</p><!--l. 23596--><p class="indent" >  Dermot shakes his head, shyly. He does not feel the spirit of freedom that courses
through her veins. “Someone has to watch our things.”
</p><!--l. 23599--><p class="indent" >  She shrugs, too far down her path to change gear now.
</p><!--l. 23601--><p class="indent" >  She has arrived. She has seen the enemy and it is only her own inhibition. She
pushes her way through the tightly packed crowd and jumps up onto the dance ﬂoor.
The music is beating and people are swaying and singing. She does not know the
words, but she wants to join in. She dances with hands raised and eyes closed,
allowing the music to infuse her spirit. The movements are instinctive and primal. She
does not care about appearances. Freedom has reached her mind, and freedom is not
about control.
</p><!--l. 23610--><p class="indent" >  As she looks around her, seeing others in the same state of release, she recognizes
the look. The look, the very image that she always wanted to imitate, it is that carefree
look of freedom. It is the face of not caring.
</p><!--l. 23615--><p class="indent" >  Just look at the beauty. The sexy bodies, writhing in their expansiveness, riding on
their buoyancy, having shed their earthly burden. This is where she wants to be right
now.
</p><!--l. 23619--><p class="indent" >  In front of her, in a black dress that clings to her body, with short blonde hair and a
long, pale neck, she recognizes someone. Not their face, but their understanding. The
blond girl grins at her and moves closer. Preeta grins back, happier than she has
ever been, connecting with her chromatic opposite, uniﬁed by erasure of
guilt and worry, worlds from distant galaxies brought together by music and
beer.
</p><!--l. 23626--><p class="indent" >  They dance together, holding out hands to one another. They ripple and move
together, as though they were both spirits yin and yang, lock and key. The girl moves
forward and touches her. They slide together with eyes half closed, and kiss. Not a
short kiss, but a long intense kiss, with tongue. A surge of excitement ﬂoods through
her. How daring, how contraire! How unbelievably cool she is! Every part of her is
aroused.
</p><!--l. 23633--><p class="indent" >  She turns to look back for Dermot. Then she sees the horriﬁed road-kill at the bar,
gaping is disbelief. The madness had carried her away, but why should she
care?
</p><!--l. 23637--><p class="indent" >  Come on, she thinks, this is every boy&#x2019;s dream. Two girls instead of one. She lifts
out her hand in a regal beckoning as she dances as if to invite him into an
unholy trinity, inviting him to share in her adventure, but he is paralysed. This
is way too much. It had taken all his daring to talk to her in the ﬁrst place.
Now the thought of parading in front of the entire club with two gorgeous
women is just too much. She sees him crumble slightly, not quite able to
understand what has happened or how he managed to get into this. Then his
deﬂation turns to discomfort and panic and he turns to ﬂee, to expunge the

dream.
</p><!--l. 23648--><p class="indent" >  She wants to go to him, but the girl in front of her is now pressing in close running
her hands down her back, which seems like an opportunity that is too good to miss.
This is my adventure, she thinks. I can save him later.
</p><!--l. 23660--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

