 id="x1-44r3"></a>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-0"></a>
<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-172">Part</span><span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-172"> 3</span>
</p><!--l. 23660--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-172">White Christmas</span>
</p><!--l. 23660--><p class="indent" >

</p><!--l. 23660--><p class="indent" >

</p><!--l. 23664--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-45r41"></a>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-0"></a>
<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">41</span>
</p><!--l. 23667--><p class="indent" >  Imagine a conversation, the ﬁrst words of a language. It begins simply, an embryo
of clear statements: the exchanges of proper names and mutual humilities. Gradually
the babble swells in sophistication, in context and convolution. It matures and
crystallizes with its own grammar—a lattice to support and guide the organic growth
of its ideas.
</p><!--l. 23674--><p class="indent" >  Then, as the rigidity of the lattice begins to feel small, life-giving dialogue
strains against the captivity, ﬂowering in deﬁance of an unwanted and resented
structural conformity. An arms race begins, between the need to express more
elaborate intellectual growth, and the need to package uncertainty in a safe
scaﬀolding.
</p><!--l. 23680--><p class="indent" >  Layers of establishment accrete around the struggling organism, choking it. The
beast collapses under the weight of a cancerous armour-plating. Bureaucracy, once the
friend that supported the spindly shoots of adventure in their growth, has built a
mausoleum for thought and creativity.
</p><!--l. 23686--><p class="indent" >  Rest not in peace, but in perpetual debt to the system: a mortgage of
ever-outstanding yet mediocre reporting, ever queued up to exhaust the conversation,
to stiﬂe its power to innovate. This language, Jonas believes, is the language of
administration.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 23693--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 23694--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 23697--><p class="indent" >  Freezing fog has lain a veneer of perfectly smooth ice onto the ground. He
cannot even make it up the slight incline. He sees a car attempt its start up
and slide back down, sideways into a tree. No sense in trying to make it that
way.

</p><!--l. 23702--><p class="indent" >  Jonas drives south, once again, following the snaking road out beyond the ring road,
from the conference hotel. The road is still slippery, but the adaptive tyres are holding
on to their promise for now.
</p><!--l. 23706--><p class="indent" >  The events of two days ago are still fresh in his mind. He has driven this route
several times now, and it brings back awkward feelings.
</p><!--l. 23709--><p class="indent" >  He dropped Martin oﬀ with his mother, that day, just half an hour before she
ﬁnished work. He told her that they could talk later, no time now, and that he had to
rush oﬀ. She swallowed her anger for the time being, and it felt as though he had
gotten oﬀ lightly.
</p><!--l. 23714--><p class="indent" >  It won&#x2019;t last long. She will remind him of it soon.
</p><!--l. 23716--><p class="indent" >  Something has changed in him since the experience. He has survived one attack on
his life. What about the next one? Surely, feeling ones mortality makes one
stronger.
</p><!--l. 23720--><p class="indent" >  Arriving back at the council oﬃces, after his social seminar cleansing, messages
queued up in the message centre lie in wait for him. He has oﬃcially taken a day&#x2019;s
leave to wind down, but there is no escaping the next step. There lay the memo he was
putting out if his mind. It calmly informed them all that the government had
intervened and placed research back together with church matters, back as it was in
the 1990s. Unlikely bed-fellows, thrust back into an irreligious union by the politics of
fear.
</p><!--l. 23729--><p class="indent" >  He read his messages numbly, absorbing their content without letting them alter his
spirit. What else could one do? Then he returned to the hotel retreat to unwind, in the
pursuit of knowledge.
</p><!--l. 23733--><p class="indent" >  Jonas spent the next days making sense of things, using the social seminar as a base
for this meditation. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">What kind of society are we living in? Am I an outdated fossil,</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">who should move over for a new age? Can I be so wrong in my beliefs? Can I just</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">stand aside and let things fall into disarray?</span>
</p><!--l. 23739--><p class="indent" >  He arrives now at the oﬃces in a new frame of mind. Hostility has gestated within
him. He feels like a soldier resigned to the prospect of battle, intensely aware of
failing to achieve any of his worldly goals. It is surely time to rectify that. But how
does one ﬁght an immovable object? A little civil disobedience?
</p><!--l. 23745--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I have to try to do something for Sara, </span>he thinks. But what?
</p><!--l. 23747--><p class="indent" >  Perhaps it is time to put on his academic hat for a while. He should try to contact
the project team for a start. He has no idea what is going on there. They just seem to
have disappeared. He is still her advisor, after all. And what about Professor Hart? He
might have some clout.
</p><!--l. 23753--><p class="indent" >  His intern, John, tells him: “I called a friend in embassy circles and he said that
the American embassy has decided to go on alert due to some threatened
action. The French are protesting at their behaviour and are playing silly
buggers by going oﬀ in a huﬀ. Now riots have started there and in Eindhoven
too.”
</p><!--l. 23759--><p class="indent" >  “This is what happens when governments and politics get involved in knowledge
management.”

</p><!--l. 23762--><p class="indent" >  “Can you try to ﬁnd out what Professor Hart is doing at the moment. Is he in the
country? Tell him about this development and the eﬀect it is going to have on his
research.”
</p><!--l. 23766--><p class="indent" >  “Okay. I&#x2019;m on it. Anything else?”
</p><!--l. 23768--><p class="indent" >  “I need to think. I going to need the details of our past agreements.”
</p><!--l. 23770--><p class="indent" >  “Have you tried the archive?”
</p><!--l. 23772--><p class="indent" >  He nods. “It&#x2019;s worth a try.”
</p><!--l. 23774--><p class="indent" >  “Oh, Jonas?”
</p><!--l. 23776--><p class="indent" >  “Yes?”
</p><!--l. 23778--><p class="indent" >  “A policeman has been trying to contact you. An American, I think. Bishop?”
</p><!--l. 23780--><p class="indent" >  “Ugh. That can wait.”
</p><!--l. 23782--><p class="indent" >  He returns to his oﬃce to access the ﬁles, whose information is not available by
mobile. Knowledge and experience are our saviours.
</p><!--l. 23785--><p class="indent" >  A functionary from the ministry, who has been loitering in the wings, sees him as
he is leaving the building.
</p><!--l. 23788--><p class="indent" >  “Jonas Lindgren? I&#x2019;m glad I found you.”
</p><!--l. 23790--><p class="indent" >  The feeling isn&#x2019;t mutual.
</p><!--l. 23792--><p class="indent" >  “You were not at the meeting the other day.”
</p><!--l. 23794--><p class="indent" >  “I was not.”
</p><!--l. 23796--><p class="indent" >  “It was an important announcement.”
</p><!--l. 23798--><p class="indent" >  “There was an emergency.”
</p><!--l. 23800--><p class="indent" >  “But you must have seen the memo by now. You must have heard.”
</p><!--l. 23802--><p class="indent" >  He nods sternly.
</p><!--l. 23804--><p class="indent" >  “Then I hope everyone is going to go at this with their full vigour.”
</p><!--l. 23806--><p class="indent" >  “We have other things to clear up ﬁrst.”
</p><!--l. 23808--><p class="indent" >  “Like what?”
</p><!--l. 23810--><p class="indent" >  “Like research projects that are in full swing. People&#x2019;s lives that are being thrown
into disarray because of this. I have a student who is stranded in the ﬁeld,
and a collaborative project with the space agencies that is already falling
apart without your help. Somehow, I need to ﬁx these things that have been
broken.”
</p><!--l. 23816--><p class="indent" >  “Jonas, why are you still working on this? You know that everyone is going to be
working on the Africa project now.”
</p><!--l. 23819--><p class="indent" >  “That doesn&#x2019;t come into force until the new year. I am still a scientist. Science can&#x2019;t
just stop.”
</p><!--l. 23823--><p class="indent" >  He laughs. He actually laughs.
</p><!--l. 23825--><p class="indent" >  “Then perhaps it&#x2019;s time do some real science and apply yourself to what the board
has decided is our strategic focus.”
</p><!--l. 23828--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Astronomy is 1derful</span>.
</p><!--l. 23830--><p class="indent" >  “You are compromising my ability to work by trying to tell me how to
progress.”
</p><!--l. 23833--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">And interesting 2.</span>
</p><!--l. 23835--><p class="indent" >  “We have made the decision to focus on this environmental science.”

</p><!--l. 23837--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">The ear3voles around the sun. . .</span>
</p><!--l. 23839--><p class="indent" >  “Famine relief is not environmental science.”
</p><!--l. 23841--><p class="indent" >  “I hope you&#x2019;re not going to be diﬃcult over this, Jonas.”
</p><!--l. 23843--><p class="indent" >  “You are not doing anyone a favour with this, whatever you might think.
People are going to rebel. You cannot simply freeze student fellowships. It&#x2019;s
unethical.”
</p><!--l. 23847--><p class="indent" >  He regards him pityingly for several seconds and says: “I&#x2019;m going to send someone
down to advise about the new administrative procedures. It should help you adjust to
the new system. In future it won&#x2019;t be possible to let money disappear into these
non-approved sidelines. We want to make sure that we get the maximum amount out
of our research.”
</p><!--l. 23853--><p class="indent" >  Jonas watches him leave.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 23856--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 23857--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 23860--><p class="indent" >  Switch the mobile into interface mode, but combo is frozen. Nothing working.
Dials the help desk and is deﬂected with nonsense. “I can&#x2019;t interface to my
combo.”
</p><!--l. 23864--><p class="indent" >  “Are you not running our system?”
</p><!--l. 23866--><p class="indent" >  “Of course I am. What else would I be running?”
</p><!--l. 23868--><p class="indent" >  “Might have installed something diﬀerent.”
</p><!--l. 23870--><p class="indent" >  “No.”
</p><!--l. 23872--><p class="indent" >  “Then there must be something on your machine that is preventing the license
server from giving you access.”
</p><!--l. 23875--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 23877--><p class="indent" >  “Have you downloaded any music or video? Or game modules?”
</p><!--l. 23879--><p class="indent" >  “No.”
</p><!--l. 23881--><p class="indent" >  “Have you viewed any pictures by non-registered artists.”
</p><!--l. 23883--><p class="indent" >  “Registered by whom?”
</p><!--l. 23885--><p class="indent" >  “Guess.”
</p><!--l. 23887--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t think so.”
</p><!--l. 23889--><p class="indent" >  “Well that is probably the cause. You will have to pay a license fee to who
ever it is and then the data will probably be freed up and the conﬂict will be
resolved.”
</p><!--l. 23893--><p class="indent" >  “Are you telling me that I can&#x2019;t access my work because of some unwanted data
that I have received, against my will, from someone I do not know that is forcing me
to pay for a license that I don&#x2019;t want?”
</p><!--l. 23897--><p class="indent" >  “Welcome to the future.”
</p><!--l. 23899--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Astronomy is 1derful. . .</span>
</p><!--l. 23901--><p class="indent" >  “Forget it.”

</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 23905--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 23906--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 23910--><p class="indent" >  “All I am trying to do is to get at our funding with the collaborative space
project. My student has been refused access to funds that are legitimately
hers.”
</p><!--l. 23914--><p class="indent" >  “Our rules say that we need co-authorization from at least one other partner.
Russians, ESA, NASA. . .”
</p><!--l. 23917--><p class="indent" >  “Can&#x2019;t we get it?”
</p><!--l. 23919--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m afraid that no one is talking at the moment. There is some kind of scare on and
congress has just broken a number of international agreements and withdrawn a lot of
funding.”
</p><!--l. 23923--><p class="indent" >  “Then we&#x2019;ll just have to take it from something else.”
</p><!--l. 23925--><p class="indent" >  “Unfortunately, it looks as though all of our accounts are going to be frozen now.
The right and the Christian People&#x2019;s Party are asking for a shake up after the news
from the U.S.”
</p><!--l. 23929--><p class="indent" >  “So. can we get the money or not?”
</p><!--l. 23931--><p class="indent" >  “New rules are going to prevent us from doing that.”
</p><!--l. 23933--><p class="indent" >  “Is there nothing we can do?”
</p><!--l. 23935--><p class="indent" >  “Not really.”
</p><!--l. 23937--><p class="indent" >  He sighs.
</p><!--l. 23939--><p class="indent" >  “The best I could do would be to cover minor expenses on our general kitty fund. I
could give you an advance now for the amount, but then you will have to apply for for
a travel reimbursement after that.”
</p><!--l. 23943--><p class="indent" >  “After you have already given me the money?”
</p><!--l. 23945--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, of course. That&#x2019;s what advance means.”
</p><!--l. 23947--><p class="indent" >  “So why can&#x2019;t I just apply for the reimbursement now? It&#x2019;s already paid for, and she
has ﬁnished the trip.”
</p><!--l. 23950--><p class="indent" >  “Because you have to ﬁll out the travel form. I can give you an advance until
then.”
</p><!--l. 23953--><p class="indent" >  “But the transaction is ﬁnished. Completed.”
</p><!--l. 23955--><p class="indent" >  “And when you have travelled, you can claim it back.”
</p><!--l. 23957--><p class="indent" >  “Oh, for crying out loud.”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 23960--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 23961--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 23964--><p class="indent" >  A wave of protest rings through the virtual æther of academia, like a World War II

air-raid siren. Take cover, the bombs are coming. The tolling of the Reason Bell spells
judgement in the works for an intellectual future.
</p><!--l. 23968--><p class="indent" >  “<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">What is an intellectual anyway?</span>”
</p><!--l. 23970--><p class="indent" >  The question is posed with the clear resonance of rhetoric. It reverberates in the
artiﬁcial ambience of the meeting. The words could have been read by a vicar as
the opening of a sermon. In truth, they ring with the irony of an assumed
loss.
</p><!--l. 23975--><p class="indent" >  The debate has reached a level of agitation that Jonas has seldom seen in without
actual physical presence. A debate was, of course, inevitable; it has not taken long to
self-organize.
</p><!--l. 23979--><p class="indent" >  In a circular theatre of tense participants; they sit, like the members of a war
council, academics and scientists from Universities, College and industry. Even the
press has come to observe and report on the transcription. They have come to search
for meaning, to blow oﬀ steam and even to talk of strategies for reversing the
perceived damage of the leaked decision. Is it still possible to overturn the
judgement?
</p><!--l. 23986--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">What is an intellectual anyway?  </span>The rhetoric hangs in the virtual air.
</p><!--l. 23989--><p class="indent" >  “I think it is clear that intellectuals are people who want to inﬂuence society with
their ideas. They are not just scientists, they are more than that.”
</p><!--l. 23993--><p class="indent" >  “So you are saying that they are more than simply those who have a College
education?”
</p><!--l. 23995--><p class="indent" >  “Of course. Are politicians intellectuals? People in marketing? They inﬂuence
society with their ideas, but we rarely think of their daily ramblings as intellectual..”
</p><!--l. 23999--><p class="indent" >  “Politicians and marketeers are merely the plumbers and carpenters of inﬂuence
mechanics. They are not usually the progenitors of the ideas themselves. Not the ideas
that change science or even society. They do not conform to a level of importance that
warrants the title intellectual.”
</p><!--l. 24004--><p class="indent" >  “But people are arguing that society doesn&#x2019;t need academics. We have burned
ourselves on that stove before. We need people we can use. Professionals and
craftsmen, not puﬀed up thinkers.”
</p><!--l. 24008--><p class="indent" >  “What makes you think that there is any contradiction between the need for
professionals and the need for thinkers?”
</p><!--l. 24011--><p class="indent" >  “Well, look at what happened in the information technology bubble. There was
enormous demand, but no one to step in. There were plenty of graduates but they were
not ready to take on the job. They knew the theory but they didn&#x2019;t know how to get
down and dirty. The same with biotech. We did not master these ﬁelds quickly
because we did not have people who had practical knowledge of the day to day
tasks.”
</p><!--l. 24018--><p class="indent" >  “My academic colleague is correct. We do not need thinkers, we need people who
can implement existing ideas well. Let other countries innovate and make the
mistakes.”
</p><!--l. 24022--><p class="indent" >  “Doesn&#x2019;t our country have a responsibility to innovate, as one of the world&#x2019;s richest
countries?”

</p><!--l. 24025--><p class="indent" >  “Indeed it does. Professionalism,” as if spitting, “It is the scourge of academia. It&#x2019;s a
goddamned virus.”
</p><!--l. 24028--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t think I know what you mean,” another says.
</p><!--l. 24030--><p class="indent" >  “What I mean is that young people used to have a right to an education. Now they
only have a right to a <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">profession</span>. It&#x2019;s not about ideas and independent thought
anymore, it&#x2019;s about training people to behave like good little soldiers.”
</p><!--l. 24035--><p class="indent" >  “Professionalism is ﬁling the sharp edges oﬀ society. It is making everyone into
silent, uncontroversial trained monkeys. Think no evil, do no evil. It is the opposite of
intellectualism.”
</p><!--l. 24039--><p class="indent" >  “I think this may be somewhat overstated. I think some of us do survive. I took on
this job, hoping that I could help to reverse that trend.”
</p><!--l. 24043--><p class="indent" >  “I left my teaching post for a sabbatical, hoping to make a diﬀerence, but there is no
perceived value to intellectualism in the state system. It has been smeared as
something for a slightly unpleasant elite for so long that people have rejected it. All
that matters now is the accumulation of wealth.”
</p><!--l. 24049--><p class="indent" >  “As long as it is no longer about innovation, our task is hopeless. We are just a
political can opener.”
</p><!--l. 24052--><p class="indent" >  “If it is not about innovation, what is it about then?”
</p><!--l. 24054--><p class="indent" >  “Multiplication. It&#x2019;s about making more and more of what you already have. Mass
consumerism. Thou shalt not create, thou shalt produce and consume, and ﬁll out a tax
form at the end of it, but you&#x2019;ll not get any points for inventing something new, and
upsetting the status quo, incurring development costs.”
</p><!--l. 24060--><p class="indent" >  “No, that&#x2019;s not true. We can still get money for new projects.”
</p><!--l. 24062--><p class="indent" >  “Only if we are guaranteed a quick return. Only if we can turn it into a ‘product&#x2019;
straight away.”
</p><!--l. 24065--><p class="indent" >  “We have tried to convince the government leadership before, but they have no
incentive to listen.”
</p><!--l. 24068--><p class="indent" >  “They have their own club. The blinkered ruling elite. The system is corrupt. If you
do not agree with them, they brand you as a trouble-maker. Democracy has perished
in their hands.”
</p><!--l. 24072--><p class="indent" >  “This is supposed to be the knowledge-based society. It has become the ignorance
society – the consumer society. The ministry has seen to that.”
</p><!--l. 24075--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s right. We are not even allowed to teach what we want. We have to
teach what the students think they want, or whatever is politically correct.
How the hell can they know what they need to know when they don&#x2019;t know
anything?”
</p><!--l. 24080--><p class="indent" >  “The whole thing started going pear-shaped when they started focusing on this idea
of better ‘management&#x2019;, where management is supposed to mean competitive
leadership. But the role of management is not commercial dictatorship, it&#x2019;s about
coordination. Management ought to be be a conduit—something that receives and
coordinates the autonomous activities of the specialists under its wing. Not under its
command! A leader is something else entirely.”
</p><!--l. 24088--><p class="indent" >  “The people with the purse strings are just ignorant. It&#x2019;s not their fault.”

</p><!--l. 24091--><p class="indent" >  “That means that we are just playing a game of made-up rules to get money for the
development of society. But we cannot ﬁgure out what we&#x2019;re getting. It&#x2019;s like pulling
the lever on a one-armed bandit in a Casino. Throw the dice and see what comes
out.”
</p><!--l. 24097--><p class="indent" >  “The bureaucrats are burying us. They claim with a straight face that their formalia
are there to keep us on the straight and narrow, you know – to help us along.
Naturally, the eﬀect is the opposite.”
</p><!--l. 24101--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s not that simple. It&#x2019;s the child society. No one trusts academics anymore to
know what they are doing. So they have to put us in straitjackets, with so many strings
attached that we can&#x2019;t even wriggle. We have to <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">apply</span>, in writing, to carry
out every little movement, we make no decisions by ourselves. And every
application has to have ‘milestones&#x2019; and ‘deliverables&#x2019; because non-experts want to
feel as though they have some kind of control over what we are going to be
doing with our time and what they are going to be out of it. It&#x2019;s absolutely
ridiculous.”
</p><!--l. 24111--><p class="indent" >  “If we knew what was going to happen, we wouldn&#x2019;t have to do research. That&#x2019;s the
whole point. They have made a mockery of the whole idea.”
</p><!--l. 24115--><p class="indent" >  “Can you imagine what they would say if we demanded the same kind of
accountability from the ministry. Which calculator are you going to use to add up your
sums? What decisions are you going to make in each week of this year? It&#x2019;s
ridiculous!”
</p><!--l. 24120--><p class="indent" >  “There is no trust anymore. Academia is run like a prison camp.”
</p><!--l. 24122--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t disagree, but let&#x2019;s not lose our cool.”
</p><!--l. 24124--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t know what I&#x2019;m doing here anymore.”
</p><!--l. 24128--><p class="indent" >  “If we ﬁnally get permission to lift a ﬁnger, there are reports to be written for every
milestone about what we did. The armour plating is so heavy that the beast does not
walk.”
</p><!--l. 24133--><p class="indent" >  “All this management nonsense. Our lives are just ﬁlled up now with artiﬁcial
goals, by the administrators and the committees and the bureaucrats. So many that we
don&#x2019;t move forward. We never have time to innovate because we are too busy talking
about what we want to do, or should have done.”
</p><!--l. 24139--><p class="indent" >  “Without their bureaucracy, the mystique of the state evaporates.”
</p><!--l. 24142--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s the red queen scenario. You have to run, ever faster, just to stand still.”
</p><!--l. 24145--><p class="indent" >  “Change society from the bottom up. Make them respect intellectuals again, I
say.”
</p><!--l. 24148--><p class="indent" >  “But how long is that going to take?”
</p><!--l. 24150--><p class="indent" >  “Respect for the engineers. Life has become too easy. All you have to do is push a
button and you can have whatever you want. But what are we going to do on the
day the mobile network breaks down? The day when the power fails and
we can no longer warm up your factory prepared food in your microwave
oven? If no one remembers how to repair anything, if no one knows how it all
works?”
</p><!--l. 24158--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t joke about it. It&#x2019;s serious. Less and less of tax payers&#x2019; money is going to do

anything other than moving. In computer science, we call it a spin-lock. Busy waiting.
Sit there burning calories going nowhere. The nation would be healthier if we spend
the time running on a treadmill.”
</p><!--l. 24163--><p class="indent" >  “All right, all right. So what are you suggesting we do about it?”
</p><!--l. 24165--><p class="indent" >  “Well how about paying attention to our wishes, for a start?”
</p><!--l. 24167--><p class="indent" >  “We do that surely. . .”
</p><!--l. 24169--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s exactly my point. You don&#x2019;t. You say you are going to, you set up all the
procedures and formal machinations to take care of the debate, and then you just
dump the results in the waste-paper basket.”
</p><!--l. 24175--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s the virtual enactment of Zeno&#x2019;s paradox. As soon as you think you are close to
getting somewhere, the powers that be deﬁne the remaining distance to be twice as
far.”
</p><!--l. 24179--><p class="indent" >  Danger, ﬁre and ash. AIDS, SARS, pandemic ﬂu, malaria, cancer. The world is
complex and dangerous. It&#x2019;s hopeless to try to be anything, do anything, change
anything. It&#x2019;s the law of Jante. If you want risk, try bungee jumping. Just don&#x2019;t try to
make a diﬀerence—you are no one amidst forces beyond your control. Lie down and
face your fate like a good sheep would.
</p><!--l. 24186--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s the intervention of the politics of fear in the brave challenges of the
future.”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 24191--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 24192--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 24195--><p class="indent" >  A valve is opened, blowing rude steam in the face of the ministry. When an
authority acts without the basic agreement of its subjects, its authority is
compromised, and it will hear protest. Aftermath is the time for both reﬂection and
retribution. Both are on their way, Jonas knows.
</p><!--l. 24200--><p class="indent" >  Roness says: “Are they coming to slap out wrists? What did they expect?”
</p><!--l. 24202--><p class="indent" >  “It wasn&#x2019;t going to be possible to keep this under wraps for long,” Jonas
defends.
</p><!--l. 24205--><p class="indent" >  “They are practically comparing the ministry to the maﬁa!”
</p><!--l. 24207--><p class="indent" >  “Maybe the maﬁa could start research funding,” Jonas mumbles.
</p><!--l. 24209--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 24211--><p class="indent" >  He shrugs. “The maﬁa love all the over-regulation in our society. It gives them new
opportunities. Every time the government regulates something to death, they have a
new market. Spirits, cigarettes, meat. Now why not research? Desperate scientists on
some fund racketeering.”
</p><!--l. 24217--><p class="indent" >  “Our ministerial overlords seem to have done a deal behind his back to undermine
the decision of the working group. All our time has just been wasted. It was just a
diversionary tactic – something to keep them busy, while the administration rigged the
ballot.”

</p><!--l. 24224--><p class="indent" >  A woman of perhaps ﬁfty, masculine and ferocious, with glasses that she uses as a
weapon, arrives in the wake of the debate. She was born for civil service, Jonas
thinks. She was forged in the ﬁres of mount Doom from the genes a hospital
matron and a ﬁling cabinet. Her intransigence will be both legendary and
immutable. She has come to express her absolute displeasure at the lack of serious
cooperation expressed in an unfortunate debate that was originated within these
walls.
</p><!--l. 24233--><p class="indent" >  “Society can not stop innovating,” Jonas stands fast. “It is a slippery slope. It is
Lewis Carroll&#x2019;s Red Queen. You have to run to stand still. As soon as you stop trying,
you fall behind. Society will lose the skills it needs to maintain its basic infrastructure.
What will happen when the power goes out?”
</p><!--l. 24239--><p class="indent" >  The functionary from the ministry feels no sympathy.
</p><!--l. 24241--><p class="indent" >  “The political decision has been made.”
</p><!--l. 24243--><p class="indent" >  “Without consultation.”
</p><!--l. 24245--><p class="indent" >  “There was ample opportunity to address the discussion.”
</p><!--l. 24247--><p class="indent" >  “The wool was pulled over our eyes.”
</p><!--l. 24249--><p class="indent" >  “People will fall into line. They have to. It has already been decided.”
</p><!--l. 24251--><p class="indent" >  “Do you have kids?”
</p><!--l. 24253--><p class="indent" >  She raises her eyebrow.
</p><!--l. 24255--><p class="indent" >  “Well then, you already know that the worst way to try to make someone
do something is to tell them they have to. You cannot order someone to be
creative.”
</p><!--l. 24259--><p class="indent" >  “Is that some kind of threat?”
</p><!--l. 24261--><p class="indent" >  “It is a rational observation. You have no doubt seen the transcripts of the open
debate.”
</p><!--l. 24264--><p class="indent" >  “These people will have to abide by the decision. The government has decided
that the country needs people working on the environmental, good Christian
projects.”
</p><!--l. 24268--><p class="indent" >  Jonas fumes at her.
</p><!--l. 24270--><p class="indent" >  “Mr. Lindgren, you should not consider funding any work that does not
fall under this umbrella for the present. To do so would be contrary to your
mandate.”
</p><!--l. 24274--><p class="indent" >  “And what about work could probably have strong environmental spin-oﬀs. What
about that investment?”
</p><!--l. 24277--><p class="indent" >  “If it&#x2019;s not within the next two years, it is no good to us. We have to show the
OECD that we are a top class research country.”
</p><!--l. 24280--><p class="indent" >  “What you are saying does not even make sense!”
</p><!--l. 24282--><p class="indent" >  “May Jesus Christ take you into his heart, Mr. Lindgren. Let&#x2019;s move on.”
</p><!--l. 24284--><p class="indent" >  “Then why not let us be one by leaving research to people who understand
it?”
</p><!--l. 24286--><p class="indent" >  She sighs, something like a frown. “We need results, not people playing cowboys
and Indians across the country with the country&#x2019;s taxes.”
</p><!--l. 24290--><p class="indent" >  “Do you have any idea what motivates research?”

</p><!--l. 24292--><p class="indent" >  “We have been making funds available for some time to stimulate activity in the
area.”
</p><!--l. 24295--><p class="indent" >  “Then good luck getting call girls to do research.”
</p><!--l. 24297--><p class="indent" >  “What? Mr. . .”
</p><!--l. 24299--><p class="indent" >  “You cannot pay people to innovate. It comes from an entirely selﬁsh desire to
procreate. We don&#x2019;t just do it for money.”
</p><!--l. 24302--><p class="indent" >  “What do you think you are talking about? This is not a game for little boys, Mr.
Lindgren. I thought you were more serious than that.”
</p><!--l. 24305--><p class="indent" >  “Research is precisely a game for little boys and girls,” he challenges. “If it isn&#x2019;t,
you won&#x2019;t get what you are looking for.”
</p><!--l. 24309--><p class="indent" >  “What I want is world class science. Research. And it&#x2019;s your job to deliver it.
Science, Jonas. Not play. Science.”
</p><!--l. 24312--><p class="indent" >  “Please don&#x2019;t use that word,” he says. “It oﬀends me, coming from your
lips.”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 24316--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 24317--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 24320--><p class="indent" >  Later, Jonas is sitting at his desk in the frustrated silence of the aftermath. A priority
message from Interpol Research arrives. Secure transmission. Puzzlement and
trepidation hover within him; Jonas opens the message.
</p><!--l. 24325--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Have noted your protests against Christian Party budget change. . .blah blah. I</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">work for a global Interpol consortium including FBI, MI5, blah blah blah. This is a</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">matter of international security. I think you have a technology that we could use. I</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">have already cleared you and your group for possible security work. Can</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">fund a certain amount of work that seems related to what you are doing. .</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">.</span>
</p><!--l. 24333--><p class="indent" >  Jonas reads the message several times and laughs.
</p><!--l. 24335--><p class="indent" >  A friend?
</p><!--l. 24337--><p class="indent" >  A new development, or something bubbling forth from the hot spring?
</p><!--l. 24339--><p class="indent" >  Something for Sara, after all?
</p><!--l. 24341--><p class="indent" >  Where the hell does this come from?
</p><!--l. 24343--><p class="indent" >  But this is surely something important.
</p><!--l. 24345--><p class="indent" >  A meeting should be arranged.
</p><!--l. 24347--><p class="indent" >  In private.
</p><!--l. 24349--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Sorry Joe, I am going to have to commit a sin.</span>
</p><!--l. 24352--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-46r42"></a>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-0"></a>
<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">42</span>
</p><!--l. 24356--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">A football stadium converted into a church.</span>
</p><!--l. 24358--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">“And everybody said Amen and Amen and Amen. Praise the Lord!”</span>
</p><!--l. 24360--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">“Praise the memories of John and George! The Lord spoke to them and made them</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">righteous! And we shall reap their harvest!”</span>
</p><!--l. 24364--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">“God is love and he is all powerful! God can restore your marriage! He can give</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">you wisdom to make good decisions. Open your hearts and your pocket books to the</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Lord.”</span>
</p><!--l. 24368--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">“I want y&#x2019;all to say unto yourselves: this is the day the Lord has made, and I am</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">going to enjoy it!”</span>
</p><!--l. 24371--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">“Hallelujah!”</span>
</p><!--l. 24373--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">“And I shall send my children to a school of Jesus Christ. And I will reach out to</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">my Muslim neighbours and bring their children from their schools to our</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">schools!”</span>
</p><!--l. 24377--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">“Praise Jesus!”</span>
</p><!--l. 24379--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">“And you will have no worries. Because God is looking after you. You come here</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">and pray and the Lord will hear your voice. Fall down, Beccy! Feel the presence of the</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Lord within you!”</span>
</p><!--l. 24383--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Hallelujah!</span>
</p><!--l. 24391--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-47r43"></a>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-0"></a>
<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">43</span>
</p><!--l. 24393--><p class="indent" >  Project funding cancelled. Message from Oslo. Means it could be time to consider a
job. Can she really start all over again?
</p><!--l. 24396--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Wrap your head around that, girl.</span>
</p><!--l. 24398--><p class="indent" >  Should have seen it coming. Could have. Interference from freakin&#x2019; ring-bearers.
What is the world coming to? This was something she really wanted to do.
</p><!--l. 24402--><p class="indent" >  Of course, there&#x2019;s no denying that she has never been one to stop and think about
the way her life is going, or what could happen. She is always more concerned with
the day to day. Things usually just work out, more or less the way you want, but today
certainty seems less than guaranteed. Let&#x2019;s face it, to go chasing after a stick that
someone threw oﬀ the end of the world was probably not a plan that will put her in the
history books. Now the curtain has come down on that farce and it&#x2019;s back to square
one.
</p><!--l. 24411--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Make note for future lives: exercise patience before running into danger.</span>
</p><!--l. 24414--><p class="indent" >  Duh.
</p><!--l. 24416--><p class="indent" >  Better not get too down.
</p><!--l. 24418--><p class="indent" >  She has spent some time convalescing. Out here in the country one can do
all kinds of cheesy things at the hotels: a jacuzzi with blue and pink disco
lighting, surrounded by country and western memorabilia, and Nashville
nonsense, organized line dancing in the evenings. Not exactly her idea of
fun.
</p><!--l. 24424--><p class="indent" >  She has been outside, but not far. The fragrances of mountain grasses are entirely
gone now, frozen away by the sudden cold. Late summers and sudden winters: they
seem to advance every year. The mountain is white again and the world is light years
away.
</p><!--l. 24429--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Time to look after me, </span>she thinks.
</p><!--l. 24431--><p class="indent" >  “Bea, girl.”
</p><!--l. 24433--><p class="indent" >  “Hey you, still alive?”
</p><!--l. 24435--><p class="indent" >  “Getting there. Whatchu doing?”

</p><!--l. 24437--><p class="indent" >  “Just got home from work. Shower time. You?”
</p><!--l. 24439--><p class="indent" >  “Stuck. Need some cozin&#x2019; and some luvvin&#x2019;.”
</p><!--l. 24441--><p class="indent" >  “Hey, Genius. Don&#x2019;t give up. Coming home soon?”
</p><!--l. 24443--><p class="indent" >  “Hope so.”
</p><!--l. 24445--><p class="indent" >  “When?”
</p><!--l. 24447--><p class="indent" >  “ASAP, Cool Thing.”
</p><!--l. 24452--><p class="indent" >  Fever has ﬁnally drained from her and she feels strong. The chance to
rest has actually been welcome. Old Donald Duck comics (paper), movies
and news on the TV. And Bea. The girl might not have had more than an
average schooling, but she is a Professor when it comes to making her feel
better.
</p><!--l. 24458--><p class="indent" >  She hasn&#x2019;t felt like a prisoner, precisely, more like a raptor in a tar pit. She lost
them, the French team. She failed to get what she wanted. She fell behind. Her raison
d&#x2019;être evaporated. She ought to pick herself up and move on. Find a new
one.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 24463--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 24464--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 24467--><p class="indent" >  At two o&#x2019;clock in the afternoon, her premonition is realized. The leather beat-bitch
tramps her chequered garb into the mountain hotel&#x2019;s lounge and regards her with that
absent bitchiness she is so good at.
</p><!--l. 24471--><p class="indent" >  Her cardboard-on-toast voice tolls: “It&#x2019;s over.”
</p><!--l. 24473--><p class="indent" >  Sara Stensrud glances up at her from the tablet in her lap.
</p><!--l. 24476--><p class="indent" >  “Call you later, mum,” she says, completing a diﬀerent conversation, and meets her
unassailable nonchalance. “What&#x2019;s over?”
</p><!--l. 24479--><p class="indent" >  Steroid Sally stands is poise, as a rock would poise, in the entrance to the lounge,
with face-lift pony-tail sucking her backwards, and cold blue eyes avoiding those of
the only person in the room. “They have surrendered. All of them. The army is
rounding them up now.”
</p><!--l. 24485--><p class="indent" >  “The football gangs?”
</p><!--l. 24487--><p class="indent" >  She nods, chewing some kind of gum, as if masticating ﬂavoured plastic can blow
smoke in Vibe&#x2019;s face. Looking anywhere, everywhere but at her.
</p><!--l. 24490--><p class="indent" >  “And their friends. Out of their depth in this weather.”
</p><!--l. 24492--><p class="indent" >  “Does that mean we can get out of here now?”
</p><!--l. 24494--><p class="indent" >  “We&#x2019;re getting rid of you.”
</p><!--l. 24496--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Likewise, bitch.</span>
</p><!--l. 24498--><p class="indent" >  “District will be up to clear you later. Be good, and say nice things, or you might
end up with a ﬁne.”
</p><!--l. 24501--><p class="indent" >  She backs out of the entrance, turns and leaves.

</p><!--l. 24504--><p class="indent" >  District will clear her later? Like she were under arrest or something? In
your dreams, Sally. She can think of no good reason to stay here any longer
than necessary. She&#x2019;s just afraid I might say something about her hobby. .
.
</p><!--l. 24509--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Say nice things. . .</span>
</p><!--l. 24511--><p class="indent" >  In other words: I know you saw me distributing illegal spirits, and you&#x2019;d better not
say a word, or I&#x2019;ll have you.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 24515--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 24516--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 24520--><p class="indent" >  The news from Saskwatch Sally is a turning point.
</p><!--l. 24522--><p class="indent" >  What can she do here now that her project has been pulled out from underneath
her? Dr Lindgren says he will sort something out, but what the hell is that supposed to
mean? Since when did he ever come up trumps?
</p><!--l. 24527--><p class="indent" >  Call comes in. Luck of the devil.
</p><!--l. 24530--><p class="indent" >  “Sara Vibeke Stensrud?”
</p><!--l. 24532--><p class="indent" >  “Ehh. . .yes. Sort of, anyway.”
</p><!--l. 24534--><p class="indent" >  “My name is Edward Bishop. I work for Interpol&#x2019;s research centre. I spoke brieﬂy
with Dr Jonas Lindgren and I would like to talk to you about doing a job for me,
perhaps permanently.”
</p><!--l. 24538--><p class="indent" >  She checks her message board.
