</p><!--l. 24546--><p class="indent" >  More details are in some other attachments..
</p><!--l. 24548--><p class="indent" >  “Just wanted to speak to you directly. Look at this, then we can talk in a little
while.”
</p><!--l. 24551--><p class="indent" >  “Thanks, I&#x2019;ll look at it.”
</p><!--l. 24555--><p class="indent" >  She stares out of the window at the rock just beyond it one last time. It seems to
symbolize her predicament. From the inside of the hotel, the rock looks harmless and
scenic, biding its time: just a painting on the canvas of the daylight. But, if
she goes outside, it is rough and hard and sharp and cold. It is dangerous. It
cuts.
</p><!--l. 24561--><p class="indent" >  How much we sacriﬁce of reality, she thinks. Pain is truth, if anything is. This rock.
This cage. It is time to be leaving. Time to reclaim the world of pain and
future.
</p><!--l. 24565--><p class="indent" >  Could have sworn she saw Ethanol Emma talking to the man at the hotel desk.
Probably selling her moonshine. He is an old cardiganed shrew with a bulbous red

nose that tells her he is more of a country alcoboy than mountain guide. She goes out
there.
</p><!--l. 24571--><p class="indent" >  “Did you see what happened to that police woman?”
</p><!--l. 24573--><p class="indent" >  “Who?”
</p><!--l. 24575--><p class="indent" >  “You know, tall weight lifter. I don&#x2019;t know her name. She was right here.”
</p><!--l. 24577--><p class="indent" >  “She has probably gone.”
</p><!--l. 24579--><p class="indent" >  “Ah.”
</p><!--l. 24581--><p class="indent" >  “So you heard the news?” the balding receptionist asks.
</p><!--l. 24583--><p class="indent" >  “Yes. We&#x2019;re not quarantined anymore.”
</p><!--l. 24585--><p class="indent" >  “That means the busses will be running again from tomorrow morning.”
</p><!--l. 24588--><p class="indent" >  “Does that mean there will be a bus soon to Oslo?”
</p><!--l. 24590--><p class="indent" >  “Just got word from the Express. First one is due in tomorrow at six in the
morning.”
</p><!--l. 24593--><p class="indent" >  “Nothing sooner? I&#x2019;m in kind of a hurry. Now that we&#x2019;re all free.”
</p><!--l. 24595--><p class="indent" >  “Eh, no. Not unless you want to sit with me to the town. I&#x2019;m going down the
mountain later. I can&#x2019;t wait for some supplies. You could get a train from the
station.”
</p><!--l. 24599--><p class="indent" >  “Really?”
</p><!--l. 24601--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s not a limousine, but it&#x2019;ll roll down the hill.”
</p><!--l. 24603--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, yes, yes, yes! Thank you!”
</p><!--l. 24605--><p class="indent" >  “All right then,” he chuckles. “Be ready in an hour. . .”
</p><!--l. 24607--><p class="indent" >  “Check me out!”
</p><!--l. 24609--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Not like that, Grampa!</span>
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 24611--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 24612--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 24615--><p class="indent" >  She packs her rucksack quickly, stuﬃng everything in as quickly as possible. No
sense in being tidy now. With luck she will be home before long where real clothes
await and she no longer has to live in tent fabrics. She is not certain how the
local police will react to her simply leaving, but cross that one when we get
there.
</p><!--l. 24621--><p class="indent" >  She can imagine the incendiary glare of Suicide Sally threatening to melt her own
icy demeanour. There must be a volcano beneath that ice. A real mud pool. Give
yourself a facial.
</p><!--l. 24625--><p class="indent" >  The little box she received from the American has been waiting on her dressing
table, like the mysterious visitor from 2001: A Space Odyssey, ever since she received
it. She packs it into her backpack. She has been staring at it for minutes on
end, without being able to penetrate its secret. A note is attached to the box.
“Sara—don&#x2019;t try to open this until December 12th,” it says. It seems to be
locked, so there must be some reason for the message. She placed it next to her

mirror and tried everything barring telepathy to reveal its mystery. Perhaps
they simply wanted her to have a Christmas present. Maybe it doesn&#x2019;t matter
now.
</p><!--l. 24636--><p class="indent" >  New message from mystery sponsor.
