</p><!--l. 24661--><p class="indent" >  She waits for the call, sitting cross legged on her bed, holding a tablet. Incoming.
She opens.
</p><!--l. 24665--><p class="indent" >  “Hello.”
</p><!--l. 24667--><p class="indent" >  An older man.
</p><!--l. 24669--><p class="indent" >  “Hello, Sara. Thank you for responding. I have need for your skills in several ways.
I have a police operation to conduct. It has to do with the gang violence and the rise of
radical groups. I can&#x2019;t tell you the details until you come and sign non-disclosure
agreements. This is conﬁdential police business.”
</p><!--l. 24675--><p class="indent" >  “So you are police?”
</p><!--l. 24677--><p class="indent" >  “I am interpol, Norwegian branch.”
</p><!--l. 24679--><p class="indent" >  “I have been working on a collaborative project which now seems to have been
halted.”
</p><!--l. 24682--><p class="indent" >  “I heard. The expansion of Chri. . .certain inﬂuences in the United States has
resulted in a sudden change of budget. Space and BioTech in particular have been
axed in favour of so-called ‘Moral Research&#x2019;. Enormous pressure has been levied on
their international partners to withdraw from the projects.”
</p><!--l. 24688--><p class="indent" >  “Are we supposed to live in the dark ages now?”
</p><!--l. 24690--><p class="indent" >  “I suppose so. Sara, would you be interested in coming to work for me?”
</p><!--l. 24692--><p class="indent" >  “What would I do?”
</p><!--l. 24694--><p class="indent" >  “Close to what you have already been doing. Working in a team. I can guarantee
that the work will be at least as interesting and challenging as you have been doing.
Now you get to work with humans and machines.”

</p><!--l. 24699--><p class="indent" >  “We should talk when I get home. I&#x2019;ve been a bit out of it. Sick.”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 24703--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 24704--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 24707--><p class="indent" >  They are driving along the winter road. Her escape chute. The snowplough has
wiped and stacked the landscape, giving them tunnel vision. She is a mole burrowing
through a trough of feta cheese.
</p><!--l. 24711--><p class="indent" >  “Looking forward to going home to your folks?” the hotelier asks.
</p><!--l. 24713--><p class="indent" >  “Yes!” she agrees.
</p><!--l. 24715--><p class="indent" >  “They should be glad to see you after this trouble.”
</p><!--l. 24717--><p class="indent" >  Ah, the trouble.
</p><!--l. 24721--><p class="indent" >  He is right. It will be good to get home, but her decision to leave quietly could
backﬁre: her immunity to others&#x2019; instructions has always served as a provocation to
them, as her brother with attest. Always she has faith that nothing bad will happen.
She has duck feathers, as well as the beak. Trouble runs oﬀ her, to her brother&#x2019;s
annoyance. She knows how to use her looks to activate forgiveness when
necessary.
</p><!--l. 24731--><p class="indent" >  It is dark by the time they reach the small town station. She thanks the hotelier and
steps out of the warm cocoon into a biting chill. They have timed the journey so that
she will not have to wait more than a few minutes for the train to arrive, so she
shouldn&#x2019;t have to freeze her nipples oﬀ for too long.
</p><!--l. 24737--><p class="indent" >  She pulls out her backpack from the rear seat and waves a good bye. The car moves
oﬀ and then stops a little way down the road, but he doesn&#x2019;t get out, so she turns to
ﬁnd the platform.
</p><!--l. 24741--><p class="indent" >  Moonlight lights up the mountains behind her. Pretty, but it&#x2019;s time to say her
good-byes. The road she has arrived on stretches back up the valley, snaking its
way up the mountain; on it, a blue light, far oﬀ, reaches out to her across the
darkened pass, as if pointing across the mountain with the long, icy ﬁnger of the
law.
</p><!--l. 24747--><p class="indent" >  Her heart skips a beat. A police car this way comes.
</p><!--l. 24750--><p class="indent" >  Beat Bitch Sally? Who else could it be? Frank, coming to say good-bye?
</p><!--l. 24753--><p class="indent" >  She turns to see what became of the hotelier and sees that he has received a call,
which he takes on an old hand-held receiver. He looks about as if searching for her
and she knows then that the call is about her. Damn. It was an even bet, but she is not
sticking around to be talked to or stopped.
</p><!--l. 24759--><p class="indent" >  Vibe turns and walks away from the vehicle towards the small station building.
There are not many places to hide here precisely, but she can lie low.
</p><!--l. 24763--><p class="indent" >  This is not a time to allow herself to feel guilt for leaving. If she just keeps moving
around, they should never have to meet. Anyway, as long as she is near civilization,
they know where she is by her mobile. It&#x2019;s not like she could hide. The blue light is

edging closer. It will arrive before the train comes.
</p><!--l. 24769--><p class="indent" >  She checks the time. Just a few minutes until the train arrives. Browse some
magazines, buy a book? There is a platform barrier here, she sees. The best place for
her to be is on the other side of that barrier.
</p><!--l. 24774--><p class="indent" >  She heaves her backpack onto her frame one more time and heads for the
gate.
</p><!--l. 24776--><p class="indent" >  “Where do you think you are going?”
</p><!--l. 24778--><p class="indent" >  She ﬂashes her mobile strap. “I have a pass for the train.”
</p><!--l. 24781--><p class="indent" >  “Not with that, you don&#x2019;t,” he says, pointing at her backpack.
</p><!--l. 24783--><p class="indent" >  “But. . .what?”
</p><!--l. 24785--><p class="indent" >  “Train is extremely full this evening and there is no room in the cabin. You&#x2019;ll have
to check that in as freight. Over there. Better hurry.”
</p><!--l. 24788--><p class="indent" >  He points her in the direction of the baggage oﬃce.
</p><!--l. 24790--><p class="indent" >  Registered freight and luggage. Special baggage. Post. Post?
</p><!--l. 24792--><p class="indent" >  She goes to the postal desk on a sudden whim.
</p><!--l. 24794--><p class="indent" >  “Eh hello. I&#x2019;m in a bit of a hurry. Can I send this to my address in Oslo?”
</p><!--l. 24796--><p class="indent" >  “You can, if you can pay for it,” he laughs.
</p><!--l. 24798--><p class="indent" >  “When would it arrive?”
</p><!--l. 24800--><p class="indent" >  “That depends where you live.”
</p><!--l. 24802--><p class="indent" >  “Oslo. Centre.”
</p><!--l. 24804--><p class="indent" >  He consults a list, as if he doesn&#x2019;t know the answer. “Probably tomorrow
afternoon. You would have to be there to receive it, or collect it from the
depot.”
</p><!--l. 24808--><p class="indent" >  “Okay. How much?”
</p><!--l. 24810--><p class="indent" >  She has some money from her mum now. She can aﬀord this. It will even
make the journey more pleasant. She has to suppress a hopping up and down
motion.
</p><!--l. 24813--><p class="indent" >  “Scales,” the clerk barks.
</p><!--l. 24815--><p class="indent" >  She rests the pack on the scales.
</p><!--l. 24817--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s already tagged,” she says.
</p><!--l. 24819--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Train now arriving for Oslo Central Station on platform 2.</span>
</p><!--l. 24821--><p class="indent" >  Damn, she thinks. This is cutting it a bit ﬁne.
</p><!--l. 24823--><p class="indent" >  He scans the pack and extracts her details, taking a little longer than she feels is
necessary under the circumstances.
</p><!--l. 24826--><p class="indent" >  “All right. This looks okay. You can send second class and save a little, but I don&#x2019;t
recommend it.”
</p><!--l. 24829--><p class="indent" >  “No. That won&#x2019;t be necessary. Just get it to me as quickly as you can!” She grins,
giving him the school girl look.
</p><!--l. 24833--><p class="indent" >  “Ooookaaaayy. Here&#x2019;s a copy of an agreement. Read the top part. Sign to accept.”
He indicates for her to download it from the counter, working at a clockwork speed,
with no indication of knowing the meaning or urgency.
</p><!--l. 24838--><p class="indent" >  She looks over the form. “All right. Everything seems to be in order.”

</p><!--l. 24842--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Train on platform 2 leaves immediately for Oslo Central Station. Passengers are</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">advised that there will be no waiting.</span>
</p><!--l. 24845--><p class="indent" >  Through the window she can see the police car park outside. She sees Saskwatch
step out of the car and start towards the station.
</p><!--l. 24849--><p class="indent" >  “Eh—so can I just leave this with you?”
</p><!--l. 24851--><p class="indent" >  “Anything dangerous in here? You checked the box?”
</p><!--l. 24853--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, yes.”
</p><!--l. 24855--><p class="indent" >  “In a hurry are we?”
</p><!--l. 24857--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Thats what I said!</span>
</p><!--l. 24859--><p class="indent" >  “Actually yes,” she smiles sweetly, remembering her demeanour. “I have to catch
this train, and it&#x2019;s supposed to be very full.”
</p><!--l. 24862--><p class="indent" >  “I see. Well, it looks as though everything is in order.”
</p><!--l. 24864--><p class="indent" >  “So I&#x2019;ll get this tomorrow?” she asks, redundantly, but hoping for a dismissal.
</p><!--l. 24866--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s what the man said.”
</p><!--l. 24868--><p class="indent" >  “Great service. Thanks.”
</p><!--l. 24870--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Train now leaving for Oslo Central Station on platform 2.</span>
</p><!--l. 24872--><p class="indent" >  No time!
</p><!--l. 24874--><p class="indent" >  “You&#x2019;d better go,” he says calmly, “if you want to catch that”.
</p><!--l. 24876--><p class="indent" >  She exhales. “Thanks!”
</p><!--l. 24878--><p class="indent" >  She turns to leave and her eye catches that of the policewoman, through the
window, glaring at her. She has been spotted. Saskwatch turns towards the door from
the exit side of the building.
</p><!--l. 24882--><p class="indent" >  Vibe&#x2019;s heart skips another beat, but she forces herself to pretend that she has not
seen her. Without much encouragement, she walks quickly to the back-door leading
towards the platform and trots towards to the platform barrier, breaking into a run as
she goes. The conductor-barrier registers her ticket and the human waves her
through.
</p><!--l. 24888--><p class="indent" >  She runs for the train.
</p><!--l. 24890--><p class="indent" >  Doors close.
</p><!--l. 24892--><p class="indent" >  Whistle blows.
</p><!--l. 24894--><p class="indent" >  Behind her, no one is following.
</p><!--l. 24896--><p class="indent" >  She plops herself down into her designated seat and allows herself to calm her
beating heart.
</p><!--l. 24899--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I am going home.</span>
</p><!--l. 24901--><p class="indent" >  She is looking forward to the prospect of being back in the city, where time runs at
the proper rate.
</p><!--l. 24905--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-48r44"></a>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-0"></a>
<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">44</span>
</p><!--l. 24907--><p class="indent" >  Silver eel, electric and hushed. It carries Vibe from the pods of rocky leviathans, in
the high ground, into the lower pastures of the capitol. Back towards to Oslo&#x2019;s basin of
attraction. A journey of several hours. Time for sleep.
</p><!--l. 24912--><p class="indent" >  Urban re-entry deep-fries her in a sensory feed. Sizzling data streams boil her. She
is ﬁsh&#x2019;n&#x2019;chips. She is Burger&#x2019;n&#x2019;fries. This is the 24-hour Deli. Yet it contains
the life support, the basic feeds to buoy 21st Century incompetent life. It
has proper clothes, the trappings of ceremony, and warm bodies for tactile
relief.
</p><!--l. 24919--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Hello immersion tank, my silver lining.</span>
</p><!--l. 24921--><p class="indent" >  The train deposits her rested and more lightweight soma at Oslo&#x2019;s central station
with just enough possessions to ﬁnd her way home. It feels good to have the city
coursing through her senses once again. Mountains are necessary and beautiful, but
above all they reﬁne one&#x2019;s appreciation of the city.
</p><!--l. 24927--><p class="indent" >  It is about 20:40 hours when she arrives in Oslo. She tightens the straps on her
mobile to better absorb the subtle notiﬁcations from the smart environment. The
canopy of the city is both dark and light at the same time.
</p><!--l. 24932--><p class="indent" >  There has been a light rain in the capital and the air is cool but fresh. Compared to
the mountains, it seems damp and almost warm here.
</p><!--l. 24935--><p class="indent" >  Vibe takes a town-bike from the stall and cycles the half kilometre or so to her
small two-room ﬂat. She is itching to shower and change into something more like
clothes. Something beﬁtting a girl.
</p><!--l. 24939--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I used to be that, </span>she thinks.
</p><!--l. 24941--><p class="indent" >  It is quiet and dusty in the ﬂat. No air has circulated here for over a week. The level
in the toilet is low, where the water has evaporated. She has bought fresh milk from
the corner Deli for making tea.
</p><!--l. 24946--><p class="indent" >  After a purging shower and hair cure, she puts her mobile pieces in to be washed,
and switches to her house combo.
</p><!--l. 24949--><p class="indent" >  As she does so, a message comes in for her:

