</p><!--l. 24960--><p class="indent" >  She stares in horror at the message, her mouth wide open.
</p><!--l. 24962--><p class="indent" >  She sits down.
</p><!--l. 24964--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">The bitch!</span>
</p><!--l. 24966--><p class="indent" >  Then again.
</p><!--l. 24968--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">The bitch!</span>
</p><!--l. 24970--><p class="indent" >  Now she has gone out on a limb.
</p><!--l. 24972--><p class="indent" >  If she has used police privilege against her, she&#x2019;d better have a pretty good
explanation.
</p><!--l. 24975--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">What the hell have I done to deserve this?</span>
</p><!--l. 24977--><p class="indent" >  She summons calm. There was nothing she urgently needed in the pack. Her tablet
and a few clothes, mostly, and gear she doesn&#x2019;t need here. But that is hardly the
point.
</p><!--l. 24981--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">What the hell are you afraid of, you stupid freaking bitch?</span>
</p><!--l. 24983--><p class="indent" >  She sits for a long time with a frown that is half way towards wanting to cry. Too
much stress lately. Too much.
</p><!--l. 24986--><p class="indent" >  She needs to feel calm and complete. She needs her shiny conﬁdence back. Sleep
will help, but she is the opposite of tired at this moment.
</p><!--l. 24989--><p class="indent" >  Consideration calls forth the spirits of healing.
</p><!--l. 24991--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I know what to do, </span>she thinks. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">This doesn&#x2019;t matter. It can be sorted tomorrow or</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">even the day after. There are ways to deal with it.</span>
</p><!--l. 24993--><p class="indent" >  She considers calling her mum, but that will just make her want to complain and
even cry about it. Not going to happen.
</p><!--l. 24996--><p class="indent" >  She stabs at her combo and pulls up her buddy list. Neighbours are useful
sometimes. Geography isn&#x2019;t dead yet. Paul, where are you? Just back from a trip. You
busy?
</p><!--l. 25000--><p class="indent" >  She invites her chum over and strips him. She needs to feel the heat of
someone between her legs. He obliges her, as any half-sane male would.
Afterwards, she sends him on his way and settles into her cocoon, feeling
empowered.
</p><!--l. 25005--><p class="indent" >  Text to Bea.
</p><!--l. 25007--><p class="indent" >  “Back in black, babe. Just male-nutrished. Wanna come and sleep over?”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 25011--><p class="noindent" >

</p><!--l. 25012--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 25017--><p class="indent" >  “Dr Jonas Lindgren. My name is Edward Bishop. I work with Interpol. I have a
project where I need some urgent consulting. Would you be willing to help
me?”
</p><!--l. 25021--><p class="indent" >  Bishop follows Jonas as he walks through the sterile lobby of the research council
oﬃces, in the centre of town. He has been waiting there for a few minutes and was
told that Jonas would come out from a meeting in a short time. The secretary pointed
a telling biro at him as he appeared.
</p><!--l. 25027--><p class="indent" >  Reporters have gathered outside the Research Council: headline hunters and
interview hounds. A crowd of them is accreting.
</p><!--l. 25030--><p class="indent" >  Jonas looks wary and tired, but not unreceptive. “Help? What kind of help did you
have in mind?”
</p><!--l. 25033--><p class="indent" >  “I left a message for you. It has to do with your work on autonomous agents and
inﬂuence networks.”
</p><!--l. 25036--><p class="indent" >  Jonas stops and regards the older man.
</p><!--l. 25038--><p class="indent" >  “That was you,” he says thoughtfully.
</p><!--l. 25040--><p class="indent" >  “That was me.”
</p><!--l. 25042--><p class="indent" >  “I mentioned to you my student. Well, ex student, as it turns out. Did you try
her?”
</p><!--l. 25045--><p class="indent" >  Bishop nods. “Yes, I am in touch with her. In fact, I have an appointment to meet
her here.”
</p><!--l. 25048--><p class="indent" >  As the words come out, a slim beauty in dark, booted jeans with a broad leather belt
and a short white winter-jacket appears through the main entrance, swishing her hair
to one side. She sees Jonas and strides up to the two men.
</p><!--l. 25053--><p class="indent" >  “Hello,” she says. “What the hell is going on out there?” Then: “Remember
me?”
</p><!--l. 25056--><p class="indent" >  She seems a little thinner and a little tougher than the last time he saw her, but he
responds with an air of pleasant surprise, for someone obviously a little stressed
out.
</p><!--l. 25060--><p class="indent" >  “Sara, speak of the devil.”
</p><!--l. 25062--><p class="indent" >  “And angels appear!” she chastizes with smiling eyes.
</p><!--l. 25064--><p class="indent" >  “I am Ed Bishop,” Ed Bishop adds.
</p><!--l. 25066--><p class="indent" >  “Ah hei, nice to meet you. So you two know each other?”
</p><!--l. 25068--><p class="indent" >  “Ah no, no we don&#x2019;t. Not yet. But now that we are all here, I would very much like
to talk to you both. This is a matter of some importance and I know that it is going to
interest you.”
</p><!--l. 25072--><p class="indent" >  Jonas looks around, as if wondering where they should go. His oﬃce? The
receptionist is waving to him.
</p><!--l. 25075--><p class="indent" >  “Jonas, Kaja is here. . .” she whispers.
</p><!--l. 25077--><p class="indent" >  She points out of the entrance at a ﬁgure in a long coat, paused at the foot of the
steps with a small child.
</p><!--l. 25080--><p class="indent" >  “Damn.” he says.

</p><!--l. 25082--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">It never rains, but it pours.</span>
</p><!--l. 25084--><p class="indent" >  He casts a worried look at his visitors. “I can&#x2019;t see her now.” Then to the
receptionist: “Tell her I had to go out would you?” He looks panicked. “Please, both
of you, come this way.”
</p><!--l. 25089--><p class="indent" >  He practically pushes them along a corridor, leading to a separate but connected
part of the building.
</p><!--l. 25092--><p class="indent" >  “Come on, this way. I don&#x2019;t want to run into her on the way out.”
</p><!--l. 25094--><p class="indent" >  Vibe and Bishop regard one another quizzically.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 25096--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 25097--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 25100--><p class="indent" >  As he shuﬄes them out, Sara says. “Don&#x2019;t suppose you&#x2019;ve you talked to the
embassy? Have you heard from the team?”
</p><!--l. 25103--><p class="indent" >  He shakes his head. “Sorry.”
</p><!--l. 25105--><p class="indent" >  “I think I want to kill someone.”
</p><!--l. 25107--><p class="indent" >  He grunts. “Governments are shutting the door on everyone&#x2019;s future, not just
yours.”
</p><!--l. 25110--><p class="indent" >  “Aren&#x2019;t there laws protecting against this kind of thing?”
</p><!--l. 25112--><p class="indent" >  “Glad you asked,” he winces without further embellishment.
</p><!--l. 25114--><p class="indent" >  He leads them into something of a blind alley within the building; the only way
forward is an emergency exit.
</p><!--l. 25117--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m really sorry for this,” Jonas says. “I have some personal matters that are
taking up my time. We won&#x2019;t have any peace if she ﬁnds us, and we can&#x2019;t
go out front because of the reporters. Let&#x2019;s go out and try to ﬁnd a coﬀee
shop.”
</p><!--l. 25122--><p class="indent" >  They seem agreed. Jonas pushes the ﬁre exit bar and they slip out into bright, grey
daylight.
</p><!--l. 25125--><p class="indent" >  It one of those damp days when sounds travels more eﬃciently than usual,
when cars make more noise and passing aircraft seem almost to be upon you.
Crackling winter tires break up the air making it hard to talk. Not far away from
them, there is an unholy sound of roaring people ﬂocking, from the old Blitz
house.
</p><!--l. 25131--><p class="indent" >  “What&#x2019;s going on there?” Jonas asks.
</p><!--l. 25133--><p class="indent" >  “Youth activists, It think,” Bishop says. “They have organized a some kind of
demonstration. I think it&#x2019;s some commemoration—or commiseration of the old Blitz
house.”
</p><!--l. 25137--><p class="indent" >  “Looked like there were Nazi hecklers throwing things at them when I passed there
a moment ago.”
</p><!--l. 25140--><p class="indent" >  She sees that Jonas looks a little freaked.
</p><!--l. 25142--><p class="indent" >  “We shouldn&#x2019;t go that way.”

</p><!--l. 25145--><p class="indent" >  “They&#x2019;re just people,” Vibe says. “A bit too loud, but they&#x2019;re probably
harmless.”
</p><!--l. 25148--><p class="indent" >  He shudders.
</p><!--l. 25150--><p class="indent" >  “I suppose I&#x2019;m getting too old for this kind of thing.”
</p><!--l. 25152--><p class="indent" >  “People with a cause to unite them,” Bishop mutters. “A mob.”
</p><!--l. 25154--><p class="indent" >  “Yesterday it was Christian Rights on the stands on Karl Johan. Old people
complaining about young people. Plus ça change, eh? Maybe I&#x2019;m turning into one of
them.”
</p><!--l. 25158--><p class="indent" >  “Was there violence?”
</p><!--l. 25160--><p class="indent" >  “No, no. Well, not physical, though I&#x2019;m not convinced their message is any better
than a thump in the face. Small town politics, but there is big money behind it all.
They&#x2019;re probably more dangerous than a few louts. They have ties to established
institutions. They take each other more seriously.”
</p><!--l. 25168--><p class="indent" >  “I heard some gang was coming to get <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">us</span>,” Vibe says to Jonas.
</p><!--l. 25170--><p class="indent" >  Bishop nods. “Tried to get your advisor here. Come on, let&#x2019;s go back up this way.
We can walk through to St Hanshaugen. It shouldn&#x2019;t be too slippery.” He starts oﬀ up
the road that snakes up the hill, passing by blocks of ﬂats built along the
curvilinear road. There are plenty of cars parked on each side to conceal them
from watching eyes, and they can cut in to the many pedestrianized side
streets.
</p><!--l. 25177--><p class="indent" >  Vibe looks at Jonas, intensely. “Really?”
</p><!--l. 25179--><p class="indent" >  He nods. “Really. They never got as far as you. You went away at the right time, but
they probably would have.”
</p><!--l. 25182--><p class="indent" >  “Right now their cronies are busy with a protest rally. You&#x2019;ll be okay for
now.”
</p><!--l. 25186--><p class="indent" >  “So, Mr. Bishop, what is it you do exactly? You still haven&#x2019;t told me.”
</p><!--l. 25188--><p class="indent" >  “Nor me,” Vibe adds.
</p><!--l. 25190--><p class="indent" >  “Yes. This is where it gets diﬃcult to explain. I have an interesting job,” he
procrastinates, slowing his stroll to face them. “Basically you could say that I am
employed to apply the science of control and maintenance to policing our society. I
work for the police force. Interpol.”
</p><!--l. 25196--><p class="indent" >  “Coppers aren&#x2019;t just running around hitting people over the heads with their
truncheons anymore, eh?”
</p><!--l. 25199--><p class="indent" >  “Well, there is still a bit of that too, I&#x2019;m sure.”
</p><!--l. 25201--><p class="indent" >  “Does it pay well? Career prospects?”
</p><!--l. 25203--><p class="indent" >  He laughs at Vibe&#x2019;s odd question. “Not really. International policing has to make its
own money these days. We invest in businesses and currencies and run things like a
charity—donations from interested Samaritans, and so on. You can&#x2019;t ﬁght corruption
in governments if you are on their payroll. So funds are limited. I get a comfortable
amount.”
</p><!--l. 25210--><p class="indent" >  “So you don&#x2019;t work for the Norwegian police?”
</p><!--l. 25212--><p class="indent" >  “We are part of the international branch, but we are formally part of Norwegian
police force, yes.”

</p><!--l. 25215--><p class="indent" >  “And you say you need our help?”
</p><!--l. 25217--><p class="indent" >  He smiles. “Yes. Two diﬀerent reasons, as it happens. Finding people with a science
education isn&#x2019;t all that easy these days. Recruiting people to work for something other
than money is just as hard. You both have expertise that overlaps with our own.” To
Sara, “You have been doing some very interesting things in the VR. Perhaps you have
some friends too. I am not sure about that, but I know at least that you are
involved.”
</p><!--l. 25225--><p class="indent" >  Her eyes widen and she laughs nervously. “What things? What makes you think it
is me?”
</p><!--l. 25228--><p class="indent" >  “Well, mainly because it is my job to know.” He winks.
</p><!--l. 25231--><p class="indent" >  Vibe smiles sweetly.
</p><!--l. 25233--><p class="indent" >  “The bottom line is this,” he says. “Law and order, the world over, is going down
the tubes, largely due to the fact that people no longer see the need to rely on one
another as citizens. That makes it hard for the police forces of the world to function
properly.”
</p><!--l. 25238--><p class="indent" >  “Uh, here it comes.” Vibe gives him a look.
</p><!--l. 25240--><p class="indent" >  “Police forces are struggling against the odds. Something has to be done to
preserve their potency. After the big cuts in resources, in the last decade, police
are no longer really equipped to deal with the rising criminal gang culture.
When vigilante groups start to spring up, then you know the you are in serious
trouble.”
</p><!--l. 25247--><p class="indent" >  “Where&#x2019;s Batman when you need him?”
</p><!--l. 25249--><p class="indent" >  Jonas is following the conversation, but his head is scanning around to see who
might be following them.
</p><!--l. 25252--><p class="indent" >  “We are trying to preserve that potency, partly with the help of governments and
partly in spite of them.”
</p><!--l. 25255--><p class="indent" >  “Are you talking about the game business?” Jonas asks. “It was in the news a while
back. About the American government spreading its message of peace and
capitalism?”
</p><!--l. 25259--><p class="indent" >  Bishop regards him. “That&#x2019;s part of it,” he agrees. “But it&#x2019;s much more complicated
than that. The whole thing is a battleground and our research has shown that the
messages they are trying to convey are complex and intermingled. I&#x2019;d have to explain
some of the background. . .”
</p><!--l. 25265--><p class="indent" >  “Please, go ahead. I&#x2019;m interested. You know I had no idea that the police did
research.”
</p><!--l. 25268--><p class="indent" >  Vibe nods. “Does this have to do with the job you mentioned.”
</p><!--l. 25270--><p class="indent" >  Bishop nods. “All right. Let&#x2019;s see where do we begin?” He points up a side road.
“Let&#x2019;s go up here.” The road is quieter and it is easier to hear him speak. “So, let&#x2019;s say
there are several theories about how to keep society in order. There is the
expression of rules in law, but how to enforce? We can start with rule by <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">fear</span>.
Fear of reprisal, whether it be incarceration or punishment, ﬁnes, torture in a
dictatorship, or the threat of what might happen if people do not behave by law. .
.”

</p><!--l. 25280--><p class="indent" >  “Happy thoughts. Okay, so we have done fear.”
</p><!--l. 25282--><p class="indent" >  “Then there is the dogma of good habits. Prevention.”
</p><!--l. 25284--><p class="indent" >  “If everyone is good, then everyone else sees them being good and wants to join in,
and so the whole world is just hunky dory?”
</p><!--l. 25287--><p class="indent" >  “Exactly.”
</p><!--l. 25289--><p class="indent" >  “What else?”
</p><!--l. 25291--><p class="indent" >  “Well, now we have to decide if we have democratic law or edict from an authority,
like a church.”
</p><!--l. 25294--><p class="indent" >  “Which you are going to tell us is an oxymoron, because no one can agree
on what is right and wrong.” Vibe kicks herself internally for involuntary
huﬃness.
</p><!--l. 25298--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Grow up, girl. Just relax.</span>
</p><!--l. 25300--><p class="indent" >  She ﬁnds herself wishing that she were sitting somewhere working on
her thesis, programming or doing something where she did not feel out of
place.
</p><!--l. 25303--><p class="indent" >  “No, no one ever agrees. The point is not that everyone in a democracy has to agree.
A suﬃcient majority has to agree, but what&#x2019;s more important then is that the
remainder of society has to accept defeat. They have to sacriﬁce their ideals for the
sake of the whole system. It is a trade oﬀ and the result does not necessarily have to be
benign. It just has to be agreed.”
</p><!--l. 25310--><p class="indent" >  “So that&#x2019;s the catch?”
</p><!--l. 25312--><p class="indent" >  “The catch is that people do not accept defeat anymore, because they can pretty
much do as they please. We all have the tools and the means to do essentially as we
like today. That makes it very diﬃcult to maintain the traditional institutions of
government. It makes it hard to police rules that are openly considered irrelevant by a
population without a sense of civic duty.”
</p><!--l. 25319--><p class="indent" >  Jonas is nodding. “Money pulls the strings these days,” he says. “It has nothing to
do with democracy. You just need money. The only voting democracy we have is in
kids&#x2019; mobile polls and pop contests.”
</p><!--l. 25324--><p class="indent" >  “Some people have said that the real threat is global capitalism. That is the West&#x2019;s
form of terrorism. It&#x2019;s not terrorism, of course, but it is a kind of a virus against
democracy, in the real sense.”
</p><!--l. 25328--><p class="indent" >  “Apes used to groom one another and that is how a clan was bound. Now we
exchange money. It&#x2019;s just virtual grooming. Little gluons that bind society
together.”
</p><!--l. 25332--><p class="indent" >  Jonas seems to be enjoying this peculiarly abstract discussion. Vibe thinks it is all
just a bit odd, here in the middle of town.
</p><!--l. 25335--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Hello! I&#x2019;m here. . .</span>.
</p><!--l. 25337--><p class="indent" >  “Nature abhors democracy,” Bishop adds. “It is ineﬃcient — except in very special
conditions.”
</p><!--l. 25340--><p class="indent" >  “So I don&#x2019;t get it. Where is this going?” Vibe says, silencing incoming on her
mobile. “Where do we come into this?”
</p><!--l. 25343--><p class="indent" >  “You know about controlling the behaviour of autonomous agents.”

</p><!--l. 25345--><p class="indent" >  “Robots, maybe. . . Come on, let&#x2019;s go up here.”
</p><!--l. 25347--><p class="indent" >  Jonas leads them into an avenue that rises even more steeply through the residential
functionalism, towards some shops.
</p><!--l. 25350--><p class="indent" >  Bishop stops for a moment, panting at the exertion of walking up the steep
incline.
</p><!--l. 25353--><p class="indent" >  “There are basic principles . . . involved . . . that can be transferred. And besides. .
.we are also using robots: virtual robots . . . in game playing.”
</p><!--l. 25356--><p class="indent" >  “What for?”
</p><!--l. 25358--><p class="indent" >  He takes several breaths. “For encouraging people . . . to obey the law, . . . and have
a sense . . . of civic duty.”
</p><!--l. 25361--><p class="indent" >  “People can be bought or manipulated.”
</p><!--l. 25364--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, they can. We can. Or you can brainwash them.”
</p><!--l. 25366--><p class="indent" >  “<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Brainwash them?</span>” Vibe&#x2019;s exclamation seems to be suggesting that they have lost
their marbles completely.
</p><!--l. 25369--><p class="indent" >  “If you can make everyone agree by brain-washing them from an early enough age,
how can you say that it is wrong? How do you know that you are not already
brainwashed? Maybe its a good thing. You have agreement, after all. And it&#x2019;s a legal
game move in the democratic process.”
</p><!--l. 25375--><p class="indent" >  “But that&#x2019;s manipulation.”
</p><!--l. 25377--><p class="indent" >  He nods. “Sure. Point to a country or society where this has not happened. What
society does not preach some form of moral righteousness? Do you mind if we stop
here a moment?”
</p><!--l. 25381--><p class="indent" >  She shrugs.
</p><!--l. 25383--><p class="indent" >  Jonas adds: “Politics used to assume individual maturity and deal with objective
issues of society&#x2019;s development and the governance of popular intellect. Now it is full
steam ahead in talking directly to people&#x2019;s emotional brains, manipulating their
subjective beliefs and views of the world. It&#x2019;s telling us how to think and
feel.”
</p><!--l. 25389--><p class="indent" >  “And that mollycoddling is needed precisely because we are all getting more
selﬁsh.”
</p><!--l. 25392--><p class="indent" >  “You address individual subjectivity because people are no longer a uniform ideal
gas. It has to be personal, or they don&#x2019;t care.”
</p><!--l. 25395--><p class="indent" >  They pause to catch their breath. Sara texts a message to someone furiously and
refocuses. She is not fully certain that she understands what she is doing here. Jonas
does not seem disturbed or surprised by the conversation, rather he seems distant, as if
thinking about something else.
</p><!--l. 25401--><p class="indent" >  “So,” Bishop concludes, as if turning a page, after his moment. “All of this brings
us to the virtual reality games. They have become the new battleground for
indoctrination. It&#x2019;s about the competition of doctrines in a group: who is most eﬃcient
at tapping into people&#x2019;s instincts and needs.”
</p><!--l. 25407--><p class="indent" >  “The survival of the ﬁttest doctrine?”
</p><!--l. 25409--><p class="indent" >  “Partly. Well. There are many degrees of freedom here. Money plays a role
too—social currency. I shouldn&#x2019;t get these things muddled.”

</p><!--l. 25412--><p class="indent" >  “The survival of the richest.”
</p><!--l. 25414--><p class="indent" >  “For an idea or a doctrine to take hold, it just has to be robust and sustainable
amongst the forces and processes that move society. It does not have to be right or
wrong, it only needs to have support in the processes of the day. That is why we are
able to pass laws about all kinds of things that seem immoral.”
</p><!--l. 25420--><p class="indent" >  Jonas nods. “Like patenting genes. Drug companies have the power, using the
money they command, to distort the balance of opinion in their favour by paying for
huge indoctrination campaigns.”
</p><!--l. 25424--><p class="indent" >  “This has become par for the course,” Bishop agrees. “There is no one who is not
using these techniques today. Not even us.”
</p><!--l. 25427--><p class="indent" >  Bishop talks directly to Vibe. “I have been looking you up. Do you know how rare
it is to ﬁnd someone with an education like yours? Someone close by who has actually
studied similar problems? You could be invaluable to us, with your knowledge of the
techniques. Imagine applying your knowledge to social engineering instead of
robotics.”
</p><!--l. 25433--><p class="indent" >  Sara is not sure whether she feels a little taller, because he clearly respects her, or a
little freaked out, because he is a weirdo who has her in his sights.
</p><!--l. 25437--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m . . . ﬂattened,” she says.
</p><!--l. 25439--><p class="indent" >  They continue on up the hill to the small shopping street, and pause at the
crossroads. With busses thundering past, the conversation falls to Jonas and Bishop.
Cannot really hear what they are saying. She is left to mull over the idea of working
with a megalomaniac with a social justice complex, or signing on to social security
and considering prostitution as a career.
</p><!--l. 25446--><p class="indent" >  She feels like a fraud. How could she, of all the unlikely souls, possible do this
job—whatever it is he is even asking her to do. It seems totally weird and more than a
little immoral. After everything that has happened to her in the past couple of weeks,
there must be some simpler option than this?
</p><!--l. 25453--><p class="indent" >  “Let&#x2019;s go in here,” Jonas says, pointing to a coﬀee shop with plenty of
room. “I&#x2019;m going to have to leave pretty soon, I fear. but you should keep on
talking.”
</p><!--l. 25457--><p class="indent" >  They sit around a table and can look one another in the eyes for the ﬁrst time. The
sounds of the road fades into the background.
</p><!--l. 25460--><p class="indent" >  “The more you look at society,” Bishop rants, “the more you realize that it is not
what you think it is.”
</p><!--l. 25463--><p class="indent" >  “Of course,” Jonas agrees, understanding his point, or at least believing that he
does.
</p><!--l. 25466--><p class="indent" >  “We play these elaborate charades that we make up to pretend we are satisﬁed.
They conﬁrm our visions of what is good and right. You remember as a child how you
used to make believe? You pretend to play out scenarios? Well you don&#x2019;t stop as an
adult. You just think you do.”
</p><!--l. 25472--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">What am I doing here?</span>
</p><!--l. 25474--><p class="indent" >  “All right. So civilization is a deception according to you?” Sara drones, in a funk.
“We have society, politics, commerce. Isn&#x2019;t that civilization?” She recalls the game of

civilization and its basic milestones.
</p><!--l. 25479--><p class="indent" >  “Well, it sort of works, so it is not a deception. But only in terms of deeds.”
</p><!--l. 25482--><p class="indent" >  “Hello?”
</p><!--l. 25484--><p class="indent" >  He smiles vaguely, pursing his lips. “Everyone has their own delusions and it
is not just some conspiracy, as some people think. They really believe in
these delusions. That is the point. We are all out there, trying to control the
world, but the world is really controlling us to a far greater extent and we just
fantasize our involvement in it. But then you must have seen all of this in
your ﬁeld? I mean, all of these emergent phenomena in biology are cases in
point.”
</p><!--l. 25493--><p class="indent" >  “Is it worth saving?” Jonas sighs.
</p><!--l. 25495--><p class="indent" >  Vibe cuts in with some searing logic that raises their eyebrows. “If you are a purist,
and society cannot be protected by legitimate, authorized means, then you can make
the argument that it does not deserve to exist. It is doomed to failure. Stability will
surely be lost to competing opportunism.”
</p><!--l. 25501--><p class="indent" >  Bishop laughs in appreciation. “Yes!”
</p><!--l. 25503--><p class="indent" >  “It wobbles.”
</p><!--l. 25505--><p class="indent" >  “It rocks and capsizes! So you need a police force to balance the boat. Mobsters
have become sophisticated now. They are providing all kinds of signals of
their own. Business and religion are in there too, if you care to distinguish
them.”
</p><!--l. 25510--><p class="indent" >  “And for the good news?”
</p><!--l. 25512--><p class="indent" >  “The good news is that all of the money that we were forced into spending on
anti-terrorism measures, to appease the United States, in the early years of
this century, is now proving to be a good investment for helping us with the
gangs.”
</p><!--l. 25517--><p class="indent" >  “Computer tools?”
</p><!--l. 25519--><p class="indent" >  “Information is power. Even the simplest-minded form of gang has a structure that
is based on relationships and interactions. It is all networking. The tools we
have developed to study networks have allowed us to see connections and
important clues that we might never have understood. You have a network model,
tied to a database and then you perform correlations. And then there is the
VR.”
</p><!--l. 25526--><p class="indent" >  “Gaming technology?”
</p><!--l. 25528--><p class="indent" >  “Exactly. They have masted quite diﬀerent skills: they don&#x2019;t analyze the present,
they create the present in incredible detail.”
</p><!--l. 25531--><p class="indent" >  “And people think they can use it to control us?”
</p><!--l. 25533--><p class="indent" >  “We are more gullible than ever before,” Bishop says seriously. “It&#x2019;s no
joke.”
</p><!--l. 25536--><p class="indent" >  Sara nods. “I can go along with that. . .”
</p><!--l. 25538--><p class="indent" >  “You might think it sounds like a bad conspiracy theory, but it is just the day to day
mechanics of marketing, essentially. And it is getting easier. People are not as critical
of what they hear as they used to be. Take the example of you two. The mob, or some

vigilante group, whatever, you see, misunderstood something about your work. They
found a title on the web.”
</p><!--l. 25545--><p class="indent" >  “My old thesis?”
</p><!--l. 25547--><p class="indent" >  “Yes - it has all the right words for an uneducated mind to attract attention. We
believe that they are looking for you because they are trying to master these
techniques for themselves. Lucky for us, people don&#x2019;t understand much of what they
read anymore. We have already apprehended two men who were sent to possibly
kidnap you.”
</p><!--l. 25553--><p class="indent" >  “And who is it you want to inﬂuence, Mr. Bishop?” Jonas asks, entirely
dispassionately.
</p><!--l. 25556--><p class="indent" >  “Everyone. I want to make sure that there is a fair ﬁght in the information, so that
no one can usurp our lives. Some people think that means you have to leave things
alone. But they forget that every living system needs maintenance to keep it looking
good.”
</p><!--l. 25561--><p class="indent" >  A low buzz emanates from Jonas&#x2019;s wrist. “Excuse me,” he says. He gets up and
walks away to speak in private.
</p><!--l. 25564--><p class="indent" >  Bishop mutters on philosophically. “To have a working society, you need to have a
whole chain of self-fortifying things in place. It&#x2019;s so fragile.”
</p><!--l. 25567--><p class="indent" >  Vibe watches Jonas, looking somewhat agitated and feels a little sorry for him.
Something is going on today for him. Perhaps his life is not as cushy as she has
assumed.
</p><!--l. 25571--><p class="indent" >  “So you think it&#x2019;s all breaking up?”
</p><!--l. 25573--><p class="indent" >  “Look around! Who has respect for the law? If people don&#x2019;t basically agree
with the justness of a law, they will not enforce it themselves, and then the
police can&#x2019;t do anything but erode their own authority by trying to enforce
it.”
</p><!--l. 25578--><p class="indent" >  “We take more liberties than before? We&#x2019;re more liberal. Is that the same
thing?”
</p><!--l. 25581--><p class="indent" >  “We have to respect the idea of abstaining from certain behaviours for the good of
others. We have to obey the laws we create. We must respect the people who make
and enforce the law, and they also have to respect it themselves. Even that isn&#x2019;t easy.
We have a huge problem in some areas with police thinking that they are
above the rest of society and that the law basically does not apply to them
– they can park their cars in a no-stopping street. That only leads to other
people imitating their lawlessness and turning tiny transgressions into large
ones.”
</p><!--l. 25593--><p class="indent" >  She nods. “I could tell you a story about rural policing.”
</p><!--l. 25595--><p class="indent" >  “All of this is failing, Sara. Our work is about ﬁghting that reversal by reminding
people of the values that society is based on. It is a new kind of meta-policing if you
like.”
</p><!--l. 25599--><p class="indent" >  Jonas interrupts.
</p><!--l. 25601--><p class="indent" >  “Look, I apologise, but I&#x2019;m going to have to go back. Maybe you can keep me
informed. It sounds as though Sara can help you with what you need. And I am happy

to support this. This is very interesting.”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 25605--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 25606--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 25609--><p class="indent" >  The café is quiet at this time of day. Oil paintings, dark and brooding, ﬁll the walls
of room, between its large windows; the imagery is somewhere between fascinating
and disturbing.
</p><!--l. 25613--><p class="indent" >  “Who&#x2019;s the artist?” she asks.
</p><!--l. 25615--><p class="indent" >  “Oh.” He laughs absently. “I&#x2019;m not sure.”
</p><!--l. 25617--><p class="indent" >  “These are good. A bit creepy.”
</p><!--l. 25619--><p class="indent" >  “Can I get you something warm to drink?”
</p><!--l. 25621--><p class="indent" >  “Cocoa,” she says.
</p><!--l. 25623--><p class="indent" >  He goes to the counter and comes back some moments later.
</p><!--l. 25625--><p class="indent" >  “So, how was your trip to Jotunheimen. Was it holiday?”
</p><!--l. 25627--><p class="indent" >  She makes an involuntary snort and shakes her head as she sticks her nose into the
cream on top of the cocoa.
</p><!--l. 25630--><p class="indent" >  “It was ﬁeld work for my thesis. But then my project was cancelled by
a bunch of . . . by the changes in priorities.” She makes inverted commas
with her ﬁngers. “So I ﬁnd myself up shit creek without a paddle, pardon my
French.”
</p><!--l. 25635--><p class="indent" >  “Well, I can help you with a job, if I can persuade you.”
</p><!--l. 25637--><p class="indent" >  “I suppose it&#x2019;s better than the alternatives for now.”
</p><!--l. 25639--><p class="indent" >  Bishop studies her. “You are young,” he observes. “I have a group working on this.
They&#x2019;re young too, and I want you to meet them. We are an odd bunch of students and
lost academics, combined with programmers working in the gaming industry and
computer engineers with special skills. I would like to have your help. You could
bridge a communication gap for me, and if you like it, I would like to keep
you.”
</p><!--l. 25647--><p class="indent" >  Vibe smiles.
</p><!--l. 25649--><p class="indent" >  “So how do you get to do all of this stuﬀ? Why doesn&#x2019;t someone stop
you?”
</p><!--l. 25652--><p class="indent" >  “Our main cover is peoples&#x2019; lack of interest in law enforcement as an institution.
The only time they really think about us is when we are interfering in their personal
wishes.”
</p><!--l. 25656--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t know too many people with a respect for the police.”
</p><!--l. 25658--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s a global phenomenon.”
</p><!--l. 25660--><p class="indent" >  “But you have to keep slugging away at it? I guess we&#x2019;d all be pretty eﬀed oﬀ if the
police didn&#x2019;t do their job.”
</p><!--l. 25663--><p class="indent" >  He smiles appreciatively. “The maintenance theorem says that we cannot really
control anything. At best we can fool ourselves by keeping a system in a rough

balance over time. But we are never precisely in control. We only moderate the
balance of change so that it never strays too far from what we want.” He pauses to take
a sip of his cocoa. “This game that people are playing in the VR. It is designed to do
the same. It is huge. It needs to be self-maintaining because it would cost far
too much to run it hands on. There are many automatic systems that tweak
it.”
</p><!--l. 25673--><p class="indent" >  “What&#x2019;s your approach?”
</p><!--l. 25675--><p class="indent" >  “The purpose of the game is to serve the needs of the world&#x2019;s largest trans-global
companies. They are now suﬀering the from the very lack of law and order that their
own ideas have resulted in. There are many ways in which it does that. It is designed
to brainwash people with Western values, to keep them interested in warfare and
aggression, in case America needs to go to war. It&#x2019;s designed to make people respect
the authority of government. It is designed in a framework that makes all of this
manipulation quite possible.”
</p><!--l. 25686--><p class="indent" >  “Captive audience.”
</p><!--l. 25688--><p class="indent" >  “Our approach is to deﬂect other peoples&#x2019; bad messages and to support our own
message of obeying the law and thinking about your neighbour.”
</p><!--l. 25691--><p class="indent" >  “Sounds hard.”
</p><!--l. 25693--><p class="indent" >  “It is, and we have not been very good at it, but now we have a secret weapon, so to
speak. Two, if we count you.”
</p><!--l. 25696--><p class="indent" >  “Me?”
</p><!--l. 25698--><p class="indent" >  “Yes,” he chuckles. “I&#x2019;m sorry to be the one to break the bad news, but you have
fallen into a ﬂytrap. A honey pot. We have been watching your escapades on the game
for some time, learning from you.”
</p><!--l. 25703--><p class="indent" >  “Ehhh.” She laughs without humour. “You mean the back-door my friend showed
me?”
</p><!--l. 25706--><p class="indent" >  “You wish. It&#x2019;s one of the ways that we beneﬁt from the technology built in by the
government for modelling. What you have been doing in our honeypot is to introduce
a very powerful form of countermeasure. It looks like noise, but you are just one
person and you cannot possibly generate the amount of information needed to be
noise. But you have found some kind of pattern that is even more eﬀective than noise
at causing mixing, convection in the system. Instead of allowing it to fall into
its preferred conﬁguration, your activities have been preventing that from
happening.”
</p><!--l. 25717--><p class="indent" >  “My friend and I like to have a little fun with the palm heads.”
</p><!--l. 25719--><p class="indent" >  “Palm heads?”
</p><!--l. 25721--><p class="indent" >  “Gamers whose salutes are stuck on to their foreheads.”
</p><!--l. 25723--><p class="indent" >  Bishop laughs.
</p><!--l. 25725--><p class="indent" >  “You have them dancing to your merry tune.”
</p><!--l. 25727--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Like the pied piper. . .</span>
</p><!--l. 25729--><p class="indent" >  “I suppose it&#x2019;s something I learned from the VeiVeks. If you keep on applying
random strong signals to a diverse mass, you will just keep splitting it up. You&#x2019;ll never
unite them. It&#x2019;s the opposite of what they want. It&#x2019;s like saying to a group of people:

wear this fashion, no wear that fashion! Not everyone will hear all the messages, and
even if they do – not everyone <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">can </span>respond. Too many war cries just create
tension.”
</p><!--l. 25737--><p class="indent" >  “And applied to people, the same thing works.”
</p><!--l. 25739--><p class="indent" >  “People will change, yes, at some individual threshold that you can&#x2019;t really
predict. Just like the VeiVeks. So, if you want to be sure, you have to out-do
each message and you end up with an arms-race. That is not a recipe for
stability.”
</p><!--l. 25744--><p class="indent" >  Bishop nods. “That was my idea too. It&#x2019;s actually better to be hands-oﬀ. Let people
mix into stable masses – ﬁnd equilibrium by themselves. If you keep on tugging,
nothing ever settles down. They go unstable. The conclusion is that you have to makes
them all deaf so they can&#x2019;t listen.”
</p><!--l. 25750--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s not much of a thesis is it?” She feels tired now, and ready to get out of here.
She looks at her mobile as if to underline her impatience. “You mentioned a job,” she
says. “I&#x2019;m not sure what I could do.”
</p><!--l. 25755--><p class="indent" >  “If you can help us with your expertise, I can give you a position at the Police
University to get you a new thesis. You can develop your ideas for a slightly diﬀerent
purpose. ”
</p><!--l. 25759--><p class="indent" >  She looks at him with all the scepticism she can muster. I&#x2019;m a bitch, she thinks. But
why? Reﬂex? What is there to lose?
</p><!--l. 25762--><p class="indent" >  “Well, I can think about it. It seems a bit weird to me.”
</p><!--l. 25764--><p class="indent" >  “Good. So I&#x2019;d better think of my own propaganda campaign for you then.” He
sucks his cheeks for a minute. “If you came to meet the others in the group, I think
you&#x2019;d feel a little more comfortable right away.”
</p><!--l. 25768--><p class="indent" >  “Maybe.”
</p><!--l. 25770--><p class="indent" >  “Chin up!” he laughs. “You know, someone once said: ‘Minds are like parachutes.
They only work when they&#x2019;re open.”
</p><!--l. 25773--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s good,” she says glumly.
</p><!--l. 25779--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-49r45"></a>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-0"></a>
<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">45</span>
</p><!--l. 25781--><p class="indent" >  Cathy Kim is standing in the dry heat of the little ghost town in the Utah desert.
Outwardly, it appears abandoned: cheap hotels with broken doors and smashed toilet
bowls. Inwardly, it has been concealing a terrible secret.
</p><!--l. 25785--><p class="indent" >  The ghosts have been haunting here.
</p><!--l. 25787--><p class="indent" >  Until a few moments ago, this has been a centre of operations for one of
the worst religious fanatic groups. The place was just bursting with illegal
operations.
</p><!--l. 25791--><p class="indent" >  They are in home territory here. Not far away is a little town with only
eight hundred inhabitants but ﬁfty diﬀerent churches. Are they involved in
this?
</p><!--l. 25795--><p class="indent" >  No one was here, no human. But a single computer connected by parabolic antenna
to a network tap, was purring its operational readiness, handling coordinating
activities for lists of operatives.
</p><!--l. 25799--><p class="indent" >  How can so much chaos be so organized?
</p><!--l. 25801--><p class="indent" >  There are explosives here next to bibles. This is nothing more than a terrorist camp.
The blood-red rock of the surrounding desert seems to condone this stockpile of ﬁlth,
as if the blood of the enemy has been congealed into boulders and cliﬀs. There are
professional recruiting agencies operating out of this camp: preying on kids to break
into computer systems, recruiting hackers while persuading them to keep their
virginity. Lists of names and addresses on blocks of embedded memory. This will take
some time to analyze.
</p><!--l. 25811--><p class="indent" >  “Justice is a luxury some people have to ﬁght for.”
</p><!--l. 25814--><p class="indent" >  The baking heat makes her a little dizzy, or is it simply the impact of all
this?
</p><!--l. 25816--><p class="indent" >  She wants to get back into the air-conditioned safety of the car, and have the
oﬃcers take her back to civilization.
</p><!--l. 25819--><p class="indent" >  “You shouldn&#x2019;t be here, Ma&#x2019;am.”
</p><!--l. 25821--><p class="indent" >  Time to make Den deliver her from evil once and for all.

</p><!--l. 25827--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-50r46"></a>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-0"></a>
<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">46</span>
</p><!--l. 25830--><p class="indent" >  “So when are you coming back to the States?” Cathy Kim asks him cordially.
</p><!--l. 25832--><p class="indent" >  “You could come here?” Den deﬂects.
</p><!--l. 25834--><p class="indent" >  She barely shakes her head. “No, they won&#x2019;t let us travel. It is considered too
dangerous these days.”
</p><!--l. 25836--><p class="indent" >  “Well, it will be a while before I can justify actual travel,” he lies. “Too much to do
over here for our mutual friends.”
</p><!--l. 25839--><p class="indent" >  He remembers her tight sensual body and feels aroused, wishing that she
could be there with him at that moment; but in this situation there is also
something about her that seems small and merely self serving. There are
surely larger concerns to think about than his pact with her. Catalin Cortina,
whom Celia has brought to him, makes her seem irrelevant. Moreover, if
she is right, then Cathy is just an agent anyway, using him like the rest of
them.
</p><!--l. 25847--><p class="indent" >  “Heads up,” she says. “There&#x2019;s a storm brewing over the Christian radical groups
here. There&#x2019;s been a police ﬁnd, indicating some kind of activism and corruption. Had
any news from your government friends?”
</p><!--l. 25851--><p class="indent" >  He shakes his head, suppressing his immediate worry. “To be honest, I&#x2019;m a bit
freaked out by the religious overtones and the anti-European sentiment in some of the
material they sent me.”
</p><!--l. 25855--><p class="indent" >  She nods. “Saw that one coming.”
</p><!--l. 25857--><p class="indent" >  “We might have to turn down the job.”
</p><!--l. 25859--><p class="indent" >  “That could mean losing your position within the consortium.”
</p><!--l. 25861--><p class="indent" >  “I know, but the alternative might mean losing my colleagues&#x2019; blessing.”
</p><!--l. 25863--><p class="indent" >  “Your job.”
</p><!--l. 25865--><p class="indent" >  “I can&#x2019;t understand why they would turn on Europe of all places!”
</p><!--l. 25867--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s not all that surprising,” she insinuates.
</p><!--l. 25869--><p class="indent" >  “What do you mean?”
</p><!--l. 25871--><p class="indent" >  “Well, look at it from an American religious perspective. The clash of secular and

religious forces is a point of divergence between Europe and the United States. Here
in U.S., we&#x2019;ve always been a religious country. People don&#x2019;t think twice about it. Even
with the separation of church and state, people embrace religion without
question. This dichotomy is about power, and Europe would not accept a
religious leadership in the same way as Americans would. So, if you are in
favour of Christian power, you have to blame Europe for putting a spanner in
the works: France, Britain, even Catholic Italy and Spain these days. It is
easy to see why Europe&#x2019;s failure to act makes people over here see you as a
threat.”
</p><!--l. 25883--><p class="indent" >  “I hadn&#x2019;t thought about it like that,” he admits. “I thought people were more
concerned with bashing Islam than in beating one another over the head with their
own religion.”
</p><!--l. 25887--><p class="indent" >  “Check. Welcome to politics.”
</p><!--l. 25889--><p class="indent" >  Den nods. He&#x2019;s seen enough of it, now that you mention it. “So, how are you
getting on?” he asks her. “I&#x2019;m still investigating some leads.”
</p><!--l. 25892--><p class="indent" >  She pauses. “Well, I got it covered I guess. Looks like you are a deﬁnitely a
centrally important person in this. But there are others sneaking in from the
sides.”
</p><!--l. 25896--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Some anonymous Spanish beauties. . ., </span>he thinks.
</p><!--l. 25898--><p class="indent" >  Kim seems to toy with something, then decides to share. “And I think I&#x2019;ve
ﬁgured out what might be going on now,” she says. “If we&#x2019;re still helping each
other.”
</p><!--l. 25902--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 25904--><p class="indent" >  “Well, between you and me, there was a piece on the information feeds recently
about the ﬁnd out in the Utah desert. They uncovered an operation by Christian
fundamentalists to gain ﬁnancial control over the political parties.”
</p><!--l. 25909--><p class="indent" >  “Financial control?”
</p><!--l. 25911--><p class="indent" >  “Yes. The root of power.”
</p><!--l. 25913--><p class="indent" >  “Both parties or just one?”
</p><!--l. 25915--><p class="indent" >  “Both. You see, they have just one chance to pass a bill through the house
giving the church equal powers to government over the police and armed
forces.”
</p><!--l. 25919--><p class="indent" >  “What? You&#x2019;re . . . That&#x2019;s unbelievable. . .”
</p><!--l. 25921--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s been hushed up, for sure, but it seems quite certain to be put to the house with
partial home voting.”
</p><!--l. 25924--><p class="indent" >  “Meaning what?”
</p><!--l. 25926--><p class="indent" >  “That government and the people get to vote on it, at short notice.”
</p><!--l. 25928--><p class="indent" >  “And you think that&#x2019;s what they want me to help with? I&#x2019;m supposed to hand it to
them on a plate by prep&#x2019;ing people for the choice?”
</p><!--l. 25931--><p class="indent" >  “Sounds like that&#x2019;s the deal. That&#x2019;s what they will pay you for, in the end, if you
deliver. Look at this.” She sends him a picture that seems to have been taken from TV
or perhaps a billboard.

</p><!--l. 25935--><p class="indent" >  He looks at it and frowns in disbelief. Apparently, they have another advertising
consultant working with them too.
</p><!--l. 25938--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Anyone could make a killing with this</span>. At least in terms of money. If they take it, the
company would proﬁt and they would be guaranteed work for a long time to come.
But at what cost? Immortal souls. When advertising gets all kittens and puppies, you
know there is some major evil going on.
</p><!--l. 25944--><p class="indent" >  But, of all the things that ought to be occupying his mind, at this moment, all he
can think about is how he can persuade Ms Cortina that his intentions are
honourable.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 25948--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 25949--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 25952--><p class="indent" >  “The bill is not popular.”
</p><!--l. 25954--><p class="indent" >  “That is not an acceptable admission. The country is falling apart and we have to
stop it.”
</p><!--l. 25957--><p class="indent" >  “So we should centralize our power for the good of the nation – and our allies. But
the ﬁrst step is to get it through here.”
</p><!--l. 25960--><p class="indent" >  He winces at a spot of heart-burn.
</p><!--l. 25962--><p class="indent" >  “Well, senator,” a non-American voice says. “America seems to have been losing its
grip on its people for some time now.”
</p><!--l. 25965--><p class="indent" >  “And that is why we need this game. It could be our most signiﬁcant opportunity to
rein in the Internet for our purposes.”
</p><!--l. 25968--><p class="indent" >  “Demonstrations have been held in several large cities. If this unrest continues we
might have to bring in the military.”
</p><!--l. 25971--><p class="indent" >  “We need to dispel the attention.”
</p><!--l. 25973--><p class="indent" >  “We&#x2019;ll have to move the research departments – move them underground.”
</p><!--l. 25975--><p class="indent" >  “You mean close ranks? That could be dangerous.”
</p><!--l. 25977--><p class="indent" >  “We can trust the intelligence agencies, but who else?”
</p><!--l. 25979--><p class="indent" >  “The control has become too decentralized. It is my opinion that we need to rein in
the pieces under a central control again.”
</p><!--l. 25982--><p class="indent" >  A glum face says, “That is the paradox isn&#x2019;t it?”
</p><!--l. 25984--><p class="indent" >  “What do you mean.”
</p><!--l. 25986--><p class="indent" >  “We had to ask the help of the world, in order to get this done in the ﬁrst place.
Now we&#x2019;re pulling out because we feel that we have lost control.”
</p><!--l. 25990--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s Dubai all over again,” another says.
</p><!--l. 25992--><p class="indent" >  “Well that is what I have been saying all along,” says an exasperated voice. “You
tend to forget that the rest of the world thinks. Not everyone falls under the
banner of your sweet indoctrination programme. Not everyone&#x2019;s kids pledge
allegiance every goddamn day!” An odd look of ﬁerceness seems to come over
him.

</p><!--l. 25999--><p class="indent" >  Dean simply stares back coldly. He has heard this kind of criticism before
from the enemies of America, but never from within his inner circle of allies.
No one has ever dared to say such a thing in a closed session of the Lion&#x2019;s
Den.
</p><!--l. 26004--><p class="indent" >  “If that is what you think, then you cannot possibly help us to meet our ideals.
America will not tolerate dissent. We stand for freedom. If you cannot agree with that,
then you have no place among us.” His arm is hurting now. What is the matter with the
world today?
</p><!--l. 26009--><p class="indent" >  “ ‘Will not tolerate dissent?&#x2019;! ” he laughs. “My god, listen to yourself. Allegiance to
freedom. It is a basic contradiction. Are we really so goddamned brainwashed that we
can&#x2019;t see it?” The man seems to have had a drink or two and will probably regret this
outburst before long, Den thinks.
</p><!--l. 26015--><p class="indent" >  “Sir, you need to get a grip on yourself. This non-cooperative thinking in Europe is
the greatest danger to American policy.”
</p><!--l. 26018--><p class="indent" >  “You assume that the American way is the only way.”
</p><!--l. 26020--><p class="indent" >  “It is our way. This political competition that the E.U. is trying to foster is
self-destructive. It is undesirable and. . .”
</p><!--l. 26023--><p class="indent" >  He stabs: “You mean you might not get your way any more? You might not have
carte blanche, tabula rasa. . .”
</p><!--l. 26026--><p class="indent" >  “America has kept the peace for decades. Our foreign policy is second to
none.”
</p><!--l. 26029--><p class="indent" >  “Are you sure? Is not diversity of opinion our greatest asset?”
</p><!--l. 26031--><p class="indent" >  “Freedom is our greatest asset. That is what we stand for.”
</p><!--l. 26033--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">The senator has fallen for the biggest slogan of them all.</span>
</p><!--l. 26036--><p class="indent" >  “But not democracy. What you talking about is actual dictatorship.”
</p><!--l. 26038--><p class="indent" >  “Leadership, sir. Leadership is a tower: a domineering monument. Democracy,
what is that? It is sprawling ecological compost heap of opinions. The singular voice
of a strong leader will always stand out against the festering swamp of democratic
discussion. With democracy, we have to assume that there is enough gelatine in the
mix to allow it to set as the heat cools oﬀ. Otherwise, you are left with a shapeless
mess. We cannot have turmoil in America, and we cannot let the wishes of other
nations, or morally decrepit individuals inﬂuence our great institutions of church and
commerce.”
</p><!--l. 26048--><p class="indent" >  “The powers of government are being eroded by peoples&#x2019; greed for democracy and
autonomy. We have to show better judgement in the kinds of message we expose
our people to if we are going to preserve this lifestyle that we all take for
granted.”
</p><!--l. 26053--><p class="indent" >  “I am starting to think that America has ﬁnally gone oﬀ the deep end in its
delusions of righteousness. Taking money from the church purse now as
well as its people and accepting its authority. I&#x2019;ve never seen anything like
it.”
</p><!--l. 26058--><p class="indent" >  “The Iranian bonyads? They are like government controlled ‘charities&#x2019; that channel
the wealth of the nation into political causes.”

</p><!--l. 26062--><p class="indent" >  “Goddamn it,” mutters the dissenter. “I am so sorry to have to say this. You are all
goddamn mad!”
</p><!--l. 26065--><p class="indent" >  The senator rises. “Sir, you are no longer welcome here. I think you will need to
cool oﬀ for a while.” He beckons to the secret service agents standing nearby. They
move in.
</p><!--l. 26069--><p class="indent" >  The man turns pale and his voice takes on a stammer. “You can&#x2019;t hold me! That&#x2019;s
outrageous! This is a <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">game</span>, senator! Not goddamn nuclear war! Where is your sense
of perspective?”
</p><!--l. 26073--><p class="indent" >  The senator shakes his head. “You are wrong, sir. The future of America may well
be jeopardized. The world needs class systems and it needs superpowers. We cannot
aﬀord to relinquish our hold. We must simply keep it at any cost. That means that our
way is the true way. There is no room for devolution.”
</p><!--l. 26080--><p class="indent" >  He looks out of the window of the meeting room to the lawn and the tree, feeling
suddenly sick, tired and light headed. And his damned arm hurts.
</p><!--l. 26083--><p class="indent" >  “Mr. Morris, are you still there? I just bought twenty acres of rolling countryside
close to a skiing resort, with room to ride horses. Do you know what expenses
landscaping engineers want these days? They can practically smell us coming. I mean
us in the upper echelons of government. They think they can wind us around their
little ﬁngers, and do you know, goddammit, they can!”
</p><!--l. 26091--><p class="indent" >  Damned heart burn. All this excitement, all the eﬀort that has gone into this behind
the scenes. He&#x2019;ll be glad when it is all over.
</p><!--l. 26095--><p class="indent" >  Through the window he can see that a large demonstration is forming outside the
government oﬃces. He is feeling a bit dizzy.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 26098--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 26099--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 26103--><p class="indent" >  Den left Catalin Cortina feeling oddly oﬀ balance. Once again, he ﬁnds himself
thrown into uncertainty. He has made the decision to stay in San Sebastian for a few
days, while he thinks about their meeting. In spite of her practical dismissal, he does
not feel yet ready to be written oﬀ.
</p><!--l. 26109--><p class="indent" >  San Sebastian is an agreeable location for thinking. There are bars here where he
can hang out, places to go to enjoy himself and think. He has seen one place where the
women seemed to be just waiting for someone to whisk them oﬀ their feet. But
something was broken in him last night.
</p><!--l. 26115--><p class="indent" >  It was her.
</p><!--l. 26117--><p class="indent" >  She changed him, his view, not merely of his work, but of himself. He thought he
was succeeding in his work; now he feels like a loser.
</p><!--l. 26120--><p class="indent" >  Suddenly, he feels the precariousness of his situation. He is clinging on to his
obligations more by luck than by judgement. It is something like the sensation of
skiing down a black run, in the Alps, at full speed, barely winging it, almost ﬂying oﬀ

into oblivion at each irregularity in the terrain, legs burning and shaking with the
eﬀort of standing up to the barrage of gravitational anomalies. This is not being in
charge.
</p><!--l. 26128--><p class="indent" >  He has to admit that she was good. She is an expert manipulator. She has
transformed his feeling of serendipitous triumph into one of minor unworthiness. She
agreed to see him at his request, but rather than convincing her of his own value, she
has turned the tables on him. He was putty in her hands.
</p><!--l. 26134--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">She is someone to look up to, no doubt about that.</span>
</p><!--l. 26136--><p class="indent" >  Den dials himself into the company network over a secure channel and sets up the
pre-arranged meeting. After a short delay, the others are in place and they regard one
another in the virtual meeting room.
</p><!--l. 26140--><p class="indent" >  “Change of plans,” he announces. “We need to discuss a new idea that has been
presented to me, which is something we need to hear. I&#x2019;m sending you the sketch
here.”
</p><!--l. 26144--><p class="indent" >  “I brought in a couple of analysts from downstairs,” a familiar voice says.
</p><!--l. 26146--><p class="indent" >  “This is Joost Langendijk and Carol Ann, our American expert.”
</p><!--l. 26149--><p class="indent" >  Kylie interrupts. “Before we start, everyone, news ﬂash! There is a rumour on the
channels that Senator Dean has died of a heart-attack.”
</p><!--l. 26153--><p class="indent" >  “Wow.”
</p><!--l. 26155--><p class="indent" >  “News.”
</p><!--l. 26157--><p class="indent" >  “Doesn&#x2019;t that potentially change the whole matter?”
</p><!--l. 26159--><p class="indent" >  “If that is true, it could mean that the game consortium would be opened
up to public inspection. The house is just waiting for a chance to bypass
him.”
</p><!--l. 26163--><p class="indent" >  “So what about the Senator?”
</p><!--l. 26165--><p class="indent" >  “We need to make sure he&#x2019;s really dead.”
</p><!--l. 26167--><p class="indent" >  “Give me a gun, I&#x2019;ll take care of it,” Kylie says.
</p><!--l. 26170--><p class="indent" >  Den ﬁnds himself conﬂicted. “We should play neutrally for now,” he says. “Until
we can assess what is going on.”
</p><!--l. 26173--><p class="indent" >  “The way to make this work is to let the others do the work. Let them mount their
counter-attack. Let the competitor embarrass themselves or screw up. If they harm
themselves, then we don&#x2019;t have to do it for them.”
</p><!--l. 26177--><p class="indent" >  “Right. With the failing billboards, this is the best approach. If we try to put in more
stuﬀ, it will just self-destruct and no one wins.”
</p><!--l. 26180--><p class="indent" >  “We could release a rumour that we are going to act soon, and provoke them to act
ﬁrst.”
</p><!--l. 26183--><p class="indent" >  “We can move the campaign out of the game.”
</p><!--l. 26185--><p class="indent" >  “Back into the real world? Interesting. . .”
</p><!--l. 26187--><p class="indent" >  “Suppose Interpol were to raid their oﬃces about now, and found some evidence
that allowed them to bring charges?”
</p><!--l. 26190--><p class="indent" >  “That would start a media frenzy just like the one after the Time article.”
</p><!--l. 26192--><p class="indent" >  “It could set them back months or years.”

</p><!--l. 26194--><p class="indent" >  “It would serve two purposes. It would point the ﬁnger back at them and it would
make the forces of law and order look legitimate again.”
</p><!--l. 26197--><p class="indent" >  “Let&#x2019;s put this into a model.”
</p><!--l. 26199--><p class="indent" >  “Eh, boss, we might have to delay on that.”
</p><!--l. 26201--><p class="indent" >  “Why?”
</p><!--l. 26203--><p class="indent" >  “We&#x2019;ve been having a little license trouble with our software. I&#x2019;m not sure what the
problem is.”
</p><!--l. 26206--><p class="indent" >  “Licenses?”
</p><!--l. 26208--><p class="indent" >  He nods.
</p><!--l. 26210--><p class="indent" >  “Well that must be ﬁxable.”
</p><!--l. 26212--><p class="indent" >  “I suppose so. But it takes a little time.”
</p><!--l. 26214--><p class="indent" >  Den groans. “It used to be that you could just use something you bought. How
long?”
</p><!--l. 26216--><p class="indent" >  “They are not licenses any more. They are liabilities.”
</p><!--l. 26218--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t know. I&#x2019;ve applied for renewal.”
</p><!--l. 26220--><p class="indent" >  “Another illegal form of taxation from the corporate empires,” Kylie adds.
</p><!--l. 26223--><p class="indent" >  “Kyl!”
</p><!--l. 26225--><p class="indent" >  Raj&#x2019;s avatar smiles. “At least food isn&#x2019;t licensed yet.”
</p><!--l. 26227--><p class="indent" >  “One step away, my friend. One step away.”
</p><!--l. 26229--><p class="indent" >  “How long?” Den asks.
</p><!--l. 26231--><p class="indent" >  “Let&#x2019;s say a day.”
</p><!--l. 26233--><p class="indent" >  “A day.”
</p><!--l. 26235--><p class="indent" >  ”Hey, guys. Scenario. You buy food for a dinner party and then have to
force each of your guests to pay the same amount that you paid for the food,
because it is licensed to the manufacturer, otherwise the food will not release its
nutrients.”
</p><!--l. 26240--><p class="indent" >  “Might be technically possible,” says Langendijk. “Genetically modiﬁed food that
can&#x2019;t be broken down without a certain enzyme. Then sell the enzyme individually to
generate extra revenue.”
</p><!--l. 26245--><p class="indent" >  They are laughing, while Den is thinking of something else entirely.
</p><!--l. 26247--><p class="indent" >  “All right, let&#x2019;s stick to the point.”
</p><!--l. 26249--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t think it&#x2019;s very funny at all.”
</p><!--l. 26251--><p class="indent" >  “Okay, who wants to ﬂip for food?”
</p><!--l. 26253--><p class="indent" >  “Raj?”
</p><!--l. 26255--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;ll go.”
</p><!--l. 26257--><p class="indent" >  “Remember to ﬂip on the way.”
</p><!--l. 26259--><p class="indent" >  “Bring sandwiches and sparkling water. The one in the fancy bottle. We might be
working late!”
</p><!--l. 26272--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-51r47"></a>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-0"></a>
<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">47</span>
</p><!--l. 26275--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Thump.</span>
</p><!--l. 26277--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Scrape.</span>
</p><!--l. 26279--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Bang bang bang. Bang bang.</span>
</p><!--l. 26281--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Thump.</span>
</p><!--l. 26283--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Jesus wept! It is eleven o&#x2019;clock at night!</span>
</p><!--l. 26285--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Bang bang bang bang bang bang.</span>
</p><!--l. 26287--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">When a child, your parents told you that the gentle sound of thunder was just fairies</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">moving house. Now, there are elephants moving in upstairs.</span>
</p><!--l. 26291--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Scrape. Scrape.</span>
</p><!--l. 26293--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">What </span>is <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">that?</span>
</p><!--l. 26295--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Scrape.</span>
</p><!--l. 26297--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Thump. Laughter.</span>
</p><!--l. 26299--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">How could any reasonable human being, be so goddamned insensitive as to</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">hammer nails into the goddamned wall, in this concrete goddamned box at 11:00</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">p.m,, 23:00 hours, in the goddamned evening?</span>
</p><!--l. 26303--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Bang BANG.</span>
</p><!--l. 26305--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Don&#x2019;t they know that people have to sleep?</span>
</p><!--l. 26307--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Have to work?</span>
</p><!--l. 26309--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">This apartment box does not know its neighbours, does not fraternize with the other</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">life-forms that use the stairwell. There is no shared toilet. If you meet someone at the</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">launderette, just ignore them.</span>
</p><!--l. 26313--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">From your box, you cannot tell where the sound is coming from. Contact sound</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">reverberates, in this rabbit-hutch, like Morse code through a submarine..</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">You feel like a ship in a bottle that collided with its fog horn. You hate your</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">neighbours for their insensitivity, but you it never occurs to you to think about their</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">needs.</span>
</p><!--l. 26319--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">To hell with them. You are never likely to meet them anyway.</span>
</p><!--l. 26325--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-52r48"></a>
<a 
