<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">48</span>
</p><!--l. 26329--><p class="indent" >  One has to admit, there is a certain austerity to it all. Someone&#x2019;s hard graft and
industrial ambition yet clings onto the present in these old brick-hulled trading
vessels. They seem like outcast elders of the global village: buildings that cry out their
dereliction and alienation. They can be tolerated, but not revered by the city of
today.
</p><!--l. 26336--><p class="indent" >  Shuttered warehouses, ﬁlled with prosperous memories, disused or adapted to
fringe life: they have all been rejected from the city&#x2019;s mainstream dreams.
The bricks recall a time when buildings were meticulously stacked, piece
by piece, not injection-molded into computer generated spaces. Rows of
individual units worked together here, in harmony, to create a functional and
pleasing pattern. Unfortunately, there is no time for such rituals in the modern
world.
</p><!--l. 26344--><p class="indent" >  But there is no doubt about it: this is construction from an age that tolerated texture
and variety. Every brick does not have to be identical. That is surely appropriate,
under the circumstances. It seems to say something about the city&#x2019;s policy. Where
is this rugged art in the brushed aluminium and glass buildings of today?
Where is the willingness toward cultural diversity, embracing the foibles of
nature&#x2019;s own materials? Where are the open arms embracing society&#x2019;s minor
tributaries?
</p><!--l. 26353--><p class="indent" >  Three ﬁgures descend the incline towards this riverside gallery of twisted past.
Over the rickety wooden bridge that crosses the river, burrowing through
unkempt trees, held in check by wrought iron railings. Rats scuttle near the
water.
</p><!--l. 26358--><p class="indent" >  The arched holes, where windows once were, are now boarded up, mostly. Imagine
the once hot, orange light of industry in these buildings: a crucible of molten iron
lighting up the arches with its promise of wealth and purpose.
</p><!--l. 26363--><p class="indent" >  Today the bricks are painted over, ﬁrst with black, prima facie canvas and
then with luminous pop art eﬃgies. These buildings are ﬁt only for troubled

youths and eccentric artists. This is not the slick polish of commerce and
orthodoxy.
</p><!--l. 26368--><p class="indent" >  Joseph&#x2019;s centre lies in this outcast realm, rehabilitating disenfranchised youth from
their self-imposed rejection. The buildings seem like a ﬁtting place to locate the
centre. Could some of this nobility rub oﬀ on the city&#x2019;s new squatters? The people of
that past were more responsible, more consumed of the necessities of their survival
than in imagined disputes and conﬂicts. This is a place to learn about the meaning of
building one&#x2019;s legacy, and abandoning whimsical destruction born out of the boredom
and absent hope of today.
</p><!--l. 26377--><p class="indent" >  What happened to that age? Where did it go? Should we be glad that no one has to
struggle for their existence anymore?
</p><!--l. 26380--><p class="indent" >  The visitors are wearing the suits of the present. They look out of place
here, Joe thinks. They are church representatives: lawyers. They come with
money in the form of glad tidings. They are coming to buy this centre. They
want to run it, to change it. They have brought their establishment with them.
One can almost taste the sour ﬂaw of reasoning, but that is not his concern.
There are no spires here. This is not where people reach out to God above.
This is where God&#x2019;s agents lurk in the shadows to capture what souls they
can.
</p><!--l. 26390--><p class="indent" >  “Our programme takes the kids who have become caught up in crime,” he will tell
them. “we get kids who have come straight from prison.”
</p><!--l. 26393--><p class="indent" >  “The Get Smart programme seems like a success. We would hope to extend it, to
bring a more Christian message to these kids,” they will reply.
</p><!--l. 26396--><p class="indent" >  Is this what he wants? Is this what these kids need? What they understand is the
currency of violence. Paying back. There is an unwritten rule of the street: people sort
out their own problems. It&#x2019;s tribal.
</p><!--l. 26401--><p class="indent" >  What should he tell them? “The increasing willingness to use weapons to solve any
dispute is their sickness. For a lot of them, their horizons simply don&#x2019;t extend any
further than their own town district. A lot of disputes start just because an outsider
strays into their territory. These kids have been picking up weapons to solve their
problems since they were eleven or twelve.”
</p><!--l. 26409--><p class="indent" >  Erland over there was convicted for grievous bodily harm. The victim was left
permanently brain-damaged for the price of a piece of dope. There is a picture here to
remind him of the consequences of his actions. All for the sake of enhancing his
reputation on the street. Respect, so they say.
</p><!--l. 26415--><p class="indent" >  This has been a place to study modern city tribalism, to learn about it and to
understand its origins. What will it become now? Will they simply try to paint over
the oﬀending surface with evangelical rituals? It might appeal to the aging wealthy
right, but it is no answer to the problem. Just because someone is singing a happy
song, it does not mean that they are well-adjusted.
</p><!--l. 26422--><p class="indent" >  Joe got involved in this programme out of his own conviction about Christian
values. He does not recall the part of the bible where it talks about brainwashing. If
the money they were supposed to get from Jonas was forthcoming, then they could

turn these suits away and carry on as usual.
</p><!--l. 26428--><p class="indent" >  So they come, he thinks, to weed out the diseased element of society, not to heal it.
And it is not merely these violent kids—just go down to the city&#x2019;s edge. There are
plenty of strange, twisted people staggering or riding bikes, bent and distended by
drug-alcohol abuse, looking like nothing that nature would have allowed: is this also
part of what humanity is? Perhaps we are all simply insane in diﬀerent ways,
perversions of nature.
</p><!--l. 26436--><p class="indent" >  Jonas would have said: “You shouldn&#x2019;t even talk of disease. It&#x2019;s opportunism. It&#x2019;s
one organism that says, hey, if you&#x2019;re gonna be stupid, I&#x2019;ll exploit the opportunity,
thank you.”
</p><!--l. 26440--><p class="indent" >  We think in static terms. Change, aging and disease: you are standing still and other
stuﬀ is getting the better of you. A little hedge trimming and weeding is ﬁne, but
killing God&#x2019;s children goes beyond the reason.
</p><!--l. 26445--><p class="indent" >  “Maybe rap is a channel that can reach them,” he hears one of them say, as they
approach the entrance.
</p><!--l. 26449--><p class="indent" >  They arrive at the entrance and step into the simple open room of the old mill,
where Joe is waiting.
</p><!--l. 26452--><p class="indent" >  “Good morning, friend!”.
</p><!--l. 26454--><p class="indent" >  A row of bulging suits, beaming at him like expectant fruit, wearing mildew like a
bad aftershave. They know their trade. Eat &#x2019;em up and spit &#x2019;em out. Infect their
kernels and let them grow into diseased bushes.
</p><!--l. 26459--><p class="indent" >  There was surely a reason why God set the burning bush alight.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 26461--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 26462--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 26465--><p class="indent" >  On the other side of town, Jonas prostrates his soul before the symphony. The
music is a soundtrack to his troubled consternation, dark and full of the tremors of
gratuitous complaint. The day has ground him down to the point at which escape was
his only option. So here he must lie, resonating with the angst, until it absorbs the
energy from him.
</p><!--l. 26471--><p class="indent" >  A symphonic masterpiece assumes command of its audience, physically and
mentally, he thinks. He has chosen a tragic, wasteland of war-torn desolation to ease
his suﬀering. Its wintery introduction of frigid strings gradually descends
into a tar pit of inescapable, strung gravity. Deep grumbling friction fades
and is replaced by a sudden race of bows hacking rhythmically like axes
clearing a forest. Then, scintillating violins, herded by grave trombones, swell
like portents of a pending revelation. Military snare drums snap him to his
senses and the sardonic tones of the woodwind mock his optimism with their
grey corroded snoring. Life is this rusty pipe – don&#x2019;t expect any more from
it.

</p><!--l. 26483--><p class="indent" >  The music penetrates him, violates his defences, and works its cleansing magic as if
the experience of this tortured symphony is a deeply acting antibiotic for his personal
strife, using up all of his emotions.
</p><!--l. 26488--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Shostakovich knows this</span>, he thinks. He understands pain. It jars from his
music.
</p><!--l. 26491--><p class="indent" >  The eleventh lifts him, shows him pride of stature, then lowers him gently to
confront the hopelessness of his misery. Then just as the thought of continuing seems
impossible a life-giving rain of strings pours over him and washes away the dirt and
decrepitation of those treacherous woodwind vermin. Finally, thundering brass and
percussive artillery shake him to alertness and leave him spent at the climactic tidal
wave of the gong. The blast ﬂings him across the universe leaving him stranded and
alone.
</p><!--l. 26500--><p class="indent" >  For minutes he cannot move or speak. Then he begins to relate once again to the
objects around him: his body, his hands. He breaths and nods. The music is his
conﬁdante. He bears his soul to this music as he could to no mere human. Thank
goodness he has the solitude to enjoy it. Still, the complexity of the symphony is still
mere child&#x2019;s play compared to life itself.
</p><!--l. 26509--><p class="indent" >  He looks about his cocoon of familiarity, at the books that he has collected over the
years. They are familiar and comforting; they are friends.
</p><!--l. 26514--><p class="indent" >  It is not the notes of life&#x2019;s symphony but the spaces in between them that heal him.
His cocoon is a controlled environment in which he can exclude everything that he
does not want. The nourishing familiarity cleanses his frustrations. The friendly
books, old friends that don&#x2019;t answer back, don&#x2019;t complain or demand. His
ﬁlm collection, fantasy to transport him away as a passive spectator. His
music.
</p><!--l. 26522--><p class="indent" >  The doorbell warbles, making him jump up in panic. Jonas collects himself and
goes to pick up the door-phone.
</p><!--l. 26525--><p class="indent" >  “Jonas, it&#x2019;s Joe. Can I come up?”
</p><!--l. 26527--><p class="indent" >  “Joe?” He rubs his tired eyes. “Come in.”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 26529--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 26530--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 26533--><p class="indent" >  “They were like a couple of wasps, Jonas.” Relentlessly and mindlessly picking
away at other people&#x2019;s business and dirty garbage. “And they were standing there just
waiting to sting at the ﬁrst sign of fear. I fear <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">them </span>more than any of the kids at the
centre.”
</p><!--l. 26538--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t know what to say.”
</p><!--l. 26540--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s not your fault.”
</p><!--l. 26542--><p class="indent" >  “Are you sure? Maybe they heard about this business over funding. It could be my
fault for starting a media circus.”

</p><!--l. 26545--><p class="indent" >  “The council funds. . . Everything has been turned upside down.”
</p><!--l. 26548--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m sorry.”
</p><!--l. 26550--><p class="indent" >  “C&#x2019;est la guerre.”
</p><!--l. 26552--><p class="indent" >  “Funny you should put it like that. More whisky?”
</p><!--l. 26554--><p class="indent" >  He shakes his head. “I suppose I&#x2019;ll have to notify the other sponsors that we won&#x2019;t
be part of these larger city projects.”
</p><!--l. 26558--><p class="indent" >  “The European thing?”
</p><!--l. 26560--><p class="indent" >  “Get Smart, Save our Schools.”
</p><!--l. 26562--><p class="indent" >  “No kidding.”
</p><!--l. 26564--><p class="indent" >  “Thing that worries me is that some of the kids have no hope without us. People
don&#x2019;t take care of their own in these communities anymore. I&#x2019;m afraid of what could
happen when we are not running the centre.”
</p><!--l. 26569--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 26571--><p class="indent" >  “The kids are not all that well balanced, Jonas.”
</p><!--l. 26573--><p class="indent" >  “What might they do?”
</p><!--l. 26576--><p class="indent" >  Joe raises his eyebrows and tilts his head slightly.
</p><!--l. 26578--><p class="indent" >  “They come to us sometimes because they feel that they are lost, that no one cares
about them. But other times they have been given an ultimatum that they
cannot handle. They lack the social skills to resolve the crises they make for
themselves.”
</p><!--l. 26582--><p class="indent" >  “And the weak shall inherit the Earth.”
</p><!--l. 26584--><p class="indent" >  “Jonas, if you have never experienced the feeling they have of being utterly trapped
by circumstances—with no possible way out, then you have not contemplated
suicide.”
</p><!--l. 26588--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">In fact, I can relate to that</span>, Jonas thinks.
</p><!--l. 26590--><p class="indent" >  These past days, he has understood, for the ﬁrst time in his life, why someone might
consider it. You are just trundling along in life, mastering your job, making everybody
happy and then suddenly something happens that is utterly dangerous to that stability.
You go into a blind alley that seems like a good move, but you realize that it&#x2019;s a cliﬀ
top. There is no way back without hurting everyone who means something to you, and
there is no way forward because there are immovable obstacles in your way.
Perhaps you are faced with a choice: to kill your lover or your child. How do
you choose? You can&#x2019;t go forward. you can&#x2019;t go back. What other choice
is there but to reset your options and start over? Remove the centre of the
problem.
</p><!--l. 26602--><p class="indent" >  “Violence is often their language. It&#x2019;s a matter of desperation. They either have to
die slowly, where they stand, or jump and get it over with quickly. But if you take your
life, you know it will hurt the people you love and that makes you feel even worse.
Eventually the pain threshold increases to the point where you cannot bear it anymore
and you self-destruct.”
</p><!--l. 26609--><p class="indent" >  It seems like those old ﬁlms from the 60&#x2019;s where people used to talk computers to
death by giving them some logical contradiction. But where it the logic?
</p><!--l. 26613--><p class="indent" >  “I didn&#x2019;t mean to . . .”

</p><!--l. 26615--><p class="indent" >  “And all the Evangelical Lutheran Lawyers want is to buy a captive audience.”
</p><!--l. 26618--><p class="indent" >  Where indeed.
</p><!--l. 26620--><p class="indent" >  He thinks of Kaja, the times she calls and asks him to be there for her. And he
usually isn&#x2019;t. Is it by choice that he prioritizes work, or is there a greater
responsibility? Could she understand this at all?
</p><!--l. 26625--><p class="indent" >  Is anything important, if it is not about the two of them?
</p><!--l. 26627--><p class="indent" >  He looks at his pile of old music CDs. One for every bad mood. A pill for every
malady. They seem like old friends.
</p><!--l. 26630--><p class="indent" >  “I have never understood religious communities,” Jonas shakes from his his head.
“It all seems hostile to me. And yet sometimes the rigours of these dogmas have
inspired great beauty, great music.”
</p><!--l. 26635--><p class="indent" >  “The music of Bach, Chopin. . . Discipline is not a bad thing.”
</p><!--l. 26637--><p class="indent" >  “Alfred Schnittke&#x2019;s fourth symphony, a perfect discipline of tonal religious
bureaucracy. Discipline is okay, Unless it is used to suppress creativity.”
</p><!--l. 26641--><p class="indent" >  “Yes.”
</p><!--l. 26643--><p class="indent" >  “Did I tell you? The government has a goon squad now—auditors who check every
action we take. We have no freedom of expression anymore, not in this current
political climate.” They will be sending more of them tomorrow. They do not
need him any more. “Oh, Joe. There are times in our lives when it seems that
disaster just piles on disaster and everything seems beyond repair. Don&#x2019;t you
think?”
</p><!--l. 26650--><p class="indent" >  He frowns into a distant space and then inhales deeply as if recalling something
important. “I have to back out of these project commitments. Did you ever read about
S.O.S.? The organization that runs it?”
</p><!--l. 26655--><p class="indent" >  He recalls some papers in a folder. Jonas shrugs. “Rings a bell. I got sort of
side-tracked.”
</p><!--l. 26658--><p class="indent" >  “Save-Our-Schools. It&#x2019;s run by. . .well, never mind.”
</p><!--l. 26660--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t back out yet. Tell them you might be delayed. I haven&#x2019;t given up thinking
about this yet.”
</p><!--l. 26663--><p class="indent" >  “Is there anything you can do, if the government has already changed its
mind?”
</p><!--l. 26665--><p class="indent" >  “The government is not the people. There are still some advantages to our
predilection for these things.” He taps on his mobile. “Bureaucracy works both ways.
Tar pits might capture the wildlife, but they also stop the predators from reaching
them.”
</p><!--l. 26670--><p class="indent" >  Joe lifts his head, as if he is signalling incongruous pride above his ﬂaring nostrils.
“You gave me an idea, Jonas.”
</p><!--l. 26675--><p class="indent" >  “An idea? You know that&#x2019;s strictly against government policy now?”
</p><!--l. 26677--><p class="indent" >  “There might be hope for us yet.”
</p><!--l. 26679--><p class="indent" >  “Hope?”
</p><!--l. 26681--><p class="indent" >  He nods.
</p><!--l. 26683--><p class="indent" >  “For us.”
</p><!--l. 26685--><p class="indent" >  “For all of us.”

</p><!--l. 26687--><p class="indent" >  Jonas raises his glass. “Hope for us yet.”
</p><!--l. 26690--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-53r49"></a>
