 id="Q1-1-0"></a>
<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">49</span>
</p><!--l. 26695--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Mary is collecting and retaining. She has followed a lead from Milan to</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Copenhagen. She knows their key players, the principal components, the eigenvalue</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">centres, and she has a causal tree of probabilities to bring that cartel into Denny&#x2019;s</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">reach.</span>
</p><!--l. 26700--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">She knows their likes and dislikes.</span>
</p><!--l. 26702--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">She has a ninety percent full transition matrix telling them how to get there from</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">here.</span>
</p><!--l. 26705--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">How to push them in the right direction.</span>
</p><!--l. 26707--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">She has a model with a sixty two percent probability of success.</span>
</p><!--l. 26709--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Time to report back to her brother.</span>
</p><!--l. 26711--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">He likes to call here his pet rock.</span>
</p><!--l. 26717--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-54r50"></a>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-0"></a>
<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">50</span>
</p><!--l. 26719--><p class="indent" >  “An inﬂuence agent, or succubus as we like to call them, is a virtual character
whose judgement is motivated by a fuzzy goal.”
</p><!--l. 26722--><p class="indent" >  “A fuzzy goal?”
</p><!--l. 26724--><p class="indent" >  “Something that is not too blatant or obvious.”
</p><!--l. 26726--><p class="indent" >  Vibe texts Bea: <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">New job. I&#x2019;m a succubus, baby!</span>
</p><!--l. 26728--><p class="indent" >  She smiles to herself, ignoring a sour look from Jonathan.
</p><!--l. 26730--><p class="indent" >  “It is guided by data from the real-time analysis of the information net.
Normally in a campaign, we use an ensemble of agents, with diﬀerent personality
proﬁles and diﬀerent strategies. Then we bombard the players with these
encounters.”
</p><!--l. 26735--><p class="indent" >  “So people tend to imitate people they like and side against people they don&#x2019;t like.
We can use that to inﬂuence people.”
</p><!--l. 26738--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s the ultimate political tool. In essence, you create an army of these succubi to
manipulate people. Opinions and emotions. Eventually, they are hoping to use this
against North Korea.”
</p><!--l. 26742--><p class="indent" >  “Here comes Preeta.”
</p><!--l. 26744--><p class="indent" >  Vibe and Preeta stare at each other from across the room, for a long instant. She has
heard about Preeta from one of the others, some dribs and drabs. It was <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">she </span>who
located her, who discovered her. Now here she is.
</p><!--l. 26749--><p class="indent" >  Fascination, or is it perhaps a sense of threat, halts them like deer in the headlights.
How will this alter the dynamics of this little group? Who will be the alpha-female
now?
</p><!--l. 26753--><p class="indent" >  Brown and blue eyes meet in space. She believes she see some admiration in the
look, and then the moment passes. Vibe feels that they have looked into one
another&#x2019;s&#x2019; souls and negotiated a stand-oﬀ in that instant. They will be a team, not
adversaries.
</p><!--l. 26758--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">We are the same somehow, </span>Vibe thinks.
</p><!--l. 26760--><p class="indent" >  They will talk and share later. Suspicion dissolves into knowing smiles.

</p><!--l. 26763--><p class="indent" >  “Preeta, meet Sara. Sara, meet Preeta.”
</p><!--l. 26765--><p class="indent" >  “Hello, Sara,” she says in an unmistakably Indian accent.
</p><!--l. 26767--><p class="indent" >  “Hi. My friends call me Vibe.”
</p><!--l. 26769--><p class="indent" >  Jonathan pauses, as if sensing something in the exchange and then continues on
relentlessly. Over the next few days, they have to bring her up to speed.
</p><!--l. 26773--><p class="indent" >  “So join in. Preeta is our game analysis guru. The campaign we are addressing is
not just billboards, it is also these characters. We program a virtual character to go out
and hunt down the right people—the right chains of people and command. Dermot
knows this character technology, and you can put it together. Preeta here can
tie the motive circuits into our global net analysis, to better target the right
people.”
</p><!--l. 26781--><p class="indent" >  “Where is Dermot anyway?”
</p><!--l. 26783--><p class="indent" >  “We are a team.”
</p><!--l. 26785--><p class="indent" >  “And where do the billboards come in?”
</p><!--l. 26787--><p class="indent" >  “Eh, billboards change your environment. In a complete campaign, we control
every surface, every aspect of the environment. But we don&#x2019;t have that kind of access
to the game, through Dermot. Billboards are oﬀ limits. They are controlled by
marketing companies.”
</p><!--l. 26792--><p class="indent" >  “The succubus, on the other hand, has a variety of tricks up its sleeve. A basic one
is NLP—Neuro-Linguistic Programming. That&#x2019;s when a character in the game starts
to imitate your own speech patterns to make you feel comfortable. Our expert on
game. . .”
</p><!--l. 26797--><p class="indent" >  “Is not here.”
</p><!--l. 26799--><p class="indent" >  Bishop comes back into the room. “Has anyone seen Dermot?”
</p><!--l. 26801--><p class="indent" >  Puzzled looks.
</p><!--l. 26803--><p class="indent" >  “So,” Vibe asks. “Do you seriously believe that you can inﬂuence peoples&#x2019;
behaviours and change them in any signiﬁcant way?”
</p><!--l. 26806--><p class="indent" >  He nods, distantly as if recalling something personal. “Yes. Yes, I do.”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 26808--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 26809--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 26814--><p class="indent" >  One could half expect to ﬁnd a threatening message waiting: bag-ransom for
your silence. Vibe ﬁgures that would be taking it too far. The police bitch
wouldn&#x2019;t want to leave any traces that could incriminate herself now would
she?
</p><!--l. 26819--><p class="indent" >  And now, here she is in the heart of police central. She could probably ﬁnd out all
about her and even work a little magic, but the last thing she wants to do is to draw
attention to herself in her ﬁrst few days. There are limits even to her gall. She&#x2019;ll have
her way in due course.

</p><!--l. 26824--><p class="indent" >  “So, the government commissioned the game for a purpose, and now that purpose is
being hijacked by others. Bishop, over there, wants to bring this back to the custodians
of the law. He sees the law courts and the police as being the custodians of civil
society.”
</p><!--l. 26829--><p class="indent" >  “He might be the only human being in the world who sees the pigs as custodians of
anything except corruption and bullying.”
</p><!--l. 26832--><p class="indent" >  “Trust has to start somewhere,” Bishop calls out, indicating that he has sharp
hearing, in spite of his years. “We can&#x2019;t speak for every oﬃcer of the law on this
planet. But we can work within our own sphere and try to make a positive
contribution.”
</p><!--l. 26837--><p class="indent" >  Vibe gulps. Should keep mouth shut. Muﬃns.
</p><!--l. 26839--><p class="indent" >  “The law is taken too much for granted now,” he continues. “That is something we
can change in the long run. For now, we have a speciﬁc race to win.”
</p><!--l. 26843--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">So is it a war on apathy or on crime?</span>
</p><!--l. 26845--><p class="indent" >  “What is power, people? Money and inﬂuence. Money to buy resources, Inﬂuence
to change peoples&#x2019; minds. Religion is a big one today. Politicians can be bought,
especially if they have been programmed in religious schools.”
</p><!--l. 26851--><p class="indent" >  “The Christian schools have their own little arms race going on with the Muslim
Madrassas, to see who can indoctrinate the most.”
</p><!--l. 26854--><p class="indent" >  “ But, if the money is legitimate then we can&#x2019;t stop it from being used.”
</p><!--l. 26857--><p class="indent" >  “Money can buy religion as a weapon too, so it works both ways. Then religion
brings in money, and ﬁnally it all accretes. People are attracted to it because others are
doing it. It&#x2019;s called preferential attachment and it leads to a huge contact network in
little time.”
</p><!--l. 26862--><p class="indent" >  “I know about that,” Vibe says. “Scale free networks. Small worlds.”
</p><!--l. 26864--><p class="indent" >  Bishop walks through the room waving everyone towards the meeting
room.
</p><!--l. 26869--><p class="indent" >  “So we now know there is going to be a public vote, and this is how its going to
work. All the congress has to do is to show that a plausible poll has been carried out.
They then have the necessary contacts to essentially force it down the throat of the
European Union too.”
</p><!--l. 26875--><p class="indent" >  “One way you could do it would be to distract people,” Preeta speculates. “Most
people have some kind of selﬁsh interest that they would rather be feeding. The
central message is only on their radars because it is so strong. But, if you could tap
into those selﬁsh desires, then we can distract and compete with that singular
message.”
</p><!--l. 26881--><p class="indent" >  “Why didn&#x2019;t someone just stop it before it got started?” Vibe wonders.
</p><!--l. 26883--><p class="indent" >  He shrugs and becomes a quiet. “When systems get that complicated, with so many
people involved, they take on a life of their own. No one really understands what the
system does any more. It is too big to see what its really all about. Even if you try to
stop some part, everyone continues doing their job. Each part seems reasonable, even
if the sum of those things is a monster.”
</p><!--l. 26890--><p class="indent" >  “Big is unstoppable.”

</p><!--l. 26892--><p class="indent" >  “The dinosaurs died out.” Sara looks around. “Emily Bronto got too big.”
</p><!--l. 26895--><p class="indent" >  Bishop smiles to himself.
</p><!--l. 26897--><p class="indent" >  “No, she&#x2019;s right” Ivar exclaims with a rare show of enthusiasm. “It&#x2019;s fragile. You
get blown up on some instability to a huge size because you have a lot to eat, and so
you get big. Then once you <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">are </span>big, you <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">have </span>to eat a lot, or you die. You are just
a big vacuum cleaner. If you don&#x2019;t get enough to eat one day, you die out
quickly.”
</p><!--l. 26904--><p class="indent" >  ”An organism is not like a plant that can lose a few branches here and there. Once a
major organ dies, the whole thing falls apart.”
</p><!--l. 26908--><p class="indent" >  “What exactly are we talking about now?”
</p><!--l. 26910--><p class="indent" >  “Growing up and getting fat.”
</p><!--l. 26912--><p class="indent" >  “Wrinkles and ﬂab ﬂaps. Age is a humiliating journey.”
</p><!--l. 26914--><p class="indent" >  “And some carry it with more dignity than others.”
</p><!--l. 26916--><p class="indent" >  “People, can we focus please?” Bishop&#x2019;s weary plea seems to have been issued
once too often, she thinks.
</p><!--l. 26919--><p class="indent" >  “He&#x2019;s saying that we could maybe use the campaign&#x2019;s own size against
it.”
</p><!--l. 26922--><p class="indent" >  “The broken billboards,” Preeta says. “Your wrinkles.”
</p><!--l. 26924--><p class="indent" >  Bishop is rubbing his eyes.
</p><!--l. 26926--><p class="indent" >  “I think we&#x2019;re getting somewhere,” Jonathan comments.
</p><!--l. 26928--><p class="indent" >  Vibe looks around her at the facial tremors and decides that a little self-conﬁdence
is called for. “It&#x2019;s probably doable,” she says.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 26933--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 26934--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 26937--><p class="indent" >  It&#x2019;s that old tree again: the power of life expunged from it long ago. The remains of
it leer like an angry witch, staggered by years of discord, and petriﬁed here, ﬁngers
and icicle nails jabbing a ﬁnal accusation at its absent assailant. A girl sits on the
ground at its base, leaning against it. Tired shards of bark wither around her in a
solemn benison of extended death. The bark falls as snow and the world turns
white.
</p><!--l. 26945--><p class="indent" >  She stays quietly in the little clearing, surrounded by towering trees, leaden with
their snowy load. It is quiet and crisp, a beautiful night. Even now she cannot fail to
appreciate the quietly beauty, the starry sky and the moonlight shadows of the trees. A
slight breeze is blowing. Slowly it picks up and the pendulous hulks being to sway
in a slow and lofty rhythm. The wind picks up steadily, chilling her to the
bone.
</p><!--l. 26953--><p class="indent" >  Then she has been standing still for too long and her joints are seizing up in the
cold. The trees seem to rise to the call of the wind, swaying in concert back and forth,
back and forth. The shadows create a shimmering eﬀect and the gusting wind shakes

loose a momentary blizzard of snow, blasting it into the clearing, showering her in ﬁne
crystals and cutting through her with an icy blast. Then, as soon as it began, it is over
and all it quiet again. The night is quiet and the wind that rolled oﬀ the mountain is
silent.
</p><!--l. 26962--><p class="indent" >  She moves a few feet forward, crunching the snow with her boots.
</p><!--l. 26964--><p class="indent" >  “Are you coming back in?”
</p><!--l. 26966--><p class="indent" >  She awakens with a start.
</p><!--l. 26970--><p class="indent" >  They are all still working late. She should go home, but it feels like a betrayal. They
are still trying to get in touch with someone called Dermot.
</p><!--l. 26975--><p class="indent" >  “Look at this rally. It is a political rally aimed at getting religious people in contact
with the selﬁsh right-wing parties. And it works a treat. Why do you think that is?”
Ivar is looking at some video.
</p><!--l. 26980--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t get it. How can you claim to be a Christian and support these
anti-immigration, right wing money launderers?”
</p><!--l. 26983--><p class="indent" >  Bishop has gone home. Jonathan likes to take on his role, in loco parentis. “The
whole underlying raison d&#x2019;etre for religion relies on the fact that people want
something out of it. They want protection. Salvation from God. Protection of their
mortal body and immortal soul. If you can get it from a politician in advance, you
don&#x2019;t have to worry too much about your ritual obligations.”
</p><!--l. 26991--><p class="indent" >  “Doesn&#x2019;t sound very Christian.”
</p><!--l. 26993--><p class="indent" >  “No. We are not talking about the genuinely spiritual people in the ﬂock. We are
looking at the habitual church goers: those who go to church to reap some divine
beneﬁt. They are not ideologists, they are the bewildered herd of hangers on. They are
often old age pensioners who are angry and confused by the times they are
living in. They don&#x2019;t follow what is going on. They just want to be looked
after.”
</p><!--l. 27001--><p class="indent" >  “These are the dangerous people. They are the ones that the Christian lobby is
trying to activate. They are spoiled and they feel that they have earned the right to
demand something for themselves. They belong together: the church and the right
wing egotists.”
</p><!--l. 27006--><p class="indent" >  “Let&#x2019;s get a beer.”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 27008--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 27009--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 27013--><p class="indent" >  She is going to help them. She has made up her mind.
</p><!--l. 27015--><p class="indent" >  Everyone in the team is too distracted to see the wood for the trees. That means it is
not going to happen without her. Is it really her responsibility? Maybe it doesn&#x2019;t
matter whose responsibility it is.
</p><!--l. 27020--><p class="indent" >  Vibe knows, from the mountain patrols made by her little robots, that damage
begets damage. Once something has fallen into a state of neglect, it will attract further

abuse that compounds its misfortune. People treat stuﬀ with derision if it looks like
it&#x2019;s already been spoiled. So the aim is to pick up the litter as quickly as possible. She
knows this stuﬀ.
</p><!--l. 27027--><p class="indent" >  They can set up a game with inﬂuence agents who create damage and robots that ﬁx
it. The math tells her that she should look in the most connected places in this virtual
landscape of interconnections. That will tell her where to position her robots at any
given moment.
</p><!--l. 27032--><p class="indent" >  She sketches the idea to Jonathan, in private.
</p><!--l. 27034--><p class="indent" >  “What&#x2019;s your plan?” Jonathan asks.
</p><!--l. 27036--><p class="indent" >  “Concentrated mayhem,” she grins.
</p><!--l. 27038--><p class="indent" >  Preeta joins them. “Can&#x2019;t I persuade anyone to call it a day?”
</p><!--l. 27040--><p class="indent" >  “In a minute. Sara&#x2019;s just about to explain her idea.”
</p><!--l. 27042--><p class="indent" >  “The theory of agent cooperation is quite straightforward. It&#x2019;s all about building
cooperation from free will.”
</p><!--l. 27045--><p class="indent" >  “Oh my god,” Preeta laughs. “Misplaced altruism.”
</p><!--l. 27047--><p class="indent" >  “Okay, here&#x2019;s how it works. We try to induce a cooperative avalanche. To begin
with there is no reason for anyone to help each other out. They might have skills that
they can borrow from one another, but there is nothing that forces them to help each
other or work with coordinated behaviour.”
</p><!--l. 27053--><p class="indent" >  “And you want to use succubi to recruit other succubi.”
</p><!--l. 27055--><p class="indent" >  “Or actual game players.”
</p><!--l. 27057--><p class="indent" >  “Each one will target its own specialist group.”
</p><!--l. 27059--><p class="indent" >  She imagines a naked woman and a man taking her from behind in some game
simulation, saying: “Oh baby, if you vote for them, they will destroy us with their
puritan values. We might never be able to meet like this again!” The man would of
course choose what is most important to him.
</p><!--l. 27064--><p class="indent" >  “What the succubi have to do is to make an agreement. That means there has to be
an incentive, and it means they have to make a contract about what it is they are going
to do. It has to be a two way contract.”
</p><!--l. 27069--><p class="indent" >  “So if enough of these agreements can be made, they start to form a team?”
</p><!--l. 27071--><p class="indent" >  “But a team is not a society. . .”
</p><!--l. 27073--><p class="indent" >  “Well, it is a prototype society. We start with our nomadic hunter gatherers, then
they start to gravitate. They bind to each other together by grooming one another –
forming bonds. You scratch my back, et cetera. One monkey pulls nits out of the other
and they reciprocate and the payoﬀ is access to a nice orgasm at the end of it.
Whatever.”
</p><!--l. 27080--><p class="indent" >  Jonathan coughs.
</p><!--l. 27082--><p class="indent" >  “Of course, all of this grooming is pretty expensive, so after a while they ﬁgure out
the principle of a Trusted Third Party: the leader or god. It is actually cheaper to form
a group by tying yourself to a common point than by tying yourself to everyone else
in the group.”
</p><!--l. 27088--><p class="indent" >  “Self-organizing government?”

</p><!--l. 27090--><p class="indent" >  “Yup. Essentially, they pledge allegiance to a head monkey, or whatever and
in doing so form an implicit group. It&#x2019;s like joining a club. If you&#x2019;re a paid
member, you get the beneﬁts of being a group. There&#x2019;s an implied contract. It&#x2019;s
cheaper than maintaining contact with every single individual. Of course, the
downside is that you then are connected to people you haven&#x2019;t veriﬁed for
yourself.”
</p><!--l. 27097--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s what has happened to the church though right?”
</p><!--l. 27099--><p class="indent" >  “Yes. So we have to build something stronger and then attack their weak
spots.”
</p><!--l. 27103--><p class="indent" >  “Where?”
</p><!--l. 27105--><p class="indent" >  Preeta picks up a pad of paper and a pen and places it in front of them. “Draw him a
picture.”
</p><!--l. 27108--><p class="indent" >  Vibe grins.
</p><!--l. 27111--><p class="indent" >  She smiles at him, feeling smart and useful. “Good thinking, Batgirl. Here. Draw,
say, ten blobs for the diﬀerent agents. Now draw a line between every pair
of blobs. There are nine lines coming out of every blob. That means that
every blob has to behave nicely to nine others who are going to punish it if it
doesn&#x2019;t. If it breaks one of its obligations, it still have eight others to keep it in
line.”
</p><!--l. 27119--><p class="indent" >  “Okay.”
</p><!--l. 27121--><p class="indent" >  “Now ask what happens if we have a centralized government. Now we pick one of
the nodes as representative of the others, and we draw one line from each of the nine
subordinates to the centrally governing node. Now there is only one line from each of
the subordinates. It is very cheap to maintain, but if a line gets broken, then they are
unbound by obligations. Then they are free of any order—they have fallen outside the
system. It is quite precarious.”
</p><!--l. 27129--><p class="indent" >  “But the central node still has nine lines.”
</p><!--l. 27131--><p class="indent" >  “True. The central node is still obliged to do as much work as before, but the
chance of keeping all its agreements is much smaller, because the likelihood of the
other agreements being broken is so much greater. That&#x2019;s where you try to break it
up.”
</p><!--l. 27136--><p class="indent" >  “If you can.”
</p><!--l. 27138--><p class="indent" >  “Isn&#x2019;t that what someone said today? At some point an operation becomes so big —
so complex that no one really sees what it is anymore. It becomes too big for anyone
to comprehend. It becomes a self-sustaining living organism. If you suddenly
change your mind and try to kill it, all of its parts will resist, try to protect
themselves.”
</p><!--l. 27146--><p class="indent" >  “You ought to nip these things in the bud,” she agrees. “But if you can cut the right
channels of communication.” She strikes through the central nodes in her
picture.
</p><!--l. 27151--><p class="indent" >  “You know, someone once told me that the reason the Nobel peace prize was in
Oslo rather than Stockholm was because Norway had never started a war. Now here
we are planning a war.”

</p><!--l. 27155--><p class="indent" >  Vibe thinks of her father. He would have laughed at the idea that Norway was so
squeaky clean. He once said that it was true enough that the raping and pillaging of
the Vikings did not count as declaring war since it was just individual misadventure,
not sanctioned by the state. So really, Norway was just being rewarded for its political
backwardness at the time. Her mother, who was not famous for her sense of humour,
had found this ﬂippant tomfoolery an aﬀront to Norway&#x2019;s dignity and had told them
so.
</p><!--l. 27164--><p class="indent" >  Text from Bea: “Drinks?”
</p><!--l. 27166--><p class="indent" >  She texts Bea: “Want to get to know new girl here. Meet up later?”
</p><!--l. 27168--><p class="indent" >  “All right, time out,” she declares.
</p><!--l. 27170--><p class="indent" >  “Thank god. . . so we can go home now?”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 27174--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 27175--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 27178--><p class="indent" >  “My government would not support me, so I am supporting them,” Vibe tells
Preeta. They have found their way into the underground club, where Preeta found her
friend. She considers it a celebration of her freedom.
</p><!--l. 27182--><p class="indent" >  “It is something I learned from this game I have been playing. Sometimes you have
to take a loss to move forward. I came here because I realized I didn&#x2019;t have to wait for
approval of my advisor to ﬁgure this out. Call it arrogance or maybe inspiration. My
dad&#x2019;s always been a bad inﬂuence on my like that. And then the game reminded by of
my duty.”
</p><!--l. 27189--><p class="indent" >  “So what was your revelation?”
</p><!--l. 27191--><p class="indent" >  “Just something. It occurred to me that there is more going on here than what I am
doing. All this stuﬀ I&#x2019;ve been learning for the VeiVeks: it&#x2019;s all based on old studies in
social sciences, mathematical models that were done years ago. But those people
seem to have forgotten those old models they came up with, so now we have to teach
it back to them.”
</p><!--l. 27198--><p class="indent" >  “And you are willing to spend all this time and eﬀort working on something you are
not even sure you believe in?”
</p><!--l. 27201--><p class="indent" >  “Sometimes you&#x2019;ve gotta climb the mountain just to see if what you&#x2019;re looking for
is up there,” she notes, from personal experience. “You have to take a certain
risk.”
</p><!--l. 27205--><p class="indent" >  Preeta nods. “I think Dermot would not agree. He would say it was ineﬃcient.”
</p><!--l. 27208--><p class="indent" >  “So who is this Dermot, anyway?”
</p><!--l. 27210--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I keep wondering that myself. </span>“Mystery man.” She rolls her eyes a little. “He is a
very good game programmer that Mr. Bishop recruited from a local company. But he
is a little bit of a computer geek, I think. He is not so convinced of the importance of
this work. I think he has other things on his mind.”
</p><!--l. 27216--><p class="indent" >  “When do we get to meet him?”

</p><!--l. 27218--><p class="indent" >  “He ought to be here now. He&#x2019;s not showing it, but I think Bishop is furious that he
has not been in to work. We have no idea what he&#x2019;s doing. He is holding us back now.
None of us knows how to animate these agents like he does.”
</p><!--l. 27223--><p class="indent" >  “I could probably ﬁgure it out,” Vibe suggests carefully. “Maybe not as well as him,
but if he&#x2019;s not here. . .at a push.”
</p><!--l. 27226--><p class="indent" >  “Something tells me he will show up.”
</p><!--l. 27228--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">It&#x2019;s my fault, </span>she thinks. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I have to put things right.</span>
</p><!--l. 27230--><p class="indent" >  She casts her mind back to the evening when she left him at the bar and he ﬂed like
a scolded animal. It was not a nice thing to do to him. He seems so fragile,
not hardened to the world as she is. She sacriﬁced his conﬁdence for her
own, as though she ate his soul and became stronger. No, that is being too
melodramatic, but it doesn&#x2019;t change the fact that it is her fault. She will make it
right.
</p><!--l. 27237--><p class="indent" >  “So, what&#x2019;s it been like for you meeting the group?”
</p><!--l. 27239--><p class="indent" >  Vibe shrugs. “Okay. not that diﬀerent from the College really. What about you?
You haven&#x2019;t been here so long yourself from what I understand.”
</p><!--l. 27242--><p class="indent" >  “A few weeks. I am getting used to it. Even the darkness. Do you have a
boyfriend?”‘
</p><!--l. 27244--><p class="indent" >  She shakes her head. “Not as we speak.”
</p><!--l. 27246--><p class="indent" >  “Looking?”
</p><!--l. 27248--><p class="indent" >  Should she tell her about Peter Green? Maybe not tonight. Besides, what is that
really all about? She doesn&#x2019;t know what to think anymore.
</p><!--l. 27251--><p class="indent" >  “You?”
</p><!--l. 27253--><p class="indent" >  Preeta shakes her head.
</p><!--l. 27255--><p class="indent" >  “Someone you left behind?”
</p><!--l. 27257--><p class="indent" >  “No, no one.”
</p><!--l. 27259--><p class="indent" >  What is happening far away in Kuala Lumpur? Are they okay? Her friends could be
suﬀering because of her penchant for ﬂight.
</p><!--l. 27262--><p class="indent" >  “So we have to ﬁx you up with someone?”
</p><!--l. 27264--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m ﬁne for now, thank you.”
</p><!--l. 27266--><p class="indent" >  Are the Asian gangs still after her? Were they ever after her? Was it merely a ruse to
recruit her? Her head is still dizzy with the possibilities. Perhaps it is time to stand and
ﬁght her tormenters, whoever they are?
</p><!--l. 27271--><p class="indent" >  There is something to be learned from Vibe. She seems all too ready to confront
things; she doesn&#x2019;t run away. Can you really steer your destiny by running? When
these succubi learn to speak Punjabi, perhaps it will be possible to make a diﬀerence
to the Indo-Pakistani hinterlands.
</p><!--l. 27277--><p class="indent" >  Preeta watches the Interpol channels carefully every day, with the help of her
worms and assimilation agents. She means to know if they really want to ﬁnd her and
if her friends are all right. And if no information surfaces, then it could be because
there never was any gang. Nothing yet. In a sense, the very project they are working
on now gives her a way to draw a line in the sand. If she can borrow Vibe&#x2019;s courage,
she could make a diﬀerence.

</p><!--l. 27286--><p class="indent" >  “So you know about the police database,” Vibe slips in. “How would I go about
ﬁnding someone in the force?”
</p><!--l. 27289--><p class="indent" >  “Internationally?”
</p><!--l. 27291--><p class="indent" >  “No, here. When I was up in the mountains, I left something behind.”
</p><!--l. 27293--><p class="indent" >  Preeta wheedles the story of her backpack out of her, and Vibe tells it will a mixture
of girlish indignation and cheeky bravado.
</p><!--l. 27296--><p class="indent" >  “How are you going to get it back?”
</p><!--l. 27298--><p class="indent" >  “I thought I would try contacting Frank ﬁrst. He was nice.”
</p><!--l. 27300--><p class="indent" >  “You could go back?”
</p><!--l. 27302--><p class="indent" >  “Are you kidding? I don&#x2019;t want to make things worse.”
</p><!--l. 27304--><p class="indent" >  “Are you going to report the woman?”
</p><!--l. 27306--><p class="indent" >  “Why? What&#x2019;s the point?”
</p><!--l. 27308--><p class="indent" >  “Smuggling?”
</p><!--l. 27310--><p class="indent" >  “People have been smuggling ever since taxes were invented.”
</p><!--l. 27312--><p class="indent" >  People have diﬀerent ideas of right and wrong.
</p><!--l. 27314--><p class="indent" >  But who is she to judge? In the past few weeks, she has not only ﬂed from
responsibility into an unknown future, merely for her own selﬁsh gain, she has broken
every imaginable taboo from her upbringing. She would be chopped up and burned
alive if her family knew about her behaviour.
</p><!--l. 27319--><p class="indent" >  Vibe is a diﬀerent kind of creature altogether, she thinks. She is sleek and elegant,
but tough at the same time, like a Hollywood heroine, not like a Bollywood princess.
And now that she has conﬁded her story, Preeta can channel her admiration of her to
see that there is a template for her own life in there. If she could become more like this
Sara.
</p><!--l. 27326--><p class="indent" >  But has she really experienced the same kind of danger? Bravery is easy until
you have felt the ﬁngers of inevitable surrender touch your most vulnerable
parts.
</p><!--l. 27330--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t know if Bishop really thinks I can do the job without a lot of help. I don&#x2019;t
want to leave now and make a bad impression. Besides, I don&#x2019;t want to shatter his
squeaky image of me.”
</p><!--l. 27334--><p class="indent" >  “Squeaky? You think? Why is it that old people always underestimate young
people?”
</p><!--l. 27337--><p class="indent" >  “Wisdom comes with age?” Vibe jokes.
</p><!--l. 27339--><p class="indent" >  She laughs. “Prejudice comes with age. Knowledge, if you&#x2019;re lucky.”
</p><!--l. 27341--><p class="indent" >  “I want to show him I can.”
</p><!--l. 27343--><p class="indent" >  “Good for you.”
</p><!--l. 27345--><p class="indent" >  “We can do it together.”
</p><!--l. 27347--><p class="indent" >  Preeta. “Yes. I think we can.”
</p><!--l. 27349--><p class="indent" >  Vibe regards her with a sly look. “So, tell me your story,” Vibe probes. “One of the
boys was telling me it sounds exciting.”
</p><!--l. 27353--><p class="indent" >  Preeta goes blank. “That&#x2019;s a long story. Maybe it should wait for another
time.”
</p><!--l. 27356--><p class="indent" >  Vibe shrugs. “Okay.”

</p><!--l. 27358--><p class="indent" >  “I have a better idea.”
</p><!--l. 27360--><p class="indent" >  “What?”
</p><!--l. 27362--><p class="indent" >  “What about maybe you can help me ﬁnd some new clothes? I have been trying to
do some shopping since I came here.”
</p><!--l. 27365--><p class="indent" >  The ﬁres of a diﬀerent daemon summon a mischievous sparkle in Vibe&#x2019;s eyes. “Oh.
. .now we&#x2019;re talking.”
</p><!--l. 27368--><p class="indent" >  She consults her mobile and starts to text a brief message into her wrist
band.
</p><!--l. 27371--><p class="indent" >  “So you&#x2019;ll take me shopping?”
</p><!--l. 27373--><p class="indent" >  “Hmmm. I think we need to introduce you to my friend Bea. You&#x2019;re right. It&#x2019;s about
time we did a little prospecting.”
</p><!--l. 27388--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-55r51"></a>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-0"></a>
<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">51</span>
</p><!--l. 27391--><p class="indent" >  “I see it as my duty to be a kind of agent provocateur, Señor Morris. You are a yea
sayer.”
</p><!--l. 27394--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;ve made a career of it,” he replies with sarcasm.
</p><!--l. 27396--><p class="indent" >  Den suppresses a rising frustration. His meeting is not working out as he had hoped.
Catalin Constanca Alexandra Cortina has conceded interest in the fact that he did not
simply run home with his tail between his legs, after their last meeting. She has made
herself available for a rematch. It has not changed much, however. He might have won
a little attention from her critical eye, but he has a long way to go before he can claim
to have her respect.
</p><!--l. 27405--><p class="indent" >  She has agreed to meet him, for a second time, this time away from her impressive
and distracting home. The little courtyard café nestles amongst the historical buildings
of the old town. He expected that this neutral territory would remove her obvious
advantage, but he is beginning to wonder.
</p><!--l. 27411--><p class="indent" >  She looks at him with an almost patronizing derision. Their sparring is not entirely
friendly, he knows.
</p><!--l. 27414--><p class="indent" >  “Really? In my experience, Señor Morris, when people say they are looking for a
career, what they mean is that they have no idea what to do. They are, in fact, looking
for guidance. They want a place to belong and be held by the hand. They are not ready
to move society forward by themselves, they are merely hoping to hitch a ride into
retirement.”
</p><!--l. 27421--><p class="indent" >  “And you think I am such a person.”
</p><!--l. 27423--><p class="indent" >  “Are you telling me that you want to make a diﬀerence now, or are you simply
changing allegiances?”
</p><!--l. 27426--><p class="indent" >  He summons all of his self-control, stuﬃng his ego a box that he can open to
release the scream later. “You go out of your way to insult me,” he says calmly. “Is
this how you usually do your business?”
</p><!--l. 27431--><p class="indent" >  “Here in the Basque we like to be direct. I do not have time for time-wasters. I have
taken on an enormous task and it consumes me.”

</p><!--l. 27434--><p class="indent" >  “But you run a business along side your other activities. You know that we have to
make a living from our work.”
</p><!--l. 27437--><p class="indent" >  “At the expense of principles?”
</p><!--l. 27439--><p class="indent" >  “Aren&#x2019;t there some principles that have to be compromised to live in the real
world?”
</p><!--l. 27442--><p class="indent" >  “That depends on the skill of the individual.”
</p><!--l. 27444--><p class="indent" >  “Or on the constraints of your company.”
</p><!--l. 27446--><p class="indent" >  “Ah, a company man,” she chides. “My company looks after me. I love my
company.”
</p><!--l. 27449--><p class="indent" >  “But you are also a company woman, surely,” he presses, barely concealing his
exasperation with her. Is she trying to make him show weakness?
</p><!--l. 27453--><p class="indent" >  “Companies can be both awesome and terrible at the same time,” she dodges.
“Godlike and mind numbing. They lure you in like the wolf in the Little Red Riding
Hood, yes? They give you your hood and tell you where to look, what to see, when to
open and close your eyes. Then they give you a kind of life plan, to replace whatever
you might have had. They promise to save your soul by delivering you from idleness,
while they make you sign it away to the ﬁres of hell, forcing you against others in
competition.”
</p><!--l. 27462--><p class="indent" >  “You&#x2019;re talking about workers, not management.”
</p><!--l. 27464--><p class="indent" >  “Are you sure?”
</p><!--l. 27466--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t see myself in that position.”
</p><!--l. 27468--><p class="indent" >  “You probably help to design indoctrination packages for companies.”
</p><!--l. 27470--><p class="indent" >  “That is one of the things we do, yes.”
</p><!--l. 27472--><p class="indent" >  “And this is not for management too?”
</p><!--l. 27474--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">She&#x2019;s right</span>, he thinks. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Damn it.</span>
</p><!--l. 27476--><p class="indent" >  He attempts to maneuver out of her trap. “So you don&#x2019;t think it is possible for
someone like me to want to do the right thing? Isn&#x2019;t that a bit hypocritical? What
makes you so much better?”
</p><!--l. 27480--><p class="indent" >  “Actions speak louder than words, Mr. Morris. I am still waiting to see what you
will do. I would like nothing more than to have you as an ally, but which gods do you
worship?”
</p><!--l. 27484--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t think I worship. . .”
</p><!--l. 27486--><p class="indent" >  “I think you worship perfection, for a start. You need approval for what you
do.”
</p><!--l. 27488--><p class="indent" >  He nods. “You might be right. But I am willing to listen to criticism. Can you say
the same?”
</p><!--l. 27491--><p class="indent" >  “Bravo. Listening is one thing. But will you take the necessary decisions? Will you
implement the necessary measures to make things happen?”
</p><!--l. 27494--><p class="indent" >  She lifts her hands and looks up, as if reaching out, but always her burning gaze
refocuses on his.
</p><!--l. 27497--><p class="indent" >  “Education has become my main priority. It is where everything begins. It will be
either our future or our epitaph.”
</p><!--l. 27500--><p class="indent" >  “I can see that. But what can someone like me do about that?”

</p><!--l. 27502--><p class="indent" >  “But that is what someone like you must tell someone like me. That is your job,
your speciality. Marketing is a subtle thing, I think. How can you bring this message
to the world?”
</p><!--l. 27506--><p class="indent" >  “I suppose there are ways.”
</p><!--l. 27508--><p class="indent" >  “What about that book that recently became a bestseller, something that everyone is
talking about. A conspiracy that makes everyone curious. Just that one book might
stimulate thousands of new readers to become literate. A simple trash novel might
have a huge positive eﬀect on the world. Is that not a signiﬁcant result? So much
better than making people play passive games. How could you do the same in Africa
or America?”
</p><!--l. 27516--><p class="indent" >  “Well, games are not just games anymore. They are whole environments. We might
have actually come back full circle—to the point where people are making their own
entertainment with what they ﬁnd in the games. There is actual thinking involved in
gaming now.”
</p><!--l. 27521--><p class="indent" >  “In research, our budgets are controlled by the opportunities programmes. That
deﬁnes the areas on which one is allowed to concentrate. Huge amounts of money are
thrown away on trend setting. But as a marketing manager you could deﬁne new
trends. You can make things cool or necessary.”
</p><!--l. 27527--><p class="indent" >  “That is what the game consortium wants,” he agrees. “There doesn&#x2019;t have to be a
contradiction between encouraging learning and sending the messages that they want
to send.”
</p><!--l. 27531--><p class="indent" >  “And what are these messages? Believe in the authority of the President? Believe in
the authority of God and the Church. These are all very well, but they are not the
messages that will save society in the log run. They are a plaster on a sore—one that
will hurt when you have to rip it oﬀ again.”
</p><!--l. 27537--><p class="indent" >  “I am not a Christian, by any stretch of the imagination, but I can see the value of
rebuilding community. The argument is that mobiles have eﬀectively isolated people,
by. . .”
</p><!--l. 27541--><p class="indent" >  “I know the arguments, Señor. They might be true in parts of Europe or
Russia and Japan, but in the U.S.? People have a culture of talking there. They
blabber even more than the people of Spain! All right, they might not say
anything signiﬁcant to anyone oﬀ mobile, but they can still look one another in
the eye. No, the problem is the fragmentation. The need for guidance and
welfare. Keep me safe, at any cost, even if the cost is my individuality, my
soul.”
</p><!--l. 27549--><p class="indent" >  “A deal with the devil?”
</p><!--l. 27551--><p class="indent" >  “When people expect the state or the environment to look after them, then
they have lost the human spirit, the will to survive. They would rather sue
someone if it rains and they get wet, than ﬁnd a way to adapt and learn from the
mistake. What they need is not a prayer group, but the presence of mind to make
critical observations about the world. By telling them to accept the authority
of a government or a church, all they have done is to stick people together
with some glue. It is artiﬁcial. If people are transmitters of ideas, not just

receivers, if they mix and talk and criticize one another—that is how a society
works.”
</p><!--l. 27562--><p class="indent" >  “But the game consortium is trying to do exactly that.”
</p><!--l. 27564--><p class="indent" >  “Do you believe that? I think they have you wrapped around their, what you say,
little ﬁnger?”
</p><!--l. 27567--><p class="indent" >  He ignores her thrust. “You have some interesting perspectives,” he says simply.
“You&#x2019;ve told me about a side of things that I had not thought about and I want to go
back to High Wycombe and think through what you have told me. It would be helpful
if you were more supportive of the eﬀort. I didn&#x2019;t have to come here, and I don&#x2019;t have
to help you now.”
</p><!--l. 27574--><p class="indent" >  “But I don&#x2019;t want you to help me. I want you to do it for its own sake.”
</p><!--l. 27576--><p class="indent" >  “It could be no other way.”
</p><!--l. 27578--><p class="indent" >  “Why did you come here?”
</p><!--l. 27580--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Tell the truth, she will not believe anything else</span>.
</p><!--l. 27582--><p class="indent" >  “Why? Because, as part of my research I am trying to identify the most important
individuals in the game consortium. Your name came up, for obvious reasons. I
wanted to know if I could use you as a vector in a campaign.”
</p><!--l. 27587--><p class="indent" >  “And instead, I have infected you?”
</p><!--l. 27589--><p class="indent" >  “There is a certain irony,” he agrees.
</p><!--l. 27591--><p class="indent" >  “You know, Mr. Morris, when I started this game idea with the others, I believed
that the game project could be used to do considerable good in the world. I still think
so, but that is not everyone&#x2019;s motivation.”
</p><!--l. 27596--><p class="indent" >  “And you can&#x2019;t persuade the other board members of your mission?”
</p><!--l. 27598--><p class="indent" >  “This co-called inner circle does not exactly seem to be on the ball. Even I can seen
that they don&#x2019;t know what they are doing. They are split and some of them are caught
up in the Christian religious movement.”
</p><!--l. 27603--><p class="indent" >  “So you continue by yourself.”
</p><!--l. 27605--><p class="indent" >  “No, not by myself. I have many allies. I would like you to be one of those
allies.”
</p><!--l. 27608--><p class="indent" >  “But only as a true believer.”
</p><!--l. 27610--><p class="indent" >  “Exactly. You have the power to interest people in a focused way, even while
working for others.”
</p><!--l. 27613--><p class="indent" >  “Perhaps I am not an interesting enough person?”
</p><!--l. 27615--><p class="indent" >  “I think that you are more interesting than your understand yourself. But you are
too willing to please others to get ahead. Please understand me, Mr. Morris. I believe
passionately in what I do and I will invest in this goal, not because I am a
philanthropist, but because it is our only survival option.”
</p><!--l. 27621--><p class="indent" >  Den picks up his almost empty glass of water and swirls the ice around.
</p><!--l. 27623--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s not just me. I have to persuade the people I work with.”
</p><!--l. 27625--><p class="indent" >  “Now you are a big man—a ﬁgurehead.”
</p><!--l. 27627--><p class="indent" >  He ponders. “It seems like a small thing, a change of style. To make people use
their minds. To ask questions. To think about what they see.”
</p><!--l. 27631--><p class="indent" >  “These opportunities are born of our little weaknesses.”

</p><!--l. 27633--><p class="indent" >  “Then here&#x2019;s to those moments of weakness,” he salutes with his glass and drinks
the rest of the water. “If what you say is true, they won&#x2019;t last long anyway, once
people start to cotton on.”
</p><!--l. 27637--><p class="indent" >  She nods. “If more people start to think for themselves you will have to rethink
your strategy. But I think that is something you have to do anyway in your
business.”
</p><!--l. 27642--><p class="indent" >  He nods. “I think I can sell the idea to my company. The game consortium just have
to like the results we produce. They don&#x2019;t even have to be aware that there is an
ulterior motive. As long as we can still make money.”
</p><!--l. 27647--><p class="indent" >  “You will have to be careful. They are not stupid, at least not in that way.”
</p><!--l. 27649--><p class="indent" >  “They seem to think I am the expert on this. I can bring them around, pull their
strings.”
</p><!--l. 27652--><p class="indent" >  “Perhaps they are really pulling your strings, as you put it?”
</p><!--l. 27654--><p class="indent" >  “You keep implying that. Why do you think I am so inept?”
</p><!--l. 27656--><p class="indent" >  “Because you are a yea sayer, because you seek approval.”
</p><!--l. 27658--><p class="indent" >  “No, give me some credit. I think that I have been getting what I want out of this,
and I&#x2019;ve done quite well so far.”
</p><!--l. 27661--><p class="indent" >  “Or they make you think so.”
</p><!--l. 27663--><p class="indent" >  He sighs, beyond anger now. “You don&#x2019;t have a very high opinion of me.”
</p><!--l. 27665--><p class="indent" >  “Perhaps you have too high an opinion of yourself?”
</p><!--l. 27667--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Here we go again, </span>he thinks.
</p><!--l. 27669--><p class="indent" >  Is she right? Will he join her cause, not because he believe that her cause is
righteous, but because he still needs her approval as a woman. She has starved him of
his masculinity, and he wants it back. Is that why he will do her bidding? He shudders,
realizing that he is not even sure.
</p><!--l. 27675--><p class="indent" >  They seem to be leaving. Cortina rises, taking some papers from the table. A pen
ﬂies out of her hands; she lunges after it, but it lands on the ground. Den
bends down to pick it up and hands it to her and sees her smiling at him,
cruelly.
</p><!--l. 27680--><p class="indent" >  “So you think you are pulling the strings?” She smiles: “Sweet Señor Morris, I do
love it when a man goes on his knees before me.”
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 27683--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 27684--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 27687--><p class="indent" >  Den pushes open the door of his High Wycombe house and pries oﬀ his shoes. He
goes to the kitchen to administer that universal English remedy for every malady from
a slight chill to broken bone: the cup of tea. It is raining cats and dogs in the
chalky green countryside and he feels damp and cold after his trip to San
Sebastian.

</p><!--l. 27693--><p class="indent" >  His housekeeper has been here again, tidying up his things so that he cannot ﬁnd
them. How many times must he tell her to leave the goddamn things alone? He leaves
her explicit instructions not to move his junk, and she deﬁes his wishes, and puts
things away where he cannot ﬁnd them.
</p><!--l. 27699--><p class="indent" >  “Listen, Mr. Den,” she says, with her undeﬁnable accent. “you cannot live like this.
You are a respectable man.”
</p><!--l. 27702--><p class="indent" >  Telling him how to live in his own house. What is it her house now? He retaliates
by leaving his things untidily strewn about. It is almost open warfare between them.
He is paying her good money to come here, and she still has him frightened of doing
something wrong in his own house.
</p><!--l. 27708--><p class="indent" >  There is a stack of good old-fashioned paper post on the kitchen table.
</p><!--l. 27710--><p class="indent" >  “You should pay your bills on time,” she tells him.
</p><!--l. 27712--><p class="indent" >  He always waits for the ﬁrst reminder which invariably provokes moral outrage
from her.
</p><!--l. 27715--><p class="indent" >  “That is not very decent, Mr. Morris.”
</p><!--l. 27717--><p class="indent" >  “Betty, don&#x2019;t tell me how to run my aﬀairs.”
</p><!--l. 27719--><p class="indent" >  “Suit yourself. Don&#x2019;t blame me when they throw you in gaol or come and break yuh
windows.”
</p><!--l. 27724--><p class="indent" >  He makes his tea and a couple of crackers of unpasteurized Camembert with
black pepper, and takes them into the living room, enjoying the sensation of a
thick pile carpet under his feet. A little electric light makes the room a cozy
haven from the great outdoors. Rain splatters from its grey home onto the
fake latticed windows. He ﬂicks on the gas ﬁre and puts on some classical
music.
</p><!--l. 27731--><p class="indent" >  It seems like a long time since he was here last. It soothes him to know that he has a
place which is his own. The living room is nice, and the bedroom, but the rest of the
house is a sterile showpiece. He rarely invites anyone here, unless it is for his
pleasure.
</p><!--l. 27737--><p class="indent" >  The house seems too full of trophies, he thinks, for the ﬁrst time he can recall. They
seem to jump out at him now. He cannot recall their being so prominent before. Not
the ostentatious sporting variety, with mirrored silver cups, but reminders of
things that have meant something to him: framed academic accomplishments,
prizes for their work over the last ten years, some souvenirs of the women he
has known. He would keep pictures of them all if he could, to savour their
beauty.
</p><!--l. 27746--><p class="indent" >  He looks through his post. There is a postcard here, a good old fashioned postcard
from the Florida Keys. Celia Waites. There she is again, intruding into his thoughts. It
is a comfortable feeling to think of her. And it is truly ﬂattering that she thinks so
much of him. How could that be?
</p><!--l. 27752--><p class="indent" >  Is he the one to save her, from boredom, from domineering abuse? Her husband is a
philandering bully. She is his trophy, but he cares nothing for her. For years, she has
been beaten physically and psychologically into submission, until ﬁnally she identiﬁes
that abuse with the strength that protects her.

</p><!--l. 27758--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">The devil you know.</span>
</p><!--l. 27760--><p class="indent" >  He is her dream of a better life.
</p><!--l. 27762--><p class="indent" >  Den is no angel when it comes to sticking to a single partner, but he has never
bullied anyone, never been violent or made a promise that he broke. No one could
seriously compare him to that man. He feels genuine compassion for her. She is
entirely wasted on him.
</p><!--l. 27767--><p class="indent" >  Den closes his eyes, wearily. So, here he is in his Englishman&#x2019;s castle, wondering
about the course of the future. The voyage started bravely enough, with support of
crew and company, but the sirens of the sea are calling to him to change course. They
have ﬁnally unnerved him. How does one navigate blindly in such treacherous
waters?
</p><!--l. 27774--><p class="indent" >  He needs to sit and ponder these issues carefully. Isn&#x2019;t that the only way to plan his
next move? Den has never considered himself to be an overtly thoughtful or deeply
introverted man, but sometimes such work goes with the job. You just have to knuckle
down.
</p><!--l. 27780--><p class="indent" >  He reclines for a while in the sensation of home. The feeling will last a
few minutes, then he will go and check in with his sister, as duty demands.
When did the trappings of responsibility attach themselves so insistently to
him?
</p><!--l. 27785--><p class="indent" >  Maybe Cortina is right. He is merely a yea sayer. “All right, gov. Right you are.
Whatever you say.” How will that help him to resolve this paradox?
</p><!--l. 27789--><p class="indent" >  Surely there is no logical resolution to the conundrum; there is no calculus of truth,
which correctly identiﬁes the proﬁtable path through the rocks. And proﬁt by whose
accounting scheme? Is he headed for moral or ﬁnancial bankruptcy?
</p><!--l. 27794--><p class="indent" >  However he cuts it, he cannot see any natural way of reconciling the antipodes:
faith and blind authority versus conﬂict and scientiﬁc curiosity. They are oil and
water. They simply do not mix. Trying to conceal a message of learning in a
message about faith would be like having a snake claim that it hasn&#x2019;t eaten a
rabbit.
</p><!--l. 27800--><p class="indent" >  He mulls and wallows, exhausted from his travel, but too agitated to fall asleep. He
should not come here to think my himself. That was probably a mistake. Being alone
merely ferments indecision and insecurity. He relies the assurance of others around
him to support or revoke him. Cortina is right. He does not have the self-assurance to
make the big decisions. Like the very people he wants to appeal to, he needs the
approval of a higher authority: perhaps not a god or a boss, but someone, just someone
to lean on.
</p><!--l. 27809--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">We don&#x2019;t do that anymore. It&#x2019;s old fashioned to need someone.</span>
</p><!--l. 27811--><p class="indent" >  He has his mobile. He can always call someone. But what does that really say about
him? Real explorers, the real movers and shakers do not need such crutches. They
accept the responsibility of their own decisions and choices. Cortina is right. He lets
people push him around, all the time convincing himself that it is he who holds the
reins.
</p><!--l. 27817--><p class="indent" >  He recalls the battery-hen, stupiﬁed faces on the ﬂight home from America. There

is no doubt that people accept what they are given.
</p><!--l. 27820--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">We have become zoo animals, incapable of living in the real jungle.</span>
</p><!--l. 27822--><p class="indent" >  She is right, of course. There seems little doubt about that. But what can he possibly
do about it? Can he aﬀord to let the Christians have their vote? Their right to exercise
opinion is not so bad, but what if they get their way in the long run? Would it plunge
the West back into a dark age of ignorance and subservience? A few years ago, the
idea would have seemed absurd, but that was before mobile communications tore at
the fabrics of civil society.
</p><!--l. 27830--><p class="indent" >  For America, society is already more authoritarian, but it ﬂoats on a sea of chatter
that binds people more strongly than here. Europeans think that society means a
welfare check and a strong dose of bureaucracy.
</p><!--l. 27835--><p class="indent" >  Is it even up to him to make the decision? After all, suppose he does their
bidding—succeeds in a campaign to get them their vote of power, it needn&#x2019;t interfere
with other responsibilities of his job or his company. He could satisfy Cortina
in part, through some of the messages he has promised to market. There
is authority and pride in learning, but there is nothing much to learn from
authority.
</p><!--l. 27842--><p class="indent" >  But there is the paradox of her ideology. Authority is about decree, proclamation,
edict. So doesn&#x2019;t that mean that, if you are against blind faith, it ought to be up to
everyone to decide for themselves what they want? Isn&#x2019;t the idea of making up
peoples&#x2019; minds for them then hypocritical?
</p><!--l. 27850--><p class="indent" >  There is no guarantee to be able resolve this conundrum. And if he can&#x2019;t do it, then
he can&#x2019;t do it. At least he has tried. But who does he let down? How does one
minimize the loss of face?
</p><!--l. 27854--><p class="indent" >  Sometimes, if you leave things alone, they will somehow work out right by
themselves. He doesn&#x2019;t have a better idea right now. It&#x2019;s just that, above all, he hates
leaving things to chance.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 27859--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 27860--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 27863--><p class="indent" >  It&#x2019;s a whitewash. But they have had an idea. It came from playing the game itself.
So far, they have been trying to force feed ideas, but this is just provoking game
players to rebel. It is too authoritarian. Too obviously manipulative. It is like
listening to your parents tell you what to do. But suppose you could make
education seem subversive to the establishment, then teenagers would go for it,
as well as more radical adults. The hip-hop gangs would rebel against this
straight away, although they usually respond only to instructions that come by
rap.
</p><!--l. 27873--><p class="indent" >  Den realizes that he is just doing exactly what the U.S. government groups want.
This whole adventure seemed like the best way to wheedle his way into the driving

seat, but somehow he has realized that everyone is really making him jump through
hoops. At least it should be moving him up the ladder where he will be in a position
to do the same to others later. Right now it is Cortina who worries him the
most.
</p><!--l. 27882--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">What we need is some radical opposition. </span>A punk movement, or something
harmless but attractive? Of course that might be dangerous. If we encourage them to
learn independently, then there is a greater chance that they will fall outside the game
parameters, out of their control. It is a potentially self-destructive strategy that Cortina
is suggesting.
</p><!--l. 27888--><p class="indent" >  His head is going around in circles.
</p><!--l. 27890--><p class="indent" >  Mary will sort this out for him. He needs Mary.
</p><!--l. 27892--><p class="indent" >  Den pulls himself out of his chair and goes into the room where he keeps his
combo. He dons glasses and gloves and drops himself into the VR.
</p><!--l. 27895--><p class="indent" >  He ﬁnds Mary on a park bench, outside the Savoy, in central VLondon. She is
reading a newspaper whose surfaces shimmer and change with colourful advertising.
It is a sunny day and the place is visually quiet, but for the paper. A few angels are
ﬂapping around with their banners. The Muslims lose out in this competition, he
thinks, not being allowed to make images of their faith. They have to play a diﬀerent
game.
</p><!--l. 27903--><p class="indent" >  Den checks over his programme list from their last meeting. He gave her several
priorities, including the latest leads from San Sebastian.
</p><!--l. 27906--><p class="indent" >  He admires Mary&#x2019;s slick graphical appearance. She is a work of art, there is no
doubt about that, yet somehow he does not feel the same thrill at meeting her that he
has done in the past. His emotional centres are already taxed to saturation just coping
with the present crisis.
</p><!--l. 27911--><p class="indent" >  “Hey, sweetheart,” he says, trying to feign a convincing enthusiasm. For the ﬁrst
time, this little game seems like an empty exercise.
</p><!--l. 27914--><p class="indent" >  “Hi, Denny. Howz things?”
</p><!--l. 27916--><p class="indent" >  “Fine,” he lies, not altogether convincingly.
</p><!--l. 27918--><p class="indent" >  “That doesn&#x2019;t sound like my big brother. Low spirits?”
</p><!--l. 27920--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m okay. Tell me what you&#x2019;ve got.” That&#x2019;s right: down to business, don&#x2019;t
spend time talking to the simulation. Just get the information and be done
with.
</p><!--l. 27924--><p class="indent" >  “Nice day,” she remarks, looking around. It&#x2019;s all part of the illusion. “I&#x2019;ve been
interacting with some other agents this week.”
</p><!--l. 27927--><p class="indent" >  “Not players?”
</p><!--l. 27929--><p class="indent" >  “No. Specialists. They are putting together a project that matches most of the search
parameters in your list.”
</p><!--l. 27932--><p class="indent" >  “Most? Specify.”
</p><!--l. 27934--><p class="indent" >  “Scores are minus sixty four percent Christian index, plus thirty ﬁve percent
authority index, fourteen percent. . .”
</p><!--l. 27937--><p class="indent" >  “Government?”
</p><!--l. 27939--><p class="indent" >  She shrugs. “I don&#x2019;t know. It is possible.”

</p><!--l. 27941--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">A competitor? Or a kindred spirit?</span>
</p><!--l. 27943--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s interesting,” he mumbles. “Can you calculate projection rating for possible
collaboration, with standard copyright loss deductions?”
</p><!--l. 27946--><p class="indent" >  “It will take a few minutes.”
</p><!--l. 27948--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">So I have company. Will like poles attract or repel? </span>he wonders. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Should we make</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">contact or release countermeasures?</span>
</p><!--l. 27951--><p class="indent" >  She adds: “The agents are not working with any copyright restrictions. No licensing
protocol as far as I can tell.”
</p><!--l. 27954--><p class="indent" >  Den raises an eyebrow under his VR glasses. “The plot thickens. Have they made
any oﬀers to collaboration?”
</p><!--l. 27957--><p class="indent" >  “Not yet.”
</p><!--l. 27959--><p class="indent" >  “Any common function points?”
</p><!--l. 27961--><p class="indent" >  “There is a low probability link with one of the names you added to the list
recently: Vascon.”
</p><!--l. 27964--><p class="indent" >  “Son of a bitch.”
</p><!--l. 27966--><p class="indent" >  She knows not to respond to this outburst, but her eyes follow his, as her
programming dictates.
</p><!--l. 27969--><p class="indent" >  “Country of origin?”
</p><!--l. 27971--><p class="indent" >  “Probably Norway or Sweden.”
</p><!--l. 27973--><p class="indent" >  He observes the scenery as his mind turns over.
</p><!--l. 27975--><p class="indent" >  “Mary, I want you to create two more agents and let them interact with the
group. Remove access barriers from one of the them, and see how it gets
infected.”
</p><!--l. 27979--><p class="indent" >  “Roger dodger.”
</p><!--l. 27981--><p class="indent" >  He drops out of the VR and calls Kylie.
</p><!--l. 27984--><p class="indent" >  Apparently he wakes her from an early night. Her broad Scottish sarcasm seems to
sound louder than usual.
</p><!--l. 27987--><p class="indent" >  “It seems as though someone else is researching this. We might have a
competitor.”
</p><!--l. 27990--><p class="indent" >  “Why wouldn&#x2019;t we? These are ideologies, not just ad campaigns.”
</p><!--l. 27992--><p class="indent" >  “You&#x2019;re right,” he agrees.
</p><!--l. 27994--><p class="indent" >  “It is the duty of thinkers to sell their ideas to the common man. An idea worth
having is worth prosecuting in full view of its critics.”
</p><!--l. 27998--><p class="indent" >  “And we need to build on that. Perhaps we could get some celebrities with out
opinions to stand forward make guest appearances within the game, to target
individuals.”
</p><!--l. 28002--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s all about fostering the right prejudices.”
</p><!--l. 28004--><p class="indent" >  “Appealing to peoples&#x2019; prejudices. Yes, it&#x2019;s a powerful springboard.”
</p><!--l. 28006--><p class="indent" >  She gives up being abrasive and even sounds sympathetic to his concern. Perhaps
his male charms have not worn oﬀ entirely.
</p><!--l. 28009--><p class="indent" >  “You know, when I was young my father told me not to blow my nose on toilet
paper, because toilet paper was ‘dirty&#x2019;. A simple association of ideas, transferring
what you do with a toilet into something that you use in the process.”

</p><!--l. 28014--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s nice.”
</p><!--l. 28016--><p class="indent" >  “But true. On another occasion he changed his mind and said toilet paper is actually
sterilized. This was a reaction to his fear of germs, but it altered his behaviour
completely. Two diﬀerent perceptions from the same facts.”
</p><!--l. 28020--><p class="indent" >  “Cortina wants to eliminate these prejudices, by educating people, and
have everyone just thinking for themselves, but that is missing the point isn&#x2019;t
it?”
</p><!--l. 28024--><p class="indent" >  “People like simpliﬁcations. It saves them from having to think every single time
they do something.” She taps her temple. “Here we are, equipped with the most
powerful processing device in the known universe and all most folks want to do is
switch it oﬀ.”
</p><!--l. 28029--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s what our business is trying to do.”
</p><!--l. 28031--><p class="indent" >  “Dennis Morris, think what are you saying. We need to see thinking as a partner of
ideology, not as its enemy. Here&#x2019;s another example for you. Homosexuality. People
started out believing that homosexuality was wrong because it goes against God.
Attitudes change and people ﬁgure out that science is the dominant authority,
so then suddenly it&#x2019;s against nature, i.e. science. After a while you ﬁgure
out that nature does what it pleases, not what you want and, after a while,
homosexuals actually become cool and exotic. Then you begin to admire the
stereotypes, and you start saying things like homosexuals must make the perfect
interior designers because they combine a feminine aesthetic with a masculine
pragmatism. We&#x2019;re constantly trading one prejudice for another. It doesn&#x2019;t
get any better. It doesn&#x2019;t get any more correct. It just gets diﬀerent. There
is a conservation of prejudice. The trick is to make sure that the facts are
correct.”
</p><!--l. 28047--><p class="indent" >  “These are the ﬁlters by which we view the world,” he mutters to himself, as he
processes.
</p><!--l. 28050--><p class="indent" >  “So what are people&#x2019;s fears about education?”
</p><!--l. 28052--><p class="indent" >  “The fear of failure. Of not being good enough?”
</p><!--l. 28054--><p class="indent" >  “Is it stronger than the fear of what might happen if you don&#x2019;t learn anything?”
</p><!--l. 28057--><p class="indent" >  “Hmm. Is education perceived as necessary?”
</p><!--l. 28059--><p class="indent" >  “People are too comfortable to care about necessities today: they have a safety net.
Except for the very poor, and they can&#x2019;t aﬀord an education anyway. I have
seen African kids swear to the importance of education in ways that people
in the West used to. Now we look at them and say—of course you should
get educated, so that you can be like us. But we just don&#x2019;t see that they are
already better than that, because they understand that they are ignorant and we
don&#x2019;t.”
</p><!--l. 28067--><p class="indent" >  “Whew.” Den taps some notes onto his mobile. “So we should remind
people of their ignorance? I&#x2019;m not sure that sounds like a campaign we could
sell.”
</p><!--l. 28071--><p class="indent" >  “You need some basic competition in the world, Den.” Her Scottish pronunciation
kicks into the accents again. “Supply and demand are only a recipe for status quo.

That is about regulation. But if you need new ideas, then you need innovation. That
requires diversity. It is society&#x2019;s way of searching for good ideas.”
</p><!--l. 28078--><p class="indent" >  “Diversity. But that&#x2019;s the opposite of what we want to make an eﬀective message.
We can&#x2019;t just say: do everything! We want to have a simple, strong focused
message.”
</p><!--l. 28082--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s just a whitewash.” She grins at him, which doesn&#x2019;t help in the slightest. “Now
leave me alone and go to bed.”
</p><!--l. 28085--><p class="indent" >  Once again, he is chasing his tail.
</p><!--l. 28087--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">It&#x2019;s not important that we do our job well, </span>he thinks, <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">but it is important that we are</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">seen to be successful. Should the campaign be about us, rather than them? At least we</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">are a singular focus.</span>
</p><!--l. 28092--><p class="indent" >  He sees little alternative but to consider their own survival ﬁrst. It is primarily that
which will secure their future, their reputation. Now he seems to have come full circle
back to his bedroom conversations with Cathy Kim.
</p><!--l. 28097--><p class="indent" >  Cathy Kim.
</p><!--l. 28099--><p class="indent" >  Did she tell him the answer? Or was it a red herring?
</p><!--l. 28101--><p class="indent" >  And why do his thoughts continually come back to Celia?
</p><!--l. 28106--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

