<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">53</span>
</p><!--l. 28149--><p class="indent" >  Dermot is thinking that he would like to give up on the farce. Preeta has not
been back for several days after her ﬂing on the town, and he has not been
motivated to ﬁgure things out without her. Since then he has been hiding
himself. Now he has heard from Bishop that she is spending time with this new
girl.
</p><!--l. 28155--><p class="indent" >  Another girl.
</p><!--l. 28157--><p class="indent" >  He has been holed up in his old oﬃce, along with his gaming buddies.
</p><!--l. 28159--><p class="indent" >  “So you know this one idea they had to change the continent of Africa and
North Korea was, like, to kidnap kids,” a voice insists. “You know, like alien
abductions.”
</p><!--l. 28163--><p class="indent" >  “What the hell is the point of that?”
</p><!--l. 28165--><p class="indent" >  “Then what you do is to give them an education. A Western education. Then you
return them to the jungle or wherever, like nothing ever happened.”
</p><!--l. 28169--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s cool.”
</p><!--l. 28171--><p class="indent" >  “The abductees have experienced a diﬀerent world and they now know how to think
and how to deal with the modern world.”
</p><!--l. 28174--><p class="indent" >  “You let them be direction agents for change. The idea is that they will be the new
generation that breaks with the past.”
</p><!--l. 28177--><p class="indent" >  “Well, it&#x2019;s plausible, I suppose.”
</p><!--l. 28179--><p class="indent" >  “So does this makes us conspiracy nuts or just cynical?”
</p><!--l. 28181--><p class="indent" >  “Neither. It&#x2019;s a perfectly legit op&#x2019;.”
</p><!--l. 28183--><p class="indent" >  They laugh.
</p><!--l. 28185--><p class="indent" >  “Op&#x2019;?”
</p><!--l. 28187--><p class="indent" >  “Intelligence operation.”
</p><!--l. 28189--><p class="indent" >  Dermot examines the range of expressions on their faces. It is not always easy to
know who is serious and who is joking.
</p><!--l. 28192--><p class="indent" >  “What about when they wanted to invade all those middle eastern countries?”

</p><!--l. 28195--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah, then they had to spread this doctrine of war and interventionism, whereas
they had been like totally hands oﬀ before then.”
</p><!--l. 28199--><p class="indent" >  “That was when they ruined Star Trek—the most important TV show ever made.
Coz, you can&#x2019;t have a message of peace and optimism getting so popular across the
world. So better change all the stories from peace and exploration to shoot up battles,
and broken prime directive interventions. Just like the U.S. government. It went from
being like a model of what the government could be to an imitation of what it really is.
Then the fans killed it.”
</p><!--l. 28207--><p class="indent" >  “Are you sure?”
</p><!--l. 28209--><p class="indent" >  “So are you saying it was conscious manipulation that caused the gulf wars or vice
versa?”
</p><!--l. 28212--><p class="indent" >  “I dunno, man. I&#x2019;m just pissed oﬀ about Star Trek.”
</p><!--l. 28214--><p class="indent" >  Dermot is glad of the company of his colleagues. In one way, they drive him crazy,
but at least he understands what they want from him. At least he doesn&#x2019;t want to have
sex with them.
</p><!--l. 28218--><p class="indent" >  As for this business of Bishop&#x2019;s, he is glad to get away from it for a while. He is
employed to work on gaming related projects, on an hourly basis, but it doesn&#x2019;t say
anything in his contract about hunting down and persecuting anyone for their religious
beliefs. What are they? The Ku Klux Klan backwards? Why is he so hung up
on religion, anyway? Dermot can agree that abuse of power is a bad thing,
but isn&#x2019;t the church a good thing? If it brings comfort to people who cannot
succeed without help, isn&#x2019;t that as good as any other kind of institution of
society?
</p><!--l. 28227--><p class="indent" >  Bishop has been looking tired and grey lately: lined and dusty, as if he has been
cradled and absorbed by some giant moth. It has not seemed like a good time to
disturb him. That and the fact that he is avoiding Preeta.
</p><!--l. 28231--><p class="indent" >  Bishop says that they are trying to make society stable, but Dermot is not sure that
he really understands the logic. Stability means that something is sluggish, hard to
change, hard to control. Isn&#x2019;t it change he wants? Too much stability is called
stagnation.
</p><!--l. 28236--><p class="indent" >  And what would it take to de-stabilize it? Rumour or propaganda, call it what you
like. These are the weapons of information. Viruses that spread like wildﬁre. It doesn&#x2019;t
take long to discredit someone. But what are the repercussions?
</p><!--l. 28242--><p class="indent" >  Dermot is trying to concern himself with other things: things that do not hurt his
head.
</p><!--l. 28245--><p class="indent" >  Even just burying himself in the details of work on the project would be okay, if he
didn&#x2019;t feel so pathetic. But he does. Where did all these imported geniuses come
from? What use is he? Now there is a third person involved. Sara. Another girl. He
wishes he could face them with cheer and self-conﬁdence, but all he feels is that he is
a freak.
</p><!--l. 28252--><p class="indent" >  Preeta has started to send him messages. Where are you? What are you doing? Now
he has received another message from her. He ought to reply, but it is diﬃcult. He&#x2019;ll
do it soon.

</p><!--l. 28256--><p class="indent" >  The last one says that they are going out to buy clothes: she and the new girl. Does
he want to join them and have a make-over? Sounds like a nightmare. What does he
know about that anyway? Clothes ought to be just simple to choose and cheap so
you can throw them away and get new ones often. And someone should just
decide for you what to wear, so you don&#x2019;t have to spend time and worry
thinking about it. It should be the government&#x2019;s responsibility to decorate the
people.
</p><!--l. 28264--><p class="indent" >  He texts “I can&#x2019;t make it, I have a date.” Then he deletes the text and cancels the
reply.
</p><!--l. 28267--><p class="indent" >  He wishes he did have a date. That would be an exaggeration, but he has been
working his way to persuade Christina to let him come back and see her. He needs to
see her. He wants to touch her. He can almost imagine the grimace of her suspicion.
The trouble is that all he can think about is her. He wants to save her, to hold her, to . .
. you know.
</p><!--l. 28273--><p class="indent" >  He read once that no one ever loved anyone for being perfect. You generally end up
loving people for their faults. If that is true, then he must be madly consumed by love
for Christina.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 28279--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 28280--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 28283--><p class="indent" >  Christmas is approaching and it brings with it a rush of dread for Dermot.
It means that he will be alone again; or. more correctly, it means that his
aloneness will be on display again. He will be tasked to defend it, by all the
self-righteous assholes who think their lives are better than his. And know they are
right.
</p><!--l. 28289--><p class="indent" >  Christmas trees are going up in shop windows and this symbol of good cheers has
activated his depression gene, ﬂooding him with useless hormonal misery. I am a
mutant, he thinks. This crude symbolic slogan induces sickness in him, not health and
cheer.
</p><!--l. 28294--><p class="indent" >  He has been building up his resolve. There must be some kind of aerobics
programme or something that he could join to improve his self-image.
</p><!--l. 28298--><p class="indent" >  He has been in and looked at the work the others are doing. This new girl is
pretty good, for an amateur. The campaign they are supposed to be ﬁghting
seems to be accelerating. Most of the available surfaces are now occupied by
subliminal advertising. About the only thing they still have control over is the
weather.
</p><!--l. 28305--><p class="indent" >  They are trying to make a succubus by taking an existing agent and modifying it.
They are guessing at these things and doing quite well, but they need his help. How
could anyone but him see what he sees inside this code? Look at the beauty of the
stanzas of precision language! Maybe he is not so useless after all. He feels a bit like

a school child who has been asked to comment on the meaning of Keats
except that, where such humanities left him only confused and unmoved,
these stanzas burst with meaning, both intriguing and logical. He knows this
stuﬀ.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 28316--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 28317--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 28320--><p class="indent" >  It is a moody day beyond the glass pane, as though the world has been pulled inside
a giant bottle, like those model ships they used to make. The canopy of the cloud and
light seems to press down upon the streets, as if squeezing from it an electricity that
lifts the hairs on his neck.
</p><!--l. 28326--><p class="indent" >  Preeta has ﬁnally persuaded him to meet. Alone. He does not want to see the new
girl, or the others. Not yet, at least. She places her coﬀee cup down on the window sill
table, and climbs up onto the stool beside him. They sit there looking out onto the
town from the window.
</p><!--l. 28332--><p class="indent" >  “They put the tinsel on the trees all wrong here,” Preeta says, looking at the tree
across the road and trying to strike up a conversation.
</p><!--l. 28336--><p class="indent" >  The silver tinsel is hung in radial stripes: spokes emanating from the point of the
tree to the base, like go-faster stripes.
</p><!--l. 28339--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s the way we do it here,” he defends.
</p><!--l. 28341--><p class="indent" >  “But the tinsel is supposed to look like snow resting on the branches. You&#x2019;re
supposed to coil it around the tree.”
</p><!--l. 28344--><p class="indent" >  He looks at her blankly.
</p><!--l. 28346--><p class="indent" >  She nudges him. “It is supposed to look like a tree, not a nuclear warhead!”
</p><!--l. 28350--><p class="indent" >  It is cold out in the wintery wonderland. They can sit and do their work in the
coﬀee shop overlooking the shoe store on Grensen: on the edge of Oslo reality. It is
hard to work here, with the bustling interruption of the customers, but it is pleasant
until someone opens the door and douses them with icicles of frozen air that stab at
their bare skin.
</p><!--l. 28357--><p class="indent" >  The coming of Christmas has always been hard for Dermot. It is the time when
society crystallizes into a single shape, a shape into which he cannot ﬁt. The
lattice has no space for him in its perfection. It is the ultimate inducement to
conformity.
</p><!--l. 28362--><p class="indent" >  “I can never quite get used to the roads here,” she says. “They seem too perfect, too
cold.”
</p><!--l. 28365--><p class="indent" >  “They work, more or less.”
</p><!--l. 28367--><p class="indent" >  “Look,” she says. “I am sorry about me. I behaved very badly. We might have
ﬁnished our succubus if I hadn&#x2019;t pushed you away. I am very ashamed.”
</p><!--l. 28371--><p class="indent" >  He shakes his head. “Don&#x2019;t worry about it.”
</p><!--l. 28373--><p class="indent" >  She shakes her head.

</p><!--l. 28375--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m just a bit over sensitive these days. It&#x2019;s not your fault.”
</p><!--l. 28377--><p class="indent" >  “And I can be thoughtless.”
</p><!--l. 28379--><p class="indent" >  He smiles slightly, feeling better.
</p><!--l. 28381--><p class="indent" >  “So how is the project working out without me?”
</p><!--l. 28383--><p class="indent" >  “Vibe, the new girl, is very good.”
</p><!--l. 28385--><p class="indent" >  “Vibe?”
</p><!--l. 28387--><p class="indent" >  “Well, her name is really Sara. I&#x2019;m not quite sure why she calls herself
Vibe.”
</p><!--l. 28390--><p class="indent" >  “What&#x2019;s she like?”
</p><!--l. 28392--><p class="indent" >  “She&#x2019;s very nice. You&#x2019;d like her.”
</p><!--l. 28394--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">That&#x2019;s what I&#x2019;m afraid of.</span>
</p><!--l. 28396--><p class="indent" >  “And she is not frightened of anything.” She laughs a little nervously. “I think she is
quite fearless.”
</p><!--l. 28399--><p class="indent" >  Dermot laughs in his own way. “What about you? ”
</p><!--l. 28401--><p class="indent" >  “Me?”
</p><!--l. 28403--><p class="indent" >  “You made it here. All this way from Malaysia.”
</p><!--l. 28405--><p class="indent" >  “Oh.”
</p><!--l. 28407--><p class="indent" >  “How could you do that? I mean just cast yourself into the arms of fate like
that?”
</p><!--l. 28410--><p class="indent" >  She shrugs. “I have been doing that all my life. I have always been lucky by it. Not
bravery, something else.”
</p><!--l. 28413--><p class="indent" >  Dermot looks at her with pained but genuine admiration. How he wishes that he
could be the same.
</p><!--l. 28416--><p class="indent" >  Preeta says. “Well look. Someone got me ﬁred. But at the same time, someone sent
me here.”
</p><!--l. 28419--><p class="indent" >  “Well, I&#x2019;m glad you&#x2019;re here,” he says, surprising himself most of all.
</p><!--l. 28421--><p class="indent" >  Preeta grins broadly and, seeing his crimson cheeks glow, decides not to let him
dwell on his embarrassment. “I&#x2019;ve been out with the new girl and her friend quite a
lot. I like them.”
</p><!--l. 28425--><p class="indent" >  “Really. What do you do?”
</p><!--l. 28427--><p class="indent" >  “Mostly drink beer and meet friends. Stay out late.”
</p><!--l. 28429--><p class="indent" >  “Last night? I tried to contact you.”
</p><!--l. 28431--><p class="indent" >  “Mostly, we drank a lot of beer until very late. Then Sara&#x2019;s friend came with even
more beer. She said it was for breakfast.” She giggles.
</p><!--l. 28435--><p class="indent" >  They settle down into a quiet pondering, watching the snowﬂakes fall. Preeta sings,
“I&#x2019;m dreaming of a white. . ..”
</p><!--l. 28438--><p class="indent" >  “Girlfriend,” Dermot ﬁnishes,
</p><!--l. 28440--><p class="indent" >  They laugh.
</p><!--l. 28442--><p class="indent" >  They are not so diﬀerent, she thinks. What is the diﬀerence between ﬂeeing a
physical persecution and ﬂeeing a mental persecution from yourself? She actually
feels sympathy for him. She is not accustomed to having feelings for anyone at
all.

</p><!--l. 28447--><p class="indent" >  “You know,” she says, “I am going to be here for the winter at least. You
could invite me for Christmas.” She adds: “If you wanted to, of course. .
.”
</p><!--l. 28451--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t you want to spend Christmas with your girl?”
</p><!--l. 28453--><p class="indent" >  She shrugs. “I don&#x2019;t even know her. And besides, perhaps I would like to escape
from myself for a week.”
</p><!--l. 28456--><p class="indent" >  He smiles. “All right, I&#x2019;d like that.”
</p><!--l. 28458--><p class="indent" >  “You are not Christian are you? I mean songs and stuﬀ?”
</p><!--l. 28460--><p class="indent" >  He laughs. “No, nothing like that.”
</p><!--l. 28464--><p class="indent" >  “Didn&#x2019;t you celebrate Christmas in Malaysia?”
</p><!--l. 28466--><p class="indent" >  “I was brought up a Muslim.”
</p><!--l. 28468--><p class="indent" >  “Not even secular Christmas?”
</p><!--l. 28470--><p class="indent" >  “What&#x2019;s that?”
</p><!--l. 28472--><p class="indent" >  “What most people celebrate.”
</p><!--l. 28474--><p class="indent" >  “I didn&#x2019;t know about it. Or I don&#x2019;t think I did.”
</p><!--l. 28476--><p class="indent" >  “Not even from TV?”
</p><!--l. 28478--><p class="indent" >  She shrugs.
</p><!--l. 28480--><p class="indent" >  “You wouldn&#x2019;t have been allowed?”
</p><!--l. 28482--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t know.”
</p><!--l. 28484--><p class="indent" >  “Really.”
</p><!--l. 28486--><p class="indent" >  She looks glumly into her coﬀee. “The hardest thing to accept sometimes is that
you can actually think for yourself. We are taught to believe what people tell us. We
are encouraged not to ask too many questions.”
</p><!--l. 28491--><p class="indent" >  “For the sake of eﬃciency it is best not to question everything all of the
time”
</p><!--l. 28494--><p class="indent" >  “Even when I was paid to think, I was not expected to think for myself. My boss
thought of me just a stupid slave.”
</p><!--l. 28497--><p class="indent" >  “So you left?”
</p><!--l. 28499--><p class="indent" >  “So I . . . branched out.”
</p><!--l. 28501--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s what you get for underestimating people.”
</p><!--l. 28503--><p class="indent" >  “Well, the reality is that I was sacked for my thinking.”
</p><!--l. 28505--><p class="indent" >  “Sacked?”
</p><!--l. 28507--><p class="indent" >  “He couldn&#x2019;t lose face. My boss. You know, in India we have castes. We don&#x2019;t talk
about it much, but everyone understands it.”
</p><!--l. 28510--><p class="indent" >  “Perhaps you should.”
</p><!--l. 28512--><p class="indent" >  “The ruling class believes that the lower castes are . . . beneath them. There is
not just upper class and lower class in India – there is a whole spectrum of
prejudice.”
</p><!--l. 28516--><p class="indent" >  He shrugs barely with his lips. “I&#x2019;m sorry.”
</p><!--l. 28518--><p class="indent" >  “I will not say that society could do without classes but I will say that lower class
does not mean worthless or stupid. I was the one who solve the problems,” she says,
suppressing anger.
</p><!--l. 28522--><p class="indent" >  He nods.

</p><!--l. 28524--><p class="indent" >  “Perhaps it is not something you have experienced directly.”
</p><!--l. 28526--><p class="indent" >  He shakes his head, uncertainly. Generally he is good enough at punishing
himself.
</p><!--l. 28529--><p class="indent" >  “It is reason enough to run away.”
</p><!--l. 28531--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t you feel much like a slave here too? I mean, is it so much better
here?”
</p><!--l. 28534--><p class="indent" >  “Here it is diﬀerent,” she thinks aloud. “I am treated like an equal, even though I am
expected to do a job.” She smiles. “Besides, you don&#x2019;t work very hard here. For me, it
is like a holiday.”
</p><!--l. 28538--><p class="indent" >  Dermot grins and hides it in his mocha latte. She might be right about some of the
family people, but she obviously hasn&#x2019;t seen the guys at SmartMob Gaming and
Hosting.
</p><!--l. 28542--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;ve been working quite a bit lately, but not on the right things,” he admits.
</p><!--l. 28545--><p class="indent" >  “Does that mean you are going to come and help us ﬁnish our succubus?”
</p><!--l. 28547--><p class="indent" >  “I suppose I should.”
</p><!--l. 28549--><p class="indent" >  “You don&#x2019;t want to miss it. It is actually a lot of fun since the new girl came. She
makes a nice atmosphere.”
</p><!--l. 28552--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Change the subject.</span>
</p><!--l. 28554--><p class="indent" >  “When you ﬁrst came here, you said there was a problem with the game that might
work to our advantage. At least, that&#x2019;s how I heard you.”
</p><!--l. 28557--><p class="indent" >  “Yes. I said that. There are problems.”
</p><!--l. 28559--><p class="indent" >  “What kind of problems?”
</p><!--l. 28561--><p class="indent" >  “Well the visible symptoms are things like broken billboards and sims going
wrong. There are bugs in the system. I realized that much before I came
here.”
</p><!--l. 28565--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, I&#x2019;ve seen that.”
</p><!--l. 28567--><p class="indent" >  “But that&#x2019;s not the problem. It&#x2019;s just what we see.”
</p><!--l. 28569--><p class="indent" >  “So what is the problem?”
</p><!--l. 28571--><p class="indent" >  “Well, I don&#x2019;t know. My guess is that there are too many human interests in the
simulations. Money, power, propaganda – you know, it&#x2019;s all going on. Big companies
are playing the game like a new marketplace. Smart buﬀering can ﬁlter out advertising
from video, but not from the game, so the game represents a new channel for selling
things. That much is obvious.”
</p><!--l. 28578--><p class="indent" >  “So is there a problem with the advertising?”
</p><!--l. 28580--><p class="indent" >  “Well, yes and no. I think it is the outsourcing of the game coding that has led to the
problems we are seeing with rendering.”
</p><!--l. 28583--><p class="indent" >  “What do you mean?”
</p><!--l. 28585--><p class="indent" >  “The game is too ambitious for any one company or organization. They have split
up the development into partnerships, with a set of rules and regulations in the
contracts.”
</p><!--l. 28590--><p class="indent" >  Getting a message through to someone when you want to is not as straightforward
as it could be, he knows, from personal experience. But it helps at least to have a rule
book, so you know what game you&#x2019;re playing. He wishes he had one for his personal

life.
</p><!--l. 28595--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah – we&#x2019;re one of them.”
</p><!--l. 28597--><p class="indent" >  “Ruling class, working class.”
</p><!--l. 28599--><p class="indent" >  “Well, and a bit of anarchy. . .”
</p><!--l. 28601--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s too big.”
</p><!--l. 28603--><p class="indent" >  “For users?”
</p><!--l. 28605--><p class="indent" >  “For the planet.”
</p><!--l. 28607--><p class="indent" >  Dermot laughs but cuts its short when he sees her reaction. “Sorry. I don&#x2019;t
understand what you mean.”
</p><!--l. 28610--><p class="indent" >  “They have tried to cope with the demand by outsourcing to slave companies.”
</p><!--l. 28613--><p class="indent" >  “Yes. Like us.”
</p><!--l. 28615--><p class="indent" >  “The errors are occurring because of the sourcing companies are just following the
rule book. But there is an error or an omission in the book. They haven&#x2019;t considered
the eﬀect of conﬂicts between the billboards and the avatar simulations. There are
segmentation problems that I have seen in the code during testing.”
</p><!--l. 28621--><p class="indent" >  Dermot shrugs. “Bane of the programmer. Segmentation.”
</p><!--l. 28623--><p class="indent" >  “But by having so many people working on the same thing, without any reasonable
protections, there are collisions and contentions.”
</p><!--l. 28626--><p class="indent" >  He nods. “I&#x2019;ve noticed some of that, it&#x2019;s a pretty simplistic interface.”
</p><!--l. 28628--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s why people trust it, but trust doesn&#x2019;t imply reliability. Well, that&#x2019;s only one
problem. The game has built in load balancing, right?”
</p><!--l. 28631--><p class="indent" >  He nods.
</p><!--l. 28633--><p class="indent" >  “It moves the diﬀerent characters from machine to machine. That&#x2019;s how they can
run it all on cheap PC hardware and spread it around the world and capture third
world markets.”
</p><!--l. 28637--><p class="indent" >  “Of course,” he says impatiently. Does she think he&#x2019;s stupid now?
</p><!--l. 28639--><p class="indent" >  “But even with the load balancing the expected throughput is now too
high.”
</p><!--l. 28641--><p class="indent" >  He waits for the conclusion.
</p><!--l. 28643--><p class="indent" >  “Not for the system, but for the users. There is a limit to how much information
humans can absorb. They are already at the maximum theoretical limit for human
perception. If you anything bigger, it just starts to get worse.”
</p><!--l. 28648--><p class="indent" >  “How do you know what the limit is?”
</p><!--l. 28650--><p class="indent" >  “I was reading a research paper from somewhere in Japan. They have a lot of
experience of this.”
</p><!--l. 28653--><p class="indent" >  He is giving her a look.
</p><!--l. 28655--><p class="indent" >  “I read sometimes, okay? I want to go back to college when I can aﬀord
to.”
</p><!--l. 28658--><p class="indent" >  “Okay,” he says. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">What did I say?</span>
</p><!--l. 28660--><p class="indent" >  “I was reading some of the references that are in the deep documentation for the
game manuals. It seemed like a natural thing to do to ﬁgure out this problem, so that
our company could make a good impression.”
</p><!--l. 28665--><p class="indent" >  “You think there are too many messages in the game.”

</p><!--l. 28667--><p class="indent" >  “The density is most likely too high. Even programmers and testers are being
aﬀected. I saw things in Malaysia that you probably do not have access to. When they
send the job to us, they don&#x2019;t expect us to understand anything, but what they don&#x2019;t
realize that we do our jobs well.”
</p><!--l. 28672--><p class="indent" >  “So?”
</p><!--l. 28674--><p class="indent" >  “Something has not been going right. There are rooms in the VR where odd stuﬀ
has been going on. Some of the controlling avatars have been altered and the program
seems to be stabilizing around a conﬁguration that is not what we were asked to
deliver.”
</p><!--l. 28679--><p class="indent" >  “I think that the process surrounding the program and all of its integrated pieces has
somehow reached the point where it is working against itself. The game rules are
about persuasion and I think that, in testing this game, the persuasion has
fed back—persuaded some of the programmers in your team to alter the
avatars.”
</p><!--l. 28685--><p class="indent" >  Dermot&#x2019;s eyes widen. What a seriously cool idea. A program that re-programs its
programmer. Could it be possible? There is something in what she is saying. That is
reason of itself to go back and help them work on this.
</p><!--l. 28690--><p class="indent" >  “I am not saying that this is a simple or direct action. It is subtle. It has layers of
complexity. It cannot be just a simple thing. It is more like a popular movement that
has been started.”
</p><!--l. 28694--><p class="indent" >  “Did you report it to the bug centre?”
</p><!--l. 28696--><p class="indent" >  “The requests got rejected every time I tried to initiate contact.”
</p><!--l. 28698--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I know that feeling</span>, Dermot thinks, thinking of his attempts to contact
Christina..
</p><!--l. 28701--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s a trust problem. Actually it is easier to wait until the other party comes to you.
That way it is easier for them to trust the connection.”
</p><!--l. 28705--><p class="indent" >  Dermot considers the idea, still thinking of Christina. There is something to
it.
</p><!--l. 28707--><p class="indent" >  “We still need to work on this campaign. We can&#x2019;t do anything about the
