</p><!--l. 28998--><p class="indent" >  The bar is more or less empty, and Joe has forsaken his new jeans for a pair of beige
slacks and a brown shirt, under his anorak. Back to old habits. Chocolate colours and
clichéd styles. Today, Joe looks like a Christian missionary. What happened to
Africa&#x2019;s burgeoning fashion industry?
</p><!--l. 29005--><p class="indent" >  “You know the latest? The American group has bought our youth organization. It&#x2019;s
going to be taken over by the Methodist church of Atlanta.”
</p><!--l. 29009--><p class="indent" >  “Nice.”
</p><!--l. 29011--><p class="indent" >  ”I have to go and meet them.”
</p><!--l. 29013--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s why you&#x2019;re looking so stylish today.”
</p><!--l. 29015--><p class="indent" >  Joe grunts as he sips at his beer. “And something else.”
</p><!--l. 29017--><p class="indent" >  Jonas raises an eyebrow.
</p><!--l. 29019--><p class="indent" >  “We were raided by police yesterday.””
</p><!--l. 29021--><p class="indent" >  “Really? What happened?”
</p><!--l. 29023--><p class="indent" >  “Terror alert.”
</p><!--l. 29025--><p class="indent" >  “Terror alert? Muslims?”
</p><!--l. 29027--><p class="indent" >  He shakes his head. “Christians. They&#x2019;ve been buying just about everything that
plugs straight into the psyche. Then they can stick their corporate logo onto it and
claim the authority of Jesus Christ.”
</p><!--l. 29032--><p class="indent" >  “Jesus Christ,” Jonas agrees and gulps his beer.
</p><!--l. 29034--><p class="indent" >  It feels good to be hiding out with Joe in this bar. The past couple of weeks has
been intense to the point of exhaustion. Jonas&#x2019; lack of self-control has made the issue
of the diversion of research funds into a national news item. Some even think that
international news agencies have taken an interest in the story. The furore has been
building and he is becoming inundated with requests for interviews and comments.
Perhaps this was not strictly what he intended, but it bears a certain moral
justice.
</p><!--l. 29042--><p class="indent" >  “You know, it got me thinking. The policeman who coordinated the arrest when you
were being followed. He said something about these vigilante groups originating in

youth groups and centres. Kids of around eighteen who are looking for their purpose
in the world. I started asking questions around some of the kids who spend a lot of
time on the net.”
</p><!--l. 29049--><p class="indent" >  “And?”
</p><!--l. 29051--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t know. Some of them might even come from our group.”
</p><!--l. 29053--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t you wish you had that research money now?”
</p><!--l. 29055--><p class="indent" >  Jonas drinks a slug of beer and looks around the bar. He likes to see the art and the
rows of bottles on the shelves, even if he never tastes any of it. Old beery habits die
hard. A few more people in the bar wouldn&#x2019;t hurt, as long as they were there to shield
them from attention rather than to demand their piece. None of the regular ﬁxtures are
here.
</p><!--l. 29062--><p class="indent" >  “Radical Islam or Christianity. The return to tribalism,” he philosophizes. “Kids
who are eighteen or nineteen, trying to understand the world. Angry and disowned.
Whether they come from the foothills of Kashmir or Setesdal, they are all ruled with
an iron ﬁst by elders who maintain the tribal traditions.”
</p><!--l. 29068--><p class="indent" >  “There are people out there just waiting to prey on kids of that age. You ﬁnd people
spreading out leaﬂets at Mosques and churches. Even at our group. I haven&#x2019;t
noticed it much fortunately, but I&#x2019;m sure it goes on. They are careful that
their spreading programs don&#x2019;t target people like me who could put a stop to
it.”
</p><!--l. 29074--><p class="indent" >  “These are dangerous times.” There is a certain exhaustion in his voice.
</p><!--l. 29076--><p class="indent" >  Joe continues. “The Evangelical Christians are tribalizing the south of the U.S. like
an industry now, and even here in parts of Scandinavia. They are isolating themselves
from the wider law, dealing with problems internally and ignoring the criminals
within their midst. People are in denial. Europe is becoming Africa, as Africa tries to
become Europe.”
</p><!--l. 29083--><p class="indent" >  Jonas laughs. “Africa? I never thought of it that way.”
</p><!--l. 29085--><p class="indent" >  Joe shrugs. “Sure, why not. The problem in Africa has always been that people will
not rise to the challenge of helping each other out of poverty. They think
small. They don&#x2019;t trust government. Government has been the enemy for so
long, so tribalism persists. If you don&#x2019;t have a sense of wider civic duty, how
can you create a civil society? Basic services, impartial administration. .
.”
</p><!--l. 29092--><p class="indent" >  Good to see Joe has not forgotten his intellectual heritage in working with these
kids, Jonas thinks. Youth centres need people like him with a smarter version of
reality than they normally oﬀer. If people can just get past ﬁguring out which
gang to belong to, it might be possible to save society from the breakup it is
experiencing.
</p><!--l. 29098--><p class="indent" >  “Are you going to stay on at the youth centre?”
</p><!--l. 29100--><p class="indent" >  “Not sure I can.”
</p><!--l. 29102--><p class="indent" >  “They want to get rid of you?”
</p><!--l. 29104--><p class="indent" >  “No. They want me to stay, but I can&#x2019;t swallow this new style of leadership. At the
same time, I don&#x2019;t want to abandon the kids.”

</p><!--l. 29107--><p class="indent" >  “What do they have in mind for it?”
</p><!--l. 29109--><p class="indent" >  “More like a church community with prayer meetings and preaching.”
</p><!--l. 29111--><p class="indent" >  “I suppose that&#x2019;s what they do.”
</p><!--l. 29113--><p class="indent" >  “Missionaries do not have to spread their doctrine as part of their work. We have
always tried to keep that part of the church out of the centres. We want people to think
for themselves. Most of them are there precisely because others have been doing their
thinking for them, in the ﬁrst place.”
</p><!--l. 29119--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s your French education showing through.”
</p><!--l. 29121--><p class="indent" >  “Liberté, egalité, fraternité? It&#x2019;s not politics either.”
</p><!--l. 29123--><p class="indent" >  “You know what they say. Religious leaders, are just politicians in dresses.”
</p><!--l. 29126--><p class="indent" >  “They say that?”
</p><!--l. 29128--><p class="indent" >  “Apparently.”
</p><!--l. 29130--><p class="indent" >  “It doesn&#x2019;t have much to do with the spirit anymore. People don&#x2019;t think that God is
listening, maybe.”
</p><!--l. 29133--><p class="indent" >  “Cause God never got himself a mobile. . .”
</p><!--l. 29135--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t laugh, Jonas.”
</p><!--l. 29137--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m not laughing. I am saying it is what you can expect if you place all your
hope in someone else. People have to take responsibility for themselves. It&#x2019;s
just no good to palm oﬀ the responsibility on someone else or something
else.”
</p><!--l. 29143--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s why we&#x2019;re here, getting drunk?”
</p><!--l. 29145--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s why we&#x2019;re here, getting drunk.”
</p><!--l. 29147--><p class="indent" >  “Too many people, just falling apart. You can see them one moment working well
in some niche of society, getting along, playing their role. Then something changes
and they cannot adapt.”
</p><!--l. 29151--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">We don&#x2019;t make kids that can adapt any more. They are too protected, too factory</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">moulded. They learn one thing – just one thing and when they are no longer needed,</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">they get thrown on the garbage pile. A pile of wasted humanity, sustained with pain</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">and reality killers.</span>
</p><!--l. 29156--><p class="indent" >  Jonas drinks from his own glass.
</p><!--l. 29158--><p class="indent" >  “You know, I&#x2019;ve seen kids <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">age </span>from twenty-seven to forty-something in just a year.
Youth vanishes in an instant. I&#x2019;ve seen it many times. The girls get thin and
starve, then they get help and they get fat and red, with high blood pressure.
Skin creases and bulges. They end up at the centres. Lost, helpless. We try
to remind them about how to live in a society, except it&#x2019;s not a society this
thing you have here. It&#x2019;s a machine now. And if you don&#x2019;t ﬁt in, you are just
replaced by a new part, not repaired. People are just components to be replaced
here.”
</p><!--l. 29168--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Good intentions fraught . . .</span>
</p><!--l. 29171--><p class="indent" >  Joe studies his distant expression. “Do you think I am too weak? Do you think that
I should just pick up and move on – go somewhere else and start again? Or should I
stay and ﬁght, like you?” He points to a newspaper. “They are advertising that now.
Kids call it rebooting. You do a reset on your life. Move somewhere, start

again.”
</p><!--l. 29178--><p class="indent" >  “Why run away?”
</p><!--l. 29180--><p class="indent" >  “Is it running away? Or is it seeking adventure?”
</p><!--l. 29182--><p class="indent" >  “If you need to ask I think you know the answer.”
</p><!--l. 29184--><p class="indent" >  Joseph regards him with his powerful black features and penetrating eyes. “Jonas,
look at all you have done. You have achieved far more than I ever have. Every time I
look at you, something has changed. You have achieved something and that is
good.”
</p><!--l. 29189--><p class="indent" >  Jonas laughs. “What have I done?”
</p><!--l. 29191--><p class="indent" >  “Your research. Knowledge, learning.”
</p><!--l. 29193--><p class="indent" >  “No. . . I think that&#x2019;s has all collapsed.”
</p><!--l. 29195--><p class="indent" >  “You have something to show for your work. A legacy.”
</p><!--l. 29197--><p class="indent" >  “What use is it now? The politics of the day are saying that knowledge and research
are pointless.”
</p><!--l. 29200--><p class="indent" >  “People always try to take advantage and knock you down.”
</p><!--l. 29203--><p class="indent" >  “This is the story of the Tower of Bullshit? And all the men did perish? No, I am
not trying to build anything. I am a plumber, Joe. I spend most of my time ﬁxing
things. But I would love to build something again.”
</p><!--l. 29208--><p class="indent" >  “So would I.” Joseph reaches into his back pocket and pulls out a chain. Hanging
on the chain is a small ﬁgure made of wood. “Look. I wanted to give you
something.”
</p><!--l. 29213--><p class="indent" >  “Give me something?”
</p><!--l. 29215--><p class="indent" >  “I got this when I was a child. I kept it because I thought it was a powerful image.”
he says. “Now I would like you to have it.”
</p><!--l. 29218--><p class="indent" >  “Me? But why? Don&#x2019;t you want to keep it?”
</p><!--l. 29220--><p class="indent" >  “For a heathen, you are one of the most spiritual people I know, Jonas. I would like
you to have it.” He dismisses Jonas&#x2019; sceptical expression. “Don&#x2019;t worry, it is not a
Christian thing. It&#x2019;s from the old religions of the west of Africa. Did you know that the
banks of the Niger were one of the few civilizations of the world that were not
hierarchically organized? No pyramid of power. Just distributed cooperation of small
groups.”
</p><!--l. 29228--><p class="indent" >  “I. . .eh. . .did know, yes. That&#x2019;s very kind of you . . . but what have I done to
deserve a gift? And such a precious one?”
</p><!--l. 29231--><p class="indent" >  “Just a little ju-ju between friends.”
</p><!--l. 29233--><p class="indent" >  He smiles and stares at the piece to conceal his embarrassment. How does one
receive such a gift?
</p><!--l. 29236--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Graciously, of course</span>.
</p><!--l. 29238--><p class="indent" >  He shakes Joe&#x2019;s hand and thanks him again, certain that he does not deserve any
such gift. As an academic he has been persuaded to abandon the pursuit of knowledge
to decide on funding policy. He has betrayed his roots. Even as a human
being, he is far from angelic in his attitudes or accomplishments. Kaja would
laugh at him know if she knew of this exchange. If he is so great, what is he
doing hiding out here in a brown bar in the middle of the city, looking for

cardiovascular relief in a glass of beer, instead of standing up to the hawks of
government?
</p><!--l. 29247--><p class="indent" >  Jonas looks down the long bar to where the old drunk usually hangs onto the
woodwork, not talking to anyone, just downing his beer. He is not there today, not yet.
Then a thought strikes him.
</p><!--l. 29252--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Has Joe lost his faith?</span>
</p><!--l. 29254--><p class="indent" >  Jonas&#x2019; eyes looks deeply into his dark friend&#x2019;s face, as if searching for the meaning
of this development. Joe seems to be happy staring into his beer for a moment, and
Jonas feels suddenly tired and worn.
</p><!--l. 29258--><p class="indent" >  It reminds him of something. His life seems to roll past him, as if on ﬁlm and he
sees something that he should have seen a long time ago. He stares back at the space
on the end of the bar, where the old drunk usually hangs out. Where is that loser?
Where is that sad old fuck who comes here to avoid company and drown his
sorrows?
</p><!--l. 29264--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">It&#x2019;s me</span>, he thinks. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I am that sad old fuck.</span>
</p><!--l. 29266--><p class="indent" >  Just give me a beer and let me stagger home alone.
</p><!--l. 29269--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Where did it go wrong?</span>
</p><!--l. 29271--><p class="indent" >  It is possible to do everything right and still fail?
</p><!--l. 29273--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">It&#x2019;s you, idiot.</span>
</p><!--l. 29275--><p class="indent" >  He sees himself staring back from the mirror.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 29280--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 29281--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 29284--><p class="indent" >  Kaja&#x2019;s mother calls and asks him to be more helpful. His son needs him. What do
these people want from him? They profess to care but all they do is demand his
attention. They give him nothing in return, not even understanding. So why do they
hold on to him? Why won&#x2019;t they simply let him go?
</p><!--l. 29291--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Punishment at the hands of our loved ones</span>, Jonas thinks.
</p><!--l. 29293--><p class="indent" >  We are their chance to let down their barriers and let the ﬂood gates roar. An
understanding ear becomes a garbage chute for relief. No doubt he is partially to
blame, but what is it that makes them perceive each issue as a conﬂict, with points to
be won?
</p><!--l. 29299--><p class="indent" >  He can hear her voice even now. “You&#x2019;re so goddamn selﬁsh, Jonas. You buy me a
gift, but you don&#x2019;t get me anything I want. You buy something that you think I should
have. Have you never thought if my feelings? All you can see is your own precious
life.”
</p><!--l. 29305--><p class="indent" >  “And you see more?”
</p><!--l. 29307--><p class="indent" >  “Oh, so now it&#x2019;s my fault? That&#x2019;s typical!”
</p><!--l. 29309--><p class="indent" >  She will spend half the day just stewing in hormones, not getting anywhere, just
feeling confused and lost. There&#x2019;s not a chance of rational thought.

</p><!--l. 29313--><p class="indent" >  “Evenly happy for the rest of your life? How is that possible?”
</p><!--l. 29315--><p class="indent" >  “Do we really need these extremes?”
</p><!--l. 29318--><p class="indent" >  Then his secretary calls. “It&#x2019;s the girl I mentioned. She is still trying to get to you.
You should really take one of her calls, just to give her some satisfaction.”
</p><!--l. 29322--><p class="indent" >  “I know. I should.”
</p><!--l. 29324--><p class="indent" >  Sara is not to blame for this mess; she is still trying to reconcile the changes that
have taken place in such a short space of time with what she thought was the plan for
her future. Suddenly one ﬁnds oneself on a completely diﬀerent road, headed for the
unknown. He knows all about that.
</p><!--l. 29329--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I ought to call Sara, </span>he thinks. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I ought to call Kaja,</span>
</p><!--l. 29331--><p class="indent" >  He has been disinclined to call and discover who she is seeing at this moment in
time. That and all of the chaos of the past weeks seems to have disabled his sense of
responsibility towards his patchy family.
</p><!--l. 29335--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">We hurt the people we love. Why can&#x2019;t we just resist the temptation to strike</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">out?</span>
</p><!--l. 29338--><p class="indent" >  Obviously because there are no barriers. The threshold for venting senseless
frustrations is too low. Everyone needs a valve, but that is no excuse for blasting our
nearest and dearest with bad-tempered steam.
</p><!--l. 29343--><p class="indent" >  Marriage was a release from all that, of course. It transformed the hard creativity of
romancing into a simple contract of obligations. Like the law itself: just an excuse to
stop thinking about how to behave well. Just follow the contract and you will be a
good person. But it didn&#x2019;t last either.
</p><!--l. 29349--><p class="indent" >  Well, he is not convinced. You cannot buy your future in a box, with a money
back guarantee. When you put a dog on a leash it is not generally for its own
good.
</p><!--l. 29353--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Joe has lost his faith.</span>
</p><!--l. 29355--><p class="indent" >  The revelation is like a lightening bolt from the Lord himself. Is the whole
world falling apart? Joe seems to be clinging on to the idea of it, but he has
already lost the battle? And the clothes—is that where the jeans come from?
Perhaps he cannot wear the fake garb of a would-be priest any more. He will
not say it, and Jonas can not ask him, but somehow they both understand
it.
</p><!--l. 29362--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Yes that&#x2019;s it.</span>
</p><!--l. 29364--><p class="indent" >  Jonas can see it. Joseph is too smart, too rational to be a religious man. His faith has
been shaken. He has asked the forbidden questions. But, for now, he is trying to
continue with his duties.
</p><!--l. 29368--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">You can always live a lie, for the sake of appearances, </span>he thinks.
</p><!--l. 29370--><p class="indent" >  Maybe that is actually his easiest path through life?
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 29372--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 29373--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>

<!--l. 29376--><p class="indent" >  Kaja calls and asks for a truce. They have not spoken for some days. He leaves a
message.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 29380--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 29381--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 29386--><p class="indent" >  The man, the bureaucrat, has arrived. He swaggers around his department
like the town bully. The ministry has sent him to make sure that their plan is
enforced.
</p><!--l. 29390--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">His mandate is like my croissant, </span>Jonas thinks <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Layer upon layer of paper thin</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">deception, rolled up and blown up on an empty core of hot air.</span>
</p><!--l. 29394--><p class="indent" >  If only there were some administrative coﬀee one could use to wash it all
down.
</p><!--l. 29397--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">There is no point in my even being here? It is a farce.</span>
</p><!--l. 29403--><p class="indent" >  Presumably they gave him this job to emasculate him. Vociferous researcher: too
smart for his own good, rein him in, neutralize by promotion within the ranks?
Control and regulate. The more they steam towards nominal de-regulation, the more
rules they implement to ‘guide&#x2019; its progress.
</p><!--l. 29409--><p class="indent" >  What remains of his scientiﬁc mind knows that it is useless of them to try, and
useless of himself to protest. You can&#x2019;t cage something that wild and still expect it
to live. It&#x2019;s like putting a rare animal in a zoo, or plucking and pressing a
beautiful ﬂower to have it. Life withers and dies in captivity. The more you try
to control it, the less of it is real. At the same time, you cannot argue with
denial.
</p><!--l. 29417--><p class="indent" >  Now, they are ready just to punish someone who has disobeyed government policy
for the good of the people. So, does all this protestation make him a terrorist? A
revolutionary? Robin Hood?
</p><!--l. 29421--><p class="indent" >  Jonas is right about his decision to oppose them: of that he is certain, but they have
puppies and kittens on their side. How can you argue against a humanitarian cause
and still use words like ‘ethics&#x2019;? Every conscientious person, with respect
for themselves, knows that you are supposed to preserve life in desperate
circumstances. How could one not spend money on the African famine? How could
selﬁsh and elitist research be of any use to mankind when there are people
suﬀering?
</p><!--l. 29429--><p class="indent" >  Apparently, preservation does not extend to investing in the survival of our whole
way of life: our future.
</p><!--l. 29432--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">We have become ﬁre-ﬁghters, and charity is a bucket of cold water in a growing</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">conﬂagration of politics.</span>
</p><!--l. 29435--><p class="indent" >  The sanguine bully that the ministry has sent to coerce him is regrettably pleasant in
his administration of their medicine, sporting joviality and an array of blunt
administrative instruments in his cause. Jonas does not want to force a dislike of

everything he represents onto its animated cadaver, but he ﬁnds himself projecting
more animosity than restraint. The man pretends to be their friend, but the charade
wears pretty thin.
</p><!--l. 29443--><p class="indent" >  “It is such a pleasure to ﬁnally meet you.”
</p><!--l. 29445--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I am about to hurt you.</span>
</p><!--l. 29447--><p class="indent" >  “As you know, some new rules have come into force.”
</p><!--l. 29449--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I just cut oﬀ your head.</span>
</p><!--l. 29451--><p class="indent" >  Jonas has the sick feeling of being railroaded by a cattle herder with no ethical or
moral manifesto. His interest is purely in moving up the food chain, by shifting the
economic game pieces around the board so that government ministries can feel good
about their half-assed pledges to the media.
</p><!--l. 29457--><p class="indent" >  “We all need a little breathing room from this reallocation. A little slack in
the rope, so it doesn&#x2019;t strangle us,” Jonas tells him, as nicely as he can. “It
is wrong of the ministry to make this decision that will kill oﬀ Norwegian
research.”
</p><!--l. 29462--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s a shame,” he agrees. “But it is what has been decided.”
</p><!--l. 29464--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">It&#x2019;s a sham, you mean.</span>
</p><!--l. 29466--><p class="indent" >  He is just following orders.
</p><!--l. 29468--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Soldier, ask not.</span>
</p><!--l. 29470--><p class="indent" >  Jonas recalls Ed Bishop&#x2019;s comment about democracy: people have to go along with
the decisions once they have been made. Does that mean he being undemocratic in
this behaviour? Let&#x2019;s face it, no one was asked to vote on this decision. It was a
unilateral action. The government is betraying its people with its indolent and supine
acceptance of commands that don&#x2019;t even come from an agent of any country or
people. This is direct pressure from American, Christian lobbies. They represent
neither U.S. nor Norwegian policy. We ought to be viewing this travesty as an
inﬁltration of national security, not as a directive to be accepted with nauseous
servility.
</p><!--l. 29481--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Douse us in cheap guilt and change our whole economic strategy. Are we so</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">push-over?</span>
</p><!--l. 29484--><p class="indent" >  Jonas has still not come to terms with losing Sara. And losing her to the police of
all things. Since when did the forces of creative anarchy transfer to become part of the
sentinels of establishment? At least she has a home for the time being, and income.
She is a smart kid, but he needs to feel that he has done more to protect her from what
is going on.
</p><!--l. 29491--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">All our futures lie in the hands of people like her.</span>
</p><!--l. 29493--><p class="indent" >  So he returns to the business of making his conscience feel better. He fends
interviews with journalists who have caught wind of the scandal he has leaked. Now
his minder is there to keep him in check.
</p><!--l. 29499--><p class="indent" >  “Of course, we are deeply committed to solving this problem.”
</p><!--l. 29501--><p class="indent" >  After the day&#x2019;s interviews, Jonas feels spent and hollow. Reiterating his own
message so many times, he is not even sure that he believes it himself anymore. His
scientiﬁc training makes him suspicious of any ‘truth&#x2019; that trips oﬀ the tongue. He

pulls one of the journalists to one side.
</p><!--l. 29507--><p class="indent" >  “In reality, we are not free to make these decisions. The ministry has put both
sides in shackles. I can try to resist those forces and they can try to push
them, but there has to be a point of balance in the middle. Luckily, their own
system is preventing such a rapid change from taking place. You cannot force
the bureaucratic leviathan you have created to be ﬂexible when it suits your
needs.”
</p><!--l. 29514--><p class="indent" >  “Would you agree that corruption is so ingrained into the daily lives of
government that they really cannot see anything wrong with what they are
doing.”
</p><!--l. 29518--><p class="indent" >  “Only in an academic sense. Any hierarchy of command is, by deﬁnition, corrupt
and self-serving, but let&#x2019;s not exaggerate.”
</p><!--l. 29521--><p class="indent" >  Now he has received a number of calls and threats from oﬃcious persons at the
ministry, suggesting that he could be arrested for treasonous behaviour if he continues.
He wonders if they could they set the crime team onto him now, with his new friends
at Interpol?
</p><!--l. 29526--><p class="indent" >  He ﬁnds himself becoming impatient with the process, approaching a point at
which he must decide whether or not to allow himself to become angry, or whether to
suppress the urge and maintain his equanimity.
</p><!--l. 29531--><p class="indent" >  He has disturbed a lot of people today, including himself.
</p><!--l. 29533--><p class="indent" >  When he returns the next day, there is a memo from the chief administrator. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Mr.</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Lindgren, due to new construction renovation, we ﬁnd that we are in need of your</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">oﬃce to store the necessary building materials. We hope this does not inconvenience</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">you signiﬁcantly.</span>
</p><!--l. 29539--><p class="indent" >  This is how they humiliate someone in government service.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 29543--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 29544--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 29547--><p class="indent" >  Christmas is approaching, hark the herald angels advertise.
</p><!--l. 29549--><p class="indent" >  Jonas walks along Karl Johan, admiring the prosperity of the retailers and their
wares. It is good to see the world working, the wheels of fortune grinding on their
investments. It is good, even to see so many people out of their homes, simply
walking around. The power of Christmas is still strong. Some things never
die.
</p><!--l. 29555--><p class="indent" >  Designer drum beats pump out their own wares onto the shopping street, warming
the twilight chill with musical toddy. The rhythms seep involuntarily into his psyche,
defying his own reticence and teasing him to dance, as he has never actually been able
to do in his entire life. The producers are good; they know their trade. But he wonders
how much it costs kids to play it.
</p><!--l. 29562--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Oh come, all ye faithful, and subscribe to our streamed hypnosis. It&#x2019;s not as</span>

<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">expensive as you think. And the sacrament of copyright law will commit you to</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">oblivious ﬁnancial servitude for your incidental pleasure.</span>
</p><!--l. 29567--><p class="indent" >  Just thirty years ago, it was possible to buy recorded music and be done with. Now
everything is licensed by the hour.
</p><!--l. 29570--><p class="indent" >  A woman approaches who reminds him of Kaja, but knows immediately that it
could not be her. This woman walks at a calculated pace, on designer shoes
that cry out exhibitionism, prying distance between herself and the waves of
pedestrians that shuﬄe about her. That is not Kaja. He has been trying to reach
her for a whole day, but she has not been answering him. The tables have
turned.
</p><!--l. 29577--><p class="indent" >  Jonas browses the shop windows, looking at the electrical goods for inspiration.
They are all foreign, even now. If he were allowed to do his job, some of
these could be Norwegian. If he could only convince government to reform
their attitudes to risk and investment. If the country is to survive the next
generation with declining oil revenues, it will have to innovate, not merely
import, even if it means manufacturing. But the country is barely trained for it.
Education is little more than attitude engineering and button pushing now. The
house-of-cards economy is still buoyed by fossil fuels and fossilized ideas. Sooner
rather than later that wealth must expire and be replaced by something more
permanent. His job is about securing that permanency, if only they could see
it.
</p><!--l. 29590--><p class="indent" >  A gang of teenage boys comes along the street, wearing red and silver tinsel like
football scarves. Did they bother going to school today? A couple of police on
horseback are clopping along behind them, at a discrete distance. The sight of
uniforms take his mind back to Sara.
</p><!--l. 29596--><p class="indent" >  He has walked more or less all the way around the shops now, as the daylight has
faded. With the long nights moving in, he feels tempted to simply go home and sleep,
but it is only four o&#x2019;clock. He should work some more. If he goes home, it would
become a self-fulﬁlling prophesy.
</p><!--l. 29602--><p class="indent" >  Jonas backtracks and goes into a little shop to buy coﬀee. Simple pleasures are
what carries you through the hard times. Besides, the shop is unusually quiet, which
suits him perfectly.
</p><!--l. 29606--><p class="indent" >  He chooses the appropriate blend of beans and asks for them to be ground. The
lighting inside the shop makes it look even darker outside now. The bluish hue of
evening is descending rapidly. He gives his card to the young boy behind the counter
and waits for him to deal with the transaction.
</p><!--l. 29612--><p class="indent" >  Then, through the window, even through the reﬂections, he sees her across the
street. It is Kaja.
</p><!--l. 29615--><p class="indent" >  She emerges from a side alley between two shops, smiling and laughing. Behind
her is a man he does not know. He head is thrown back joyfully. The man is some
years older than she. Jonas is suddenly impatient to complete his purchase and see
where she is going.
</p><!--l. 29620--><p class="indent" >  He feels a stab of something undeﬁnable, something like betrayal but more violent.

Is it jealously or anger? What does it matter? His every muscle pulls taut with a
surging scream and he begins to shake with the adrenalin rush. Of course she would
not answer him if she had spent the entire night and day with a new lover. How could
he have been such a fool?
</p><!--l. 29627--><p class="indent" >  When he emerges clumsily from the shop, she is already far down the street. He
begins to run after her, not wanting to be seen, but not wanting to lose sight of her
either.
</p><!--l. 29631--><p class="indent" >  Are they lovers? They must be! He is not an attractive man, but then Jonas has
never understood what turns women on. The thought of her in bed with him burns like
an ice-water ﬂooding into his lower body.
</p><!--l. 29635--><p class="indent" >  He follows them for some distance, back to her apartment feeling a mixture of guilt
for his intrusive voyeurism and anger at her callous mind games.
</p><!--l. 29639--><p class="indent" >  She clasps the man as though they are about to part company. But then they pause.
Some new possibility seems to have emerged between them. He follows her
inside.
</p><!--l. 29643--><p class="indent" >  This is so like her, he thinks. And what a fool is he, who falls for her promises and
assurances every time? He has been proven the fool time and time again. What
possession drives him to prevaricate in ending this charade?
</p><!--l. 29647--><p class="indent" >  It could be true that people need change about every ten years. The timer starts
ticking and we either we change or we enter into an emotional crisis. Those who
marry at twenty learn it when they are thirty; those tho change jobs when they are
thirty learn when they are forty. . . What hope is left except to accept stagnation? To
make peace with endings?
</p><!--l. 29654--><p class="indent" >  Their end was like a fabled nightmare: telephone calls that she would ignore in his
presence and then ﬁnd an excuse to return later; visits from ‘old friends&#x2019; and
ex-boyfriends; her increasing lack of interest in him. Finally the signs could not be
ignored and his fears consumed him in a rain of presumed truths, like a stoning from
the inquisition.
</p><!--l. 29660--><p class="indent" >  In the chill, it begins to snow.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 29662--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 29663--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 29666--><p class="indent" >  Jonas crawls back to the oﬃces the next day, still feeling like a wounded animal. He
has not spoken to anyone. He escaped the evening by throwing oﬀ his shoes and
settling down with a glass of ﬁne Madeira and Honegger&#x2019;s grave symphonic
rumblings.
</p><!--l. 29671--><p class="indent" >  More snow is forecast today. That pleases him. Somehow, the snow seems to light
up the city with optimism. There is still something in that peace and goodwill to all
men nonsense, when it snows. Such a pity that it melts so quickly in the
city.

</p><!--l. 29676--><p class="indent" >  He nears the site of the neighbouring demolition that has been taken over for
parking spaces, and hears the protracted complaint of a motorist getting closer. The
man is trying to enter the parking area, but the security guard is explaining some kind
of problem.
</p><!--l. 29681--><p class="indent" >  “My parking space is taken.”
</p><!--l. 29683--><p class="indent" >  “Sorry sir, there is no reserved parking today.”
</p><!--l. 29685--><p class="indent" >  “But I work here. How am I, are we supposed to. . .”
</p><!--l. 29687--><p class="indent" >  “Sorry, sir. You cannot park you car in its reserved spot today, we are expecting
visitors from the ministry. They have reserved these spaces.”
</p><!--l. 29691--><p class="indent" >  “I wasn&#x2019;t told.”
</p><!--l. 29693--><p class="indent" >  “You can park in the unmarked spaces over there.”
</p><!--l. 29695--><p class="indent" >  “But how are we going to ﬁnd our vehicles again?”
</p><!--l. 29697--><p class="indent" >  “Just move along, sir. We don&#x2019;t have time to discuss this now.”
</p><!--l. 29699--><p class="indent" >  So the ministry is screwing with everyone&#x2019;s heads today. Somehow seeing someone
else&#x2019;s meaninglessly stunted predicament helps his own spirits. He refuses to believe
that the point of authority is to reduce ordinary people to powerless ignominy, but
sometimes it is a hard theory to refute.
</p><!--l. 29705--><p class="indent" >  Of course, when it snows later, you won&#x2019;t be able to ﬁnd the cars again, he thinks to
the guard as he walks past him. The guard stares through him to make it clear that he
is no one.
</p><!--l. 29709--><p class="indent" >  Jonas arrives at the research council oﬃces and walks unwillingly down the
corridor to the day&#x2019;s ritual humiliations. He would rather transport himself away from
here to help Sara, or ﬁnish his business with Kaja, but he wills himself forward with
cheerless eﬀort. He has no usable oﬃce to attend, but he can make use of the other
facilities the building oﬀers.
</p><!--l. 29716--><p class="indent" >  Things are moving in the research debate. Well, he wasn&#x2019;t going to stand still and
be steam-rollered by a minor minister, at least not without a ﬁght. His new spiritual
low incites him to make the matter international now. When one of the richest nations
faults on its responsibilities to its poorer neighbours, the matter goes beyond local
politics. Today, he feels like stabbing back.
</p><!--l. 29723--><p class="indent" >  Almost as soon as he has posted a commentary to a research magazine editorial, his
combo signals an unusual call invitation. At about the same time, he receives a text
from Joe, saying that he should expect a call.
</p><!--l. 29728--><p class="indent" >  He pushes aside some of the boxes from his desk, to make room to sit down. The
call is from Spain. Spain? He rummages around for some glasses and accepts the
invitation. He enters the virtual meeting room.
</p><!--l. 29732--><p class="indent" >  He ﬁnds himself on a balcony overlooking the sea. A slight sound of surf is audible.
It feels a little uncomfortable, sitting like this in his oﬃce. He has never been a great
fan of using glasses. The inconsistencies between vision, sound and touch make him a
little nauseous.
</p><!--l. 29738--><p class="indent" >  A woman is standing beside him, looking out at the breaking waves. She is slim and
attractive, with dark hair and a middle aged face, young and old at the same
time.

</p><!--l. 29742--><p class="indent" >  “My name is Connie Cortina,” she says. “I am executive director of a company
called Vascon.”
</p><!--l. 29745--><p class="indent" >  “Jonas Lindgren,” he reciprocates.
</p><!--l. 29747--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s nice to meet you, Dr Lindgren. I&#x2019;ve been following some of the debate, thanks
to a friend of yours.”
</p><!--l. 29750--><p class="indent" >  “Who? Joe?”
</p><!--l. 29752--><p class="indent" >  “Joseph, Joe, yes.” She exudes an elegance that Jonas ﬁnds charming. “I hope you
don&#x2019;t mind my interruption. I have been reading about about your struggles for
Norwegian research. I ﬁnd them very interesting.”
</p><!--l. 29758--><p class="indent" >  “Thank you,” he says, uncertain of what else to say. “What can I do for
you?”
</p><!--l. 29762--><p class="indent" >  “I wanted to lend you my support.”
</p><!--l. 29764--><p class="indent" >  “Your support?”
</p><!--l. 29766--><p class="indent" >  “Yes.”
</p><!--l. 29768--><p class="indent" >  Now he is perplexed. “What kind of support? How can you help me?” Then, he
adds: “Forgive me, I don&#x2019;t mean to be rude.”
</p><!--l. 29772--><p class="indent" >  She shakes her head, matter of factly. “Moral support to begin with. It
is hard work to go against one&#x2019;s own government. I wanted to talk to you
about my own experiences and perhaps lend you some of my thoughts on
this.”
</p><!--l. 29777--><p class="indent" >  “Are you for or against my writings?”
</p><!--l. 29779--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t think of it really in terms of sides. There is only one alternative for any
country—to survive.”
</p><!--l. 29782--><p class="indent" >  “What do you do?”
</p><!--l. 29784--><p class="indent" >  She considers her answer for a split second. “My company is a large concern. It
sponsors good-work projects in research and education. It is rather complicated
to explain why and how. Let&#x2019;s just say that I am always looking for allies
around the world. Those of us who believe in such things are few and far
between.”
</p><!--l. 29790--><p class="indent" >  Jonas laughs without humour. “That&#x2019;s interesting,” he says, unsure of how to
respond. “What kind of allies are you looking for?”
</p><!--l. 29793--><p class="indent" >  “People who can stand up to the storm and face the future, as you have done.” She
wants be his friend.
</p><!--l. 29796--><p class="indent" >  “Well, I am open to all kinds of input,” Jonas says. “But I&#x2019;m a little taken
aback.”
</p><!--l. 29799--><p class="indent" >  Cortina smiles at him and swishes her hair. “My company has many specialities, but
information is our business. I have a group that works with the police forces
of many countries to trace threads of crime and corruption. We have work
related to the global VR games. But, whenever I can I return to the issue of
education.”
</p><!--l. 29805--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t follow you.”
</p><!--l. 29807--><p class="indent" >  “An incident that you reported recently, related to a threatening phone
call was correlated by people working with our company, with data from

international police forces and our models put together a scenario that was very
interesting.”
</p><!--l. 29812--><p class="indent" >  He starts. “Me? How did you know? I&#x2019;m not sure I understand. I thought you were
talking about the research articles. . .”
</p><!--l. 29816--><p class="indent" >  “This is very complicated, señor Lindgren, but your police report formed a missing
link that allowed us to see connections in the patterns of behaviour across Europe. My
company specializes in this kind of analysis, and we work with Interpol to weed out
organized crime.”
</p><!--l. 29821--><p class="indent" >  “Maﬁa?”
</p><!--l. 29823--><p class="indent" >  “Not just the maﬁas. There are many players in the game. The report was useful
because it placed activities in this area close to others that were close to others. . .and
so on. We have expert modellers who put together hypotheses about organized
criminality.”
</p><!--l. 29828--><p class="indent" >  “This is all a bit confusing for me. I am new to this. I am not used to being so . . .
involved.”
</p><!--l. 29831--><p class="indent" >  “In this instance, we were able to use it to shut down the group who contacted
you.”
</p><!--l. 29834--><p class="indent" >  “You. . .? But I heard that . . . Can I ask who it was?”
</p><!--l. 29836--><p class="indent" >  “Just amateurs, associated with a Christian religious group from Eastern Europe.
They were not very smart, and that helped us to pin-point their identities. I doubt that
you will hear from them again.”
</p><!--l. 29841--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s amazing. I&#x2019;m a bit ﬂabbergasted.”
</p><!--l. 29843--><p class="indent" >  “Take a moment.”
</p><!--l. 29845--><p class="indent" >  “How can you know about this police business. Are you with the Interpol group
here?”
</p><!--l. 29848--><p class="indent" >  “I know of them.”
</p><!--l. 29850--><p class="indent" >  “But you&#x2019;re not working with them?”
</p><!--l. 29852--><p class="indent" >  “No, but our company is very powerful. We develop the systems used by the police
forces and we donate some funds to them whenever we can.”
</p><!--l. 29855--><p class="indent" >  “And this gives you access to their data?”
</p><!--l. 29857--><p class="indent" >  “Exactly.”
</p><!--l. 29859--><p class="indent" >  “So, if I am hearing you correctly, then from this, you became interested in me,
here in backwater Norway?”
</p><!--l. 29862--><p class="indent" >  “Not really. At least not directly. It is just that the power of analysis, sometimes
brings you to places you do not expect, Mr Lindgren. That is why we do research,
no?”
</p><!--l. 29866--><p class="indent" >  “Yes. I&#x2019;m trying to remember that.”
</p><!--l. 29868--><p class="indent" >  “And so we come to the other matter.”
</p><!--l. 29870--><p class="indent" >  “Of course.”
</p><!--l. 29872--><p class="indent" >  “I started to look into your work, wondering if there were any deeper reason why
you were approached.”
</p><!--l. 29875--><p class="indent" >  “Was there?”

</p><!--l. 29877--><p class="indent" >  “Possibly. I don&#x2019;t think so. I&#x2019;m not sure. But I learned something of the dilemma
you are facing.”
</p><!--l. 29880--><p class="indent" >  “Any in particular?”
</p><!--l. 29882--><p class="indent" >  “You see I have several projects that I have made my work, and one of them is
ﬁghting ignorance.”
</p><!--l. 29885--><p class="indent" >  Jonas does not know how to respond. Conversations in the VR are hard to interpret.
The body language is primitive.
</p><!--l. 29889--><p class="indent" >  “Ignorance is not bliss,” he jokes.
</p><!--l. 29891--><p class="indent" >  “Not unless you are a radical Christian activist,” she parries.
</p><!--l. 29893--><p class="indent" >  Jonas&#x2019; radar ﬂicks on. “Christian radicals. They seem to be cropping up everywhere
these days.”
</p><!--l. 29896--><p class="indent" >  “Yes they do, don&#x2019;t they?”
</p><!--l. 29898--><p class="indent" >  “But Joe. . .”
</p><!--l. 29900--><p class="indent" >  “You have a number of good projects in your research council proposals and they
are about to be turned over by a directive that comes from one of the most powerful of
these groups.”
</p><!--l. 29904--><p class="indent" >  He nods inside his glasses.
</p><!--l. 29906--><p class="indent" >  “I want to ask you not to allow these important projects to be displaced by a cheap
political gambit that your government is being coerced into.”
</p><!--l. 29910--><p class="indent" >  “It seems that I no longer have the power to make that decision.”
</p><!--l. 29912--><p class="indent" >  “Hold oﬀ as long as you can. This is a matter of importance.”
</p><!--l. 29914--><p class="indent" >  “What makes you say that?”
</p><!--l. 29916--><p class="indent" >  “This pressure to divert your funds is not based on a sound judgement. It could still
blow over. There are groups working against these organizations in several countries,
and on several fronts.”
</p><!--l. 29920--><p class="indent" >  He thinks of Sara, and Edward Bishop. “Yes,” he says. “Yes, I know.”
</p><!--l. 29922--><p class="indent" >  “The team you would send to the famine area will achieve nothing. That is not their
purpose. The aim is simply to delay progress in more important works. I know this to
be true.”
</p><!--l. 29927--><p class="indent" >  “But how?”
</p><!--l. 29929--><p class="indent" >  “Because I attended the meeting at which the decision was made.”
</p><!--l. 29931--><p class="indent" >  Jonas looks shocked. She cannot see his expression in the VR, but she can probably
guess from his silence.
</p><!--l. 29935--><p class="indent" >  “You were at the meeting?”
</p><!--l. 29937--><p class="indent" >  “Yes,” she says quietly. “It was a meeting of the game consortium in fact, but the
originators of the game are people with powerful friends and strong motivations.
Some of them are good and some of them are not so good.”
</p><!--l. 29942--><p class="indent" >  “Who?”
</p><!--l. 29944--><p class="indent" >  “Oh, the rich and the bad and the ugly. You know. People who still have power, but
are seeing it crumble in this new age of street gangs and mob wars. The famine aid is
just a cover. Money means nothing in this situation. What matters to them is that they
can exert control over society&#x2019;s thinkers.”

</p><!--l. 29951--><p class="indent" >  “It has always struck me as odd that, when one can simply eliminate billions of
dollars of debt, or that countries can continue to go on with budget deﬁcits the size
the U.S. has, that one would need famine relief from a source like research
money.”
</p><!--l. 29956--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, money doesn&#x2019;t exist. If you wipe out money, we still have everything except
for the ﬁnancial acrobatics that the banks perform. And when you realize that our
world is ruled by an enormous Virtual Reality game called the global economy, it
makes perfect sense. It is pure pinball based on a ﬁctitious scoring system.
Anyone can say: I don&#x2019;t care what my score is, at any time. The only real
consequence is that they piss oﬀ all the other players. But it doesn&#x2019;t change anything
real.”
</p><!--l. 29965--><p class="indent" >  “So when a government from one of the richest countries in the world comes and
tells you that you have to divert funds from research to famine relief, you know that
they are covering up something.”
</p><!--l. 29969--><p class="indent" >  “Exactly.”
</p><!--l. 29971--><p class="indent" >  Jonas feels a little stunned, numb in his seat. His hand knocks into one of the sheets
of plasterboard that they have ﬁlled his oﬃce with and it jars him back to disoriented
concentration.
</p><!--l. 29975--><p class="indent" >  “All right,” he says, taking some breaths. “All right.”
</p><!--l. 29977--><p class="indent" >  Ms Cortina gives him some time to think. Then she says: “But, of course, you are
asking yourself why.”
</p><!--l. 29980--><p class="indent" >  He nods.
</p><!--l. 29982--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Damn right.</span>
</p><!--l. 29984--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, tell me.”
</p><!--l. 29986--><p class="indent" >  “Well,” she treads carefully. “I wish I could tell you exactly why. I am not sure I
understand it myself.”
</p><!--l. 29989--><p class="indent" >  “But you have an idea? A theory?”
</p><!--l. 29991--><p class="indent" >  “Yes I do.”
</p><!--l. 29993--><p class="indent" >  “So?”
</p><!--l. 29995--><p class="indent" >  “The church leaders who are sponsoring this activity have seen a trend. They see
that people are getting dumber.”
</p><!--l. 29998--><p class="indent" >  Jonas laughs despite himself. “Getting dumber?”
</p><!--l. 30000--><p class="indent" >  “Yes. Society has been dumbing down for decades. They see this as an opportunity
to get back what they have lost to science over the years.”
</p><!--l. 30003--><p class="indent" >  “You are serious, aren&#x2019;t you?”
</p><!--l. 30005--><p class="indent" >  She nods. “Knowledge is religion&#x2019;s greatest enemy.”
</p><!--l. 30008--><p class="indent" >  “Because knowledge is subversive?”
</p><!--l. 30010--><p class="indent" >  “It is counter to the authority of the church.”
</p><!--l. 30012--><p class="indent" >  “Yes. . .”
</p><!--l. 30014--><p class="indent" >  “They locked up Galileo, had a go at Darwin. . .”
</p><!--l. 30016--><p class="indent" >  Cortina&#x2019;s ﬁgure comes closer to his, ﬁlling his vision.
</p><!--l. 30018--><p class="indent" >  “And you think society is getting dumber.” He nods. “Well, I can&#x2019;t disagree with
that.”

</p><!--l. 30021--><p class="indent" >  “It is an inevitable process. Perhaps it is even a phase that every civilization has to
go through.”
</p><!--l. 30024--><p class="indent" >  “Yes,” he thinks, not really agreeing with her, but the wheels and cogs of his mind
race with thoughts that he has had a thousand times, yet never quite assimilated into a
coherent jigsaw puzzle.
</p><!--l. 30028--><p class="indent" >  “When society learns, it begins with real hard-earned knowledge. It takes a long
time and a lot of sweat to acquire. Sometimes we have worked for years to achieve
it.”
</p><!--l. 30032--><p class="indent" >  She is talking about herself, Jonas thinks. This is a smart lady, however eccentric
she might be.
</p><!--l. 30035--><p class="indent" >  “Gradually,” she continues, “Knowledge becomes assimilated into our
consciousness at a deeper level. We begin to speak of it without the need to explain
or elaborate. We begin to take it for granted and see it as a part of who we
are.”
</p><!--l. 30040--><p class="indent" >  Jonas pulls himself back from his own thinking to follow her. “You mean society
takes it for granted.”
</p><!--l. 30043--><p class="indent" >  “Yes. Finally, that hard earned knowledge gets passed on to those who have not
toiled and struggled for it, to those who have not tasted the sweat on their
brows or the thrill of understanding; that is when we begin to disrespect it.
The knowledge becomes like a war veteran, something laughably caught up
in a past struggle. We reduce it to simpliﬁcations, to slogans and jargon,
perhaps even to Three Letter Abbreviations, whose stories and details we
have now forgotten. At that point, damage has occurred. Society has lost the
value of the knowledge. And a whole new generation must relearn it all over
again.”
</p><!--l. 30054--><p class="indent" >  She makes a eureka noise and freezes amoment. The background imagery in
the VR changes. She projects them into an image of the Los Angeles traﬃc
machine.
</p><!--l. 30058--><p class="indent" >  “Here,” she says. “Look at this traﬃc chaos. It speaks of miracles, Jonas.” She calls
him Jonas. “That so many careless, half-competent idiots can get behind the wheel of
such dangerous equipment, and not simply end up in a pile of torn metal, seems
astonishing, don&#x2019;t you think?. There is surely a lesson to be learned from
it.”
</p><!--l. 30065--><p class="indent" >  “What lesson?”
</p><!--l. 30067--><p class="indent" >  “That trained monkeys can do this task,” she says. “We are so proud of ourselves
for mastering this simple task, and yet it means nothing. It requires little skill that is
not merely the domain of our primitive brains.”
</p><!--l. 30072--><p class="indent" >  “It is mainly motor skill, yes,” he agrees, acknowledging the pun.
</p><!--l. 30074--><p class="indent" >  “The same is true for most things. Once the hard part of thinking up the inventions
is done, once the technology is in place, you don&#x2019;t need to be a great expert. You don&#x2019;t
need great precision or ﬁne control to make the world work. It is robust. There are
basic protective instincts built into humans that allow them to escape the most bizarre
of catastrophic ends. We don&#x2019;t need to be utter control freaks – things will

sort themselves out. We just need a little faith. That, of course, is what the
church relies on. What is truly surprising is that we advance – and that requires
conviction and concentrated eﬀort.” Her hands gesticulate with a passion.
“For all our reputed intelligence, we get by on nothing more than primitive
instinct for most of the time. And yet we have surpassed that reﬂex in our
creativity, in science and in art.” She shakes her head and continues more quietly.
“Now that we have created our lap of luxury, we must not fall asleep in it, like
Rumpelstiltskin.”
</p><!--l. 30093--><p class="indent" >  Jonas looks at her with admiration. He wishes he could see what she really looks
like. “You don&#x2019;t think you might be overstating things just a little bit?” Even as he
says it, he knows that she is right.
</p><!--l. 30097--><p class="indent" >  “No, Mr. Lindgren, I am not. I wish I were. But already the forces of trivial
economics and faith are dominating the behaviour of society.”
</p><!--l. 30100--><p class="indent" >  He cannot disagree with that. It&#x2019;s the paradox of the century.
</p><!--l. 30102--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">We&#x2019;re consumed by trivia so there&#x2019;s no room in our heads for expertise. At the same</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">time, we&#x2019;re so singular in our privacy that we cannot even mix the ingredients of a</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">half-baked society.</span>
</p><!--l. 30106--><p class="indent" >  “Society truly is becoming the proverbial ‘bewildered herd&#x2019;.”
</p><!--l. 30108--><p class="indent" >  “This dumbing down of society is not just about entertainment. It concerns our
most important institutions, our education, our subservience.” Jonas wonders how her
passion would sound if she were speaking in Spanish. “I am here partly because your
friend, Joe, is part of a group working against the kind of ignorance that some would
have us perpetuate.”
</p><!--l. 30115--><p class="indent" >  “The Get Smart programme. Yes. What ignorance, in particular, are you speaking
of?”
</p><!--l. 30118--><p class="indent" >  “Today it is the leaders.”
</p><!--l. 30120--><p class="indent" >  Jonas laughs now with genuine amusement.
</p><!--l. 30122--><p class="indent" >  Cortina laughs too. “Perhaps I am talking too much? It is a habit of mine.”
</p><!--l. 30125--><p class="indent" >  “Please continue. Our leaders. . .”
</p><!--l. 30127--><p class="indent" >  “Our leaders, yes. Well, you know, in our information society, it is not the leaders
who are the card holders anymore. In ancient times, in the days when Europe was a
melange of warring houses, it was a hierarchical society. The leaders and their aids
were the most educated persons and all they needed was obedience to carry out their
commands. They had their Machiavellis and others to advise them, but basically the
expertise was at the top.”
</p><!--l. 30135--><p class="indent" >  “But today the expertise is at the opposite ends of the tree.”
</p><!--l. 30137--><p class="indent" >  “Exactly. The roots are dying and the leaves prosper but for the fact that they are
shackled to their roots and their aids, the inﬂexible branches. Now they want to stop
that from changing, by stunting the leaves, by taking away from people the basic right
to be good at something, to succeed. The right for one person to be better than
someone else.”
</p><!--l. 30145--><p class="indent" >  “Hmm.” Jonas nods. “Everyone is equal until proven guilty.” He nods. “I know this
tendency. It has been around since the seventies here. It almost ruined our maths

education.”
</p><!--l. 30155--><p class="indent" >  “Before it was only the poor who had the luxury of ignorance. Now it is the
opposite. The rich and powerful—who can lead because they are already <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">ahead </span>in the
Western view of economics—are increasingly falling behind the curve required to
understand the world. This is dumbing down. Yet they retain the power to bludgeon us
with instruments beyond their understanding, simply because we all play the game of
money.”
</p><!--l. 30163--><p class="indent" >  “Welcome to my world.”
</p><!--l. 30165--><p class="indent" >  “It aﬀects everyone. We are simply closer to it.”
</p><!--l. 30167--><p class="indent" >  “So how do we change it?”
</p><!--l. 30169--><p class="indent" >  “I am asking you to take a stand. Norway has a history of standing up for moral
principles. I am asking you to do this now.”
</p><!--l. 30172--><p class="indent" >  “But you realize that I, too, am just a puppet of the government if they want me to
be?”
</p><!--l. 30175--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t believe it,” she says, shaking her head and piercing him with the shrewdness
of her gaze. “Whenever They make laws, they set traps for themselves. Use your
imagination.” She smiles. “You must think me slightly mad to come to you and say
such a thing; but, you must understand the reason.”
</p><!--l. 30181--><p class="indent" >  Jonas nods.
</p><!--l. 30183--><p class="indent" >  “In a sense, technology is a test for society. It enables us, allows us to cooperate,
use agriculture to feed millions, make tools for others, have division of labour. But
there is also a trap. We have moved from being a loosely-knit ﬂock of do-it-alls into a
tightly woven fabric of specialists.”
</p><!--l. 30189--><p class="indent" >  He nods, impatiently. “Yes. But we are killing oﬀ the specialists now. Now that we
need them.”
</p><!--l. 30192--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, you see it too. These specialist skills are of paramount importance to our
society. Once we have division of labour, there is no turning back. We no longer
possess all the skills to survive without our neighbours. If the electricity suddenly
were to go away, or the telephone suddenly refused to allow you to talk to the
producers of things, could you survive? We have seen what happens in the great
natural disasters that wipe out civil infrastructure. People become lawless and
opportunistic savages again—just as the poor areas of the U.S. we are seeing
now.”
</p><!--l. 30202--><p class="indent" >  He sees it. If trust in the delegation of responsibility breaks down, if the roles are
not carried out properly, the system itself breaks down, and no one can ﬁx it, because
they no longer have the skills to do anyone else&#x2019;s job.
</p><!--l. 30207--><p class="indent" >  Today, society is not just local, it is globalised to the point at which the entire world
could crash if a part of the system ceased to work. As the Romans were fond of
saying: society is never more than four meals away from anarchy. Perhaps <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">that </span>is what
killed the dinosaurs, Sara might say.
</p><!--l. 30213--><p class="indent" >  “So you see that we are committed to civilization. We cannot go back to a simpler
life, at least not without causing massive fatalities. But society is becoming lazy,
dumbing down. We have invented technology after technology that makes us

into passive, button-pushing servants of machinery, reducing real knowledge
to simplistic, searchable keywords. In a few years, the dumbing down of
school curricula will result in a consumer culture with no skills. When that
day comes, there will be no one to repair the machines, no one to save us
from the collapse. Without education, society is on a downward spiral to
disaster.”
</p><!--l. 30224--><p class="indent" >  Jonas stares at her, half seriously, half wishing that she had picked any
other day of the year to bring this to him. He cannot quite ﬁnd the words to
respond.
</p><!--l. 30228--><p class="indent" >  She examines his intensity, as if reading him. “Mr. Lindgren. I have been ﬁghting
for this belief for as long as I can remember. Sometimes when I lie down at night, I
feel that I am helpless against this tide, as if I am drifting on a restless ocean, with no
port in sight and no lighthouse to warn me of the rocks. And yet I think this: if
a group of philanthropic industrialists can produce a counter-force to this
senseless plundering of the globalized economy, then so be it. It is a fair
ﬁght.”
</p><!--l. 30237--><p class="indent" >  “In just a few years, the canvas of the world could be repainted,” he ponders. “Skill
is easily squandered, and not so easily regained.”
</p><!--l. 30240--><p class="indent" >  He looks about at the scenery, which has reverted to their seaside balcony.
</p><!--l. 30242--><p class="indent" >  “But, there is a chance: it is not certain that the government can bring about their
own plan. There are, in fact, rules and regulations that are getting in their way. Things
don&#x2019;t move as fast as they would like.”
</p><!--l. 30246--><p class="indent" >  “So you could delay it? Perhaps even stop it.”
</p><!--l. 30248--><p class="indent" >  “We&#x2019;ll see. It would be a funny irony indeed if the Norwegian state bureaucracy
were the ultimate barrier that prevented this plot from being implemented. Truly a
clash of the titans: the irresistible force meets the immovable object.”
</p><!--l. 30254--><p class="indent" >  She smiles. “I like the idea.”
</p><!--l. 30256--><p class="indent" >  “If I can tie things up in process for a while and distract from the issue, it might not
pass through the ministry for some time.”
</p><!--l. 30259--><p class="indent" >  “Politics is about timing. If you delay it, it could become unimportant to them.
They might even change their mind.”
</p><!--l. 30262--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, a change of context could mean a change of priorities, yes. Perhaps it would
even be possible to make them actively support research again with some kind of
advertising campaign..”
</p><!--l. 30266--><p class="indent" >  “This is what the game itself is about. This is why we are here.”
</p><!--l. 30268--><p class="indent" >  “A battle for the greatest cause.”
</p><!--l. 30271--><p class="indent" >  Jonas remembers where he is, in his overrun oﬃce, in the middle of a bureaucratic
tackle for a ball that no audience really cares for. If he hadn&#x2019;t invested so much
of his life in science and the people who do it, he might be less inclined to
put himself in the ﬁring line. But this is his moment. Fate has handed him
Excalibur and told him to save the world. He can at least try to save a few of its
souls.
</p><!--l. 30278--><p class="indent" >  “You should have met my student,” he says. “This is really all just the theory of

signals. She is an expert.”
</p><!--l. 30281--><p class="indent" >  “Then use her. Make people stand up for their survival.”
</p><!--l. 30283--><p class="indent" >  He can see himself as a knight. “A campaign to save education from the clutches of
theocracy.”
</p><!--l. 30287--><p class="indent" >  “Remember to use your greatest asset: thinking. If, like the politicians and
advertisers, you only paint in broad strokes, with a fat brush, you cannot go
into detail—you are an impressionist. You might be lucky and get some of
those details by chance, but your fortune is not in your hands. Wave a ﬂag,
pick a brand, sing an anthem. . . You need to be more speciﬁc to push the
buttons.”
</p><!--l. 30294--><p class="indent" >  “And I even have an idea how. . .”
</p><!--l. 30296--><p class="indent" >  “Our technology can help you. It was developed for searching for gene actions in
humans, but it allows us to trace the channels of cause and eﬀect in the actions of any
information system. It is very powerful, and it is being used by the international law
enforcement agencies already.”
</p><!--l. 30301--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s how you found me.”
</p><!--l. 30303--><p class="indent" >  “Yes.”
</p><!--l. 30305--><p class="indent" >  “So you can unwind the ecological web.”
</p><!--l. 30307--><p class="indent" >  “In a sense, yes.”
</p><!--l. 30309--><p class="indent" >  “A mixture of delay and de-stabilizing the current policy.”
</p><!--l. 30311--><p class="indent" >  He experiences a feeling of satisfaction as if something has been accomplished.
Remember the days when he was still a teacher, not just a bureaucrat? He used to
measure the success of his time by whether anything was communicated,
whether any deeper understanding was achieved, whether they had moved
forward.
</p><!--l. 30317--><p class="indent" >  “So, if you see a colour that is too strong in your landscape. . .”
</p><!--l. 30319--><p class="indent" >  “Paint over it with big whitewash stokes.”
</p><!--l. 30321--><p class="indent" >  She nods as if this was something she has always known.
</p><!--l. 30323--><p class="indent" >  “Just like Sara,” he says absently.
</p><!--l. 30325--><p class="indent" >  “I must leave this meeting now,” she says. “But I am glad we had this talk. Good
luck with your work.”
</p><!--l. 30328--><p class="indent" >  Jonas makes a bowing nod. “Thank you. It has been a pleasure meeting
you.”
</p><!--l. 30331--><p class="indent" >  “Yes,” she agrees.
</p><!--l. 30333--><p class="indent" >  “Perhaps we can keep in touch?”
</p><!--l. 30335--><p class="indent" >  The image dissolves without an answer and he is left staring at boxes and
plasterboard.
</p><!--l. 30338--><p class="indent" >  Later in the day, as he walks out to the Lighthouse café, he thinks about their
conversation again. How it all makes sense to him.
</p><!--l. 30341--><p class="indent" >  As he passes the demolition parking, he stops and looks at the cars with momentary
surprise. It fades quickly into satisfaction and then laughter. Freshly fallen snow has
transformed the randomly parked cars into utterly indistinguishable white humps of
snow.

</p><!--l. 30346--><p class="indent" >  He mouths the words: “Told you so”.
</p>
