>
<!--l. 30349--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 30350--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 30353--><p class="indent" >  Jonas faces the ministry&#x2019;s administrator with as calm an expression as he can
maintain.
</p><!--l. 30356--><p class="indent" >  “How can we expect to rely on people&#x2019;s brains when we have been systematically
erasing them for the last forty years?” he says.
</p><!--l. 30359--><p class="indent" >  In response to his media attention, the ministry has issued a statement talking about
its reform of the education system. It will require a higher level of documentation and
quality control measures to make sure that the stupid academics are doing their job
properly, not just sitting around thinking. The ministry claims that kids are no dumber
than before, and that they will rise to the challenges of the new decade. This
diversion of research funds is a necessary and temporary step for humanitarian
ends.
</p><!--l. 30368--><p class="indent" >  Jonas continues, “We are beating up our thinkers, drowning them in the syrup of
administration and economic board games. The need for administration is viral. it is a
self-sustaining process. Adding more formalia is like putting an eagle into a jungle
and expecting it to ﬂy.”
</p><!--l. 30373--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">It really is true</span>, he thinks. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I am not just selling her point. Every day I get more post,</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">more mail, more telephone interruptions. In the end there is no room for anything</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">other than servicing the noise from others. When signal gets drowned in noise, we are</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">lost.</span>
</p><!--l. 30378--><p class="indent" >  “How can you expect me to sanction a change that will result in the abrupt demise
of a young girl&#x2019;s career?”
</p><!--l. 30381--><p class="indent" >  He has been bombarding the administrator with focused information about the
consequences of the proposed change. He has read them diligently: Jonas was careful
to present them with the proper protocols and procedures. And one has to give the
man his due, his does his job properly and professionally, however misguided it might
be.
</p><!--l. 30387--><p class="indent" >  He returns to him sometime later with a new set of procedures, from a diﬀerent set
of regulations.
</p><!--l. 30390--><p class="indent" >  “If you can ﬁll out this form by the end of the day so that I have it by tomorrow
morning, I can bring the matter to the attention of the European Parliament, who
might be able to bear some inﬂuence on the matter.”
</p><!--l. 30395--><p class="indent" >  “You would do that?”
</p><!--l. 30397--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s a legitimate procedure. It is part of your right of appeal.”
</p><!--l. 30399--><p class="indent" >  “I wasn&#x2019;t aware.”
</p><!--l. 30401--><p class="indent" >  “This is why you need a professional bureaucracy to manage your aﬀairs. Glad to
be of service.”

</p><!--l. 30404--><p class="indent" >  Jonas smiles a little bit on the inside. You just never know what&#x2019;s going to happen
next.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 30408--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 30409--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 30412--><p class="indent" >  Later Jonas feels suﬃcient optimism to risk calling Kaja. It is a long walk through
the snow to her ﬂat, but the cold air feels refreshingly appealing after what seems like
a long day. She receives him with a suspicious scowl.
</p><!--l. 30416--><p class="indent" >  “Martin is with my mother,” she says.
</p><!--l. 30418--><p class="indent" >  He lifts his head in acknowledgement.
</p><!--l. 30420--><p class="indent" >  “I need you to explain to me what happened last week. Why you disappeared.”
</p><!--l. 30422--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s kind of complicated,” he mumbles.
</p><!--l. 30424--><p class="indent" >  “Why won&#x2019;t you talk to me?”
</p><!--l. 30426--><p class="indent" >  He doesn&#x2019;t know how to answer.
</p><!--l. 30428--><p class="indent" >  “Isn&#x2019;t your son important to you?”
</p><!--l. 30430--><p class="indent" >  “Of course he is. . .”
</p><!--l. 30432--><p class="indent" >  “What about me? Don&#x2019;t I mean anything anymore?”
</p><!--l. 30434--><p class="indent" >  “Yes you do.”
</p><!--l. 30436--><p class="indent" >  “If you spent a little more time with us, I wouldn&#x2019;t have to spend my whole time
trying to call you and get you to do things for your son.”
</p><!--l. 30439--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s not fair, Kaj. I try to ﬁnd a good balance.”
</p><!--l. 30441--><p class="indent" >  “Oh, balance. Of course. Let&#x2019;s not let us be too important, Jonas.”
</p><!--l. 30443--><p class="indent" >  “Kaja, I love you, but you make it quite diﬃcult sometimes.”
</p><!--l. 30445--><p class="indent" >  “I love you too,” she says more softly. “But we need you to be around.”
</p><!--l. 30447--><p class="indent" >  “You have other people in your life, Kaja,” he blurts. “I can&#x2019;t be around all the
time.”
</p><!--l. 30450--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s none of your business.”
</p><!--l. 30452--><p class="indent" >  “No it isn&#x2019;t.”
</p><!--l. 30454--><p class="indent" >  “Had we been together, it would be diﬀerent.”
</p><!--l. 30456--><p class="indent" >  “But we were together and it wasn&#x2019;t.”
</p><!--l. 30458--><p class="indent" >  “You&#x2019;re no better, Jonas. You act as though your needs are more important than
mine, but you&#x2019;re just the same.”
</p><!--l. 30461--><p class="indent" >  “I have work. . .”
</p><!--l. 30463--><p class="indent" >  “Always working, yes. You never have time for us.”
</p><!--l. 30465--><p class="indent" >  “I have responsibilities, Kaj.”
</p><!--l. 30467--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t give me that bullshit. Fuck you!”
</p><!--l. 30469--><p class="indent" >  “Kaj. . .”
</p><!--l. 30471--><p class="indent" >  “Your work is just more important than we are. That&#x2019;s it, isn&#x2019;t it?”
</p><!--l. 30473--><p class="indent" >  “Sometimes it is, yes. I have to make that decision sometimes.”

</p><!--l. 30475--><p class="indent" >  “Fine, go on then. Get out! Get the fuck out of here and go to your stupid job. I
know it is more important to you than anything else – more important than
me.”
</p><!--l. 30479--><p class="indent" >  “You know that is not true – but this is real. It is not your fairy tale world.” Why did
he have to say that?
</p><!--l. 30483--><p class="indent" >  “Fuck you, Jonas!”
</p><!--l. 30485--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t exaggerate and get all upset.”
</p><!--l. 30487--><p class="indent" >  “Oh, so will you stay now? Will you spend the weekend with us now?”
</p><!--l. 30490--><p class="indent" >  “I can&#x2019;t spend the whole weekend. We can go somewhere, maybe, tomorrow.”
</p><!--l. 30492--><p class="indent" >  “Well, perhaps that&#x2019;s not convenient for me, Jonas! Maybe I can only do something
tonight. Why can&#x2019;t you just do something right for once?”
</p><!--l. 30495--><p class="indent" >  “I have to do something now. This has to be done by tomorrow, Kaja.
Hundreds of people are waiting for this. They are expecting it, relying on
me.”
</p><!--l. 30499--><p class="indent" >  “And I suppose you couldn&#x2019;t do it in working hours? You had to wait until
now!”
</p><!--l. 30501--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, actually. I was waiting for someone else to ﬁnish their part. So I
couldn&#x2019;t.”
</p><!--l. 30503--><p class="indent" >  “So that means it is not your fault if it is late. Why do you care?”
</p><!--l. 30505--><p class="indent" >  “It might not be my fault, but it is my responsibility.”
</p><!--l. 30507--><p class="indent" >  “And what about me? What am I supposed to do in the mean time?”
</p><!--l. 30509--><p class="indent" >  He shrugs. “I&#x2019;m sorry, I&#x2019;ll make it up to you.”
</p><!--l. 30511--><p class="indent" >  “Well, fuck you! Just get out!”
</p><!--l. 30513--><p class="indent" >  He looks mournfully at the ﬂoor for a moment and then summons himself to leave.
He closes the door behind him and hears her scream and throw something at the space
he has just closed between them.
</p><!--l. 30522--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

