 id="x1-60r56"></a>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-0"></a>
<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">56</span>
</p><!--l. 30525--><p class="indent" >  Vibe is playing with the sims, toying with the characters like dolls in a doll house,
as if she would ever lay her ﬁngers on anything so prosaic. She prefers the challenge
of playing with real people who don&#x2019;t know when they are being manipulated, but
there is no one suitable in range.
</p><!--l. 30531--><p class="indent" >  Preeta is working her own magic, collaborating with Dermot on some private
channel that Vibe prefers to keep well out of. The guy is seriously weird or something,
but Preeta seems to like him, so who knows. There is certainly no accounting for taste.
Preeta has been unwinding the skein of intricacies in the information network and is
gradually showing Vibe how the patterns form. She has been learning at an impressive
speed, and they have grown together into a mutual admiration society of two. Several
long days have passed getting to know one another while working on this
problem.
</p><!--l. 30541--><p class="indent" >  Preeta feels like fate herself, tangling with the ley-lines of cause and eﬀect.
Something draws her mind back to that fanciful intersection from her journey:
the child and the ice-cream. What happened to that child? Has his destiny
been realized yet? Has he changed the world forever? Is there still some role
for him to play to make his diﬀerence to the future? And what about her
own role? Will she make any contribution to the world that yet remains to
be acted out? She does not <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">feel </span>fulﬁlled yet. That, at least, must be a good
sign?
</p><!--l. 30551--><p class="indent" >  All in all, for all their petty distractions and foibles and neuroses, the rag-tag team
has been working well together. They have come together as an unlikely,
if not unholy union, working remotely or closely as moods and neuroses
dictate. But they have made several strides of progress, thanks mainly to
high spirits. That has pleased Bishop, and attracted the attention of several
others.
</p><!--l. 30558--><p class="indent" >  Vibe has been talking to Dr Lindgren now and then and he has given her his time
with a willing struggle, lending her ideas and suggestions. He seems to have some

new hobby-horse that has inspired them along their current path of action. Based on
those teasing splinters and arrowheads, they are constructing a bow from which to
launch their weapon, out of the spinal curvature of their sagging postures. It is nothing
if not back-breaking sitting at these terminals, inspecting thousands of lines of
meta-code, hour after hour. Dermot is king at this task, however, whoever and
wherever he is.
</p><!--l. 30569--><p class="indent" >  “Dr. Lindgren is really going tooth&#x2019;n&#x2019;nail at this,” Vibe tells them, as they play. “He
reckons I might not have to give up my PhD after all, if he can get past this next few
weeks without letting dropping the reins.”
</p><!--l. 30574--><p class="indent" >  “Really?” Preeta lights up in sympathetic optimism.
</p><!--l. 30576--><p class="indent" >  “Actually, I have no idea,” she confesses. “But the thought is a good one, don&#x2019;t you
think.”
</p><!--l. 30579--><p class="indent" >  “Look on the bright side,” she nods. “It must be awful not knowing?”
</p><!--l. 30581--><p class="indent" >  She smiles. “I&#x2019;m getting better at living with it.”
</p><!--l. 30584--><p class="indent" >  A disturbance wells up in the darker girl&#x2019;s hind-brain. “Will you go back, if you
can?”
</p><!--l. 30587--><p class="indent" >  Vibe regards her without expression from the corner of her eye. “I&#x2019;ll think about it
when it happens. For now, I&#x2019;m having fun.”
</p><!--l. 30590--><p class="indent" >  Although she pretends not to notice, she senses the relief in the satellite bodies
around her. There is no denying that she has found a niche here that works for her and
for the others. It is as though she is the ﬁnal spark-plug that released the energy of this
little engine. They needed her, and she delivered. It is not often that one gets to be that
appreciated.
</p><!--l. 30596--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Maybe I&#x2019;ve been chasing dreams for too long.</span>
</p><!--l. 30599--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t underestimate the value of serendipity,” Preeta says. “It is also
possible to enjoy something that you haven&#x2019;t chosen yourself.” She says it with
a wink, but Vibe feels it as a slap in the face. Vibe looks back at her and
ponders.
</p><!--l. 30604--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Hmmm. You think you know me, eh?</span>
</p><!--l. 30606--><p class="indent" >  Perhaps she is right. It is not written on her birth certiﬁcate that she always has to
get her own way. Maybe it&#x2019;s okay to let someone else make the decision now and
then. It can still be the right one. She smiles at herself, at her own prima Donna
arrogance.
</p><!--l. 30611--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Look at it this way. If it works out for the best anyway, then you really did get your</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">own way, right?</span>
</p><!--l. 30615--><p class="indent" >  Nina has been hanging around them, watching and learning. She is the sorcerer&#x2019;s
apprentice, just starting as a student, but she has already found her two role
models. There is little she can do, with or without Mickey Mouse ears or a
pointy hat, but if enthusiasm were a key, then they would have enough of
them to build a piano from here to Mars and back. Mostly she runs back and
forth, watching the others at their work, oohing and ahhing. It bolsters their
egos and keeps them supplied with drinks. Vibe&#x2019;s casual characteristic of her
was that of a badly ﬁred rat, ricocheting helplessly about the walls of its

maze.
</p><!--l. 30626--><p class="indent" >  Not everyone is so focused, however. There are other issues in the mix of this little
group than the solution of Interpol&#x2019;s socio-computational puzzle for the betterment of
mankind. Vibe and Preeta have been colluding on their own projects. These two
stealthy ginger cats have been spending time looking after their own destinies,
scouting through the nooks and crannies of police databases. Just the previous night
they spent searching through the Interpol cobwebs, looking at what is known about
Kuala Lumpur; now they have now turned their attention to the Norwegian forces,
or rather one in particular. Vibe has missing property to recover, let&#x2019;s not
forget.
</p><!--l. 30637--><p class="indent" >  It is not demanding work, but it has a certain thrill about it. This is hardly why they
are here, and there might be questions asked if they are discovered. Fortunately,
security is lax on the inside. The police database was trivial to access. It did not take
long to ﬁnd Patrol Pussy Radmila Eva Salberg, otherwise known as Jotunheimen Beat
Bitch. She strutted her way down from the North or Norway; she has worked in
Narvik, Alta and now she has been in the National Park area for two years. If oﬃcial
photos are to be believed, she is a regular beam of sunshine. More like moonshine, by
Vibe&#x2019;s reckoning.
</p><!--l. 30647--><p class="indent" >  She is good for a certain amount of gossip and tall storytelling, but it is an
incidental pass-time.
</p><!--l. 30650--><p class="indent" >  “Never mind the beat bitch. Let&#x2019;s ﬁnd Frank,” Vibe shudders. He is, after all, her
best approach after this time.
</p><!--l. 30653--><p class="indent" >  “Frank what?”
</p><!--l. 30655--><p class="indent" >  “Not sure. Try them all.”
</p><!--l. 30657--><p class="indent" >  “Ah, here we are. Frank Grøndahl. He&#x2019;s kind of cute.”
</p><!--l. 30659--><p class="indent" >  Vibe ﬂashes her eyebrows. “Actually, yes.” Then a diﬀerent thought ﬂushes her
enthusiasm. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Can you ﬁnd Peter Green?</span>
</p><!--l. 30663--><p class="indent" >  How would she explain him?
</p><!--l. 30665--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Someone I&#x2019;ve sort of been obsessing over. Someone who tried to put his hand</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">up.</span>
</p><!--l. 30667--><p class="indent" >  Maybe better to let that one go. Can&#x2019;t keep hanging on to a dead duck, or whatever
the metaphor is in this situation.
</p><!--l. 30670--><p class="indent" >  “So what do you want to do?”
</p><!--l. 30672--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Why not just send a message to Frank. Kill two birds with one asteroid?</span>
</p><!--l. 30674--><p class="indent" >  “We write.”
</p><!--l. 30676--><p class="indent" >  She writes.
     <span 
class="ptmr7t-">Dear Frank, thanks for your kindness in looking after me during my stay in</span>
     <span 
class="ptmr7t-">Jotunheimen. Sorry I didn&#x2019;t get to say good-bye. Got called to an interview.</span>
     <span 
class="ptmr7t-">Long story. Anyway, I&#x2019;m still wondering what I&#x2019;m supposed to do about</span>
     <span 
class="ptmr7t-">the mountain rescue business. Your colleague seems to have conﬁscated my</span>
     <span 
class="ptmr7t-">backpack so I can&#x2019;t get my stuﬀ. Any ideas about who I should contact?</span>
     </p><!--l. 30686--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="ptmr7t-">So anyway, maybe see you next time I&#x2019;m in town. Do you ski?</span>

</p><!--l. 30689--><p class="indent" >  She examines her handiwork and nods. Leave the end hanging, ambiguous. That&#x2019;s
good. Get those male hormones popping.
</p><!--l. 30692--><p class="indent" >  Preeta looks at her new acquaintance with a head full of questions and thoughts.
Now is not necessarily the time to be asking them all, but one day she means to
unravel some of her mystery. How can someone like Vibe exist? Doesn&#x2019;t she feel
any sense of trepidation about tinkering with mechanics of the world? She
seems to juggle with the threads of cause and eﬀect as though they are her
playthings. And, around her, the world neatly falls into place. Of course, it
cannot really be true, and yet that is the unmistakable impression that she
leaves.
</p><!--l. 30701--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">And what of me? </span>Preeta wonders. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I have been a runner, not a ﬁghter.</span>
</p><!--l. 30703--><p class="indent" >  Part of her would like to emulate her new friend; another half knows that that is
not entirely possible. You cannot capture someone else&#x2019;s spirit and hijack it
for your own. She has seen people try, and the result is neither pretty nor
ﬂattering.
</p><!--l. 30708--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">She cuts a beautiful ﬁgure though.</span>
</p><!--l. 30710--><p class="indent" >  Vibe is narrower of frame than herself and has a boyish kind of charm
that makes her look both athletic and divine. No one could deny that she is
attractive at many levels. Every motion of her body seems animated, ﬁlled with
life.
</p><!--l. 30715--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I am a China doll by comparison</span>, she thinks. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Even with more make-up, I am less</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">attractive. Because there is no beauty inside me. I am wax.</span>
</p><!--l. 30719--><p class="indent" >  Knowing the reason does not necessarily bring catharsis, but modesty owes her at
least a return on her meager investment; she will call in the favour when her life has
shed some more its old skin. There is time yet for the future, and time to explore what
she really wants. Besides, if they continue to hang out, perhaps some of Vibe&#x2019;s magic
will rub oﬀ on her.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 30726--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 30727--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 30730--><p class="indent" >  For the ﬁrst days of Advent, one might have been expecting angels to herald its
onslaught, but angels are the scum of the VR, not the glowing portents of new things
to come. Other creatures have abducted that role. And Preeta met some agents last
night. One in particular.
</p><!--l. 30735--><p class="indent" >  One of the succubi identiﬁed it, or vice versa, it&#x2019;s hard to tell. It calls itself Mary
Cheung and claims to be able to inﬂuence billboard advertising in certain
environments. She seems to want to help them. If true, this could be a major
breakthrough. Of course, no one has any idea whether she is legit&#x2019; but they have
managed to compute a strategy that can make use of her, but which does not depend
on her.

</p><!--l. 30742--><p class="indent" >  Did she appear of her own free programming, or did their own seeds sprout? They
will not have the answer to that for some time to come.
</p><!--l. 30745--><p class="indent" >  What is interesting is that this agent is also claiming something a little odd: that the
best way to achieve their goals might be through a programme of freewill and induced
thinking in the players. That seems to tally with Dr Lindgren&#x2019;s latest rantings. It seems
almost a little too good to be true. Vibe ran a factor analysis, using Preeta&#x2019;s new
software just in case someone has been pulling their sweet feminine legs. The agents
seemed legit&#x2019;.
</p><!--l. 30754--><p class="indent" >  So how do you start the world thinking? Mary Shelley&#x2019;s Frankenstein tried a
massive electric shock to the temples. Bea uses a cup of triple espresso ﬁlled to the
brim with sugar, as a potion barely ﬁt for consumption. Neither of these need go down
well with Amnesty International, or even the international power conglomerates.
What is needed is a yoghurt. A healthy new age alternative. Homoeopathic thought?
Nope, too dilute to be workable. This will be the new-new-age yoga of the mind.
Thinking had to come back in vogue eventually. Now they have to make people buy it
like it&#x2019;s going out of fashion.
</p><!--l. 30765--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t really care what we end up using this for,” Vibe relays to the room
as she chisels away on her digital sculptures. “It&#x2019;s just fun working on this
solution.”
</p><!--l. 30769--><p class="indent" >  “Do you think anyone will believe it? Do you think it will work the way we
planned?”
</p><!--l. 30772--><p class="indent" >  “You don&#x2019;t know until you try it. That&#x2019;s why we do it.”
</p><!--l. 30774--><p class="indent" >  She sees that Bishop looks pleased, and that is enough for the time being. As the
time rolls on, Vibe murmurs softly in her trance.
</p><!--l. 30777--><p class="indent" >  “So we&#x2019;re approaching doomsday now.”
</p><!--l. 30779--><p class="indent" >  “Yup.”
</p><!--l. 30781--><p class="indent" >  “Where&#x2019;s the pimp? Where are our beauties?”
</p><!--l. 30783--><p class="indent" >  “Dermot has promised us a last-minute miracle.”
</p><!--l. 30785--><p class="indent" >  She turns her head away from her screen for a moment. “Do you think he&#x2019;ll
deliver?”
</p><!--l. 30788--><p class="indent" >  Preeta nods. “Yes.” Then she adds: “If he doesn&#x2019;t, I&#x2019;ll not make him mince pies for
Christmas.”
</p><!--l. 30791--><p class="indent" >  “Mince pies, eh?”
</p><!--l. 30793--><p class="indent" >  “Mince pies.”
</p><!--l. 30795--><p class="indent" >  “You hussy.”
</p><!--l. 30797--><p class="indent" >  The days and nights run into one another in the failing light of Oslo&#x2019;s impending
winter, and the group seems to be heading for a conjunction of physical and mental
concentration. Even Jonas Lindgren has made the eﬀort to come and see their work in
person, to impute the values of science to the champagne launch, to lend it the
authority of the sceptic.
</p><!--l. 30804--><p class="indent" >  “This is a true conjuction,” Preeta decides. “That sounds pretty New Age, doesn&#x2019;t
it? Instead of a conjunction of the planets and stars, this is a conjunction of
information ﬂows and people.”

</p><!--l. 30808--><p class="indent" >  “Which we have engineered together to create a unique situation,” Jonathan
crowns.
</p><!--l. 30810--><p class="indent" >  “A situation that allows a change to occur,” Bishop enhances.
</p><!--l. 30812--><p class="indent" >  “I belive it&#x2019;s called punctuated equilibrium,” Jonas informs them.
</p><!--l. 30814--><p class="indent" >  “And evolution shall be averted for lack of a catastrophe for now.”
</p><!--l. 30816--><p class="indent" >  “All right,” Jonathan calls, “Snow machines at the ready.”
</p><!--l. 30818--><p class="indent" >  And, as they deploy their infectious mist, rolling it in from the great ocean of
communication, it forms a wave of inﬂuence that seeps almost invisibly through the
onion layers of the game. Changes begin to be seeded; perturbations destabilize the
hybrid potentials. Even in the primordial mixture of characters and notions they have
concocted, there is a new possibility threatening to emerge. It aspires to be the
blueprint for that most elusive of creatures: success.
</p><!--l. 30826--><p class="indent" >  So now the real game is on.
</p><!--l. 30831--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-61r57"></a>
<a 
 id="Q1-1-0"></a>
<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">57</span>
</p><!--l. 30834--><p class="indent" >  The Senator&#x2019;s limo careers rapidly through the Washington districts, pursued by a
posse of paparazzi journalists.
</p><!--l. 30837--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">They are like a pack of rats</span>, he thinks, <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">or enraged chimpanzees seeking their pound</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">of human ﬂesh.</span>
</p><!--l. 30840--><p class="indent" >  “We could lose this opportunity entirely at this stage,” the aid tells him.
</p><!--l. 30843--><p class="indent" >  The senator views focuses on his aid, tearing his mind away from other
things.
</p><!--l. 30845--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, it&#x2019;s almost as though someone knew exactly our strategy.” His matter-of-factness
belies his true anger at what is happening.
</p><!--l. 30848--><p class="indent" >  Dean adjusts his heart monitor, moving it aside, and pours himself a brandy as
calmly as he can. The precariousness of his condition has not yet impacted on his
equanimity. They can shoot you, but they can&#x2019;t make you beg.
</p><!--l. 30853--><p class="indent" >  This whole recent business ﬁlls him with a deep sense of suspicion and betrayal. It
is almost as though there has been some kind of conspiracy to turn the tables against
them. Only a few weeks ago it seemed as though their plan was invincible, and people
were ready for it. They believed in the church&#x2019;s authority and its rightful place at the
head of the country. Now what is going on? Stories about the legitimacy of the
operation are leaking like Iraqi oil, every bit as explosive and poisonous. Journalists
are behaving like a pack of hungry wolves, desperate to ﬁnd some ﬂaw in their
authority.
</p><!--l. 30863--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Did we oﬀend the press somehow? How did they ﬁnd out about this?</span>
</p><!--l. 30865--><p class="indent" >  Their competitors in government are rubbing their hands together in anticipation of
imminent failure. The mobile voters were supposed to force the issue for them, but the
game campaign has neither fully materialized nor been the overwhelming success that
was promised. How much money did government spend on building this wretched
white elephant?
</p><!--l. 30872--><p class="indent" >  And their little coup was to come as a surprise, and yet obviously they have known
about the plan for some time. You cannot hide things from the secret service or the

Three Letter Agencies.
</p><!--l. 30876--><p class="indent" >  What makes it worse? Despite the best eﬀorts of his team, god-damned Senator
Weisskopf is actually getting ahead in the polls again, trying to push for some
hell-blazing school rehabilitation program. How could it be that he is actually popular
in the southern states, for crying out loud? And with education? Some idiot has
miscalculated badly and will pay for their mistake.
</p><!--l. 30883--><p class="indent" >  “Can&#x2019;t you lose these goddamned sharks?” the Senator barks into his intercom.
</p><!--l. 30886--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m trying, sir,” the tinny voice of the driver replies. “We have decoys on the
way.”
</p><!--l. 30889--><p class="indent" >  “Now even the FBI are breathing down our necks,” his aid murmurs, in a state of
awe.
</p><!--l. 30892--><p class="indent" >  “Relax, they have no mandate to come in here. We are not doing anything that
would be construed as criminal. We are the ones trying to help the American people
back to a righteousness. We are free to broadcast our ideas to whomever we
wish.”
</p><!--l. 30897--><p class="indent" >  “There are no borders other than the ones we make for ourselves.”
</p><!--l. 30899--><p class="indent" >  “Amen to that.”
</p><!--l. 30901--><p class="indent" >  He takes a slug of brandy, as if ‘Amen&#x2019; were to mean ‘cheers&#x2019; and yells another
‘come on&#x2019; at the driver.
</p><!--l. 30904--><p class="indent" >  “We have not given up our strategy yet, but things are right on the edge. Our
game parameters are based on one set of assumptions. I&#x2019;m not sure that they
are still valid now.” His aid mumbles, almost to himself, apparently in more
distress than the senator himself, and almost as if he believes that the senator is
not really listening to him—which is probably true. Denial is a powerful
medicine.
</p><!--l. 30911--><p class="indent" >  “The educational campaign is making us look stupid,” Dean grates. “We have been
practically reduced to a comic chapter on the anthropology of ceremonial cultures.
Long robes and gold and sequins. They practically turn the Reverend into a side-show
Carney.”
</p><!--l. 30917--><p class="indent" >  “The church leaders have been expressing their worry.”
</p><!--l. 30919--><p class="indent" >  “We can&#x2019;t aﬀord to spend any more on this. There are other matters to attend to as
well.”
</p><!--l. 30922--><p class="indent" >  “Spending is only slightly over budget.”
</p><!--l. 30924--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m talking about the riots, man,” he growls. “What use is a shepherd if he doesn&#x2019;t
even have a ﬂock?”
</p><!--l. 30927--><p class="indent" >  His aid continues: “FEMA are addressing the problems of riots, but they are not
getting anywhere fast. Some of them are turning nasty—anti-government, and
anti-church demonstrations too in the state of California. But the state governments
have no resources to implement the action plans. They&#x2019;re not going to stop anytime
soon”
</p><!--l. 30934--><p class="indent" >  Dean barks a scoﬃng laugh. “The Federal Emergency Management Agency?” He
pronounces with mock reverence. “Hah! What kind of joke are they. In a situation
like this, they are the masters of an empire of dirt. What are they going to

coordinate into action, eh? Fifty years of the American people looking at
government as their enemy, and we have an emaciated infrastructure. The country
is collapsing from lack of maintenance, and all because Americans won&#x2019;t
pay taxes. If we were running the show, things would be diﬀerent. You can
say one thing about the church and that is they know how to manage their
ﬁnances.”
</p><!--l. 30945--><p class="indent" >  The car lifts them high into the air, leaving their stomachs behind, as his aid
receives an incoming call. A glaze descends over him, or is it perhaps a nausea? If a
condemned man can lose heart, his own has apparently skipped a beat. He looks
squarely at his master.
</p><!--l. 30950--><p class="indent" >  “That was Jennifer. The Canadians have promised that they will withdraw their
support for the military actions in the Middle East and Africa if the vote goes ahead.
The Canadian foreign minister said. . .”
</p><!--l. 30954--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, yes, I get the picture. How in the blazes have they caught wind of this
now?”
</p><!--l. 30957--><p class="indent" >  “That means that there will be signiﬁcant pressure on the senate.”
</p><!--l. 30959--><p class="indent" >  “Another leak.”
</p><!--l. 30961--><p class="indent" >  “It would seem to be the case.”
</p><!--l. 30963--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah, diddly.” Dean is apparently succumbing to the inﬂuence. He seems like a
huﬀy child now.
</p><!--l. 30966--><p class="indent" >  The car careers around another bend, evoking another curse from his lips. The aid
begins typing away at his tablet, looking grim, nervous and pale.
</p><!--l. 30970--><p class="indent" >  “You know, my kid has a brother in the VR. Beth and I didn&#x2019;t want any more kids,
so we got one of these sims that are designed for third world families. You
know, the kind that&#x2019;s meant to stop them from wanting too many mouths to
feed.”
</p><!--l. 30975--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, sir. I know the kind.”
</p><!--l. 30977--><p class="indent" >  “They are actually not a bad little invention. Nice piece of American engineering.”
</p><!--l. 30980--><p class="indent" >  The aid lacks the heart to tell him that the invention is Japanese, perhaps because
his cardiac account is already struggling with arrears. The car swerves around a bend
and hits a bump which sends them ﬂying into the air. The senator&#x2019;s brandy spills on
his leg.
</p><!--l. 30986--><p class="indent" >  “Damned game.”
</p><!--l. 30988--><p class="indent" >  “Yessir.”
</p><!--l. 30990--><p class="indent" >  “What about this Morris? Isn&#x2019;t he supposed to be working for us?”
</p><!--l. 30992--><p class="indent" >  “Do we really know if he is any good?”
</p><!--l. 30994--><p class="indent" >  “If he isn&#x2019;t we can sue him for all he&#x2019;s got.”
</p><!--l. 30996--><p class="indent" >  “But then it will be too late.”
</p><!--l. 30998--><p class="indent" >  “Our message will be heard eventually. The Lord will guide us.” He reaches for the
bottle of brandy, but another swerve makes him miss. “If necessary, we can remind the
House of Representatives of their obligations. Michael has dirt on most of
them.”
</p><!--l. 31004--><p class="indent" >  “You mean blackmail?”

</p><!--l. 31006--><p class="indent" >  “Why not”
</p><!--l. 31008--><p class="indent" >  “But can we get away with it?” The aid&#x2019;s spineless voice is shrill now.
</p><!--l. 31010--><p class="indent" >  Dean sits back in his seat without moving. The car seems to have stabilized and is
driving smoothly on a freeway. There is a silence to chill the warmth of the car&#x2019;s
interior. It seems to beckon to the ghosts of past failures and invite the circling of
vultures.
</p><!--l. 31015--><p class="indent" >  “We&#x2019;ll do as we please,” he pronounces sternly, looking out of the window at
something indeterminate. “It was people like us who built America. The law was
made to protect us, not defeat us.”
</p><!--l. 31019--><p class="indent" >  “And the FBI?”
</p><!--l. 31021--><p class="indent" >  “Our hearts are pure.”
</p><!--l. 31023--><p class="indent" >  “They do not know anything speciﬁc yet.”
</p><!--l. 31025--><p class="indent" >  “Do you think they really despise us?” he says, absently. “China and Russia are
doing their damndest now to squeeze us out of central Asia. If we don&#x2019;t move quickly,
we could be set back years. Canada has been asking us to go easy on the French and
the Africans.”
</p><!--l. 31030--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">What is he talking about now? </span>His voice has begun to take on a slight slur. Is it the
brandy, or perhaps another minor stroke?
</p><!--l. 31033--><p class="indent" >  “Sir, are you all right? Do you need your medication?”
</p><!--l. 31035--><p class="indent" >  “Idiot!”
</p><!--l. 31037--><p class="indent" >  Dean stirs from his statue-like pose and leans forward. He seems to be staring into
space.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 31041--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 31042--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 31048--><p class="indent" >  “So,” Ivar babbles, to ﬁll a predicted void. “What are you going to do when this is
all over?” He jabs his apple onto the end of a knife and thrusts it in front of Preeta&#x2019;s
mouth.
</p><!--l. 31052--><p class="indent" >  “Over?” she laughs. “What makes you think this is going to end?”
</p><!--l. 31054--><p class="indent" >  “It is not the journalist&#x2019;s perogative to suppose,” he plays.
</p><!--l. 31056--><p class="indent" >  “Don&#x2019;t believe in that concept.” She raises a palm. “Sorry. This is like the pot of
gold at the end of the rainbow. It&#x2019;s only there because they know you can never reach
it.”
</p><!--l. 31061--><p class="indent" >  “It is not over,” Bishop murmurs. “What have we really done? There is no stability.
We haven&#x2019;t stopped anything. Perhaps we have delayed something. But this isn&#x2019;t
going to help society ﬁnd a direction to latch onto. We&#x2019;re still a visionless economic
merry-go-round.” He refocuses on the little group. “The important thing was to
assemble a strong counterforce. That is the role of police, after all. I think our little
group is onto something here. The FBI has set up some tests. They are going to be
looking carefully at what we&#x2019;ve done. We should try to solve them well. It will give us

credibility and practice.”
</p><!--l. 31072--><p class="indent" >  “You don&#x2019;t think we are ready to handle ourselves now?”
</p><!--l. 31074--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s not the point.”
</p><!--l. 31076--><p class="indent" >  “Well,” Preeta says. “We might have been ‘assembled&#x2019;, and we might be a success
so far. What really interests me is who has been coordinating all of this? Who is
behind it all? And don&#x2019;t tell me it is all coincidence that all of us are here together
with the right tools for the job.”
</p><!--l. 31082--><p class="indent" >  Bishop stares at her for a long instant, with a new respect and a kindly smile. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Good</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">girl, </span>he thinks. “Does it really matter?”
</p><!--l. 31086--><p class="indent" >  “Shouldn&#x2019;t we be allowed to know?”
</p><!--l. 31088--><p class="indent" >  Bishop purses his lips and avoids the remark. “None of this will make any
diﬀerence in the long run unless something happens to back it up.”
</p><!--l. 31091--><p class="indent" >  Jonathan, ever at his heels, adds: “We&#x2019;ve had our little forest ﬁre, cleared some
space so we can see the wood for the trees. But the forest lives and it will
try to close in again. We have to hope that the signals we&#x2019;ve sown are good
ones.”
</p><!--l. 31096--><p class="indent" >  “In the end, it&#x2019;s not what we do that matters. It&#x2019;s what ordinary people think, and
how they react. The law doesn&#x2019;t exist without the basic agreement of common folk.
They are the material we are trying to bend into shape.”
</p><!--l. 31102--><p class="indent" >  “One thing though,” Ivar laughs, in that geeky boyish way that he cannot control.
“You have to admit, it&#x2019;s pretty cool to know that our main weapon against the
corruption of Christianity was Christmas.”
</p><!--l. 31106--><p class="indent" >  Vibe winks. “Pagan festival.”
</p>
