</p><!--l. 31110--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 31113--><p class="indent" >  In the game, Vibe&#x2019;s appearance is that of a stunning young woman, with a mere
sheen of metallic spray to clothe her female form. Her skin-tight attire covers more
her psyche than her avatar&#x2019;s body. Dermot ﬁnds himself staring and Preeta is equally
entranced at her audacity.
</p><!--l. 31119--><p class="indent" >  She has with her a friend whom she calls Bea, who is equal in height but with a
subtly diﬀerent, similarly audacious ﬁgure. They have been playing along with the
agents. Things are working out, thanks to Dermot&#x2019;s handiwork.
</p><!--l. 31123--><p class="indent" >  “This game is pretty cool.”
</p><!--l. 31125--><p class="indent" >  “Think it&#x2019;s worth a BAFTA?” Dermot asks.
</p><!--l. 31127--><p class="indent" >  “The morality barometer is pretty cheesy.”
</p><!--l. 31129--><p class="indent" >  “It was supposed to be.”
</p><!--l. 31131--><p class="indent" >  Mary Cheung is waiting for the girls when they arrive.
</p><!--l. 31133--><p class="indent" >  “So, are you with us?” Vibe asks.
</p><!--l. 31135--><p class="indent" >  “Yes. Can I tag along?”

</p><!--l. 31137--><p class="indent" >  “Reckon that would be all right.”
</p><!--l. 31139--><p class="indent" >  “You should meet my brother,” Mary says. “He is going to be so excited.”
</p><!--l. 31141--><p class="indent" >  And that means, he will do what she tells him.
</p><!--l. 31143--><p class="indent" >  So, the ghosts and denizens of the game have become adept at manipulating their
creators, Dermot thinks. It is not really a big surprise though, is it? After all, the game
rules are designed with just that in mind. They built the ultimate propaganda
machine: naturally it would work on them too. But unlike a gun, a weapon of
destruction, it does not kill: rather it becomes part <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">deus ex machina</span>, taming its
master.
</p><!--l. 31156--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

<a 
 id="x1-62r58"></a>
