<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">58</span>
</p><!--l. 31159--><p class="indent" >  There is a gnawing in the wall, as if a giant woodpecker has taken nest there. She
can&#x2019;t remember the doorbell ever sounding like that.
</p><!--l. 31163--><p class="indent" >  “Hello?”
</p><!--l. 31165--><p class="indent" >  No one on the speaker.
</p><!--l. 31167--><p class="indent" >  There is a soft knock on the door. Of course, there is someone ringing from within
the building. What on Earth could that be about?
</p><!--l. 31170--><p class="indent" >  She opens the door and stares at the intrusion.
</p><!--l. 31172--><p class="indent" >  It is him!
</p><!--l. 31174--><p class="indent" >  Frank is here.
</p><!--l. 31176--><p class="indent" >  He is carrying her backpack over one shoulder.
</p><!--l. 31178--><p class="indent" >  “Hi, Sara.”
</p><!--l. 31180--><p class="indent" >  The crease of shock ebbs into a thundering of blood in her ears. She might
always get her way, but there are certain limits beyond which one expects to
succeed.
</p><!--l. 31184--><p class="indent" >  “Oh my god, hello!” she stammers, struggling to quell a visceral tempest of
questions and emotions.
</p><!--l. 31187--><p class="indent" >  Frank grins in amusement at her petriﬁcation.
</p><!--l. 31189--><p class="indent" >  “Can I come in? This is pretty heavy.”
</p><!--l. 31191--><p class="indent" >  She looks at the backpack and remembers her manners. “Eh, yes! Yes! Sorry, come
in!”
</p><!--l. 31194--><p class="indent" >  He steps through the doorway and she closes it behind him, peering curiously
around the hallway to make sure that no other lurkers are hiding in the shadows. How
did he get in?
</p><!--l. 31198--><p class="indent" >  “How did you get in?” she asks, ﬁnally.
</p><!--l. 31200--><p class="indent" >  “There are certain advantages to being an oﬃcer of the law,” he winks. Frank
releases the backpack from his shoulder onto a pile of her shoes. “Oops, sorry. I
thought you might like to have this back.”
</p><!--l. 31204--><p class="indent" >  “Are you kidding?”

</p><!--l. 31206--><p class="indent" >  “Nope. All checked and accounted for.”
</p><!--l. 31208--><p class="indent" >  “Thank you! I mean, I didn&#x2019;t expect you to bring it. . .”
</p><!--l. 31210--><p class="indent" >  He grins back at her. “Actually, as it turns out, I was coming to Oslo anyway. I have
a course at police college for a few of days, so I thought I&#x2019;d see if you were home. You
left in kind of a hurry and I wasn&#x2019;t sure if I had maybe done something to oﬀend
you.”
</p><!--l. 31215--><p class="indent" >  She shakes her head in surprise, momentarily at a loss for words, and deﬁnitely not
the coolest cookie she has ever baked. “Like what?”
</p><!--l. 31219--><p class="indent" >  He shrugs. “I thought we were getting to be friends, so I was disappointed when
you were suddenly gone.”
</p><!--l. 31222--><p class="indent" >  “I didn&#x2019;t really have time,” she begins. “I got this call, about a job.”
</p><!--l. 31225--><p class="indent" >  “A job? I thought you were studying?”
</p><!--l. 31227--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, it&#x2019;s kind of a long story.”
</p><!--l. 31229--><p class="indent" >  “All right.”
</p><!--l. 31231--><p class="indent" >  “But I had to leave in a hurry. It was nothing personal. I did send you a message. .
.eventually. It took a little while to ﬁnd you.”
</p><!--l. 31234--><p class="indent" >  “Good.”
</p><!--l. 31236--><p class="indent" >  “So. . .so. . .you&#x2019;re here!”
</p><!--l. 31238--><p class="indent" >  “Yes,” he conﬁrms. “Service with a smile.”
</p><!--l. 31240--><p class="indent" >  “I. . . Oh my god. Ehh, so, look, have a seat. Sorry about the mess. I wasn&#x2019;t
expecting anyone.” She moves some papers and a few cups from the table, and laughs
nervously.
</p><!--l. 31243--><p class="indent" >  He takes oﬀ his jacket and walks the few steps through a doorway to sit himself
down on the sofa. It is a small apartment, but cozy.
</p><!--l. 31246--><p class="indent" >  “Nice apartment,” he says.
</p><!--l. 31248--><p class="indent" >  “Thanks. So, eh, would you like some coﬀee or tea or something?”
</p><!--l. 31250--><p class="indent" >  “Actually, I can&#x2019;t stay long, but maybe later?”
</p><!--l. 31252--><p class="indent" >  Later? “Oh, okay.” She examines his face. He looks less vulnerable here: harder,
more conﬁdent, at home. She is not sure what she feels. “So are you going to be
staying for long?”
</p><!--l. 31256--><p class="indent" >  “A few days.”
</p><!--l. 31258--><p class="indent" >  “You already said that. Stupid me.” She was not prepared for this. It&#x2019;s not fair! “So
where will you be staying?”
</p><!--l. 31262--><p class="indent" >  “There&#x2019;s a hotel close to the college. Majorstuen.”
</p><!--l. 31264--><p class="indent" >  She nods.
</p><!--l. 31266--><p class="indent" >  “So tell me, “ he asks. “What did you do to upset my colleague? How did this end
up getting conﬁscated?”
</p><!--l. 31269--><p class="indent" >  She shrugs. “It&#x2019;s a long story. It doesn&#x2019;t matter.”
</p><!--l. 31271--><p class="indent" >  “Good to have it back though?”
</p><!--l. 31273--><p class="indent" >  “My stuﬀ is in here,” she aﬃrms.
</p><!--l. 31276--><p class="indent" >  “Maybe you should check everything is okay.”
</p><!--l. 31278--><p class="indent" >  She nods. “Good idea.”

</p><!--l. 31280--><p class="indent" >  Vibe drags the sack into the living room and clips it open. She peers into what was
her home for the better part of a week. The pack is quite full: soft items on the top,
heavier ones below. She begins to empty the contents onto the ﬂoor around her,
making an impromptu campsite.
</p><!--l. 31286--><p class="indent" >  “Making a mess,” she smiles, feeling a little as though she is undressing in front of
him.
</p><!--l. 31289--><p class="indent" >  He seems to sense her discomfort. “Can I use your bathroom?” he asks.
</p><!--l. 31291--><p class="indent" >  She nods. “By the door.”
</p><!--l. 31293--><p class="indent" >  The contents of the rucksack appear to be intact. It doesn&#x2019;t even seem as though
anyone has looked through them. Pussy beat bitch was obviously just messing with
her. Her tablet is there. It still contains some of the work she did before she left. It
hasn&#x2019;t been synchronized with home yet.
</p><!--l. 31299--><p class="indent" >  Seeing this backpack again brings a feeling of strangeness to be home again.
So much has changed. So many new things in her life. For a split second,
she misses her family: her brother, her mother. Then she feels silly at the
response.
</p><!--l. 31304--><p class="indent" >  She has crossed a boundary within herself these past weeks, an unexpected frontier
of realization. Perhaps that is what it means to grow up, or perhaps it is the ﬁrst of
many changes in her life. It doesn&#x2019;t really matter, does it? She has seen through the
deceptions that life attempts to pile on. There will be no more romantic fantasies
in her life from now on. There is a sense of ending, as well as a sense of
beginning.
</p><!--l. 31312--><p class="indent" >  In the bottom of the backpack is a hard item that brings a new dread. She
looks at the box from Mrs. Laurent. There it is. Her nemesis, in monolithic
form. She could open it now. But does she need to? Does she want to know
what is in it? Perhaps some things are better left unknown? She places it
on a small table, where she can look at it, and ponders its form. What will
she release if she opens it? How will it change her new life? A life that it
working out well, which she is enjoying. Could she have both lives? Is that
greedy?
</p><!--l. 31322--><p class="indent" >  Frank stands in the doorway. “Okay?” he says.
</p><!--l. 31324--><p class="indent" >  She looks at him. “Okay,” she replies with a trace of melancholy, and her throat
contracts so that she has to swallow to relieve the ache of guilt.
</p><!--l. 31328--><p class="indent" >  Frank looked after her when she was sick. How many people have done that for
her? Now he has come all the way here with her backpack, on the slightest of hints.
And he is nice, in an odd sort of way: not really the kind of person she expected to
like, but the fact is there. And he clearly likes her.
</p><!--l. 31334--><p class="indent" >  “You know”, he says, “it&#x2019;s not that far to Majorstuen. Maybe we can meet up while
I&#x2019;m here?”
</p><!--l. 31337--><p class="indent" >  She smiles. It is only about a kilometre. “But you&#x2019;re not staying long.” The words
seem strange in her mouth as though she is not quite sure how to phrase them
suddenly. Why did she even say that? What does it matter how long he is here
for?

</p><!--l. 31342--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">He didn&#x2019;t ask to marry you, stupid.</span>
</p><!--l. 31344--><p class="indent" >  “Well. It&#x2019;s not that far to Oslo either, and I&#x2019;m getting transferred soon.”
</p><!--l. 31346--><p class="indent" >  “Where to?”
</p><!--l. 31348--><p class="indent" >  “Guess.”
</p><!--l. 31350--><p class="indent" >  She smiles optimistically and then it fades. He looks down at his feet.
</p><!--l. 31353--><p class="indent" >  “Okay then,” he nods and moves to exit.
</p><!--l. 31355--><p class="indent" >  Vibe feels disappointment envelop and ﬂood through her, in an instant. She has not
really understood, before now, exactly what she feels about him. Their journey
together has been serendipitous rather than planned, and all the time she has been
distracted by a diﬀerent, stupid romantic fantasy.
</p><!--l. 31361--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">It is possible to enjoy something that you haven&#x2019;t chosen yourself.</span>
</p><!--l. 31363--><p class="indent" >  Frank seems to reconsider and stops himself. “Give me a hug?” he asks, almost
apologetically.
</p><!--l. 31366--><p class="indent" >  Vibe explodes into a toothy grin and leaps up from the backpack, embracing him
needily. More than he expected, he reciprocates hesitantly.
</p><!--l. 31369--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Damn it</span>, she thinks, <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I have to take charge here</span>.
</p><!--l. 31371--><p class="indent" >  She pushes back from him and kisses him ﬁrmly on the lips for several seconds
before looking him in the eyes and grinning.
</p><!--l. 31374--><p class="indent" >  “Wow!” he laughs back in amazement. Then again: “Wow!”
</p><!--l. 31376--><p class="indent" >  They laugh and hug again and steal another kiss.
</p><!--l. 31378--><p class="indent" >  “See you soon then,” she says.
</p><!--l. 31380--><p class="indent" >  “See you soon, Sara.”
</p><!--l. 31382--><p class="indent" >  They part slowly with a glancing farewell, grinning like two stupid adult
kids.
</p><!--l. 31384--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Boys! </span>She smiles. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">So stupid, so necessary.</span>
</p><!--l. 31386--><p class="indent" >  Sara Vibeke Stensrud looks up to the ceiling to take in the moment. She feels
somehow lighter than before, and jumps up and down twice to test the notion. The
future is there in front of her. She knows a way forward. Perhaps it is only one of
many paths, or perhaps it is the right one. She doesn&#x2019;t really care. It feels good and
that, after all, is a good enough reason to follow it. Everything is going to be okay, she
thinks.
</p><!--l. 31394--><p class="indent" >  Then, almost as an afterthought she remembers herself and smiles. Bea has got to
hear this.
</p><!--l. 31397--><p class="indent" >  So then, out with the mobile.
</p><!--l. 31406--><p class="indent" >  <mbp:pagebreak/>

