<span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-248">59</span>
</p><!--l. 31406--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="ptmb7t-x-x-172">Epilogue</span>
</p><!--l. 31411--><p class="indent" >  It is May, soon to be summer, and all the trees are exploding with green and white
blossoms. The heavy pollen-leaden odour of the bushes makes the air thick and hard
to breathe.
</p><!--l. 31415--><p class="indent" >  Jonas is out walking.
</p><!--l. 31417--><p class="indent" >  For a few moments, he has time to be alone with his thoughts, thoughts that tumble
amidst a garden of possibility, which borders on a landﬁll of corruption. He has
brought a book with him—a novel, no less. He took it in virtual deﬁance of his
pursuers. When was is it last he was able to read for mere pleasure? How long has he
been shackled by responsibility, his pleasure centres immobilised by fatigue? All that
could be about to change.
</p><!--l. 31425--><p class="indent" >  He settles onto a wooden bench in the glade of the park, in a spot where he can
enjoy the still water of a nearby pond. These moments of rest will do him good before
they ﬁnd him. A few words of something other than project descriptions, or rules and
regulations: it helps to quench the impatience.
</p><!--l. 31431--><p class="indent" >  The park is relatively quiet here, at this late hour of the day. Most people are
already on their way home from work, but there are some here. A woman strolls past
him with her child and he pauses to admire their harmony. One has to envy the look of
placid contentment, the calm rapport she seems to have with the youngster,
as if some inner telepathy soothes their companionship with complete and
mutual understanding. It is not exactly the way he frames his own image of
fatherhood, with Kaja. Others seem to make relationships work, why couldn&#x2019;t
he?
</p><!--l. 31441--><p class="indent" >  Perhaps there is a dozen reasons, perhaps there is only himself to blame. The time
for judgement has, at any rate, passed. Now the challenge has become a diﬀerent one:
one of continuation, of redressing past mistakes and moving on with future
possibilities. He has been compiling a list of things he owes Martin, and now
that there is more distance between them, he is even interacting better with
Kaja.

</p><!--l. 31449--><p class="indent" >  Jonas can imagine now how a glacier feels, thawing from its own private ice age: all
that independent water, once in free ﬂight, dragged down into a pool of anonymity,
locked into bondage by the grip of an oppressive winter, ﬁnally feeling its spirit
released by a kinder, warmer sun. It signals the beginning of a new cycle. To happen
all over again?
</p><!--l. 31456--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Perish the thought.</span>
</p><!--l. 31458--><p class="indent" >  The woman continues on with her child, smiling at that sun, without a visible worry
in the world. He envies her. He actually envies her.
</p><!--l. 31463--><p class="indent" >  In her footsteps, something stranger still: a large bearded man, dressed in black
jeans and rock-group nano-shirt, ambles comically into view. Jonas turn his head
slightly to see the man stoop and pick up the ice-cream paper which her child
has dropped. He places it, with visible annoyance, into a litter bin near the
bench.
</p><!--l. 31469--><p class="indent" >  Observe this overt display of civic responsibility! It is cause enough to be taken
aback. The man is not a park employee. He is an ordinary man, with no apparent
connection to her. On the other hand, he is about the right age, about the right proﬁle.
Could this be the result of Edward Bishop&#x2019;s work? Has this man been inﬂuenced in
his thinking, in his attitudes by a succubus?
</p><!--l. 31476--><p class="indent" >  It is surely too early to tell who is responsible: whether the eﬀect of their
campaigning is measurable, or whether he is just an anomalous occurrence, a
fortuitous anachronism of the modern world. However you look at it, this is a wonder
to behold.
</p><!--l. 31481--><p class="indent" >  His mobile vibrates suddenly, with a simple message from Sara.
</p><!--l. 31483--><p class="indent" >  She replies simply: “The vice president was an algorithm?” He smiles at the
response, uncertain whether she is joking or not.
</p><!--l. 31486--><p class="indent" >  Jonas posted a quote from a former Vice-President Al Gore: something about ”the
greatest discovery of all this research is that we can no longer can separate basic from
applied science The disciplines are connected in ways they have never been before. . .”
It seemed like an appropriate encouragement of her current work at the time:
something to keep her on the hook of expectation. The machinations of bureaucracy
are not over yet as far as her PhD is concerned, but Sara is a survivor. She will do all
right, no matter what happens next.
</p><!--l. 31495--><p class="indent" >  Jonas tries to open his book. He has a lot on his mind that wants to say its piece.
Reading seems out of the question. Another good plan extinguished.
</p><!--l. 31499--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Soon, soon.</span>
</p><!--l. 31501--><p class="indent" >  This apparently bottomless process of defending the institutions of research and
education has been long and arduous. It has taken him through trials and ordeals of
stamina that would break many. Another man might have crumbled before him, but
he has been partially anaesthetised by his own personal conﬂict. Jonas has
weathered the adversity with a brave face; but he also also senses that he has
approached breaking point several times along the way, as a donkey&#x2019;s back
is broken under the incremental addition of an inﬁnity of falling pieces of
straw.

</p><!--l. 31511--><p class="indent" >  But why should he care about any of that today? Today, he could be the survivor
himself. This could be it: the end of this little battle for his integrity. Now that the sun
is shining, he no longer cares as much for the problems of oﬃce. He is purged by a
pregnant sun and his own endocrine reaction. The burgeoning warmth of the day
surrenders his worries to the realms of the academic, pun or no pun. And now also: a
relative calm has fallen over his personal life, leaving him to feel unconcerned
about the outcome of the ﬁnal challenge: the one ﬁnal obfuscation that will
permit substance to triumph over style. Politics will surely have to accept
reason.
</p><!--l. 31522--><p class="indent" >  But it is a delicate business, and not quite done yet. No wonder inﬂuence campaigns
have to be planned so carefully: if the sun alone can cleanse an individual&#x2019;s purpose
and passion, what hope does one have of ruling anyone&#x2019;s attention? Each little
environmental signal is simply part of a grand regatta of impulses, sailing
into the ﬁnish line, competing for the attention—for the prize of the human
brain.
</p><!--l. 31530--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">And if there were a god, he would have to be pretty disappointed that such a</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">powerful and expensive instrument could be played so easily, by so trivial a</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">troubadour.</span>
</p><!--l. 31535--><p class="indent" >  It will not be long now. He had better put his book away and start walking. He will
head towards the canopy of the trees to ﬁnd some shade.
</p><!--l. 31539--><p class="indent" >  Jonas gets up from the bench and stands tall. More than ever, at this moment, he
feels as though he is alone, but surviving. It gives him a taste almost of power, of
self-conﬁdence. It evokes an eerily surreal sensation. He feels taller, when he walks:
he feels every step. It is dizzying. He feels larger than life somehow, hypersensitive.
Motion is accentuated.
</p><!--l. 31546--><p class="indent" >  It is supremacy.
</p><!--l. 31548--><p class="indent" >  Mastery over oneself.
</p><!--l. 31550--><p class="indent" >  He takes no particular pleasure in the feeling. That might come later. For now, it
simply is. He acknowledges it rationally and ﬁles the observation for possible use, like
the orderly clerk that he is.
</p><!--l. 31555--><p class="indent" >  And then he comes to the little wooden bridge that bisects the pond.
</p><!--l. 31558--><p class="indent" >  He knows that they will have been alerted to his work by now, at the ministry. The
ﬁnal stage has to include them, as the EU commission challenges them to conﬁrm
their surrender of research funds against the basic guidelines of the community. And
therein lay an unexpected pitfall for the government.
</p><!--l. 31564--><p class="indent" >  There is, of course, a diﬀerence between making the decisions and actually
wielding the axe. Both turn out to be double edged swords, so to speak. If a
bureaucracy can hinder the implementation of the research council&#x2019;s independent
decisions, then the council has an equal power to obstruct their intervention with
bureaucracy. The mindless leviathan does not take sides, it merely lumbers with the
obstinacy of habit. A commander of government can easily run aground on the perils
of its own bureaucracy, for commanders generally trust their soldiers, under
threat of execution, incarceration or even ex-communication. What will be his

punishment?
</p><!--l. 31575--><p class="indent" >  He has seen through their game. The tune they dance to is one of short term gains:
fast rewards and sound-bite press releases, neither methodical nor considered
decisions. So, he has been learning the tricks of the trade and has moved his pieces
carefully on the board to manoeuvre his opponent into a check mate. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Shah mat! </span>Die
king..
</p><!--l. 31581--><p class="indent" >  It has ground him down, and worn him out, but he is still standing. So, at this
moment, he has earned the right to be in the park, observing the young and the
beautiful, without risking the guilt or repercussions that have haunted him over the
past year. And, my goodness, the spring hatches these beautiful visions of
womanhood from their cocoons in numbers. It does not matter that they are merely
distant fantasies. To him, they represent hope.
</p><!--l. 31590--><p class="indent" >  For a moment he believes he sees Edward Bishop, but no, it is someone else. He has
gotten to know the older man a little over the past months. He is looking older these
days, but with a contentment about his work. Bishop claims that they have put
a temporary cork into organized crime: maﬁa, vigilante groups, churches.
Those organizations are opportunistic scavengers, who operate best when
society is broken and fearful. If the game&#x2019;s many signals were to heal and unite
people, if it were to be a unifying force for good, strengthening and educating
people rather than driving them apart, it would signal an end to their power.
He is their worst enemy. Someone built a crooked house, and his team is
straightening it out. The world of tomorrow will live in the House that Bishop
built.
</p><!--l. 31605--><p class="indent" >  That the churches have not visibly succeeded in usurping the power from western
states tells them that someone, somewhere must be playing their games: games that
his team has spiked with altruism. It would make an interesting research project
to follow who is doing what to make it all work, but they have to simply
take it on trust for now. That&#x2019;s ﬁne. Somewhere in the world, pretty much
anything you can think of is happening somewhere. That&#x2019;s what diversity
does for you. As long as the melody resonates, it will ﬁnd its place in the
symphony.
</p><!--l. 31615--><p class="indent" >  Bishop&#x2019;s team is a bright constellation and they have helped him in unimaginable
and intangible ways. Without them he might not have understood how to avoid the
ﬁnal move in his own game of chess. It was the Indian girl, Sara&#x2019;s new friend
who told him: “Why is it that you didn&#x2019;t think of simply asking anyone for
help?”
</p><!--l. 31621--><p class="indent" >  It was an excellent question.
</p><!--l. 31623--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Have we become so independent, so disconnected that we cannot even ask our</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">friends and neighbours to help us out in a time of trouble?</span>
</p><!--l. 31627--><p class="indent" >  People don&#x2019;t ask each other for help anymore. His mobile doesn&#x2019;t have a menu
option for that. It took an alien to diagnose the malady.
</p><!--l. 31632--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">What is wrong with us that we cannot even recognize and come together when we</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">have common goals?</span>

</p><!--l. 31635--><p class="indent" >  They have become Africa, as Joe said. Life is mercenary in a selﬁsh world.
</p><!--l. 31638--><p class="indent" >  So he asked for help.
</p><!--l. 31640--><p class="indent" >  And Bishop&#x2019;s bright constellation was happy to assist. He shrugged at the
suggestion that he was being generous. “My voice has been heard,” he conﬁded. “I&#x2019;ve
done my little recruiting campaign and we&#x2019;ve put together a plausible new force. My
little mission has been fulﬁlled. Where does it takes us? Just to the next phase. Maybe
yours in the next phase.”
</p><!--l. 31647--><p class="indent" >  “What you&#x2019;ve done will last, as long as there are people with skills to carry on the
team,” Jonas assured him. “With people like Sara at the wheel, a little bureaucracy
won&#x2019;t be enough to stop it.”
</p><!--l. 31651--><p class="indent" >  They might never know what was really going to happen. But that is not really the
point is it? The point is that it is happening all the time. It never stops. And they are
just participants and spectators. It&#x2019;s all one big fairground ride, where big splashes are
really just little ripples. The game will continue with or without the VR. It has been
running since the start of time. Right now, it involves the future of education and of
society.
</p><!--l. 31660--><p class="indent" >  Jonas approaches the fountain pool and takes a last peek at his book and his
moment arrives.
</p><!--l. 31663--><p class="indent" >  “Mr. Lindgren!”
</p><!--l. 31665--><p class="indent" >  It is the detestable Leif Erik Larsen, accompanied by two police oﬃcers. Bishop
has provided them, and is watching their progress from somewhere. They will do
their jobs, but their will not step over the line of the law for this petty power
seeker.
</p><!--l. 31670--><p class="indent" >  “Good day, Mr. Larsen.”
</p><!--l. 31672--><p class="indent" >  “I had a little trouble ﬁnding you. I believe you know why I am here.”
</p><!--l. 31674--><p class="indent" >  He nods, carefully placing his paperback novel inside a small plastic carrier bag,
and putting it into a deep pocket of his jacket to protect it.
</p><!--l. 31677--><p class="indent" >  “You want me to cancel the appeal application to the European Union&#x2019;s arbitration
board.”
</p><!--l. 31680--><p class="indent" >  “That would be the polite thing to do.”
</p><!--l. 31682--><p class="indent" >  Jonas smiles.
</p><!--l. 31684--><p class="indent" >  “We do not consider it proper procedure to go over our heads.”
</p><!--l. 31686--><p class="indent" >  “Funny that you should talk about proper procedure,” he says.
</p><!--l. 31688--><p class="indent" >  “There is procedure and there is etiquette.”
</p><!--l. 31690--><p class="indent" >  “Yes.”
</p><!--l. 31692--><p class="indent" >  “So, you will withdraw the application.” It is not a question.
</p><!--l. 31694--><p class="indent" >  “You are cutting it a bit ﬁne.” Jonas looks at his watch, ceremonially. “But then the
ministry is rarely in a hurry.”
</p><!--l. 31697--><p class="indent" >  “The deadline has not passed.”
</p><!--l. 31699--><p class="indent" >  “Unfortunately, it is too late. We won&#x2019;t be able to make the deadline for withdrawal
now.”
</p><!--l. 31702--><p class="indent" >  “You have to cancel this,” he says with a certain imperative.

</p><!--l. 31704--><p class="indent" >  Jonas shrugs. “I would love to help, but I left the codes on a tablet on my
desk. I didn&#x2019;t synchronize them anywhere. We would have to go and ﬁnd
them.”
</p><!--l. 31708--><p class="indent" >  “Then that is what we shall do.”
</p><!--l. 31710--><p class="indent" >  “It isn&#x2019;t very convenient now,” Jonas smiles. “I have taken the afternoon
oﬀ.”
</p><!--l. 31713--><p class="indent" >  “Mr. Lindgren, you do understand that hindering the state could be considered an
oﬀence.”
</p><!--l. 31716--><p class="indent" >  “That would be criminal and irresponsible of me,” he issues ﬂatly. “Not my
style.”
</p><!--l. 31719--><p class="indent" >  “I have to warn you that, if you fail to cooperate, you could be arrested, and charges
could be brought against you.”
</p><!--l. 31722--><p class="indent" >  Jonas shrugs. “I don&#x2019;t think that will be necessary.”
</p><!--l. 31724--><p class="indent" >  “Good, then we shall go to your oﬃce now.”
</p><!--l. 31726--><p class="indent" >  Jonas looks at his wrist again. “People will have gone home now.”
</p><!--l. 31728--><p class="indent" >  “Stop procrastinating!” Larsen spits. “Come with us now. We are going in there to
cancel the order, before it goes through and I will need you to accompany me and
show me where the codes are.”
</p><!--l. 31732--><p class="indent" >  Jonas nods. “Very well”
</p><!--l. 31734--><p class="indent" >  They walk briskly through the park. Jonas does not drag his heels much beyond
what is involuntary sulking. They have a car and escort waiting, but it would be
quicker to walk back to his oﬃce, if truth be known. No matter, that is not his
concern. The car carries them through the town&#x2019;s traﬃc machine, the few blocks to the
small hill where the oﬃces of the Research Council are located and they step out into
the cobbled street.
</p><!--l. 31742--><p class="indent" >  The building looks dead now, though it is hard to tell from down here. Larsen and
his entourage herd him to the main entrance, where his mobile identiﬁes
him and a code opens the door. They pass through the empty reception and
summon the elevator. The metal-glass box lifts them to the ﬂoor where Jonas has
an oﬃce and deposits them in front of a new pair of glass doors. They are
locked.
</p><!--l. 31749--><p class="indent" >  A yellow cone with a stop sign is placed in front of the doors, and behind them,
they can see a man with a buﬃng machine working. A sign hangs on the
doors.
     </p>
