<!--l. 31760--><p class="indent" >  The glass doors are locked.

</p><!--l. 31762--><p class="indent" >  “Open the doors,” Larsen instructs.
</p><!--l. 31764--><p class="indent" >  Jonas shrugs. “I don&#x2019;t have keys to this door. The administration doesn&#x2019;t grant mere
employees keys to the building.”
</p><!--l. 31767--><p class="indent" >  “Mr. Larsen, don&#x2019;t waste time.”
</p><!--l. 31769--><p class="indent" >  “Really, I do not have the key to this door.”
</p><!--l. 31771--><p class="indent" >  He knocks on the glass doors to attract the attention of the man with the buﬃng
machine. If he hears, he does not respond.
</p><!--l. 31774--><p class="indent" >  “Isn&#x2019;t there someone we can call?”
</p><!--l. 31776--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t know the number of the company who cleans here.”
</p><!--l. 31778--><p class="indent" >  Larsen becomes agitated. “Can&#x2019;t you open this?”
</p><!--l. 31781--><p class="indent" >  “Not without a key.”
</p><!--l. 31783--><p class="indent" >  “Can we break in?”
</p><!--l. 31785--><p class="indent" >  The police oﬃcer makes a shake of his head. “I&#x2019;m afraid we don&#x2019;t have the
authority to do that. Mr. Larsen. Not without an order from the court.”
</p><!--l. 31789--><p class="indent" >  He grows red. “I am the government. We make the law!”
</p><!--l. 31791--><p class="indent" >  “Not today, sir.”
</p><!--l. 31793--><p class="indent" >  His face trembles with hatred and anger. He is bursting with some recrimination,
some threat of repercussion, but he manages to contain it. He prances back and forth
for several minutes, looking for some clue, but time is ticking on. There are no clues
here. He could try to ﬁnd out who is in charge, but Jonas knows that the cleaning staﬀ
will not part with their authority to close the ﬂoor lightly. There is actually little that
any of them can do now.
</p><!--l. 31801--><p class="indent" >  Apparently realizing the hopelessness of it, he swings around and storms out of the
building alone. He cannot get in. The building does not belong to any of
them.
</p><!--l. 31805--><p class="indent" >  Jonas smiles. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">So this time the victory will not be yours either. Today, the janitor has</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">the ﬁnal word.</span>
</p><!--l. 31809--><p class="indent" >  He shrugs to the police oﬃcers.
</p>
<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 31813--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 31814--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 31822--><p class="indent" >  Even after all this time, Den is still confused about the way Catalin Cortina treated
him. He is puzzled over her rejection of him as a man. It is not as if he tried to seduce
her, though even that would have been better than what transpired. He feels soiled
somehow by his encounter with her, and still he cannot quite escape the need to repair
the misunderstanding, to win her approval.
</p><!--l. 31829--><p class="indent" >  That vanity might be the source of his unease could not possibly occur to
him, for he has never seriously understood why other people, inclined along
alternative planes of thought, cannot simply extend their friendship with physical
intimacy, as would he in the same situation. When people allow themselves to be

seduced, either mentally or physically, everyone feels so much better afterwards.
Why would anyone bother to abstain? It is like a cessation of hostilities, a
bridge of trust—a private bond between souls, not some merely superﬁcial chit
chat.
</p><!--l. 31839--><p class="indent" >  Of course, this is simply the blindness of a man that comes about from an excessive
focus on his own performance. He is the Ptolemaic centre of his own universe:
everything else revolves around that focal point of self.
</p><!--l. 31844--><p class="indent" >  He sought to use Catalin Cortina as a fulcrum for his own ascension; instead she
gave him homework to do, as if her were little more than a naughty school boy. Now
he ﬂips between wanting to do the homework, to please the teacher, and wanting to
purge all thought of the woman from his mind.
</p><!--l. 31850--><p class="indent" >  A causal onlooker might ﬁnd the predicament an unreasonable and triﬂing
concern, and imagine him to be wallowing in an obsequious self-pity: but
that is only because they do not fully know him, or even begin understand
what makes him who he is. There are good reasons for his ambivalence. His
inner circle has noticed how he seems encumbered by a melancholy, but one
does not ask about the whys and wherefores of such things in this day and
age.
</p><!--l. 31858--><p class="indent" >  More than anything, he is unsatisﬁed with his own performance. He does not feel
that circumstances have allowed him to demonstrate his abilities. An omen of failure
hangs over him now, like a thief swinging in the gallows. Oddly, that thought weighs
upon him more than most. Is it a failure to impress? Failure to steer the course of
things? What is it?
</p><!--l. 31865--><p class="indent" >  Kylie McLachlan has been supportive in her tangential way, making fun of him, at
his expense. Her humour and casual courting will carry him through it; she is a friend.
And sensing his resilience, in spite of his wound, she has refrained from rubbing salt
in the real sore.
</p><!--l. 31870--><p class="indent" >  If Den has hoped to rule the world, then he cannot do it as long as he cares what
someone thinks about him.
</p><!--l. 31873--><p class="indent" >  Den looks at the invitation on his tablet screen.
