<!--l. 31883--><p class="indent" >  Vascon. That&#x2019;s her, playing with him. Teasing him.
</p><!--l. 31885--><p class="indent" >  He could grow to despise her for that. And yet he knows that she knows that he
cannot strike back. The only way he could get back at her would be to beat her at her
own game, and that is exactly what she wants.

</p><!--l. 31890--><p class="indent" >  He is most inclined to simply do nothing.
</p><!--l. 31892--><p class="indent" >  Instinct tells him: he can neither go forwards nor backwards, nor choose between
the gods who have summoned him for their bidding. The only alternative is to stand
still, to carry on business as usual. Den the player had been played. And yet, as a
pawn in someone else game of chess, he will be discarded unless he is useful.
Circumstances seem to have drawn the burden of responsibility not merely around
him, but partially away from him; the religious factions have been backing oﬀ
somewhat, in the light of recent and certain revelations (no pun obviously
intended).
</p><!--l. 31902--><p class="indent" >  And, now that he is no longer their centre of attention, he feels oddly disoriented, as
if he has lost his compass bearing. Have the church leaders and their stooges gone
underground, into some doomsday crypt? Have they been arrested? He has not
received a single word from them or about them. Nor has there been any direct
communication from the government contractor, though that need not mean anything
other than that they expect their job done. Perhaps it is time to make a mark that
people will notice, once again?
</p><!--l. 31911--><p class="indent" >  Revenge? Pay-back? It would be a crude gesture, an unworthy gesture.
</p><!--l. 31914--><p class="indent" >  No, no need for that. The world needs directed imaging. He provides that
service better than anyone. Therefore he is needed. It is the simple logic of
commerce. So why does he not ﬁnd comfort in the syllogism? However he
shuﬄes his cards, he cannot help but feel uneasy: one day these government
level contracts might come to a close, then it will be back to catching small
ﬁsh.
</p><!--l. 31921--><p class="indent" >  For now, he will simply bide his time. Business as usual.
</p><!--l. 31923--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I don&#x2019;t know how to do anything else</span>, he thinks miserably. <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I don&#x2019;t know how to be</span>
<span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">anyone else.</span>
</p><!--l. 31926--><p class="indent" >  Besides, there is nothing like a pre-arranged routine to legitimise the avoidance of
the present.
</p><!--l. 31929--><p class="indent" >  He ﬂips further down his list of other messages, weeding out the advertising, until
he comes to a report from his sister. She has been quiet of late. That is another thing
that makes him uneasy. Mary informs him simply that the missionary herd is still
moving forward through the game. Other than that, she is still engaged in some
exploratory work, but nothing on that yet.
</p><!--l. 31936--><p class="indent" >  Yeehah. So the work of the church is still on-going, even if it has, for the present,
been sucked almost entirely into the virtual realm. There is no stopping the word of
the Lord. Somewhere, they are still out there, and you can bet that men in black suits
will come knocking again. He is not sure whether that is a good thing or a bad thing.
Perhaps she can negotiate his formal contrition with the gods of fortune, as long as she
is out there.
</p><!--l. 31944--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Move on.</span>
</p><!--l. 31946--><p class="indent" >  Further down the list is another note about the bio-tech giant: Vascon.
</p><!--l. 31948--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Vascon, Vascon, Vascon.</span>
</p><!--l. 31950--><p class="indent" >  Companies rule the world today, but this is too much. There is no getting away

from the head that roars loudest, unless someone from the oﬃce is playing a trick on
him. The woman&#x2019;s tentacles seem to extend like creeping roots across half
the world, in some form or other. She is a genuine nexus of power, while
he is merely a wanna-be yea sayer. She has both wealth and inﬂuence. She
hangs in the shadows, lightly plucking the strings, while he is trying to tug
away on them. And on top of that, he is unable to dislike her. He admires
her.
</p><!--l. 31959--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Bitch.</span>
</p><!--l. 31961--><p class="indent" >  What he needs is a rest. A rest—and to talk to the one person who can both
sympathize with his feelings and advise him about his strategy towards Catalin
Constanca Alexandra Cortina: Celia Waites. After all, she was practically complicit in
placing him before this multi-headed hydra. It might not be exactly fair to use her as
his amateur psychologist, but it would certainly give him a legitimate reason to visit
her.
</p><!--l. 31969--><p class="indent" >  Yes, Celia.
</p><!--l. 31971--><p class="indent" >  Since bumping into her in San Diego, Den has found himself thinking a lot of her.
She has qualities—several qualities—that he admires greatly. She is elegant, demure,
sexy but vulnerable, and she has excellent taste. She was surely thinking of his best
interests when she connecting him to Cortina. That must be worth something in
return.
</p><!--l. 31977--><p class="indent" >  Suddenly he is swimming in a memory of their time together: a curious meeting of
minds and body, but wholly satisfying, unlike his short experience with Cathy Kim.
Where did she go?
</p><!--l. 31981--><p class="indent" >  But surely he has better things to do than to go half way around the world just to
satisfy his conscience? Well, not just his conscience. She is a fascinating woman and
he has a feeling that she will be glad to show him more than a few fascinating things
about herself. . .
</p><!--l. 31987--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">I don&#x2019;t know how to do anything else. I don&#x2019;t know how to be anyone else.</span>
</p><!--l. 31990--><p class="indent" >  Den sighs with something akin to resignation, or could it be recognition?
</p><!--l. 31992--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">“We have met the enemy, and he is us”, </span>he recalls reading.
</p><!--l. 31994--><p class="indent" >  He looks down at his tablet and pulls up a list of things to do on his calender.
Meetings, brainstorms, reports to write. It is all there: all he needs to ﬁll his head with
pointless emptiness. But that is not what he is going to do. He ﬂicks through it all
several times, up and down, looking at it with weary disinterest. He has formed a
diﬀerent plan, and he intends to say yea to it.
</p><!--l. 32001--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">No more procrastination.</span>
</p><!--l. 32003--><p class="indent" >  His clicks his acceptance of the Vascon invitation and it is mailed in return, then he
pulls up his directory. And now he is going to call Celia.
</p><!--l. 32007--><p class="indent" >  Yes.
</p><!--l. 32009--><p class="indent" >  He will call her.
</p><!--l. 32011--><p class="indent" >  He is going to call.
</p><!--l. 32013--><p class="indent" >  He punches call.
</p>

<div class="center" 
>
<!--l. 32015--><p class="noindent" >
</p><!--l. 32016--><p class="noindent" >*</p></div>
<!--l. 32020--><p class="indent" >  Another doorbell warbles. The old door-com phone falls oﬀ its hook as he lifts
it.
</p><!--l. 32023--><p class="indent" >  “Hi it&#x2019;s Christina, can I come in?”
</p><!--l. 32025--><p class="indent" >  Christina? Dermot searches his mind to see if there is anyone—anyone else he
knows by that name.
</p><!--l. 32028--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Christina? Surely not?</span>
</p><!--l. 32030--><p class="indent" >  The search returns with failure and the inevitable conclusion sets his heart and mind
racing.
</p><!--l. 32033--><p class="indent" >  “Yes, yes, of course.” He is shocked. Confused. “Come in,” he says, clicking the
door opener.
</p><!--l. 32036--><p class="indent" >  The ﬁgure that meets him from the stairwell is a study in tragedy. She is a skeleton,
thin to the point of malnutrition.
</p><!--l. 32039--><p class="indent" >  His imagination races through the possible causes. In a game, such a change could
be the result of disease or hardship: a lack of points scored in earlier rounds.
Could that also be the case here? Perhaps an eating disorder? Or poverty? She
was never very good with money. She was never very good at looking after
herself.
</p><!--l. 32045--><p class="indent" >  It is practically summer, but she is wearing a long black duﬄe coat to contrast with
her blond pallor. Her face seems greyer now; it is not merely pale. She has lost
something. It hurts him to see her like this: she is a dream that has developed a fault.
A tragic fair angel.
</p><!--l. 32050--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m not disturbing am I? Are you expecting someone?” She looks frightened,
unsure, a mere fragment of her former self.
</p><!--l. 32053--><p class="indent" >  “No, no.”
</p><!--l. 32055--><p class="indent" >  “I thought I would say hello. Is that okay?”
</p><!--l. 32057--><p class="indent" >  “Of course,” he says. “Wow. That&#x2019;s great. Can I get you some tea or something?”
</p><!--l. 32059--><p class="indent" >  She looks into his eyes, searching his face with an almost tearful insecurity, as if
she expects him somehow to be lying to her. “No thanks.”
</p><!--l. 32062--><p class="indent" >  “So how are you?” he musters, after too long an interval.
</p><!--l. 32064--><p class="indent" >  She smiles, uncertainly. She does not know how to answer. She simply shakes her
head slightly.
</p><!--l. 32067--><p class="indent" >  “Are you still living in the same place?” he fumbles, leading her to a sofa.
</p><!--l. 32070--><p class="indent" >  “A lot of strange things have been happening lately. So many strange things.”
</p><!--l. 32072--><p class="indent" >  “What kind of things?”
</p><!--l. 32074--><p class="indent" >  She looks at him with that look again, as if she is saying: are you one of them? Her
expression ﬂirts with paranoia.
</p><!--l. 32077--><p class="indent" >  Dermot might not be a king in the realm of social relationships, but he can
recognize the signs people make with their faces. He has always been better at looking

than engaging. There is something wrong here. Something has happened to her. She is
not animated in the same way as before. The parameters are diﬀerent. Something is
broken. And she is scared: frightened of what she might learn, from what he might
say.
</p><!--l. 32084--><p class="indent" >  “Just things,” she answers and looks suddenly worried. “Where is everyone?” She
stares ahead into space, occasionally glancing fearfully at him, as if to plead for his
permission to be there. He considers how he might answer, and to which
question.
</p><!--l. 32089--><p class="indent" >  “I don&#x2019;t know,” he says simply. “Who?”
</p><!--l. 32091--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s so quiet.” Then a shy smile ﬂickers across her mouth, as if sensing that her
worry is excessive. “So how are you?”
</p><!--l. 32094--><p class="indent" >  He nods. “I&#x2019;m okay. Too much to do.” He laughs, trying to lighten the mood.
“Always trying to do too much.”
</p><!--l. 32097--><p class="indent" >  “You&#x2019;re pretty smart, aren&#x2019;t you?”
</p><!--l. 32099--><p class="indent" >  He laughs again. “Well, I don&#x2019;t know about that. . . Hey, do you still see that friend
of yours?”
</p><!--l. 32102--><p class="indent" >  “As if anyone cared about me.” She sits, huddled into her duﬄe coat, thin as a rake,
her hands deep inside her pockets. “What are you watching?” She points to the
TV.
</p><!--l. 32106--><p class="indent" >  “News. I like to watch the news.”
</p><!--l. 32108--><p class="indent" >  “Is it war? A lot of funny things have been happening lately. It seems like we are at
war sometimes.”
</p><!--l. 32111--><p class="indent" >  He laughs, but she does not return the laugh. He wonders if she really means
it.
</p><!--l. 32114--><p class="indent" >  “Can I get you some tea? Are you sure? Would you like a piece of cake?”
</p><!--l. 32116--><p class="indent" >  “Cake?” She looks hopeful.
</p><!--l. 32118--><p class="indent" >  “I have some chocolate cake.”
</p><!--l. 32120--><p class="indent" >  She looks disappointed. “No thanks.”
</p><!--l. 32122--><p class="indent" >  “So do you still see your friend down in Little Asia much?”
</p><!--l. 32124--><p class="indent" >  She considers his question, as if dredging a slow computation from the bottom of
her mind. Her eventual response is not what he expects.
</p><!--l. 32127--><p class="indent" >  “I like the Chinese. They are sort of peaceful—and smart. They had this great
civilization.”
</p><!--l. 32130--><p class="indent" >  Dermot does not let go of his point. Perhaps she did not understand him. He knows
that she visited a friend down near all the Vietnamese restaurants. She was always
talking about it. “But you had a friend who lived down there. You used to visit him.
Do you still see him?”
</p><!--l. 32136--><p class="indent" >  She looks at him, examining him as if she is looking for some sign of betrayal or as
if he is talking a foreign language. Or is she blocking out his thoughts? It does not
compute.
</p><!--l. 32140--><p class="indent" >  “The Chinese built the wall, you know. It&#x2019;s supposed to be huge, visible from space.
I&#x2019;ve been going to the library you know.”
</p><!--l. 32143--><p class="indent" >  He nods. “That&#x2019;s right.”

</p><!--l. 32145--><p class="indent" >  “I used to go to the Deichmann a lot. I used to read. I didn&#x2019;t have anyone to talk to
so I used to talk to the people in the books.”
</p><!--l. 32148--><p class="indent" >  “Yeah, it&#x2019;s good to escape in books,” he injects, supportively.
</p><!--l. 32150--><p class="indent" >  “I like the library.”
</p><!--l. 32152--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s been a while since I was in a library,” he thinks out loud.
</p><!--l. 32154--><p class="indent" >  “It must be a good thing to read a lot. You&#x2019;re pretty smart, aren&#x2019;t you?”
</p><!--l. 32156--><p class="indent" >  He shrugs.
</p><!--l. 32158--><p class="indent" >  “Everyone would stare at me in the library. I think they hate me there.”
</p><!--l. 32160--><p class="indent" >  Dermot frowns. “Hate you? No they don&#x2019;t. Perhaps you feel that when you are
depressed, but that doesn&#x2019;t mean that it&#x2019;s true.”
</p><!--l. 32164--><p class="indent" >  She smiles momentarily, happy at his answer, but then the inﬁnitesimal intervention
of grace crumbles into fear once again.
</p><!--l. 32167--><p class="indent" >  “Anyway, how are you?”
</p><!--l. 32169--><p class="indent" >  He nods. “Okay. Okay, you know. I, eh, am working hard as usual. Thinking of
travelling now.”
</p><!--l. 32172--><p class="indent" >  “You have a pretty high IQ right?”
</p><!--l. 32174--><p class="indent" >  “I&#x2019;m not sure everyone would agree!” he laughs, more suspiciously this
time.
</p><!--l. 32177--><p class="indent" >  “You could be smart.”
</p><!--l. 32179--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">She must be desperately lonely</span>, he thinks, and feels a ﬂood of sympathy for her
now. He compares her ﬁgure with how she looked when he ﬁrst saw her, when all he
felt was blind yearning and searching admiration. It was he who was the misﬁt then.
She looked so normal, so much more respectable than he did. Now look at
her. What could happen to a person to transform them so? What could go so
wrong?
</p><!--l. 32186--><p class="indent" >  “So do you have someone that you talk to regularly?” he asks,
</p><!--l. 32188--><p class="indent" >  “You mean the doctors? They are all bastards. They think they can just tell you
what to do and manipulate you.”
</p><!--l. 32191--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Doctors?</span>
</p><!--l. 32193--><p class="indent" >  “They put me away for a while.”
</p><!--l. 32195--><p class="indent" >  “What about your parents?”
</p><!--l. 32197--><p class="indent" >  “Parents?”
</p><!--l. 32199--><p class="indent" >  “Didn&#x2019;t they live across the bay? In. . .what&#x2019;s it called. . .”
</p><!--l. 32201--><p class="indent" >  She shakes her head. “They&#x2019;re dead.”
</p><!--l. 32203--><p class="indent" >  He frowns. They are not dead. He saw her together with her mother before he broke
oﬀ his contact with her. Does that mean they are not talking to her? Surely parents
would not abandon their child, not even a diﬃcult one.
</p><!--l. 32207--><p class="indent" >  “Everyone is trying to manipulate you all the time, take advantage. It&#x2019;s not
fair.”
</p><!--l. 32210--><p class="indent" >  “Dead? How do you mean?”
</p><!--l. 32212--><p class="indent" >  “Doctors, pretending to care. They just take advantage of you.”
</p><!--l. 32214--><p class="indent" >  Dermot stores a dulled shock, as though someone is feeding a persistent and
persistently painful electric current through his body. Has someone taken advantage of

her? Is that what has tipped her over the edge? He is not sure what to believe. Earlier
he might have been unnerved by the thought of someone even touching her,
but his growing sense of disbelief has been dulled down even further with
endorphins.
</p><!--l. 32222--><p class="indent" >  “That&#x2019;s not good,” he says stupidly.
</p><!--l. 32224--><p class="indent" >  They sit in silence for a few minutes while she watches the images on the TV, and
Dermot struggles to prove that he is not mute.
</p><!--l. 32227--><p class="indent" >  “Why is it so quiet?”
</p><!--l. 32229--><p class="indent" >  He ﬂinches from his racing thoughts. “Sorry. My fault.”
</p><!--l. 32231--><p class="indent" >  “No, outside.”
</p><!--l. 32233--><p class="indent" >  He shrugs.
</p><!--l. 32235--><p class="indent" >  ”No one is around. I guess everyone is staying at home. It&#x2019;s Sunday.”
</p><!--l. 32237--><p class="indent" >  “Is it Sunday?.”
</p><!--l. 32239--><p class="indent" >  “Perhaps they are on holiday somewhere. Holiday.”
</p><!--l. 32241--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s weird, I mean without people. Is it a war?” She picks up a leaﬂet on his coﬀee
table and looks at it. “Are you joining the church?”
</p><!--l. 32245--><p class="indent" >  “Eh, no. I don&#x2019;t know.” He takes it from her and packs it away at the bottom of a
pile of papers, embarrassed. No one is supposed to see that.
</p><!--l. 32248--><p class="indent" >  “Someone told me to join too,” she says.
</p><!--l. 32250--><p class="indent" >  “Maybe it would give you something to do?” he suggests. A church would at least
give her someone to watch over her, something to be part of.
</p><!--l. 32253--><p class="indent" >  She shakes her head fearfully.
</p><!--l. 32255--><p class="indent" >  “Bad men.”
</p><!--l. 32257--><p class="indent" >  Dermot exhales, sensing an incumbent heaviness prey upon him. He resets his
mind, and summons his strategic faculties, realizing that he bears no emotional debt
toward her, but somehow feeling culpable. If the visit is disturbing, it merely conﬁrms
to him, once and for all, that he has made the right decision to walk away from her all
those months ago.
</p><!--l. 32264--><p class="indent" >  Pausing to chew his upper lip, he glazes over and extends into what seems
like a space behind her face, for a long moment, looking both through and
beyond her into his future—into her future. His imagination is easily up to such
prediction; he is used to making such analyses in games. And for a moment it is as
though time passes before him and a possible future it played out. It is a future
that he has seen before and which he knows only too well. It is something
that conﬁrms his belief that truth can be stranger than ﬁction and it holds
a terrible fascination for him. It is the impossible, and he has made it the
forbidden: an image that frightens him and fascinates him in equal measure. He
beholds it and acknowledges it. Then his wandering mind gradually re-contracts
back into the most immediate present, where she is trying not to watch him
stare.
</p><!--l. 32278--><p class="indent" >  He makes his decision.
</p><!--l. 32280--><p class="indent" >  Dermot takes her out to a local coﬀee shop and buys her something to eat. He is not
sure how else to make her leave, in a nice way. He tells her that he is expecting a

visitor soon and that he has to return home.
</p><!--l. 32284--><p class="indent" >  “I should get back home soon.”
</p><!--l. 32286--><p class="indent" >  She nods. “Everyone in the ﬂats pointed at me you know. When I came.”
</p><!--l. 32288--><p class="indent" >  “Attractive girl like you. They might look to catch a glimpse of you.”
</p><!--l. 32291--><p class="indent" >  She smiles.
</p><!--l. 32293--><p class="indent" >  “It&#x2019;s quiet. Are you sure it&#x2019;s not war?”
</p><!--l. 32295--><p class="indent" >  He looks at her head, so close to his, her emaciated face, her malnutrition. Inside
there is a brain, somehow damaged. What connections are missing from her program
to so distort her view of the world? What perceptions have emphasized the poor
judgement?
</p><!--l. 32300--><p class="indent" >  Is it the result of lethargy, inaction? Is it due to drug use, or lack of it? Is it a trauma
that has shut down some crucial circuit, or perhaps a conspiracy of parts in her brain
that have fragmented into independent, schizophrenic agents, all competing for
dominance, and all of them losing. On top, there is still a remnant of her former
beauty. She could be beautiful again. She has the framework, but not the
support.
</p><!--l. 32308--><p class="indent" >  If he were to provide some suﬃciently strong, unifying message, could he steer her
confusion back into some form of integrated sanity? It is a powerful idea. They have
done it for society, with the team. If they can do it for society, could they not do it for
the society of mind? If he took her and retrained her in basic skills, like a dog, could
those brain connections be re-established? Could she return to her former state of
grace?
</p><!--l. 32317--><p class="indent" >  “Your guest is coming,” she says. “Bye then.”
</p><!--l. 32319--><p class="indent" >  He nods.
</p><!--l. 32321--><p class="indent" >  “Come by sometime,” she says.
</p><!--l. 32323--><p class="indent" >  She walks oﬀ into the distance and Dermot wonders what he should do. She does
not look back at him, she simply walks oﬀ in the wrong direction for going home. She
has become a phantom, a lost soul.
</p><!--l. 32327--><p class="indent" >  <span 
class="ptmri7t-x-x-109">Can she be repaired? </span>he wonders.
</p><!--l. 32330--><p class="indent" >  He balks at the thought. Involvement would only mean a script for his own cerebral
imbalance. She would drag him down like a lead balloon towards a black
hole.
</p><!--l. 32334--><p class="indent" >  Dermot walks back towards his ﬂat. He will play some music and consider the
matter. For now, his logical mind serves only to inform him that his decision to keep
to himself is both justiﬁable and correct. Getting to know people is just too dangerous
a sport for someone like him.
</p><!--l. 32340--><p class="indent" >  One is better oﬀ alone.
</p><!--l. 32342--><p class="indent" >  Dermot closes the door behind him and tries to forget the incident. If he sees her
again, he will deal with it when the time comes.
</p>
   
